SCOPE_NOTE: The receptacle at the top of a rain-water pipe which gathers the water from one or more outlets or gutters on the roof.
A large natural or artificial body of water, sometimes covered, used to collect and store water for a particular function, eg. industrial or public use.
A large drain or conduit for carrying away wastes.
A dam which can be raised or lowered to regulate the flow of water.
A pipe through which water is conducted.
A receptacle for the storage of water.
The structure at the top of a draw well.
A building over a well housing machinery for raising the water. Often consisting of a DONKEY WHEEL or HORSE GIN.
A multi-purpose farm building.

Soil marks and other features of natural origin, including periglacial frost wedging, solifluction deposits, abandoned water courses, etc, recorded to avoid future confusion with features of human origin.
A forest killed by rising sea-level. Nowadays only tree stumps survive.
A single line, or pair of roughly parallel lines, of pits set at intervals along a common axis or series of axes. The pits are not thought to have held posts.
A communal dining room, especially in schools, colleges and monasteries.
A wall or masonry construction built for the purpose of retaining or supporting a bank of earth, wall, rampart etc.
A set of marks found on the wall of a building, thought to be a form of sundial.
A structure which protects an area of ground from the weather.
A building in which horses are accommodated.
A piece of stone, usually shaped, of uncertain origin or use.
A post, usually of iron or concrete, used to support a street lamp.
An artificially raised level of ground.
A constructed space beneath the surface of the ground.
A building or room in which wood is stored.
A paved area, generally found at the back of a house.
A building equipped with facilities for bathing, and occasionally public baths.
A pipe or channel for conveying water or other liquids.
A head of water raised in a conduit system.
A long, narrow ditch designed to carry water away from a waterlogged area.
A system of artificial or natural drains and ditches used to drain off surplus water.
Any wall enclosing a building or complex of buildings, eg. prisons, dockyards, factories, etc.
A detached subordinate building. Use specific type where known, eg. DAIRY.
Component. Use wider site type where known.
A stone (including standing stones, natural boulders and rock outcrops) decorated with carved motifs.
A tower built to display a large clock.
A building used to store coal.
Earthworks of uncertain date and purpose, consisting of cross-shaped banks sometimes with an accompanying ditch. Their distribution is largely confined to North Yorkshire.
An oval shaped area of land enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.
An area of land enclosed by two parallel ditches. Use with specific shaped enclosure where known.
A place where material used for burning is stored.
A gateway with one or more chambers over the entrance arch; the flanking towers housing stairs and additional rooms. Use with wider site type where known.
The slab or place on which a fire is made.
An area of land which has been drained or cleared for habitation and/or cultivation.
A length of straight, curved or angled earthwork or cropmark of uncertain date or function.
Area feature visible as an earthwork or cropmark with no known function.
A post bearing one or more signs indicating the direction, and often the distance, to specified locations or routes.
A structure used for the lifting of boats and other water craft.

An open area of water, usually artificial and enclosed by dock gates or locks, lined with wharves and warehouses, where barges, narrow boats and other canal vessels can load and unload goods and supplies.
A place where canal boats are built and maintained.
A tunnel with a canal running through it.
A large wooden structure built alongside the edge of a river where boats may lie for the loading and unloading of goods and passengers.
Use for free standing column.
A layer of stone, brick or boards, etc, on which people tread. Use broader site type where known.
Component: Use wider site type where known.
A painting or mural executed directly onto a wall.
A garden building on an estate used by fishing parties.
A purpose-built, or modified, building where organizations and associations meet for presentations and consultation.
Purpose built workers' accommodation comprising single rooms with communal eating and washing facilities. Usually for short stay accommodation only.
Use both terms.
A house or hut for a nightwatchman; including parish watch houses in churchyards and private watch houses, eg. in dockyards, factories, etc.
A steam driven winding engine house for raising coal to the surface.
Use both terms.

A building used by the society, fraternity or order organized under this name with initiatory rites, mystic signs of recognition and various degrees of dignity or honour, for social or benevolent purposes.
A shop where fish is sold.

An educational institution, introduced in the 1960s. Distinguished from universities by traditionally training technicians in business, industry and commerce for an immediate local area, and offering more part-time classes, etc.
A market building, pre-19th century, incorporating other function rooms, eg. theatres, courtrooms, schoolrooms.
A room used primarily for storing food and drink.
A farm with a pond, river, lake or tanks where fish are kept and bred for commercial purposes.
An establishment where people get their hair dressed and cut.
A disused term for a hospital caring for and treating patients affected with acute or chronic mental illness.
A row of columns supporting an entablature.
A chapel within a parish church containing an altar and one or more tombs.
A rustic building of picturesque design.
A workshop used for the manufacture of items of jewellery and/or timepieces from precious metals and precious or semi-precious stones.
A store for keeping undressed meat.
A spa building to which water was pumped from springs or wells; usually also serving a social function as an ASSEMBLY ROOM, eg. as at Bath.
A building where an officer of a county, district or municipality acting as a representative of the Crown holds inquests, including deaths through violence or accident and treasure trove.
A place where the game of squash is played.
A dwelling house forming part of a Chartist Land Colony.
A model village established by the chartists.
A cheap restaurant.
The dwelling of a blacksmith, nailer, sword cutler, etc, often adjacent to, or containing, a BLACKSMITHS WORKSHOP.
A market appointed for the sale of wool.
A building used for the storage of fish.
A college associated with, or forming part of, a university.
For Commercial organisations use OFFICE. For Military use MILITARY HEADQUARTERS.
A stable where horses are kept at livery, or are let out for hire.
A barn in which a central space is separated from side aisles by posts and braces.
A building used to prepare and store dry food such as hay and straw for the feeding of cattle.
A furnace used for melting metals for casting or for heating shot.
Use for flood defence embankment.
Use both terms.
A building or site for the manufacture of livestock fodder.
A machine used for the loading and unloading of grain to and from a warehouse
A place where specific skills are taught on short courses.
A commercial building used primarily as a trading place for wool merchants.
A storehouse for ore, often found in conjunction with a BLAST FURNACE.
An endowed school providing a liberal education for such as can afford it.
A shop where fish and chips are sold.
A factory for the manufacture of leather goods, such as shoes, saddles, etc. Use TANNERY for the manufacture of leather.
An RAF Base, used specifically for the storage and maintenance of barrage balloons.
A building or subterranean structure used for the storage of wine.
Chimney used on an industrial or commercial site.
A stall, often within a cow house, where cattle are kept individually.
Three storey house with a topshop; machinery powered by shafting through the upper floor.
A law court exercising summary criminal jurisdiction, preliminary hearings and some civil jurisdiction. Formally established by name following legislation of 1949.

A site where a building once stood as identified by a level area of ground, often compacted or made from man-made materials. Use only where specific function is unknown, otherwise use more specific term.
An interment of human or animal remains. Use specific type where known. If component use with wider site type. Use FUNERARY SITE for optimum retrieval in searches.
Use specific type of cemetry where known.
A mound or structure on which an archery, musketry or artillery target is erected. Use specific type where known.
A circle of spaced upright boulders emerging from a low, hemispherical, stony mound. The boulders may lean outwards due to pressure from the cairn material.
A site where clay is both extracted and fired to produce bricks.
A trench dug to contain a sill beam, a horizontal timber beam used as a foundation for the wall of a building. Use wider site type where known.
A tower or turret in which bells are hung.
Use ABBEY and BENEDICTINE MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
Use ALIEN PRIORY with BENEDICTINE MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
Use all terms.
A residence of the Bonhommes brethren, who followed the Augustinian rule.
A large, "bottle-shaped", oven of brick construction used in the baking or firing of pottery.
A site where the manufacture of glass bottles takes place.
A fence that indicates the limit of an area or a piece of land.
Use ABBEY with AUGUSTINIAN MONASTERY.
Use PRIORY with AUGUSTINIAN MONASTERY.

A historic term for a psychiatric hospital or institution. Refers to the infamous 13th century institution in London, called the hospital of St Mary of Bethlehem or Bethlem Royal Hospital, known for its brutal treatment of its patients.
A historic term for an institution caring for people with mental illness.
A historic term for an institution caring for people with mental illness.
Use ABBEY with AUGUSTINIAN DOUBLE HOUSE/MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
Use ALIEN PRIORY with AUGUSTINIAN DOUBLE HOUSE/MONASTERY or NUNNERY.
Use all terms.
Use PRIORY with AUGUSTINIAN MONASTERY or AUGUSTINIAN NUNNERY.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
This is the top term for the class. See RECREATIONAL Class List for narrow terms.
A defensive cattle enclosure added to fortified towers.
Use both terms.
A site where guns, mortars or searchlights are mounted. Use specific type where known.
A priory dependent on a foreign mother house. Use with narrow terms of DOUBLE HOUSE, MONASTERY or NUNNERY.
A building used for the crystallization process in alum making.
A site where alum (hydrous sulphate or salt and alumina) is quarried.
The official residence of an archbishop, eg. Lambeth Palace.
Small agricultural structure built into field walls in Cornwall.
Artificial water channel, usually leading to a mill.
A body of still water often artificially formed for a specific purpose. Use specifc type where known.
A toilet or toilets for public use.
A machine used to raise and move water and other liquids, compress gases, etc. Use more specific type where known.
A wind-powered pump for land drainage.
A small pumping station.
A room or building where a pump is worked.
A site where an army or body of troops is, temporarily or permanently, lodged, with or without entrenchments and fortifications.
A building used for a variety of administrative purposes, usually at a military base.
A building containing a weighing machine for weighing goods; sometimes found in markets, ports, etc.
Use both terms.
A farm on the estate of a manor.
A place where the popular gambling game of bingo is played.
A place where public sales of goods are made by competitive bidding.
A flat bottomed ditch flanked by mounds running to the south of Hadrian's Wall for much of its length, marking the boundary of the military zone.
The residence of a lightkeeper.
An establishment where patients can rest and recover after an operation or illness.
A shopping complex, usually indoors, comprised of a number of separate retail outlets surrounding an open space. Often on more than one level.
A large, rectangular open space at the centre of a Roman town, incorporating public spaces and a market area.
Place where a smith works iron. May be for small scale local use or within a larger industrial complex.
A military base normally between 20 and 30 acres in size, containing legionary and auxiliary battle units, which served as stores depots and winter quarters during campaigns.

A small tower or bartizan, which was often placed at the angles of a castle, to increase the flanking ability, some only serving as corner buttresses. Also used to describe the small rectangular towers situated between the milecastles along Hadrians Wall.
A defensive gun battery positioned to face out to sea to fire on enemy ships and amphibious craft.
A temporary hostel built for industrial or transport workers; for example, railway workers' hostels were provided for engine drivers.
A type of coal preparation plant for the sizing, sorting and washing of coal.
A building in which engineered metal products are finished and polished.
A place where architectural ornaments such as stone vases and urns are manufactured.
A building housing a Finnish-style steam bath.
A large store for textiles.
A meeting hall of the Temperance Society.
A building where military officers are accommodated.
A training college for the instruction of military trainees in the theory and practice of warfare.
Engineering workshop intended either for final adjustments of new machinery or the fitting of replacement parts to machinery under repair.
Use both terms.
A large, watertight enclosure in which the water is maintained at the high-tide level so that vessels remain constantly afloat in them.
A place of worship for Christian Scientists, a sect founded in the mid-19th century in America who believe that God is the only reality and can bring healing to humanity.
A place where the homeless are accommodated, permanently or temporarily.

A place of worship for Wesleyan Methodists. This was the original Methodist church from which the other denominations seceded. In 1932 they joined the United Methodists and the Primitive Methodists to form the Methodist church.
Prehistoric structure consisting of three or more standing stones in close proximity to each other, forming an unroofed approximately rectangular structure open in one direction.
Areas of indeterminate function.
a wooden, metal or stone post used to tether a horse, or other animals.
A site where metal is worked. Use specific type where known.
Living quarters for animals, birds, etc, as pets or for observation, entertainment, etc.
A building where reptiles are accommodated at a zoo or wildlife park.
A zoo building containing artificial ponds or tanks in which aquatic plants and animals are kept alive for purposes of observation and study.
A temporary kitchen set up in the field providing food for troops. Use with MILITARY CAMP if existence of this is known.
A group of planted trees or shrubs, generally of uniform age and of a single species.
Circular enclosure featuring an enclosing bank with no accompanying ditch. Use specific type where known.
A site where clay is mined from the ground.
A site where barytes (barium sulphate) is mined. Barytes is also commonly worked from the waste tips of lead mines.
A mine used for the extraction of the mineral Witherite. When secondary mineral, use with term for product, eg. LEAD MINE.
When a secondary mineral, use term for product type, eg. LEAD MINE.
A site where fluorspar or fluoride of calcium, often used as a flux by copper-ore smelters, is extracted from an open cast mine.
A single ditched 3-sided rectilinear enclosure.
A site where gypsum and anhydrate is mined.

Ditches interrupted by wide, regular causeways. Each section of ditch is about 30-40m long, and each causeway is 10-15m wide. In some cases, a network of fields has been created. Found mainly in the South East of England.
A place where osiers (willows) are grown for basket-making.
Use broader site type where known
A place where umber or oxide of iron and manganese, is extracted from an open cast mine.
A prepared area of grass on which the game of football is played.
A pedestrianized shopping street, or a more complex arrangement of shopping 'squares' and walkways.
Shallow ditches and/or poles erected across open land to obstruct the landing of enemy aircraft and gliders.
An area in a town where traffic is prohibited, often containing shops.
A bridge carrying a tramway.
Long alignment of cairns lying between two large cairns; first recognized as a site type on Sourton Tor, Dartmoor.
Used for the laying out and marking of the smaller parts of a ship prior to construction.
A place where boats are stored.
A pond with underwater arches where the poles for masts were stored to prevent them from drying and splitting.
A building where masts are made and stored.

Monument visible as a mark in standing crops or parchmarks, but where no subsurface deposits have been proven eg by excavation or other ground disturbance, in which case SUB SURFACE DEPOSIT should be used.
Workshop for the painting of vehicles, machines, etc.
A building or works in which carriages were built. Use RAILWAY CARRIAGE WORKS for sites making railway carriages.
Traditionally a mineral that could be used for striking fire but now a term commonly used to refer to various sulphides, especially iron disulphide.
A depression in the ground caused by the explosion of a mine or bombshell.
The limit to an area as defined on a map or by a marker of some form, eg. BOUNDARY WALL. Use specific type where known.
A movable bridge that swings or rotates around a central pier to provide a passageway for navigation.

A bridge consisting of a lattice girder spanning the distance between the tops of two towers. Designed to transport vehicles across the gap in a container suspended at road level by ropes under a travelling crane on the girder.
A stone, situated alongside a road, providing directions to travellers.
A structure consisting of a box or platform for carrying goods or passengers from one level to another. Use specific type where known.
A building used to house railway engines.
A building in which railway wagons can unload local goods.
A railway worked by the propulsive force of compressed air or by the formation of a vacuum.
Use both terms.
A piece of machinery on which a railway engine, carriage or wagon can be rotated at a railway terminal.
A bridge, usually resting on raised arches, carrying a railway across low-lying land or water.
A place where trams are maintained and refitted, etc.
A track consisting of flanged strips used in early colliery railways.
An outbuilding where a horse-drawn carriage is kept.
A block for mounting a horse.
Narrow, rough tracks often over upland routes used by packhorse trains to carry goods.
A road whose upkeep and repair was financed by the exaction of a toll.
A path for pedestrians only.
A road or way along a ridge of downs or low range of hills.
An abbey or priory for nuns ofthe Benedictine order.
A priory of the female Order of Knights Hospitallers.
A manor or estate owned and run by an order of knights and governed by a preceptor.
A sacred area of a building or a consecrated piece of land.
A single line, or two or more roughly parallel lines, of standing stones set at intervals along a common axis or series of axes.
A circular arrangement of spaced stone uprights set within a high bank, often interrupted by a formal entrance gap.
A stone circle featuring a stone which lies lengthways between two of the upright standing stones.
A place of worship for Jewish people.
A Roman sanctuary, devoted to the Graeco-Roman cult of Mithras.

Approximately circular or oval setting of spaced post holes indicating the former presence of a free-standing arrangement of upright timber posts. Often regarded as a wooden equivalent of the better known stone circles.
A system of overhead cables from which cars or containers are suspended (usually driven electrically).
A site, including an airfield and customs house, where air passengers embark and disembark.
A large shed for the housing of aircraft, etc.
A structure used for the housing and servicing of aircraft.
A bridge over a canal.
A simple form of stone slab bridge, particularly associated with South West England.
An abbey or priory of Augustinian canonesses.
A bridge carrying a railway track across a river, valley, road etc.
Mixed house of nuns and religious men.
A mixed house of Augustinian nuns, canonesses and canons.
A house of friars, originally hermits from Mount Carmel. Also known as ' white friars'.
A house of friars of the order of St Dominic. Also known as Friars Preachers or 'Black Friars'.
A friary belonging to the Crutched Friars also known as Crosiers or Fratres.
A friary belonging to the Pied Friars also known as Friars of Blessed Mary or St Mary de Arens.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Augustinian order.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Benedictine order.
Houses specifically of monks, canons or religious men but not friars.
An abbey or priory of Augustinian canons.
An abbey or priory for monks of the Benedictine order.
An abbey or priory of Carthusian monks.
An abbey or priory of Cistercian monks.
An abbey or priory of Cluniac monks.
An abbey or priory of Gilbertine monks.
An abbey or priory of Grandmontine monks.
An abbey or priory of Premonstratensian canons.
An abbey or priory belonging to the Tironian order.
A building where the bones of the dead were stored.
A stone coffin embellished with sculpture.
A building forming part of a colliery ventilation system exhausting stale air from shafts and headings.
Production of smokeless domestic fuel by roasting anthracite in a type of kiln.
A pile of rough stones and soil used for the growing of ferns and other plants.
A garden which consists of rocks and rock-loving plants that require little water.
A place devoted to the cultivation and exhibition of rare trees.
A garden in which a variety of plants are grown to encourage butterflies.
Buildings and works around a mine shaft with an artificial embankment on which the winding gear etc, is located.
A plant, Salsola soda, burnt to produce alkali.
Bone like material which grows in a branch-like fashion on the heads of male deer and reindeers in general.
Hollow cylinders or tubes of ceramic, wood, plastic or metal used to convey liquids, gases etc. Used in a variety of industries.
A cairn featuring a mound of small diameter (normally less than 6m), which is surrounded by a kerb of stones which are considerably taller than the mound.
The powdery residue of burnt bones.
An earth derived pigment.
A hard metallic element used in steels and magnetic alloys. Compounds containing manganese are used in glass-making and other industrial processes.
An exotic hardwood with great strength and durability.
A large, manmade pool, usually lined with tiles, rubber or similar. Can be placed in the open air, eg. a LIDO, or built as part of a covered sports centre.
A building used primarily for the performing of plays.
An area of a church, often a free-standing building, in which baptism is administered
A representation of the crucifixion of Christ or related scenes as a sculpture in a churchyard, etc.
A chapel built into the structure of a bridge.

A vertical vein of metallic ore, usually lead, occuring between walls of rock and cutting through the bedding. Often rakes have been worked from early times leaving deep trenches several km long, with adits leading off and shafts sunk at the side.
A mill used to process raw timber.
A factory used for the production of thick, flat glass used for shop window panes, etc. Plate glass is produced by rolling and casting rather than traditional blowing.
A spoil heap consisting mainly of slag, pieces of refuse material separated from a metal during the smelting process.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the smelting of metals.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the extraction of metal ores.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the manufacture of products from metals.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the processing of non ferrous metal ores.
A building where violins are manufactured and the art of violin making is taught.
A garden ornament, usually of stone or metal, designed in the the form of a vase used to receive the ashes of the dead.
A large mounted gun, now disused and placed in a prominent position as a piece of street furniture or as a "feature".
A building or group of buildings, often enclosed by a system of fortifications, used by an armed force for the storage and distribution of military equipment.
An obstruction, usually manmade, which is used to restrict or prevent access to a settlement, building or area of land. Use more specific type where known.

A reinforced concrete structure, which may be sited above ground or semi-sunken, from where it was intended to conduct the business of government from, in the event of nuclear war. Date specific to the early-mid 1950's.
Buildings and structures inhabited by agricultural workers.

A large room, similar to a dormitory, within a hospital, and used for the temporary or permanent accommodation of patients, either waiting for or recovering from operations or undergoing long term treatment.
A roofed, lightweight structure, usually attached to a house, provdiing access from and to the garden.
A large bed surrounded by an earthwork and filled with composing vegetable matter and animal waste. This was used to produce Nitre, a constituent of gunpowder.
A workshop used for the manufacture of statues, either cast or carved.
A large stone used by cattle to rub up against and so scratch themselves.
A factory for the manufacture of vehicles
A workshop used by a craftsman who works in base or precious metals.
A workshop in which products are made using wood and timber.
Previous name for Mumbai.
Mistranscription of 'll' for handwritten ligatured 'ss'. Should be Boness or Bo'ness.
A place of worship for Calvinistic Methodists, Welsh Methodists who split from the established church in 1811.
A place of worship for members of the Church of Scotland which has been Presbyterian since 1690. It is the national Church of Scotland and is free and endowed.
A plant for bottling manufactured goods, as opposed to a BOTTLE WORKS where bottles were made.
A garden containing trees or shrubs pruned and trained into various geometric, zoomorphic or fantastic shapes.
A walk bordered by trees or clipped hedges in a garden or park. Made of gravel, sand or turf, it is different from a path or avenue.
An ore, such as stibnite, containing a high proportion of antimony.
Thin rods or threads of metal formed by rolling or wire-drawing and used for a variety of purposes including electrical circuitry.
Cloth that has been woven in fixed lengths for sale.
An ornate, openwork fabric made by twisting, knotting or looping threads. Originally made by hand but more recently manufactured mechanically.
A structure used for the storage of coal.
Bordering the continents of Africa, Antarctica, Asia and Australasia, the Indian Ocean covers 28,364,000 square miles.
A sea within a sea, the Aegean consists of that part of the Mediterranean bordered by Greece and Turkey.
A sea within a sea, the Andaman Sea consists of that part of the Indian Ocean bordered by Myanmar, Thailand, Malaysia, Sumatra and the Andaman and Nicobar Islands.
Bordering the continents of Asia, Europe and North America the Arctic Ocean covers 5,426,000 square miles. Situated over the North Pole, much of the ocean remains frozen year round.
A purpose-built terrace of shops.
A light, ductile metal, used in the manufacture of aircraft etc.
Waste matter, usually liquid in form, consisting of the contents of sewers and cesspits.
A site where granite is excavated.
The edible seed of the palm tree.
A compound consisting of potassium and silica, used in various processes.
A prehistoric coffin made out of a hollow tree trunk.
A wall with niches in a CREMATORIUM to display the urns containing ashes. Use only when related to funerary site.
A building or site where bodies are burnt, and the ashes collected for burial or dispersal.
A stone used to cover a grave.
A building, site or container used to store the bones of the dead after they have been removed from graves to allow new burials.
A tomb designed in the form of a cist or stone box placed over a burial. Its outward form often reproduces the features of the classical sarcophagus or medieval effigy base.
A type of tomb in the form of a slab raised on freestanding legs.
A small hut, dwelling or cave, usually in a secluded spot, in which a hermit lived. Hermits chose to live solitary lives often due to religious motives.
An early Medieval commemorative monument in the form of a stone which has been inscribed with symbols.
A wall enclosing a precinct.
A stone or boulder which lies lengthways on the ground and may be used as a table, altar etc. Use only for isolated stones.
Use only for a monastic house of unknown status, religious order and uncertain authenticity.
A religious house governed by an abbot or abbess. Use with narrow terms of DOUBLE HOUSE, MONASTERY or NUNNERY.
Urn containing a cremation. Where component use with wider site type.
An interment of unburnt, articulated human remains. Use specific type where known.
An inhumation, usually Roman, which has been covered by tiles to form a tent-like structure over the body; the apex is covered by ridge tiles.
A place where dead bodies are buried together. Often unconsecrated ground.
A deep pit used for the burial of plague victims.
A stony mound containing or concealing deliberately deposited human remains. Use specific type where known.

A Neolithic burial monument comprising a rectangular or trapezoidal stony mound which contains either a passage at one end with or without lateral chambers, or one or more smaller chambers entered from the side of the mound.
A Neolithic burial monument comprising an approximately circular stony mound which contains a stone-built chamber, with or without additional lateral chambers.
A roughly square mound of stones which may also contain or conceal a burial.
An area of ground, set apart for the burial of the dead.
A cemetery comprising exclusively cremated human remains, some or all of which may be contained within pottery vessels.
A place of burial for members of the Society of Friends.
Use appropriate type.
An enclosed area of ground immediately surrounding a cathedral.
A Neolithic monument comprising an irregularly circular enclosing ditch, interrupted by frequent causeways, and often accompanied by an internal bank, also causewayed.
A church attached to or founded by a college.
The foremost church within a parish.
Use both terms.
A stone found on route to a churchyard on which the coffin is rested during transportation.
Use both terms.
A cross found in a market place.
A cross erected in a village.
A stone with a cross carved into the surface.
A Neolithic burial monument comprising a stone-built chamber within an earthen mound. Use more precise term where known.
A Neolithic burial monument comprising a stone-built chamber within a rectangular or trapezoidal earthen mound.
A form of Neolithic long barrow comprising an oval, rather than rectangular or trapezoidal mound.
A round barrow featuring a mound surrounded by a ditch, with no intervening berm. The ditch may be accompanied by an external bank.
Deliberate interment of a complete, or substantially complete, animal. Use the object type thesaurus term ANIMAL REMAINS where skeleton is fragmentary.
A site where the baiting of animals took place. Use more specific site type where known.
A site used for the sport of badger baiting using fighting dogs.
A pit where bears were housed for baiting and entertainment purposes. If not used for baiting use BEAR ENCLOSURE.
An arena for bull-baiting, not a tethering ring.
A building where people pay to see films and 'moving pictures'.
A building occupied by a club or commonly used for club activities.
The principal stand at a sporting ground, eg. at a racecourse.
An often ornately decorated theatre for the performance of opera.
An object supported by a crosspiece on a post, used by knights as a target in tilting.
A piece of ground on which athletes race.
An area or route marked out for the site of a race.
A piece of ground used for motor racing.
An unidentified feature on the seabed recorded by fishermen as an obstruction to trawling.
A building where advice, counselling and medical treatment is available.
A building or range of buildings used for the cleaning, crushing and loading of freshly mined coal.
A structure housing machinery for crushing coal. Usually found at the pithead of a colliery or coal mine.
Water spraying tower for cooling coke after it emerges from the furnace.
Material consisting of fragments of stone, sand, gravel, slag etc. used in the manufacture of concrete.
Machinery and equipment used in the manufacture of aircraft.
Use for cargoes of live animals only.
The cured flesh of a pig.
Grain from a cereal of the genus hordeum, often used in the manufacture of alcoholic spirits.
A straight mine entrance, driven on a constant downwards slope.

A building housing the permanent electricity generator supply for domestic use or small scale unspecified power generation on an airfield. Unlike stand by set houses, power houses had to cope with both essential and non-essential loads.
A site where methane gas, released by coal mining, is collected and processed.
A maritime monument where the vessel remains are buried in the sea bed.
A maritime monument where the hull structure and fabric of a vessel remain wholly or mainly intact.
Monument known only from primary documentary sources eg books, maps, legal records, where no physical evidence exists. Use also where a monument has been planned but never constructed.
Do not use
Metal hoops used to hold the staves of barrels in position.
Pieces of wood used to form the sides of barrels.
The meat obtained from cattle.
A mixture of paraffins distilled from petroleum and used as a fuel and solvent.
Traditionally, pieces of unleavened cake or bread usually small in size and dry, crisp and hard.
The fat removed from the carcass of a whale or seal and used in the manufacture of cosmetics and as a fuel for tallow lamps.
Narrow necked containers, originally of leather but now usually made of glass or plastic. Used for storing liquids.
Double-key with object material.
Metal, usually gold and silver, in the form of ingots prior to being minted into coinage.
An ornamental, commemorative tablet. Use with materials field when indexing.
A building in which goods were kept prior to being cleared by customs officers.
A structure or building, often within a secluded area of a garden, where people could go for quiet reflection.
A building that housed humans and cattle under one roof, with a shared entrance providing access to the cattle housing (usually downslope) and the dwelling area.
A mill in which barytes concentrates were ground to fine white powder, normally by use of flat millstones similar to those of a corn mill.
A building in which apparatus measuring the amount of water supplied/used is housed.
A structure consisting of combustible material, typically wood, on which a body is placed and then cremated, sometimes with accompanying grave goods. Use only when evidence of structure exists.
Fixed instrument to measure altitude of stars and planets.

A structure used to show the time of day by means of the sun shining on a 'gnomon', the shadow of which falls on the surface of the dial which is marked with a diagram showing the hours. Can be freestanding, usually on a pillar, or fixed to a building.
State.
City and port on the Mediterranean coast.
A long seat, usually made of stone or wood, with or without a back.
Unable to identify actual place from documentary sources alone.

Traditionally, dating from the medieval period, this was an area on the north bank of the Thames where the Merchants of the Hanse conducted their business. Now includes a similar establishment in a provincial town.
The unarticulated remains of the body of a human being. If articulated use inhumation.

A perforated stone basin usually built into the wall of a church on the south side of the altar. Used for carrying away the ablutions (wine and water used to rinse the chalice, and wash the priests hands after communion).
Use more specific term where known.

A building containing a series of seats for use by the clergy during services. The seats are usually placed in the church and as such this is a very rare monument type, being purpose-built. An example being St. Germoe's Chair in Germoe, Cornwall.
A non residential building providing recreational, social and other facilities, especially for the elderly and those with special needs.
Clothing, cloth and woven fabric manufactured from either natural or artificial fibres.
Transportation, usually wheeled or tracked, used for the conveyance of goods or people.
A clear liquid that forms oceans, rivers etc.
A cereal of the genus Triticum, which can be ground to manufacture flour for bread and pasta.
An alcoholic drink made from fermented grape juice (or occasionally other fruits).
Small fragments of wood or bark.
Fibres of wood reduced chemically or mechanically to pulp for use in the manufacture of paper.
Goods, particularly cloth and garments, manufactured from wool.
A building used for the preparation of animal skins and hides prior to the tanning process.
A mill, on two or more levels.
A type of drying house, usually circular with a conical roof.
A loft for the drying of thread or cloth.
A workshop forming part of a domestic dwelling.
A channel used for or formed by the conveyance of water. Can be natural, eg. a river or artificial eg. an aqueduct. Use more specific type where known.
Site and structures associated with the supply of clean water.
Sites and structures associated with the storage of water and waste water.
Sites and structures associated with the disposal of waste water and waterborne refuse.
An area of the floor, wall or ceiling of a building, which has been painted, carved, sculpted or decorated.
An enclosure in which ships are built and repaired, and all sorts of ships' stores are brought together.
A sheltered port for ships.
A post to which ropes are attached to secure vessels at a landing place.
Non-military maritime flood and erosion defences.
A conspicuous object, such as a beacon, used by mariners to aid navigation at sea.
A structure inclined towards the water on which a ship may be built or lowered into the water.
A beacon used for coastal navigation. Many date from the Medieval period.
Place where tanned leather is dressed and coloured.
A site used for the manufacture of leather products.
A pit or tank containing chemicals for the preserving of animal hide.
Large field or yard used to lay fabrics out ready for bleaching.
A large factory or series of workshops for the manufacture of clothing.
Large wooden hammer beams pounding cloth in a fulling solution.
A factory where hats are manufactured.
A factory or works housing machinery used to produce stockings and socks, using mechanized knitting processes.
A place where sails are manufactured.
Building for testing the condition and strength of textiles.
A workshop where baskets were manufactured.
A barrel-making workshop or factory, found in conjunction with a number of industries.
A factory where furniture is manufactured.
A place where wheels and wheeled vehicles were manufactured, originally from wood.
A factory that manufactures toys.
A building or room used for small scale manufacture. Use more specific term where possible.
A site used for the manufacture and finishing of querns.
This is the top term for the class. See MARITIME Class List for narrow terms.
A house or shelter for the storage and/or launching of boats.
A structure which protects a beach or harbour by breaking the force of the waves.
Water channel leading to water wheel.
A vertical or inclined excavation giving access to an underground mine.
A treadwheel using a donkey as motive power. Usually found operating wells.
Building containing transformers to reduce the high voltage of the National Grid to the lower voltage of domestic supply.
A rotary prime mover. Turbines may be steam, water or gas operated.
A simple wind-driven machine used for a variety of purposes.
A building housing a beam engine.
A building housing a turbine.
Expanding storage tank for gas, often includes a meter for measuring the amount used.
A horse-powered winding engine used at mining sites.
A waterworks pumping station.
A pumping station used in the production of hydraulic power, eg. in warehouse complexes, goods depots on railways, etc.
A steam-powered machine used for raising ore or water from a mine.
A type of windmill, mainly timber-framed, whose body, containing machinery and carrying the sail, rotates about an upright post.
The rectangular pit in which the lower part of a waterwheel revolves.
A large tank used for soaking alumina-bearing shale in water and chemicals, the initial stage in the alum-making process.
A site where rough stone is processed, shaped, worked or formed into finished products.
A site where artefacts are manufactured from jet.
A site where large sheets of thin metal are manufactured.
A place where boats or ships are built or repaired.
A place where silverware is manufactured.
Mill for grinding bark usually for use in the tanning industry. Use with power type(s), eg. WATERMILL where known.
A factory where buttons are manufactured.
Wind or water-powered mill for land drainage in fens or marshlands.
Any factory used for the manufacture of textiles.
A mill for beating and cleaning cloth, using soap or fullers earth.
A mill where flax fibres were woven into linen cloth.
Steel which has been formed into sheets.
Equipment including diving suits, wet suits, oxygen tanks etc. used to enable people to undertake underwater activities.
a hard metal used in a lot of alloys.
A volatile, colourless distillate of petroleum used as a solvent and paint thinner.
A place where goods are sold in bulk, rather than by retail.
Solid bars made from pure zinc.
An ore containing a high proportion of manganese.
The young of the sheep.
Tools and equipment used for agricultural purposes.
Large keyboard, percussion instruments in which strings are struck by hammers to produce notes.
A fertilizer containing nitrogen.
Potassium nitrate
Coarse jute sacking
Food, usually hay or straw, kept for the feeding of animals.

All physical evidence for a monument has certainly been completely destroyed (allowing no future reinvestigation) by activity implying substantial ground disturbance. Eg quarrying, road cutting, or natural disaster, erosion, acts of God etc.
Natural feature or area deliberately enhanced to construct a monument, eg rock carving, cave, rock shelter.
A mill for the removal by mechanical means of the dried wood and seeds of the flax and cotton plants after retting. The resulting 'tow' is then spun into linen and cotton respectively.
A mill used for the mechanized processing of silk.
An engineering site where railway carriages are manufactured.
Pond, created specifically for providing power to water-powered forges, blast furnaces, helve or other hammers.
A site where iron is smelted or iron goods made.
A factory used for the production of red lead used in glass manufacture, or white lead used as the pigment in white paint.
A marker stone showing the extent of a measure of land containing a vein of ore.
A factory where nails are manufactured.
A mill or works where needles were manufactured.
A building or site used for the manufacture of small arms and artillery pieces, etc.
When secondary product use with major product and MINE, eg. COPPER MINE.
Term for ore store/ore hopper, used particularly in Yorkshire and Derbyshire.
A stone-lined pit or tank, sometimes circular,  for concentrating ores by sedimentation.
Building or structure housing a buddle.
Where several minerals produced, use with other products and MINE, eg. ARSENIC MINE.
An area used for crushing mineral ore or stone. Often includes mechanically powered ore crushers.
A place where gold ore is extracted.
A mine for the extraction of iron ore.
A mine used for the extraction on tin bearing ore.
A small dwelling providing living accommodation for a tin miner.
A place where gold is worked into articles or products.
Large open hearth furnace often located inside a brick cone for use in steelmaking.
A furnace for smelting ore in which the fuel and ore are mixed.
A reverberatory furnace used for forging wrought iron from pig iron using coal as fuel.
A furnace in which the flame is turned back over the substance to be heated.
A hearth used for the reheating of metal slag to extract further metal.
A factory where glue is produced.
Machinery for raising and lowering men and equipment to and from the surface of a mine.
A site used for the production of items derived from animal horns.
A kiln for roasting ore.
A type of calcining kiln used in arsenic manufacture.
A pit, sometimes found close to a church or cathedral, where bells were cast in medieval times.
A building containing a small stone cylindrical furnace, eg. used for tin smelting in Cornwall.
A place where boats are built and stored.
A brass manufacturing complex incorporating battery mill furnaces, hammers, etc.
A building used for drilling out the bores of cannon and other military pieces.
A factory where cars are manufactured.
A site or establishment for the casting and refining of metallic copper.
A factory or works used for the forging and sharpening of a variety of tools including scythes, spades, etc.
Any factory or site using machine tools in a manufacturing or processing capacity.
Reheating of iron from a finery, for rolling or slitting.
A workshop or factory where bronze articles are made by casting molten metal into moulds.
A type of malt house.
A building used to smoke fish or meat.
A sugar factory.
For chemical processes making nylon, rayon, etc.
A works where bleach is manufactured.
Bleach works or bleach house for bleaching of textiles, etc.
A building or buildings used for the manufacture of candles.
A site used for the manufacture of gunpowder.
A building or buildings used for the production of paints, varnishes, colours and distemper.
A structure used to dry peat on.
A factory for the production of plastics by chemical processes.
A mine yielding rock salt.
A pit dug for the extraction of brine.
A building or buildings where soap is manufactured.
A site where tar is manufactured or combined with other substances to produce bitumen, for example.
A building or buildings used for the manufacture of all types of wax.
For reheating of worked metal or glass to make it malleable or to harden it after use for toolmaking, etc.
A furnace where metal is manufactured from ore.
An early form of lead furnace, set upon a hilltop or crest to utilize winds in smelting.
A structure in which pottery tiles were baked.
A works, including an extractive site, producing a clay of high plasticity and firmness, used as a basic raw material for porcelain.
A place of worship for Unitarians, a movement which does not believe in the Trinity but only in the Unity of Christ. Christ was to them just an exalted human teacher.
Use CANNON and SCRAP METAL if necessary.
This is the top term for the thesaurus.
A metallic alloy of iron, carbon and silicon formed by casting in a mould.
Soft limestone consisting almost entirely of calcite.
Tabelware manufactured from china clay.
Powdered coal.
Oil obtained from the flesh of the coconut and used in ointments, soaps etc.
A fuel derived by dry distillation from coal.
A reddish metal used in alloys, coins and the construction and electronics industries.
A calcareous, hard substance, the external skeleton of marine polyps, used in the manufacture of jewellery.
A light, buoyant material obtained from the cork oak. Cork is used in floats and as stoppers for bottles.
The seed of a cereal plant used in the manufacture of foodstuffs.
The white, fibrous substance surrounding the seeds of plants of the genus Gossypium, which can be spun and used in the manufacture of thread and cloth or used in its raw form as wadding or packing.
Unrefined oil used in the manufacture of petroleum.
Timber manufactured from fir or spruce trees.
An oil based derivative used as a fuel in diesel engines.
Wood which is used as fuel for fires.
Oil manufactured from fish.
Includes raw and processed.
Movable, usually functional, articles normally found in the home.
Supplies owned by, or for the use of, the government.
Boulders of unprocessed granite.
Small fragments of granite.
Wood from non-coniferous trees, eg. oak, known for their hardness.
Fish of the family Clupeidae, common to the North Atlantic. They are caught for food.
Animal skins, either raw or dressed which are used in the tanning industry to produce leather.
Large mammals, domesticated for riding and as draught animals.
Goods, including portable objects and furniture, commonly found in the home.
A dark blue powder, obtained from plants or synthetically manufactured, used as a dye.
Double-key with object material.
Solid bars made from pure iron.
Ore containing high proportions of Iron.
Stones used to edge a pavement or raised path.
Citrus fruit of a distinctive yellow colour.
The heartwood of a leguminous tree from which an extract is obtained. The extract being used for dyeing.
A cereal, yellow in colour, the grains of which are embedded in a core known as the cob.
Blocks cut from marble.
Personnel serving with one of the three armed forces - army, navy or air force.
Draught animals produced by mating asses and horses.
Military weapons, amunition and stores.
A flammable liquid that occurs naturally and is also now distilled.
Goods and equipment used to supply a navy.
A fertilizer containing nitrogen, derived from sodium nitrate.
A seed or fruit with a hard shell, often edible or used to produce oils.
The wood from trees of the type Quercus.
Ground oats used as food, often in the form of porridge.
Oil produced from the pulp of olives.
A mollusc usually used as a foodstuff.
A solid material which is combustible distilled from petroleum.
A pungent condiment manufactured from the dried berries of the plant Piper Nigrum. Use for cargoes of peppercorns or ground pepper.
Small hand-held firearms.
A large block of wood used to support the roof of a mine.
Products manufactured from plant materials.
A bitter beer brewed using charred or browned malt.
Small, marine crustaceans are used as food.
Cotton which has not been processed.
Waste material.
An alcoholic spirit distilled from sugar products, especially molasses.
A cereal used to make spirits, beer and coarse bread.
A mineral, Sodium Chloride, obtained by mining or the evaporation of brine used as a seasoning and for preserving food.
Fragments of wrought or cast iron broken up for reprocessing.
Fragments of metal broken up and set aside for reprocessing.
The grains of various plants from which new plants grown.
Medium-sized animals domesticated for their wool, skin, meat and milk.
Aquatic invertebrate animals whose outer covering is a shell, often 'farmed' to be eaten. Includes molluscs and crustaceans.
Missiles, such as cannon balls and musket balls, designed to be discharged from a gun or cannon using an explosive propellant.
Solid bars or ingots of silver.
Ammunition manufactured for use in hand held firearms.
Solid bars made from steel.
Products manufactured from stone.
Works producing a refractory clay, kaolin. An essential raw material of porcelain and some types of papermaking.
A factory where china products are manufactured.
For the production of clay tobacco pipes.
A mill for crushing flint. Crushed flint was used in the manufacture of pottery in order to whiten and strengthen the body of earthenware pottery.
A complex of buildings used for the manufacture of pottery.
A group of buildings or works where the evaporation and crystallization of sodium aluminium sulphate solution is performed.
A bell-shaped pit used in early coal mining. Use with functional type if known, eg. COAL WORKINGS.
A site where coal is processed.
The name of a class of excavations, found in chalk formations in England, consisting of a shaft sunk to the chalk, and there widening out into one or more chambers.
A pit for the extraction of fullers earth (a hydrous silicate of alumina), which was used for cleansing, and finishing, cloth and wool.
A site where iron ore is extracted.
A large pit formed by, and for, the extraction of iron ore.
A site where jet is extracted from the surface of the ground.
A place where lead ore is extracted from an open cast mine.
A ravine formed by using water to reveal or exploit a vein.
A pit from which marl, a mixture of clay and carbonate of lime, is excavated. Marl is used as a fertilizer.
A site where iron oxide and iron sulphates, used as brown pigments, are excavated.
An establishment or works where the distilling of spirits is carried out.
A stone or brick wall enclosing a park.
A straight road lined with trees along either side, also straight lines of trees found in parkland usually leading to a landscape feature.
Horizontal tunnel opening from the surface used for haulage or access to a mine. It can also be used for drainage.
A factory where aircraft are assembled.
A factory where brushes are manufactured. Use for all types of brush.
Pit for mixing raw materials with water in the preparation of a clay body.
A kiln or furnace for the firing of bricks.
An industrial manufacturing complex producing bricks.
A place from which chalk is extracted.
A place from which clay is extracted.
A kiln in which lime is made by calcining limestone or in some areas chalk.
A site where lime (calcium carbonate) is made.
A site incorporating all of the production processes for the manufacture of plaster.
A place where gypsum is extracted.
A place where sandstone is excavated.
A site where slate is quarried from the ground.
A site used for the small scale extraction and working of surface boulders.
A settlement site enclosed within a timber palisade.
A group of related buildings, primarily with a domestic function, which is arranged along a principle axis such as a main road or routeway.

Use both terms.
A settlement, usually enclosed, on a sloping hillside containing a number of oval or circular scopped house floors separated by walls or unexcavated ridges.
Underground chambers and stone passages of Iron Age date found in South West England.
A parcel of land.
A settlement without any obvious evidence for a boundary. Use specific type where known.
A turret, tower or look out occupying a prominent position to provide a view, either a separate building, or part of a villa.
An artificial fall of water often taking the form of a water staircase.
A fountain erected specifically to supply drinking water.
Temporary settlement relating to the construction of railways, viaducts, dams, etc.
A stone or brick wall either in, or enclosing, a garden.
Small building in which labourers, such as miners and tin workers. They are also associated with gardens where they provide on-site accommodation for gardeners and estate workers.
A small building in which game is hung up and kept cool.

A timber building based around a sunken hollow, the floor of which may have been suspended above the hollow to counteract dampness. Grubenhauser are believed to date from the 5th to 8th centuries AD but may be earlier. Use Grubenhauser as plural.
Residences of religious people and members of the clergy.
The official residence of a bishop.
A residence for all clergy having the sole or subordinate charge of a living.
The official residence of a dean.
The residence of a priest.
The residence of a vicar, parson or rector.
The rural residence of a country gentleman.
The principal house of a manor or village.
This is the top term for the class. See COMMUNICATIONS Class List for narrow terms.
A room used by those who have to wait at railway or bus stations, etc.
An open sided building known to have been used for sheltering cattle.
A rough shelter or dwelling, sometimes used to house cattle.
A canopy or building to cover the platforms in a railway station.
A hotel adjacent to a railway terminus. Railway hotels were often owned by a railway company.
A shaft designed to allow for the adequate circulation of air through a transport tunnel, for example.
Small discreet rural settlements which do not provide the commercial, legal or ecclesiastical services typically found within medieval urban areas.
An early form of railway for the transportation of freight by wagons on rails on a road.
An enclosing structure composed of bricks, stones or similar materials, laid in courses. Use specific type where known.
A medieval house with central open hall and two storey bays, jettied at first floor level, on either side.
A factory where metal wire is manufactured.
A factory where short wool was spun into woollen yarn to produce cloth.
Usually a complex of buildings for the processing of raw materials. Use specific type where known.
A factory where worsted, a well-twisted woollen yarn made from long staple wool and used in the manufacture of suits and other garments, was produced.
A mine used for the extraction of zinc bearing ore. Use with other metal ores extracted and MINE where necessary, eg. LEAD MINE.
A windmill with a rotating cap containing the windshaft, and a stationary body in the form of a tower.
A fortified wall surrounding a town or city.
The line of a flat rod system transmitting power from an engine or waterwheel.
This is the top term for the class. See TRANSPORT Class List for narrow terms.
Trees planted in an ornamental circle. For earthwork surrounding trees use TREE ENCLOSURE RING.
An abbey or priory of the Trinitarian brethren also named Maturins.
Use both terms.
A mine used for the extraction of tungsten bearing ore. Use with other mineral ores extracted and MINE, eg. TIN MINE.
An underground channel with a vaulted roof. Use specific type where known.
This is the top term for the class. This class includes terms with very broad definitions which could be assigned to three or more classes. See UNASSIGNED Class List for narrow terms.
A vault or crypt under a church or chapel. Use wider site type where known.
A monastic cattle ranch with associated buildings, paddocks and pastures.
A type of windlass for drawing up ore.
A natural flow or current of water issuing from a source.
A construction of unknown function, either extant or implied by archaeological evidence. If known, use more specific type.
A factory where tapestries were manufactured.
Use for places of worship. For later landscape features use, eg. GARDEN TEMPLE.
A house in a line of houses attached to and adjoining one another and planned and built as one unit.
A barn usually containing a single, central threshing floor.
A type of WATERMILL, powered by retaining seawater at high tide and then releasing it at low tide via the water wheel.
A mill used for the processing of tin ore by crazing, stamping or smelting.

Use both terms.

A marker of some form used to delineate a route, especially ones associated with pilgrimages.

Use both terms.
Unclassifiable site with minimal information. Specify site type wherever possible.
Use specific type of site where known.
A site where ores are smelted. Use more specific site type where known.
A windmill with a stationary timber body which contains the grinding machinery, and which supports a rotating cap in which the sails rotate.
A large, luxuriously appointed building used as an official residence by a member of royalty.
The residence of a miller, often attached to a mill.
A dwelling built on marshy, boggy or waterlogged land using timber piles driven vertically into the ground to raise the floor above the ground to prevent flooding.
A refuse heap.
A house for storing or drying saddles.
A small concentration of dwellings.
A fortified building or site with purpose built emplacements for artillery pieces.
A small enclosure built onto the perimeter of a Roman fortress or fort.
A manor house, which was granted a royal licence to crenellate.
A free standing small turf and timber fortlet, situated every Roman mile along Hadrian's Wall.
A major fortified place, often a town, capable of containing a large force. If Roman use LEGIONARY FORTRESS.
A building used for the accommodation of a military guard and/or the detainment of prisoners.
A sunken arena used by the Romans for training cavalry horses and recruits.
A substantial bank and ditch forming a major boundary between two adjacent landholdings. Most date from the late Bronze Age and Iron Age.
A building in which a supply of arms, ammunition and provisions for an army is stored.
A place in which gunpowder and other explosives are stored in large quantities.
A building or group of buildings, often surrounded by a system of fortifications, used as a residential and training site by members of an armed force.
An enclosure of stakes driven into the ground, sometimes for defensive purposes.
A prison site for the containment of servicemen captured in war.
A permanently occupied position or building designed primarily for defence.
A pit containing burnt ashes.
A place in which the artillery is encamped or collected together.
A fortified tower designed to house a number of artillery pieces and a small garrison. Artillery towers first appear in England in the 16th century.
Any earthworks, walling, bastion or fortified outwork, or combination of these, generally with ditch or moat.
A target range used for rifle and small arms practice and recreational purposes.

A stone commemorating the date of a specific event.

A tree named after a person or event associated with it, e.g. Byron's Oak at Newstead.
A large free-standing arch erected to commemorate a triumph or victory.

A cheap eating and drinking establishment usually serving snacks and non-alcoholic drinks.

A hiding place for stores, often underground, used by smugglers.
A fortified tower found at the angle of a castle wall.
A place where weapons are kept.

Where plan refers to layout (eg. grid) rather than ideological concept (eg. Chartist land Colony).
Unspecified. Use specific type where known.
A civic building housing fire engines and a permanent fire-fighting force.
A public institution for the care and protection of children without parents.
A building in which a judicial court is held.
A pond used for the punishment, by ducking in water, of offenders.
A natural or man-made earth mound on which a gallows was erected.
An elevated platform on which a criminal is executed.
A post set up, to which offenders were tied to be whipped.
A type of Roman lodging house, frequently sited near the town gate.
A place where money is coined under public authority.
A site with one or more defensive earthworks, often at a river crossing incorporating natural features which define parts of the curtilage.
The limit line of a parish.
A district, suburb or quarter of a town or village adjacent to a fort, with the lowest legal status accorded to a built up area.
The field or area of ground on which a battle or skirmish was fought.
An inscribed marker stone found on Hadrian's Wall.
Use both terms.
Includes crests, hatchments and supporters.
Use both terms.
An earthen bank indicating the limit of a wood or coppice
A pen, often circular and stone-walled, for rounding up livestock.
An area used for the breeding and rearing of rabbits.
A refuse heap of discarded shells.
A pound for the accommodation of livestock.
A pit where grain is stored.
A pen for holding sheep waiting to be washed.
This is the top term for the class. See CIVIL Class List for narrow terms.
An Anglo-Saxon fortified town or other defended site, not necessarily urban.
House owned by the church, often used for meetings.
Civil building in Cornwall and Devon for assay and sale of tin ingots.
A box in which letters are posted or deposited for dispatch.
A signal station incorporating equipment for visually conveying coded communications.
This is the top term for the class. See EDUCATION Class List for narrow terms.
An establishment, often forming part of a university, for higher or tertiary education.
A hall used for housing public displays.
An establishment in which people, usually children, are taught.
A school founded in or before the 16th century, for teaching Latin, later becoming a secondary school teaching languages, history, science, etc.
A pond used for the rearing, breeding, sorting and storing of fish.
A house or range of buildings in which dogs are kept, eg. hunting hounds.
A free-standing building with enough space to hang and dry nets.
An enclosed piece of land adjoining a house.
Manmade marks or earthworks which provide evidence for agricultural cultivation.
The subsoil traces of cultivation, presumed to have been caused by the use of a plough to till the soil.
Narrow ridges representing the surviving surface traces of later prehistoric cultivation.
The limit line of a field.
A ridge and furrow produced by a plough drawn between two steam engined vehicles, or a steam engined vehicle and a moveable windlass, standing on opposite headlands.
A group or complex of fields which appear to form a coherent whole. Use more specific type where known.
A field system which appears to have developed in an organic, or piecemeal, fashion over time.
A system of individually enclosed fields.
A piece of land used for the cultivation of hops.
Areas used for potato-growing.
An area of land consisting of the lord's demesne and of lands from whose holders he may exact certain fees, etc.
An enclosure used for the cultivation of fruit trees.
An earthen bank indicating the limit of a plantation.
A building used for an agricultural and/or subsistence purpose. Use more specific type where known.
A building where animals are slaughtered.
This is the top term for the class. See AGRICULTURE AND SUBSISTENCE Class List for narrow terms.
A HORSE GIN used for domestic cider manufacture, especially on farms.
A mill for grinding corn. Use with power type where known.
A building used to accommodate ducks.
The main dwelling-house of a farm, it can be either detached from or attached to the working buildings.
A building, or first-floor room in a building, for the dry and secure storage of grain after it has been threshed and winnowed.
A structure providing accommodation for poultry.
A building providing shelter for sheep and storage for fodder and shepherding equipment.
A place of worship for followers of the Pentecost (ie. emphasising the gifts of the Holy Spirit).

A building with a range of facilities for the exclusive use of its all-male membership. Rooms were often provided as offices or short term accommodation, and the club could be used for business or social gatherings.
A factory or group of buildings used for the production of plated goods. Plating is the process whereby one metal object is coated with a thin layer of another metal.
An artificial area of open water, situated on a river, enclosed by masonry and fitted with dock gates in which ships can be repaired, loaded/unloaded or berthed.
This is the top term for the class. See INDUSTRIAL Class List for narrow terms.
An area or defined space believed to have been used for trades and/or manufacturing activity. Only use when evidence for more specific site type is lacking.
A building, usually containing several dormitories, used as a cheap, short term residence. Use more specific term if known.
A Prehistoric monument type in South West England in which a natural boulder is surrounded by a man-made kerb of stones.
Small settlement with no ecclesiastical or lay administrative function.
A factory where hemp, the woody stalk of the hemp plant, used for the making of coarse cloth and cordage, was processed.
A substantial area of ground surrounded by slight univallate earthwork often interpreted as stock enclosures or as sites where agricultural produce was stored.
An establishment providing care for the terminally ill.
A building used for the care of the sick. Only to be used where part of a complex, eg. a workhouse. In such cases use with appropriate monument type.
An institution for the imprisonment of vagrants and misdemeanants.
A house consisting of a public hall with private living accommodation attached. Built from the medieval period onwards.
An abbey or priory of Gilbertine Nuns.
Use PRIORY and GILBERTINE DOUBLE HOUSE or GILBERTINE MONASTERY.
Use both terms.
A conical brick structure in which glass articles were made.
A building made chiefly of glass, used to grow plants and fruit in. Use more specific type where possible.
A building or structure for the storage of processed minerals, chemicals or agricultural products, etc. Use more specific type where known.
Use both terms.

An outlying farm or estate, usually belonging to a religious order or feudal lord. Specifically related to core buildings and structures associated with monastic land holding. Use specific term where known.
A deep gutter, drain or sink.
A large, level structure, usually of stone or timber, built alongside water to allow warships to moor for the loading and unloading of guns.
If not domestic use specific type, eg. CHURCH HALL.
A priory of Gilbertine double order of nuns and canons.
Houses specifically for men and of chiefly mendicant religious orders. The status of priory is represented in several friaries. Use with PRIORY if required.

TERM: FRIARY OF FRIARS OF THE SACK
SCOPE_NOTE: A friary belonging to the Friars of the Sack also known as Friars of Penance or Penitentia.
Site types normally or frequently associated with burials which in some instances may have had solely religious or ritual functions.
An institution for the imprisonment of felons and debtors.
A small latrine or toilet, usually built into the thickness of the wall of a castle or great house, with the waste dropping into a cess pit or straight to the outside.
Enclosed ground. Use either FISH GARTH or ENCLOSURE as appropriate.
A movable stucture which enables or prevents entrance to be gained. Usually situated in a wall or similar barrier and supported by gate posts.
A substantial structure supporting or surrounding a gate. May be ornate or monumental, and have associated structures such as lodges, tollbooths, guard houses etc.
An abbey of Franciscan nuns also known as Minoresses or Poor Clares.
A passageway, duct or pipe use for the conveyance of heat, gasses, smoke or air.

A recess in a stone or brick wall, usually bounding a garden or orchard, set two to three feet from the ground and facing south to south-east to catch the morning sun, in which a bee skep/beehive is placed. Often found in groupings of three to six.
A garden in which bees are kept.
A wall built to give shelter to sheep.
A press used to extract the juice from apples, which was then used to make cider.
A building, site or structure associated with the hunting of animals.
An enclosure used for corralling deer.
A building used to shelter deer hunters.
An area where fish are naturally present, eg. part of a river.
An enclosure on a river or seashore for preserving fish or for catching them easily.
A device for catching fish, sometimes a fence or enclosure of stakes made in a river, harbour, etc.
An outbuilding containing brewing equipment, as opposed to a large commercial BREWERY. Often found in conjunction with public houses, country houses etc.
A mill whose machinery is driven by water.
A pier of brick, masonry, etc, to which the hinges of a gate are attached.
A narrow bridge for people and animals to cross on foot.
A building in which goods or items are stored. Use more specific type where known.
A workshop in which textile fibres were spun into yarn by hand.
Includes some structures that are not strictly buildings. Use a more specific term where possible.
Use only for buildings which house motor vehicles. Includes garages for vehicle repair. For petrol sales use PETROL STATION.
The residence of a lock-keeper.
A self-service dining room, especially for workers/employees; also in institutions, such as schools, hospitals, etc.
A textile-weaving factory housing powerlooms; commonly a one-storeyed shed with wide, north-light roof carried on iron columns.
An isolated barn, cow house or shelter shed with a hayloft. Typically found in areas where farmsteads and fields were sited at a long distance from each other.
A row of balusters, usually made of stone, surmounted by a rail or coping.
A figurative or abstract design in the round or in relief, made by chiselling stone, carving wood, modelling clay, casting metal, or similar processes.
A wall between two towers or pavilions, usually surrounding a building, and often forming a major part of the defences.
A building used to accommodate elephants at a zoo or wildlife park.
A type of clothier's house, consisting of TOPSHOP and dwelling, used for hand-weaving of textiles.
A building combining a cow-house with crop storage space.
A cottage for workers on a country house estate.
Use both terms.
A specially built building where facilities exist for the playing of a variety of sports.
A covered arcade, often attached to a building, open on one or more sides.
A garden surrounded by a substantial wall.
A small body of water, either natural or artificial.
A laithe with an attached house.
A loft over a stable or barn used for storing hay.
A structure, partly underground, for the preservation of ice for use during warmer weather.
A building in which cows are milked.
An area within a building (usually the barn or stable) for storing husks from the grain crop (chaff) for animal feed after it has been threshed and winnowed in the barn.
A room or building in which riding tackle is stored.
A point of public water supply, including conduits, fountains, wells, pumps and standpipes.
A building, group of buildings or installation in which scientific experiments are carried out.
A building appropriated by a school for the purpose of teaching pupils.
A refreshment house in a public park or country house garden.
A room or part of a church where the vestments, vessels and records are kept.
A house for the keeper of a level crossing on a railway.
A building in which animals are housed. For non agricultural use see ANIMAL HOUSE and narrow terms in RECREATIONAL class.
A room in a library or institution providing periodicals, newspapers, etc.
A building where clothes are washed.
A hilltop enclosure bounded by a double line of ramparts.
A group of buildings or rooms equipped with apparatus for scientific experiments or other research, testing and investigations.
A fortress and dwelling, usually medieval in origin, and often consisting of a keep, curtain wall and towers etc.
A piece of ground over which small arms or large artillery may be fired at targets. For rocket and missile firing use ROCKET TEST FACILITY.
A hostel owned by a Christian association which provides cheap accommodation for young people.
A library for use of the public.
A large, fortified permanent Roman military base, made of timber and stone, surrounded by a rampart and ditches.
A place where hops are stored.
A place of worship for the believers of spiritualism: The belief that the spirits of the dead can somehow manifest themselves and speak with the living.

A complex of buildings, often within an enclosure, housing a pre-Benedictine Reform secular religious community. Now commonly used to describe the main church within such a complex, which over time attained higher status.
A factory or building where furniture is upholstered.
A large, circular hollow, often with a platform and seating built into the sides, used for preaching.

A circular bank in which trees have been planted for ornamental purposes or to create an enclosure. May exist purely as a bank which has been formed over the stumps of the trees which had been planted to form the enclosure.
A site, including buildings and structures, from which communication signals are transmitted.
For broadcast radio programmes use BROADCASTING TRANSMITTER, for radar transmissions use TRANSMITTER SITE.

A building used for the preparatory processes in which long and short staple flax fibres were separated by passing through combs. Flax dressing or 'heckling' shops may be located both on and off mill sites.
A workshop in which carded wool was passed through heated combs to straighten and separate the long and short fibres prior to spinning. Associated with the worsted branch of the textile industry.
A mill in which textile rags were ground, either to enable the fibres to be respun or to use the pulp in the manufacture of paper.
The sorting department of a paper factory.
A building, usually in a rural setting, with a range of facilities for the use of members.
A dockyard crane permanently mounted on a lighter.
A floating bridge, generally temporary, whose decks are supported on low flat-bottomed or hollow floats.
A small building housing a mechanism used for winding a cable.
A building or site from which a lookout can be kept.
A type of 18th century public park, with refreshment houses, concert rooms, etc.
Use specific site type, eg. KILL SITE, where known.
A brick, stone or iron receptacle for baking bread or other food in.

A small, defended settlement dating to the Early Iron Age, located on spurs, promontories or hilltops. The defences are marked by single or double trenches which originally held substantial palisades.
A factory where paper is made. Use with power type where known.
A way made for pedestrians, especially one merely made by walking (often not specially constructed).
A path running by the side of a canal or navigable river for use in towing vessels.
A path or road for pedestrians, laid or beaten in with stones or other materials.
A small enclosure for cattle, sheep, swine, poultry, etc. Use more specific type where known.
A mound in excess of 150 metres in diameter, of Late Neolithic date and presumed ritual function, eg. Silbury Hill.
Hillslope forts with wide spaced ramparts.
A building or room, purpose built for the teaching, rehearsing and playing of music.
Use only for natural features mistakenly assumed to be archaeological or natural features with archaeological significance.

Use to identify a feature, previously thought to be a monument but now disproved, or to avoid erroneous identification as a monument in future. Where a feature is regarded as an antiquity, but is unclassified, use SITE.
Also use with other metal ores extracted and MINE where relevant.
Houses specifically of nuns/canonesses or religious women.
Component. Use specific type of religious house where known.
A factory used for processing raw materials. Use more specific mill type where known. See also TEXTILE MILL, for more narrow terms.
An excavation made in the earth for the purpose of digging out metallic ores, coal, salt, or precious stones etc. Use specific type where known.
A building found at the site of a mine. Use specific type where known.
A wide ditch surrounding a building, usually filled with water. Use for moated sites, not defensive moats. Use with relevant site type where known, eg. MANOR HOUSE, GARDEN, etc.
A building or room where food is prepared and cooked.
A stone or platform on which lumps of ore are manually broken up.
A hole dug in the ground to act as a, usually temporary, communal toilet facility.
