Use with form of extraction where known. Also use MINE and other ores extracted where relevant, eg. SILVER MINE.
Use both terms.
Use Roman in a period field.
A box in which letters are deposited on delivery.

A late 17th - early 18th century house with a central chimney and fireplaces and a central door on the front; this door opened closely against the fireplaces, leaving a small lobby for access to the rooms.
A furnace or oven for burning, baking or drying. Use specific type where known.
A prison used for temporary detention. The typical village lock-up was a one-storeyed, one-celled building, sometimes of round or polygonal plan.
A small-scale railway, often for the transportation of children at a place of recreation.
An open-sided building known to have been used for sheltering animals other than cattle.
A canal built as a military obstacle, but also used for the transport of military stores, equipment and personnel.
A building or wing of a large house in which the servants would live and carry out some of their duties.
A school in which instruction is given on a Sunday, especially such a school for children connected with a parish or congregation.
A multi-purpose, two-storey barn, built on a hillside with entrances at both levels to a first floor threshing barn and ground floor animal housing.
Use both terms.
A residential district planned as a unit.
A church built within the bounds of a parish for the attendance of those who cannot reach the parish church conveniently.
A two storied open fronted structure comprising a cattle or cart shelter on the ground floor with a hayloft above. Most common in South West England.
Central functional building of a gas works. Coal is roasted in retorts producing gas and coke.
A place of worship at the site of a mortuary.
A prison for the confinement of people who owe money.
A place where (young) holiday-makers and hikers can be put up cheaply for the night.
A building used for storing tree bark.
The residence of a ferrykeeper.
A separate compartment for livestock in which they are free to move about.
A school established by a charity.
A small house or cottage at the entrance to a cemetery, usually occupied by a caretaker or gardener, etc.
Originally built as a family house. Converted into flats during the 19th or 20th century.
A farm building in which cattle are housed before slaughter.
Engine driving a continuous wire rope for the haulage of tubs in a mine and at the heapstead.
A building housing an engine, usually with an attendant boiler house and chimney. Used for winding from a pit.
A building, usually one-storeyed, for dyeing cloth.
An apparatus for burning refuse to ashes.
Use for speculatively built 19th century "model dwellings", rather than those built by a philanthropic society.
A building used for the testing of weapons for quality, accuracy and explosive power.
A flanking tower, or projection from the main walls of a defensive work from which a garrison can defend the ground in front or on the flank.
A light, open structure for the sale of newspapers, tickets, etc.
Machinery for raising and lowering men and materials to and from the surface of a mine.
Purpose-built housing for railway workers.
A storehouse in 16th and 17th century houses.
Industrial worker's house which has been purpose built by an employer, as opposed to the workshop houses used by artisans.
A site where vinegar is manufactured from soured beer, wine or cider.
A small gateway cut through the curtain wall or its flanking towers. Used primarily as an outlet for counter-attacking forces.
A place of worship within the grounds of a cemetery.
A castle built on a simple, rectangular plan, usually with a tower at each corner. This design became common in England after 1300.
Originally, a house of higher social status in a town or port, often with a storage cellar.
A Norman keep, in the form of a circular or polygonal enclosure surrounded by a wall.
A house built by a local authority.
A small building housing a lavatory.
A fortified house of two or three storeys, the lower floor being used to house animals and the upper for domestic use.
Unspecified landscape feature. Use more specific type where known.
The dwelling place of a farm worker.
A model village built in association with a factory, mill, railway, or any other industrial complex; usually built by the employer.
A hall built as a memorial to a particular person or event.
The residence of a canal worker.
A dwelling for the keeper of a canal wharf.
An office for the administration of town or country estates.
A type of GARDEN HOUSE, usually in the form of an open-fronted shelter with seat.
A 'through' BACK TO BACK HOUSE - an interlocking L-shaped plan gave each house two street frontages, thus providing better lighting/ventilation.
A building or room for the distribution of medicines, eg. in a hospital or clinic.
A special type of barn, lacking a threshing floor, usually with open walls, intended for the dry and well ventilated storage of hay only.
A house joined to another to form one building.
A structure in a garden used to house gardening implements, etc.
A room containing copper or steel vessels in which hops are added to the basic beer mixture.
A building used to house calves.
A vessel, usually made of stone, which contains the consecrated water for baptism. Use a broader monument type if possible.
A priory of double order of Fontevrault nuns and brethren.
Use both terms.
The rear part of a Roman fort, where  barrack accommodation, stables and stores were situated. Use with wider site type where known.
Use Roman in a period field.
A usually permanent defensive work. Use specific type where known.
Use Roman in a period field.
Where building foundation use specific site type where known.
Use both terms.
A friary belonging to the Franciscan order. Includes houses of both Friars Minor and Friars Observant or Capuchins.
A machine, powered by steam, gas, electricity or other energy source, which produces energy of movement. Use for stationary industrial engines rather than transport use.
Surface workings including shallow shafts, lode workings, open-pit methods and quarrying including some mines of stone, clays, compounds, etc. See also MINERAL EXTRACTION SITE.
A building or complex, housing powered machinery and employing a large workforce for manufacturing purposes. Use specific monument type where known.
A building or structure of unknown function found on a farm. Use more specific type where known.
Use both terms.
Military earthwork of unspecified type. Use specific site type where known.
A signpost, usually placed at a juntion or crossroads, bearing a number of individual signs radiating outward from the post to indicate locations in several directions.
A mill where flax is processed to make linen, thread and yarn.
This is the top term for the class. See DOMESTIC Class List for narrow terms.
An abbey or priory of Dominican nuns.
Use both terms.
A long, wooden, metal or stone vessel holding drinking water for horses.
A narrow, open container, usually where food or water for animals is put. Use specific type where known.
Places of residence.
Small stone hearth set up in a shallow pit. Burns vegetation and coppiced twigs to produce potash.
A small settlement, usually consisting of one dwelling with ancillary buildings.
A cross erected by the side of the road.
A form of inhumation in which the skeleton is interred, usually on its side, with hip and knee joints bent through an angle of more than 90 degrees.
Not a round barrow ploughed out at one end, but a specific type, the flat edge being additionally defined by stone slabs.
Not DENE HOLE.
This is the top term for the class. See DEFENCE Class List for narrow terms.
Use DYKE (DEFENCE), FLOOD DEFENCES or WATER CHANNEL as appropriate.
A form of inhumation in which the skeleton is interred, usually on its side, with the knees brought up against the chest. This is a more extreme form of crouched inhumation.
Use NUNNERY, DOUBLE HOUSE, MONASTERY or RELIGIOUS HOUSE. Use with order if known.
Use HEARTH or OVEN as appropriate.
A site where copper or copper based alloys are produced by smelting copper ore.
A place providing social, recreational, and educational facilities for a neighbourhood.
A purpose-built hall (usually 19th century) which was available for public hire and could be used for a variety of activities, eg. lectures, meetings, balls and concerts.
A purpose-built tenement. Use specific monument type where possible.
A large, usually unroofed building with tiers of seats for spectators built in various shapes and enclosing a field used for sports events.
An enclosure for the containment of a bull.
A building or structure to house railway wagons.
A university or college building set apart for residence or instruction of students. They can be located either on or off campus.
The residence of a prison governor.
A building, similar to a cart shed, but used to house traps, gigs and coaches.
Ancilliary buildings and structures associated with a military base.
A place used for the milking of cows.
Buildings, structures and sites for the training of military personnel.
Use both terms.
A building for the manufacture of condensed milk.
A building in which the fibres of new woollen cloth were raised by brushing with teazle heads.
A building licensed for the sale of beer.
Sites and structures for the transport of military personnel, vehicles and armaments.
A fortified structure used to protect civilians and military personnel from enemy bombing.
A site containing one or more artillery pieces and/or rocket launchers for firing at enemy aircraft.
A building used to store military equipment and ammunition.
A building or large scale site for the manufacture and/or storage of weapons, ammunition and equipment.
A temporary fieldwork, usually a few feet in height, constructed for defence against enemy forces.
A small house, usually on the estate of a country house, forming part of a widow's dower and intended as her residence.
A building containing a number of single roomed cells used for detaining prisoners.
A building used for meetings and other events by Scouts Associations.
A small building used as a shelter by a shepherd.
Sites, buildings and structures for the control and mounting of anti aircraft artillery. Also, structures for passive or indirect defence against enemy aircraft.
Use appropriate term.
A one-storey house.
The administrative office of a commercial concern.
A wall constructed for the purpose of confining or supporting a mass of earth or water.
A factory where carpets are manufactured.
Sites and buildings used in the coordination of the defence of the civilian population during times of war. Could also be used during times of national emergency.
Sites, buildings and structures for the defence of the coastline from sea and air invasion.
A place of worship for Roman Catholics.
Use both terms.
Sites and structures, often un-manned, intended to impede or confuse enemy forces.
Buildings, structures and sites directly associated with the operation of military airfields. See also AIR TRANSPORT SITE in the TRANSPORT Class.
Buildings, structures and sites for the detection of encroaching enemy forces.
Buildings and structures used for sending and receiving signals.
A building housing a variety of facilities, such as theatres, galleries, concert halls, etc.
A large self-service store selling foods and some household goods.
A piece of ice or a floor, often within a building, used for skating.
Building housing apparatus for testing chain links.
A workshop used for completing the shape of a product or part by turning on a lathe or wheel.
Engineering workshop housing specialized machinery such as lathes, presses, etc., for making machines.
Workshop for the construction and maintenance of boilers within an industrial complex.
An industrial site or building where the machinery is powered by a steam engine.
Workshop for the manufacture of master parts from working drawings which are then used as patterns for mass manufacture.
A steam whistle or siren used for signalling purposes.
Engineering workshop used for the final assembly of vehicles or structures from parts produced elsewhere in an engineering works.
A platform scale, flush with the road, for weighing vehicles, cattle, etc.
A building in which a sport is played. Use more specific type where known.
Use both terms.
Any church of the Anglican Communion.
A centre for the teaching of crafts.
A managed small wood or thicket of underwood grown to be periodically cut to encourage new growth providing smaller timber.
Subsidiary settlement of lay brothers attached to some Carthusian monasteries.
Mill for fine grinding of tin ore between millstones.
Use a more specific site type where known, eg. ENCLOSURE.
A free-standing structure, in the form of a cross (+), symbolizing the structure on which Jesus Christ was crucified and sacred to the Christian faith. Use specific type where known.
A churchyard or memorial cross set on a long shaft.
A small circular enclosure defined by a turf or earthern bank.
A rampart or other defensive entrenchment.
Use ABBEY and CISTERCIAN MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
An abbey or a priory of Cistercian nuns.
Use PRIORY and CISTERCIAN MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
A temporary kiln, in which the pots are stacked and baked in a pit underneath a bonfire.
A covered walk, walled on one side and usually arcaded on the other, surrounding or partly surrounding an open area in a monastery or similar complex of Christian buildings.
Use ABBEY and CLUNIAC MONASTERY or CLUNIAC NUNNERY.
Use PRIORY and CLUNIAC MONASTERY/NUNNERY.
An abbey or priory of Cluniac nuns.
A place where coal is mined.
This is the top term for the class. See COMMEMORATIVE Class List for narrow terms.
This is the top term for the class. See COMMERCIAL Class list for narrow terms.
A room or group of rooms usually below the ground level and usually under a building, often used for storing fuel, provisions or wines.
Use DOUBLE HOUSE, MONASTERY, NUNNERY   or RELIGIOUS HOUSE.
The building attached to a cathedral or collegiate church where the dean, prebendaries or monks and canons met for the transaction of business.
An area of flattened or compacted ground used for charcoal burning.
A monastic enclave dependent on a mother house.
Where secondary product use with major product and MINE, eg. LEAD MINE.
Textile mill producing calico, ie. coarse, unbleached cotton cloth.
A subsidiary form of preceptory provided with a chapel. Use specific type where known.
An artificial navigable waterway used for the transportation of goods. Nowadays also used for recreational purposes.
Use both terms.
The principal church of a diocese in which the cathedra or bishop's throne is to be found.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Small scale enterprise producing bricks but not at the same site as the extraction of clay.
Use both terms.
An abbey of the Bridgettine double order of nuns and religious men.
Use only where evidence is specific, ie. copper/tin alloy. For working of copper based alloys of unknown composition use COPPER WORKING SITE.
A structure with a roof to provide shelter from the weather for occupants or contents. Use specific type where known.
A castle surrounded by two or more lines of walled fortifications.
A building with shelves and/or stands for skeps or wooden hives, and flight holes through the walls for bees.
A type of GARDEN HOUSE situated on an island in a garden lake or canal or, more generally, by any waterside.
A building used for meetings and worship by a religious community trying to propogate its faith in an area.
A fortified site in which a gun, mortar or cannon is positioned.
Use with wider site type where known.
Stone for holding ox yokes.
A covered area used for the drying of animal hides.
A church established by a religious community to propogate its faith.
The carriage house or garage for a fire engine - especially those built by insurance companies or industrial concerns.
A structure, often movable, used as a platform for the display of a traders goods in a market.
Use both terms.
19th century school administered by a school board.
A hilltop enclosure bounded by one or more substantial banks, ramparts and ditches. Use more specific type where known.
The major tower of a fortification, often acting as its last defence.
An educational establishment where agricultural theory and practice is taught.
An artificial steep-sided earthen mound on, or in, which is set the principal tower of a castle.
An enclosed settlement surrounded by a single or double row of close-set timbers embedded in a foundation trench, without ditches or banks.
A chapel where Roman Catholics worship.
An establishment dedicated to the study of theology and religious training.
A school conducted by members of a convent.
A golf course, clubhouse and ancilliary buildings.
A house for drying wool after fulling and dying.
A building used to pump sewage from the sewers to the filter beds of a sewage works.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use with wider site type where known.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of children.
A building where nurses live.
Use both terms.
Use CHAPEL and ABBEY or PRIORY.
A path that is roofed over.
A large room with fixed seating, designed for lectures.
A specialist school for the teaching of blind people.
A place at a school where children receive medical advice, health checks and treatment.
A building or site used by the armed forces for the storage and issuing of military stores and materials.
A place provided for leisure-time activities of young people.
A barracks including stables and associated buildings housing a cavalry regiment.
A garden consisting primarily of rocks and rock plants.
A disused term for an establishment where deaf people receive education, training and social support. First set up in Edinburgh in 1760 as the Academy for the Deaf and Dumb.
A meeting place for freemasons.
Purpose-built lodgings for assize court judges. Early 19th century.
A college where the applied sciences and the mechanical arts are taught.
A building providing dining facilities and recreation for commissioned officers.
A room or a building set aside for infants and young children.
A craft or repair workshop in a boat yard, harbour or naval dockyard.
An often ornate wrought-iron bracket used to hang lamps outside public houses, shops, hotels and restaurants, etc.
A place where members of the British Legion meet.
A bishop's court for ecclesiastical causes and offences, formerly having wider jurisdiction in matters of moral discipline.
A room used for the display of merchandise for sale.
Use both terms.
A library which lends books (and sometimes other materials) to its members.
A field system with one prevailing axis of orientation, in which most field boundaries are either aligned with this axis or run at right angles to it.
A defensive enclosure created by constructing one or more lines of ramparts across a neck of land, in order to defend, or restrict access to, a spur or promontory, either inland or on the coast.
A low, hemispherical cairn surrounded by a freestanding, continuous circle of boulders.
Use appropriate term.
A large shop supplying many kinds of goods from various departments.
A mill used for the extraction and processing of starch.
A post box mounted in, or on, a wall.
A structure, into which a cart can be drawn, to enable it to be loaded from above.
A site, usually including hardstandings and associated buildings, used for the storage of military vehicles.
A mine used for the extraction of uranium bearing ores.
A site and associated buildings used by the military for various purposes. Use more specific term.
A disused term for a place where people who are physically disabled and/or have learning difficulties are cared for.
A post box mounted on a lamp post.
A site used for the production of items derived from animal bones.
An installation used for the storage of ammunition.
A pilotless aircraft armed with explosives and fuelled to stall over its intended target.
Jet-propelled, pilotless aircraft carrying a one-ton explosive warhead. Also known as the Fieseler FI-103, the V1 was nicknamed the doodlebug, or buzz bomb.
An area of hardstanding on which ammunition is stored.
The round seeds of the plant Pisum sativum which grow in pods and are eaten as a vegetable.
Conelike spikes of the hop plant used in the brewing industry to give a bitter flavour to beer and malt liquors.
Corrosive chemical compounds, usually liquids, which are neutralized by alkalis.
A cloth woven from flax.
The stem of the plant Zingiber officinale, with a characterisitc hot and peppery taste, used in cookery and medicine.
A pure starch obtained from the tubers of the plant Maranta arundinacea used in cookery as a thickening agent.
The hard, black, heavy wood of various tropical trees native to Africa and Asia, used in furniture manufacture and for making ornaments.
Unfermented wine.
A 19th century glasshouse built specifically for the fostering of camellias.
An 18th century garden building, designed in the style of a classical Ionic temple, used for standing or sitting in.
An 18th century garden building, designed in the form of a classical Doric temple, used for standing or sitting in.
A building used for the shelter and protection of deer, especially in winter.
A level space in a garden occupied by ornamental flower beds.
An often secluded garden set below the level of surrounding ground, usually surrounded with terraces.
A garden created within woodland where imported species such as camellias, magnolias and rhododendrons are grown.
A garden with one or more platforms with walks, often on different levels, usually close to the house.
Use both terms.
An airlike, fluid hydrocarbon suitable for burning to produce light, heat or power.
Sodium carbonate, usually derived from common salt, used for a variety of purposes including the manufacture of glass and soap.
Ore containing a high proportion of zinc.
Oil obtained from the liver of the cod, providing a rich source of vitamins A and D.
Pipes manufactured from iron and used for a variety of purposes.
Small seeds of the leguminous plant Lens culinaris, eaten in stews and soups.
A tower, consisting of one or several testing shafts, for testing lifts and for training personnel.
Workshop, as part of a gunpowder works complex, in which explosive is loaded into shells. Also used for expense magazine, where powder was stored between work processes.
Circular spoil heap surrounding a wide central depression, the entrance to a mine shaft.
A building used to coordinate movement of railway engines and rolling stock in the event of war.
Zinc, now mainly used for smelted zinc but has been used to include zinc ores.
A sulphate of aluminium and potassium used in the dyeing process as a mordant to increase the intake of dye into a cloth.
A waste product from smelting metal.
Beams of wood, iron, steel etc., used in the construction industry.
Explosive devices which produce spectacular visual effects when ignited.
A colourless, thick sweet liquid used in the manufacture of chemicals.
The powdery residue left after the combustion of substances, especially wood and paper.
Soft, damp soil.

Originally an area planted with evergreens or winter-flowering plants for winter display, they can also be large glasshouses built for public entertainment where the original purpose of displaying plants has either disappeared or been minimalised.
A wall in a flower or kitchen garden, containing conduits or pipes for heating the wall.
A lattice work bower or shady retreat covered with climbing plants.
A closely mown lawn used for the game of croquet.
A garden for the cultivation of herbs used for medicinal or culinary purposes.
A garden where woodland and meadow flowers grow in an apparently natural way.
An intricately designed garden in which ground coves, low shrubs or coloured earths are arranged in interlacing patterns resembling knots
Product of boiled blubber
Very fine particles of gold.
Calcium sulphate used as a fertilizer and for making plaster of Paris.
Sheets of iron or steel bent into a series of ridges and hollows to give added strength and rigidity.

A mill which ground clinker in the cement production process. During cement production a mixture of lime and clay is burnt which forms a clinker which is then ground into powder. When mixed with water it solidifies to hard cement.

The name given by the Allies during the Second World War to the German motor torpedo boat. E Boats carried two torpedo tubes and anti aircraft guns. They had a maximum speed of 39 knots and were considered superior to their Allied counterparts.
A centre attached to a prison where families and friends can visit with the inmates.
A multi-storey building in which individual blocks of flats cluster around a central service core.
A small house or a portion of a house used as a self-contained apartment.
A grass, used in paper making, native to Spain and North Africa.
A liquid derived from wood tar through a distillation process. Now used to describe timber preservative derived from coal tar.
Monument thought to be archaeological or historical but proved to be natural.

Monument either never or no longer visible above ground surface, but whose presence is indicated by proven below ground stratigraphy revealed by deliberate investigation, including geophysical survey, or other surface disturbance.
Man-made building, edifice or construction of assembled material parts.
Monument visible as a below ground man-made structure. Use for tunnels, mineworking, cellars, shelters.
Term derived from the 1993 Data Standard
A hoop or band of material put around a wheel to protect it and, when filled with air, to provide a more comfortable ride.
A cable laid under the surface of the sea, often on the seabed, for various purposes including telecommunications.
Floor cover in Roman time, where small cubes (tesserea) of one or more colours were laid in a geometric pattern.
Monument with a roof and walls or evidence of these.
A place where a product is given any finishing processes before being despatched to the user.
A type of warehouse, usually one-storeyed.
Use where the presence or nature of a monument is inferred from placenames or placename elements.
A place where vehicles can be filled up with petrol, oil, water, etc.
Matting manufactured using the fibres from the outer husks of coconuts.
A mill used for the manufacture of narrow strips of woven fabric used in the closing or fixing of garments, or for binding the edges of fabric goods.

A large communal room often occupying the full height of the building, used for functions such as meetings, entertainments etc. Traditionally found in medieval buildings but also found in later buildings emulating medieval architecture.
A factory used for the manufacture of screws.
Ore containing a high proportion of sulphur.
Ground and crushed bones used as a fertilizer.
A sulphide of copper and iron, reddish brown in colour.
Iron in the form of rails eg. for use in the construction of railways.
Hard iron ores
Clay used in the manufacture of fire bricks.
Buoys used to direct craft on water along the correct route or away from a hazard. Usually used in coastal areas.
Articles of value particularly those made with precious metals and precious stones, usually worn for adornment.

Accommodation used as an alternative to the workhouse following several Poor Law Acts. Modelled on continental examples and first erected at the end of the 1860s, it is based on the idea of a "village" of small houses accommodating a small group.
A residential establishment for the care and accommodation of children and young people.
Thin, rectangular tiles, usually made of wood, used for roofing.
Pipes manufactured from cast iron and used for a variety of purposes.
A sulphuric acid compound.
An artificial hill constructed in Tudor gardens, especially, to provide a good view.
A raised platform for the unloading of coal from waggons or other containers.
A room or building occupied by a person employed to keep accounts of workers' hours of labour.
An administrative building used by the official in charge of a dock or harbour.
A building with facilities for playing snooker.
A water-filled structure for experimental research.
The area surrounding a monastic house including conventual buildings, outbuildings, cemetery, fishponds, etc, usually marked out by a bank and/or ditch or precinct wall.
Worked pieces of stone. Use more specific type of stone where known.
A fibrous silicate mineral used to manufacture incombustible items.
Originally used to describe very strong, often thick, rope made of metal or hemp. Now can be used for protective flexible tubing encasing wires such as telephone wire.
A large building used for the storage of grain.
A store belonging to a cooperative society.
A road or way for riding on horseback within a park or estate.
Flats or houses first built by 19th century philanthropic societies as a model to encourage the development of approved working class housing.
A tall, metal structure erected as a support for electric power cables.
A shore establishment for the teaching of maritime theory and practical skills.
A building housing transformers to convert AC electricity supply for domestic use.
A place where military personnel parade, practice marching, assemble or muster for a march or any other special purpose.

An often squat building with thick, loopholed walls and a flat roof, designed to accommodate a variety of weapons, usually strategically positioned to cover a vulnerable point in a defensive system. Many were built to standardized designs.
A large scale works for cloth finishing processes.
A site in which one or more searchlights were positioned to locate enemy aircraft or surface vessels for the benefit of batteries and night fighter aircraft.
A temporary castle built to house and protect troops beseiging another castle or town.
Reinforced concrete blocks, walls or ditches designed to obstruct the progress of a tank or armoured vehicle.
Defensive fortifications such as ramparts, ditches and stone walls, built to defend a town or city.
Recovery and removal of grease (lanolin) from raw wool.
A fortified keep in the form of a tower, used as a last refuge or defence. If a component of a larger site, use KEEP.
A building or structure from which observation is kept of the approach of danger.
A large store where wool is stored.
A burial in which the body is placed in, or covered by a boat, which is then covered with earth. Use with barrow type where relevant.
A stone, slate, iron or wooden structure used to mark the site of a grave. Use only where evidence of the form is uncertain otherwise use more specific type.
An estate or manor of a subordinate community of the Knights of the Order of the Hospital of St John of Jerusalem. Includes the mother house, the Priory of St. John, Clerkenwell.
A stone on which Runes have been inscribed. Often used as memorials though not always associated with a burial.
Posts with hooks attached to allow drying new cloth to be stretched out between them.
A house or centre used for meditation, contemplation and/or prayer.
A building in which wool or cotton were beaten to clean and separate the fibres.
A complex of buildings used for the processing of metals. Use more specific type where known.
Shed for grinding rags, eg. for use in mungo and shoddy mills.
A building or structure in which processed cloth is dried.
The approximate location at which stray finds of artefacts were found. Index with object name.
Use most appropriate term.
An air raid shelter, designed to be placed in the garden. Made from prefabricated components, they were often semi-sunken and the structure then covered with soil for added protection.

The rarest of the recognized types of round barrow, consisting of a flat, wide circular mound, which may be surrounded by a ditch. They occur widely across southern England with a marked concentration in East and West Sussex.
A decoy site designed to simulate the flarepath lighting of permanent RAF stations, to lure attacking night bombers away from legitimate targets.
A decoy site designed to simulate permitted lighting, such as locomotives, furnaces and tramwire flashes, to lure attacking night bombers away from legitimate targets.

A type of prefabricated house erected, to 11 approved designs, as part of the Temporary Housing Programme, between 1944 and 1948. This scheme was devised to relieve the post-war housing shortage at a time when conventional materials were unavailable.
Finishing process for cloth, especially linen, running the cloth between heavy rollers.
A building constructed from prefabricated sections. Use more specific type where known.
A factory where food is preserved either by freezing, salting or pickling
A canal tunnel built with one or more integral towpaths
An instrument for gauging the amount of rain which has fallen over a stated period.
A building, group of buildings or installation in which experiments and observations are undertaken to gather and record information about the weather.
Engineering works dedicated solely to the manufacture and repair of boilers.

A building complex, usually including kennels and cages and built close to a port or airport, in which animals can be securely held, for a designated period, to ensure that they are not carrying any infectious diseases which could be spread to others.
An early form of railway for the transportation of freight by sleds.
A building in which pack animals could shelter.
A marker stone erected to indicate a claim to the rights, usually mineral, of an area.
A site where cobalt is mined
Steel in the form of rails eg. for use in the construction of railways.
Salt in its natural state
Pieces of material, usually decorated, used as standards, for signalling or for decoration. Often used as a symbol of a particular nation eg. the Union Flag of Great Britain.
Various seaweeds which are burnt to obtain the salts contained in their ashes, which are used in the manufacture of soap and glass.
A factory or works principally engaged in the manufacture of blasing or explosive gelatine.
A complex of purpose-built or adapted buildings used for the maintenance, storage, assembly and control of sea mines and minefields.
A warehouse, usually under the charge of CUSTOM HOUSE officials, in which goods were stored before the duty had been paid. Often found in dockyards, harbours, etc.
A market where fish is sold.
An often stately or ornate entrance to a railway tunnel.
A factory where seaplanes are manufactured.
Use both terms.
A roadside telephone box for use by motorists in need of assistance.
Used where an existing building is designated as the residence of an official.
Dry dock for the repair of ships.
A building in which textile rags are sorted according to fibre types.
A factory where fish are processed into food products.
Use for distinct structure on a large scale.
A storehouse using mechanical means of controlling temperature rather than ice or insulation.
A house used to accommodate camels, often found at a zoo or wildlife park.
A building used to accommodate hippopotami.
Complex of buildings and structures associated with the testing of jet engines.
A place for recreation with electronic game machines and gambling machines.
A large wooden gate, positioned at either end of a canal or river lock, equipped with sluices to let water through.
Covered area for making large engineered constructions such as sections of ships or bridges.

A lighthouse whose lantern is sufficiently low to be seen below low lying cloud. In locations where varying weather conditions occur a Low Light is usually accompanied by a HIGH LIGHT built alongside or nearby.
Steam engine, usually, driving a centrifugal fan to provide an air blast for a blast furnace.

A roughly circular monument featuring a low, more or less level platform of stones surrounded or retained by a low stone kerb. Some may feature a small central open area, thus resembling a ring cairn.
A building or buildings where explosives are manufactured.

Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production of pottery. Use only for sites where there is evidence of pottery manufacture but no specific monument, otherwise use more specific term.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
An official residence of an abbot during the summer months.
A place where abrasive mediums such as sand-paper and grinding wheels are manufactured.
A hospital which primarily cares for patients injured in accidents.
A building used for the collection and storage of electricity using large lead-acid batteries (accumulators).
A coke-filled tower used for the dissolving and neutralising of acid produced by alkali-making processes.
Use both terms.
A separate hospital building, or block of an asylum, where new arrivals were segregated from old inmates for a defined period. This system was developed from the mid-19th century onwards.
Religious establishment, founded in Somerset, where free love was practised.
A historic term for an institution caring for older, destitute women.
Small engineering works specialising in the production of items such as ploughs and threshing machinery.
A site for the sale or hire of agricultural machinery.
Sites used for the manufacture of aircraft.
A large metal pylon structure used to tether airships.
Use where the intervening arcade is closed but timber-framed.
A historic term for an institution offering care and accommodation for alcoholic women, an alternative to the workhouse for the destitute.
An alcoholic spirit distilled from malted barley or barley and maize or rye.
An amber like substance derived from pine or turpentine.
A brittle silvery metallic element used in the manufacture of many alloys.
An alloy, traditionally of tin and lead but now of tin, antimony and copper, used for domestic utensils.
A substance used to affect a human or animal by changing mental or physical states, particularly used in medicine.
Hair from the Angora goat
Animal skins which have the outer pelt of fur on them.
Mackerel which has been salted to preserve it.
Salmon which has been pickled in vinegar or brine to preserve it.
Canvas or similar fabric used for the manufacture of sails.
An alcoholic drink made from fermented apple juice.
For the disposal of town refuse. Some 19th century plants were linked to a power station. Later ones incorporate INCINERATORS, recycling facilities, etc.
A railway station or platform built specifically for the loading and unloading of goods.
A purpose built section of path linking two sections of a canal enabling a horse to be led over or around an obstacle such as a hill. Horse paths predate towpath tunnels.
A coastal battery designed for use in short range engagements with enemy vessels, minelayers, blockships ad torpedo craft.
A factory, or group of buildings, containing apparatus used to extract specific properties, e.g flavour or scent, from natural ingredients.
A school where Jewish children are educated.

A structure or building used in the manufacture of the explosive cordite. After the cordite had been pressed to extract moisture it was placed on racks within the stove prior to being taken to the reeling house for winding.
A building where mineral jelly was stored. Mineral jelly was used as a stabilizer in the manufacture of the explosive, cordite.
A type of bridge which has machinery and movable elements, eg. to allow vessels to pass.
A building or room, where business and/or administrative activities to do with the canals was conducted.
A bridge whose deck is directly supported from pylons by straight cables without vertical suspenders.
A building or set of rooms, primarily of the 18th century, in which social gatherings and balls were held.
A specialized form of truss bridge that extends or cantilevers from both sides of the pier, the inner 'arms' usually supporting a central span.
A movable bridge lifted at one end by chains or ropes either to stop traffic passing over it or to let traffic pass under it.
A bridge supported by large beams or girders, originally of wood or iron, now usually of steel or reinforced concrete.
A bridge whose deck is hung from above by large cables, chains or pinned iron or steel bars hanging from towers.
A bridge made up of many relatively small members joined together in a series of interconnecting triangles.
A bridge that incorporates a span that moves upwards vertically to provide a passageway for navigation.

A hole in the ground which has been created by driving or hammering an upright stake into the ground. As a feature of some archaeological sites they may often represent the only surviving evidence for the former presence of an above-ground structure.
A nunnery of nuns belonging to the Order of the Servants of the Blessed Virgin Mary or Servites.
A place where injured or endangered animals are kept and looked after.
Use both terms.
A place where ropes are made.

Nowadays a hospital block where patients suffering from psychiatric disorders receive medical and surgical treatment. Formerly a place where psychiatric patients were primarily segregated from other patients in a hospital.
A disused term for a hospital block where patients suffering from psychiatric disorders are treated and cared for. Previously a segregated area separate from other hospital patient wards.
The entrance to a tunnel. Use more specific type where known.
A building housing a number of power looms.
A place of worship for followers of the teachings of Martin Luther.
A coastal battery used for delivering fire at long distance thus forcing a warship threatening or bombarding shore installations to withdraw out of range.
An area of ground or water containing explosive mines.
A subterranean feature entered from a hillside, cliff face, etc. A cave may have been used for occupation, storage, burial, refuse, or as a hide-away. Index with site type or objects where known.
Specialized engineering workshop particularly for the production of marine engines or other large components of ships.
A sports pitch usually with a synthetic surface (ie. not grass).
A mill where long-staple hair, often from llamas, is made into yarn.
A concept dating in England from the second half of the 18th century, when hardy North American plants were relatively easy to obtain.
A place of worship and residence for Anglican nuns.
Including accommodation for animals, birds, reptiles and fish in captivity.
A stall where animals are kept individually.
A building, range of buildings or site, for the accommodation, rearing and/or treatment of animals, birds and fish, both wild and domestic.
An area within a hospital concerned with the care and medical treatment of expectant mothers.
A reinforced concrete block designed to obstruct the progress of a tank or armoured vehicle. Use more specific type where known.
When secondary product use with major product and MINE, eg. COPPER MINE.
An indoor market used for the sale of antique goods.
A road, sometimes raised as a causeway, which serves as an approach road to a building or bridge.
The residence and office of an archdeacon.
An educational establishment where the art and theory of building and construction is taught.
A building or site used for the manufacture, assembly and testing of weapons, explosives and associated military hardware.
A training establishment for gunnery personnel.
An apartment, usually with a north-light, used by artists.

TERM: Asylum For Aged And Decayed Freemasons

SCOPE_NOTE: A historic term for a charitable institution caring for destitute people with learning difficulties.
A type of public building common in the 18th and 19th century, serving as an educational and/or learned society institute.
A running track used for athletic practice and competition.
Building housing a form of early steam engine using steam at atmospheric pressure. Chiefly employed in mine pumping.
An engine house which used air pressure to power trains on the experimental atmospheric railways of the 1840s.
A brewing or baking house attached to a vernacular building, 16/17th century.
A terrace consisting of a double row of houses sharing a common back wall, characteristic of industrial cities in the North of England.
The horizontal beam on a lock gate.
A water-filled hole used for the disposal of aggregate originally used as ballast in ships.
A training school where ballet is taught.
A building used for fabricating balloon and airship envelopes.
Linear or curvilinear construction of earth, turf and stone, often, but not always accompanied by a ditch. Use specific type where known.
A cemetery for baptist followers.
Use for town gate only. For drinking venue use EATING AND DRINKING ESTABLISHMENT narrow terms.
A hairdressing establishment for men.
A house used by sea bathers.
Mill incorporating water-powered hammers for beating brass sheet, etc. into vessels, pots, etc.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
A steam engine with a horizontal beam connecting the piston and crank.
Use both terms.
A portable beehive, often made of straw.

A floating pier, comprised of a floating pierhead (SPUD) and a roadway resting on pontoons (BEETLES). The pierhead and roadway were capable of rising and falling with the tide enabling unloading of troops and equipment to occur at any state of the tide.
A floatable concrete vessel, numbers of which made up the main breakwater of the Mulberry Harbours used to secure beachheads during the allied invasion of Europe in June 1944.

A floating breakwater in the form of a hollow cruciform tube 200 ft long by 25 ft high. Bombardons were designed to reduce the height of waves and formed the outer breakwater of the Mulberry harbours.

A building within a gunpowder works complex, where the mill cake (pulverised and incorporated ingredients of gunpowder) was broken down. It was crushed or broken down by passing it between pairs of revolving gunmetal rollers in a breaking-down machine.

A building within the gunpowder works complex. During the gunpowder production process, the mill cake was broken down, pressed and then corned. The remaining dust was removed from the corned powder by tumbling it in gauze-covered revolving cylinders.
A chemical fertilizer made by treating powdered phosphate rock with sulphuric acid.
A burial site for animals.
A building or site for watching specific military activities or the movement of enemy forces, etc.
Usually distilled alcohollic drink but also used for liquids where a substance is in solution with alcohol.
A sparkling, white wine traditionally from the Champagne region of France. Now used, loosely, to refer to any sparkling white wine.
The seeds of the palm Phytelephas macrocarpa, the albumen of which, hardens resembling ivory in colour, texture and toughness and is used to make ornamental buttons etc.
A land based establishment armed with torpedoes and used to defend the coast from enemy shipping.
A long thin piece of wood,
A Palaeolithic or Mesolithic temporary site where there is evidence to suggest animal butchery. Evidence may include animal remains and a specialized tool assemblage.
A Palaeolithic or Mesolithic occupation site, excluding occupations of caves and rock shelters. Evidence for occupation may include traces of hearths and other structures.
The area beneath a natural overhang at the base of a cliff or crag. This may have been used for occupation, burial, etc. Index with site type where known.

A spatially discrete, though sometimes extensive, scatter of lithic artefacts recovered from the surface, eg. by fieldwalking, rather than from a particular archaeological context. Use particular types where appropriate.
An underground bomb-proof structure used as a command centre for military operations.
A double lock placed between tidal water and a canal, etc..
A pier where passsengers can embark and disembark and goods can be transferred to and from vessels.
A bridge which takes the towpath across the canal.
A high building at an airport from which air traffic is controlled by radio.
Use both terms.

A mound of fire-cracked stones, normally accompanied by a trough or pit which may have been lined with wood, stone or clay. Assumed to be locations where heated stones were used to boil water primarily for cooking purposes.
Use both terms.
A long ridge of earth, rocks or gravel primarily constructed to carry a roadway.

Generally rectangular structure normally used for burial purposes, and formed from stone slabs set on edge, and covered by one or more horizontal slabs or capstones. Cists may be built on the surface or sunk into the ground.
An island, partly or wholly artificial, built up by dumping timber, earth and stones onto a lake or river bed. Often revetted with timber piles or palisade.

A fairly regular system of small rectangular fields. Examples may date from the middle Bronze Age to the Roman period. The word 'Celtic' carries no chronological or cultural connotations in this context.
An engine used for directly winding up coal from deep mines, first used in the 18th century.
An underground tunnel which enables pedestrians to pass below a road, railway, etc, to reach a destination.
Building housing switch gear to control electricity supply either to the National Grid, industrial or domestic premises.
Use both terms.
A large building or structure where coal is washed, sized and graded before being sold.
A large structure, found at sports stadiums, from where television or radio broadcasts are made of the sporting events.
A large board found at sporting events, erected so as to be seen by the spectators, on which the score of a game is kept.
A building used for the storage of explosives of a non-military function, eg. mining explosives, signal explosivres etc.
The residence of a master shipwright.
A round or polygonal building containing a wheel turned by an ox to provide power.
A lodging for itinerant Irish labourers.
A large board, often attached to the side of a building, on which advertisements can be displayed. Use for external structures only.
The rigging mast of a sailing ship erected as a monument. Used for naval displays.
A covered stall at a market or fair, etc.
A three-sided structure for the production and storage of silage.
An embanked shute, often stone paved, allowing carts to tip their loads of coal from the road into a storage area.
A curved structural span which is supported at the sides or ends. May vary in shape from the horizontal flat arch through semicircular and semielliptical forms.

Traditionally a building or site where stage coaches were built. Nowadays the term is applied to buildings used for the manufacturing of the body work and furnishings of motor vehicles and railway carriages.
An institution for the detention of prisoners, surrounded by a wall and/or fence as a barrier to escape. The level of security depends on the category of inmate detained.
An institution for convicted prisoners held under a regime which strove to reform by means of silent isolation and labour.
An institution for the imprisonment of military personnel convicted under military law by a military court.

An institution for the imprisonment of prisoners who can be trusted to serve their sentence without likelihood of escape and of being a threat to the public. There is no physical barrier designed to prevent absconding.

An institution created with the merging of Gaols and Houses of Correction in 1865. Nowadays term used for a prison to which people are sent whilst remanded in custody before trial or direct from court after conviction.
A component building of an explosives works where cartridges were filled with explosives with the aid of cartridging machines.
A liquid distilled from petroleum.
Written communiques, often of a military or governmental nature, requiring fast delivery.
A bank, often faced with stone, with a hedge planted on top.
A clamp in which alum shale was burnt in the initial stage of processing.
A channel which carried processed alum as liquid from the alum quarry/works to the alum house
An institution for the detention of prisoners considered to be a major threat to public safety and/or to the security of the nation.
A terrace of houses built on a slope giving the roofline a stepped appearance.
A machine in which a heavy block of metal is used for beating, breaking or driving something.
A council-owned block of flats.
A monument consisting of parallel lines of banks, ditches, stones, timber posts or trees which appears to mark out an approach to another monument or monuments. Use specific type where known.
A monument consisting of parallel lines of spaced post- holes which appears to mark out an approach to another monument or monuments.
A pit alignment accompanied by a linear bank (or banks) running parallel and adjacent to the line(s) of pits.
A round barrow containing or covering a number of burials. Use both terms.

A subsidiary enclosure externally attached to an enclosure of known or unknown date and function. The annexe is generally smaller than, and secondary to, the main enclosure. Use more specific site type where known. Do not use for Roman military sites.
A large building, situated by or near a dock, canal, road or railway and used for the temporary storage of goods or merchandise awaiting transportation.
A temporary airfield in use during the build-up to D-Day. They consisted of a natural earth or grass surface reinforced with wire mesh.
Circular structure, normally indicated by one or more rings of post holes and/or a circular gulley, and usually interpreted as being of domestic function.
Gun battery built specifically to mount short range weapons to defend a beach against an attempted landing.
A site showing some signs of occupation but evidence is insufficient to imply permanent settlement.
A wall containing apertures to allow a weapon to be fired through it.
A building adjoining a cricket pitch with facilities for players and spectators.
A place where hats are made and sold.
A building where miners could improve their knowledge by attending lectures and using the reading room facilities.
A stable, on two or more levels.
A building providing accommodation, dining facilities and recreation for non commissioned officers.
A large body of water surrounded by land.
An area where the sport of wrestling takes place.
A depot used for the unloading of coal.
A freestanding staff upon which a flag is hung.
A crane for lowering loaded coal waggons onto a ship.

A building within a complex, such as a leisure centre, school, industrial site etc, often containing toilet and washing facilities, where individuals can change their clothes. For a changing room within a larger building, see Components.
A laundry built in conjunction with a PUBLIC BATHS.
A building used in the preparation of manure.
An ancilliary building, usually to provide gas for lighting a particular building (eg. railway stations, factories, etc) as opposed to public GAS WORKS.
A barn with steam powered threshing.
A factory where pencils are manufactured.
Series of wire mesh screens used for grading lumps of coal according to size.
A place where pheasants are reared and kept.
A tank or pond containing a layer of sand etc, for filtering large quantities of liquid.
A watertight reservoir or tank that receives sewage, and by sedimentation and bacterial action effects a process of partial purification.
Term derived from AN32 Glossary
Term derived from AN32 Glossary
A large tank used for training divers.
A single storey mill used in the textile industry.
A single storey building designed so that windows incorporated into the saw tooth roof catch the available light.
A workshop used in the manufacture and preparation of textiles.
A pit used for the prolonged steeping of the flax plant in water to separate the fibres from the wood.
A building complex with hangars and slipways built adjacent to a body of water where seaplanes can be stored and maintained.
A site which has been bombed but where there is no crater, eg. bombed buildings.
An old opencast iron ore site, which has been abandoned.
A building used specifically for testing the boilers of railway engines, both hydraulically and with live steam.
A maze used for the act of penitence.

Monument visible as substantial above ground remains, retaining evidence of architecture and materials, with walls partially or completely intact but with roof and interior walls substantially or completely destroyed.
A decorative garden, often landscaped, laid out with intricate flower beds and hedges, and often containing ornate sculptures, fountains and garden ornaments.
A fall of water. Use for artificial waterfalls if naturalistic in form, otherwise use CASCADE.
Ore containing a high proportion of tin.
Dried grass used as fodder.
A heavy substance, usually gravel, sand or lead, placed in the bilge of a ship or boat to provide stability.
Current recorded information does not give the evidence for a monument, or the information is regarded as unreliable.
A garden in which flower beds are the primary focal point.
A long bed planted with perennial flowers and plants.
A garden, often geometrical in layout, or area for the cultivation of roses.
A piece of land, sometimes man-made, completely surrounded by water.
A framework, often made of steel,  supporting a crane or similar structure, or for supporting a platform or stage.
A hard, lustrous metallic element obtained from various ores, including sphalerite, and used in roofing, alloys and for galvanizing iron.
Fabric manufactured from fibrous materials, consolidated by heat and compression so that the fibres become matted together.
Bricks capable of withstanding heat without burning. Used to line fireplaces, kilns etc.
Potassium Carbonate obtained from the ashes of burnt plant matter and used as a fertilizer.
Obstacles such as scaffolding, barbed wire and concrete blocks or cylinders placed on a beach to impede the progress of enemy soldiers, vehicles or watercraft landing from the sea.
Threads prepared for use in a manufacturing process such as spinning, weaving etc.
A mineral salt consisting of potassium chloride and mangensium sulphate, used as a fertilizer.
Metal spikes used for fixing one object to another.
A purpose built quay for supplying ships with fuel.
An office used by a qualified pilot, expert in ship-handling and with local knowledge, who assists the captain or master to take a vessel in or out of a harbour or through narrow waters.
A building, usually associated with a port or dock, where seamen could get a meal and a cheap room. Often established by religious groups for the moral betterment of seamen.
The hard material, consisting mainly of calcium compounds, which makes up the skeleton of vertebrates. Used for ornaments or ground for use in the manufacture of bone china.
Coal dust or slack, especially that of anthracite.
Rolled iron or steel formed into rails.
Blocks of cast iron as it appears when first removed from the smelting furnace.
Cylindrical, self-propelled missiles which travel underwater and explode on impact.
A cluster of piles for mooring a vessel.
A harbour constructed from floating pontoons or caissons connected end to end.
A highly-prized, hard, white, fine-grained dentine constituting the main part of the teeth of walruses, hippopotami and elephants. Used in the manufacture of ornaments and piano keys.
A cleansing agent, manufactured by reacting natural oils and fats with a strong alkali. Nowadays, formed into bars with added colouring and perfume.
The stalks of cereals separated from the grain br threshing and used as fodder, basket manufacture, thatch etc.
A room or building housing the controls to a mechanized system, eg. in a power station, airport, etc.
Dried or partially dried grapes eaten as a fruit.
The stigmas of the crocus, Crocus sativus, used as a flavouring and for colouring food.
Thick ropes and rigging.
Solid spherical objects, manufactured from stone or metal, fired from cannon.
Non bituminous coal
Cattle fodder or fertilizer resulting from the extracting of oil from seeds.
Pipes manufactured from concrete used in the construction industry for drainage etc.
An oil obtained by the distillation of wood and used as a solvent and paint thinner and in some medical preparations.
A red dye made from the dried bodies of the insect Dactylopius coccus.
A building in which the ingredients of an explosive charge are weighed into their correct proportions and mixed prior to incorporation.
Planks or boards manufactured from softwood timber.
A non-metallic element, yellow in colour, used in a variety of processes.
A factory or plant used for the manufacture of electrical machinery or components.
The fruit of certain varieties of the plant Capsicum Annum eaten as vegetables.
A preparation made from the evaporated juice of the rhizome of the plant Glycyrrhiza glabra, used medicinally and as a sweet, usually in the form of a black, chewy substance.
Soft, loose-textured, woollen or man-made fabric.
A substance designed to emit a sweet smell.
Articles, particularly drinking vessels, manufactured from glass.
Fine cotton fabric of a delicate weave.
A type of cotton cloth of a pale yellow colour.
A shed in which delicate plants are reared from seedlings for planting out later.
Use for stationary railway carriage being used for a purpose it wasn't originally intended for - office, shelter, etc.
Stiff hairs used in the manufacture of brushes.
A college where specialist skills, relating to a particular subject, are taught. Use specific type where known.
Four-seat, twin-engined medium bomber. Entered service in 1938. After serving Bomber Command from 1939-42, was converted to a torpedo-bomber and mine-layer with RAF Coastal Command.
Twin-engined monoplane originally designed as a reconnaissance aircraft, but also widely used as a trainer. Entered RAF service in 1936.
A single-seat, biplane fighter. One of the last open cockpit types to see widespread service with the RAF, equipping 10 squadrons and, at one point, 70% of the Home Defence fighter force.
American A-20 twin-engined, light, day bomber. Some supplied to the RAF and known as the Boston I. Subsequent variations adapted to night flying and re-christened the Havoc.
Wood, cut and seasoned for use as a constructional material.
The pelts of beavers used for the manufacture of fur coats and hats.
Timber sawn into long, flat, pieces used for flooring etc. in buildings.
Supplies including food, drink and equipment necessary for a journey.
Dried or partially dried plums eaten as fruit.
An odourless, tasteless powder obtained from cereals and potatoes, used for stiffening fabric.
Pieces of timber shaped for use in the construction of buildings, barrels etc.
Documents written on sheets of paper or similar, collected together and bound between protective covers.

Structures, traditonally consisting of a long shank with two arms at one end and a ring to attach to cable at the other, used to hold a ship in one place by mooring it to the bottom of the sea. Usually made of stone or metal.
A form of granite found in Cornwall
A building containing equipment used for the polishing of grains of gunpowder and extraction of the resulting dust.
Accommodation in hired rooms or a lodging house.
A building, structure or site used for the storage of charcoal.
A building in a military complex (eg. naval dockyard, castle, etc.) for preparing gunpowder.
A semi metal, poisonous element used in a variety of industrial processes and in some medicinal preparations.
Sulphates, used in medicine and to colour inks.
Fertile soil composed mainly of humus, sand and clay.
Dried kernel of coconut
Wood used to produce a dye.
Dried seedless grapes used in cookery.
Powder made from particles of stone used in mining to make the coal dust in the air less combustible.
Long narrow pieces of wood used for a variety of purposes.
Ore that has been burnt.
The flat end of a barrel.
Usually slag, a residue from burning stone, but can be used for vitrified bricks.
Developed from the ill-fated ME210, the ME410 Hornisse entered service in May 1943. Although underpowered as a day fighter the ME410 saw service over the UK as a night fighter from 1943-45.
Two-seat, single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer. Square-winged and fitted with dual controls, this popular trainer was used by British Commonwealth, as well as American and Canadian, air forces.
An aircraft designed for the testing of engines or other aircraft components.
Structures associated with telecommunications.
A floating, fixed marker used to indicate to a navigator a sea area to approach or avoid.
A mill used for the manufacture of walking sticks.
A plot of land longer than it is wide, can include any structures on it. Typical of medieval towns.
A type of bridge which was designed for temporary use and then capable of being moved to another site. Use for temporary bridges which have remained in situ since erection.
A type of temporary bridge designed by Sir Donald C.Bailey during the Second World War.
For broadcast radio programmes use BROADCASTING TRANSMITTER, for radar transmissions use TRANSMITTER SITE.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Order of Tiron.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Premonstratensian order.
A pipe is a type of barrel, also used as a measure equivalent to two hogsheads.
The seed of the flax plant used to produce oil and, in LINSEED CAKE, as fodder.
Sulphate of Barium
Frozen water. Prior to the invention of the refrigerator, ice was used to preserve food.
Commercially manufactured sodium carbonate used in glass and soap making.
The bark and wood of trees of the genus Aspidosperma used to produce tannin.
A form of limonite, found in wet ground, from which iron can be extracted.
Small pieces of wood, tipped with a chemical composition which ignites when rubbed against a rough or, if safety matches, prepared surface. Normally contained within a small box.
Aluminium oxide.
Large blocks of timber used to support railway tracks.
A group of buildings and machines, usually situated close to the pithead,  enabling the rapid, mechanized loading of goods wagons with coal.
Sand consisting of a mineral common in igneous rocks.
A bridge which is fortified at one or both ends.
A bridge on which dwellings or commercial premises have been built.
A type of bridge which completely encloses the traffic using it.
A bridge whose trusses or girders form parapets on either side of the deck.
A bridge manufactured from prefabricated sections.
A bridge in which one leaf may be retracted in a horizontal plane, passing on rollers over or under the adjacent fixed leaf.

Four-engined heavy bomber, developed by Avro from the twin-engined Manchester. Entered service in 1942 as the RAF's principal night bomber and took part in the 1,000 bomber raids as well as the famous Dam Busters raid.
North American Aviation, Inc., incorporated in Delaware in 1928.
American, four-engined, medium/heavy day bomber. Entered service in 1937. The prototype was nicknamed the Flying Fortress, which later became a registered trademark.
American, four-engined, long range, medium/heavy day bomber. Produced in greater numbers than any other American aircraft during the war.

American, four-engine, long range, heavy strategic bomber. Entered service in 1943 and used exclusively against Japanese forces. The B29s Enola Gay and Bock's Car were used to drop atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945.
American twin-engined medium bomber. Entered service with the US 22nd Bombardment Group at Langley Field in February 1941. Also served with the 14th and 39th RAF squadrons.
Oil produced from the seed of the flax plant. Used in the production of paints, varnish etc.
The oil rich seed of the plant Bracchus napus.
A viscous, bituminous pitch which can be used for surfacing roads.
A series of links joined together to form something that is flexible and strong. Usually metal, chains have a variety of uses but usually involve joining one item to another.
A place, where a corpse could be laid whilst being carried on its way to a burial, to allow the bearers to rest.
A road, used traditionally for the transportation of a corpse to a place of burial.
An open area used for drying products manufactured using an industrial process.
Open yard for keeping cattle in during winter. Used from the mid-14th century in drier, Eastern, arable counties.
Engineering works specializing in the production and maintenance of non-passenger carrying railway rolling stock.
Grinding mill for producing dyes and pigments from natural materials.
Graves known to be of shipwreck victims buried close to their site of discovery, as was customary until the 19th century, rather than in consecrated ground.
A holding on a smaller-scale than an ordinary farm.
Fat from an animal used to lubricate objects.
Poles of timber, metal etc. used as masts, booms or yards on a vessel.
Rock containing a high proportion of calcium phosphate.
Types of aircraft to aid the recording of aircraft remains and crash sites, listing aircraft by form, function and manufacturer.
A post mill in which the drive is taken down to the base of the mill by putting an upright shaft in the hollowed post.
A bridge in which the load is carried by a single beam, or beams, spanning the space between two supports.
A bridge, carrying a footpath or road, usually across marshy or waterlogged ground.
A small stone structure, usually at a spring or bog, in which dairy products were kept cool on slate shelves.
A site, including hangars, moorings and ancillary buildings, used for the storage, maintenance, take off and landing of airships.
A small brick structure attached to a house for keeping fish prior to cooking.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Poor Knights of Christ and the Temple of Solomon, commonly known as the Knights Templars
Soft, porous objects used in bathing and for cleaning. Originally made from the dried skeletons of marine sponges but now more commonly manufactured from synthetic foam.
The hard, close-grained wood of the Box or similar trees.
Any structure or object, used for the purpose of practice shooting by aerial, seaborne or land mounted weapons.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Gilbertine order.
A site where a single large balloon was attached by fine wire cables to the ground to form an aerial obstruction to attacking enemy aircraft.
Small fish, common in European waters, caught for food.
Originally gold coins issued in Florence, but later used for various coins issued on the continent. In modern Britain, the two shilling piece.
People who have paid to travel on a vessel without having to work their passage.
Savoury ingredients, such as herbs, used to add flavour to food.
Durable wood from the cedar tree.
Products manufactured from timber.
The hides of animals, either untreated or tanned.
Originally a large tract of wooded country, owned by the Monarchy, for the purpose of hunting. The royal parks of London, eg. Greenwich, are all open to the public and have been for centuries.
A hopper for the storage of ash.
Multicellular marine alga, which grows on the seashore, in salt marshes, in brackish water or submerged in the ocean.
A light, mostly wooden errected structure serving as workshop for the building, storage, repair and maintenance of boats.
A holder for weapons, explosives and ammunition.
Containers used for industrial or scientific purposes.
A container with a religious, ritual or funerary use.
This includes cosmetic containers.
A container for the storing of substances.
A flexible holder for a bladed tool or weapon.
Parts which make up a vehicle.
Equipment for digging earth, etc.
A leaf or diamond-shaped arrowhead with shallow retouching at the edges.
A place where patients have X-Rays taken to highlight an illness or irregularity.
A building used to coordinate civil defence in times of war. Can also be utilized as aid centres in times of national emergency.
An undefined structure used in the training of people in a certain skill.
An instrument used for making a loud sound for information or warning.

A complex of buildings at a seaport, comprising of a terminal building, landing pier and hangars, used for the embarkation of passengwers and/or freight on flying boat services during the 1930's-50's.
A site where the magnetic signature of ships was lowered thereby making them less susceptible to magnetic mines.
An abandoned settlement, usually of the Medieval period, often visible only as earthworks or on aerial photographs.
An object to point at words whilst reading, eg the Alfred jewel.
The seal of a papal document
An item used to join together clothing (includes footwear).
A small piece of metal or other material used to hold objects together.
An object worked on a lathe, usually the bi-product of such work.
A secondary or incidental product of a process.
Monument with roof or walls intact or substantially intact, significant survival of original features, even if building no longer in use for original function.
Not to be used for indexing. Broad term used to assist retreival of all monuments where physical evidence is recorded.
A screen dividing one part of a church from another.
An object carried about the person for religious purposes.
An object for making an offering to a deity. It includes objects concerned with curses, sacrifices, and prayers and their related objects.
Objects concerned with marriage and weddings.
A vessel for keeping the ashes of the dead after cremation.
An object used within a divinational process.
A container used to hold and or pour out liquid in honour of a deity.
A religious receptacle, especially Jewish where it contains four Hebrew texts worn during morning prayers.
An amulet containing a charm in the shape of a scarab.
An ancient Egyptian gem cut in the shape of a scarab beetle and engraved with symbols on its flat side.
A ring containing a scarab shape.
A container for a pyx which is often a canopied niche in a wall.
An Egyptian container for holding the entrails of a mummy.
A screen of wood or stone, used to divide the nave from the choir.
A sliding metal bar, often fixed to a door or similar, which moves through staples so that its end fixes into another staple or hole which is attached to a fixed object, eg a door frame.
A device for operating a lock.
A rail used to suspend objects from.
A container used in the distilling process to catch the distilled liquid.
A flake of stone struck from the core where the length is less than twice the width.
Waste flakes and cores produced in the manufacture of stone implements.
Monument type/interpretation is inferred, based on informed speculation eg by comparison with similar monuments, proximity to other monuments, topography, site character etc.
An object used in the sublimation process. It is pear shaped with both ends open.
Monument existing as an upstanding earthwork, ditch or artificial watercourse, or as a low stone built feature not covered by the other categories.

Monument whose existence is indicated by the discovery of isolated artefacts or an artefact scatter. Eg a scatter of roofing tiles indicating the presence of a building. Use narrow terms where circumstances of discovery are known.
Not to be used for indexing. Broad term to assist retreival of all monuments where non-physical evidence is recorded.

Monument whose existence is inferred from the traces of architectural features. Eg include shadow marks on building walls or beams, pillars, floors incorporated into a later structure, suggesting the existence of an earlier building.
A stone blade with one edge blunted.
A small stone blade with one edge blunted.
A building or room containing a collection of preserved plants (usually pressed and dried specimens).
A pedestal terminating in a head or bust of Hermes or some other deity.
A place used to hide something or someone.
An establishment where offenders who have committed the most serious crimes, e.g. serial killers, are confined.
A temporary fence of boards, often enclosing a building on which posters and bills are attached.
A pen or enclosure for hoggs (yearling sheep, not pigs).
For the housing of hoggs (yearling sheep, not pigs).
A yard for pigs.
A place with organized amusements for people on holiday.
A disused term for a place where people with learning difficulties are cared for.
A hospital where more 'natural' means of treatment are used rather than conventional methods.
A building in which hoops (for masts) were heated.
A piston mounted horizontally supplying power via a valve gear directly to a crankshaft or flywheel.
A water mill where the waterwheel directly drives a vertical shaft with grindstones on.
An outwork joined to the mainwork by two parallel wings.
A wheel which is turned by a horse in order to provide power. Used in mines, manufacturing and farming.
An area of ground in which horses can be exercised.
A specialist veterinary hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of horses.
A building where horses are rubbed down after training.
A frame used to lift unco-operative horses off the ground during shoeing.
The cleaning and sorting of horse hair mainly for use in the upholstery trade.
A hall used for the promotion and selling of horticultural produce and practice.
The residence and small-scale workshop of a hosier.
A specialist unit within a hospital complex. It may be a separate building or sometimes linked by a corridor or covered walkway to a main building.
A hospital building of uncertain function. Use more specific type if known.
A separate functional unit of a hospital not necessarily on the same site.
A specialist hospital for the medical treatment of patients suffering from epilepsy. Originally epilepsy was seen as a mental illness.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of urinary disorders and diseases.
Use both terms.
A laundry attached to a hospital.
A charity school, usually housed in an almshouse.
A glasshouse used for the cultivation of tropical plants.
Structure used for viewing deer hunt.
A building used as a social venue by people interested in, and involved with, the sport of hunting.
A crane whose winding mechanism was operated by hydraulic jiggers.
An engine house used to pump water to the top of an ACCUMULATOR TOWER.
A hydraulic machine used to magnify the stroke of a hydraulic piston. The pulleys and chains of a crane or other device are attached to the jigger.
Pipes used to carry water or hydraulic fluid for power transmission within a hydraulic system.
Buildings and structures associated with the creation and use of hydraulic power.
A tippler, a machine for loading wagons at a pithead, operated by hydraulic power.
Power generation by releasing stored water through a turbine driving a generator.
A 19th century spa building, usually consisting of a hotel with baths used for water treatment.
A historic term for a charitable institution caring for people with mental illness and/or learning difficulties.
A historic term for a hospital ward for patients with mental illness and/or learning difficulties.
The residence of the supervisor of an inclined plane.
A hospital for the care of patients with incurable illnesses.
An abbey unaffilliated with a particular order.
A round barrow featuring a small mound separated from a ditch of much greater diameter by a wide berm. The ditch may be accompanied by an external (or occasionally internal) bank.
A monument featuring an artificial circular shallow depression surrounded by a bank which runs around the rim of the depression.
