Hemispherical mound surrounded by a ditch (or occasionally two or more concentric ditches), often accompanied by an external (or occasionally internal) bank. Mound and ditch may sometimes be separated by a berm. Use specific type where known.
A round barrow featuring a low, wide mound surrounded by a ditch which may be accompanied by an external bank.
A cluster of closely spaced barrows and related monuments (eg. ring ditches). Use with specific barrow-types where known.

Source from which stone utilized for the manufacture of non-flint artefacts, including axes, was obtained. Applied only to sources exploited during the Neolithic and earlier Bronze Age. Do not use for flint mining or knapping sites.
An arrangement of one or more standing stones. Use particularly for isolated recumbent stones, or where original form of monument unclear. Use specific type where known.
A stone or boulder which has been deliberately set upright in the ground. Use only for isolated stones. Otherwise use specific type where known.
A form of inhumation in which the skeleton is laid out in an approximately straight line, whether face up, face down, or on its side.
A form of inhumation in which the skeleton is interred, usually on its side, with hip and knee joints bent through an angle of less than 90 degrees.
A building or site incorporating equipment used for detecting the presence of enemy aircraft or ships. Radar Stations can also be used to aid aircraft navigation in dark or poor conditions.
A temporary earthwork or fortification constructed by forces laying siege to a castle or town, etc.
A short trench used to protect troops or to provide defensive fire from, often dug for practice purposes.
A gate leading to water, either a river or the sea. Used as a means of supplying castles, for example, with goods brought by water transport.
A system of stones or wooden obstacles placed close together to impede the advance of enemy forces. Do not use for HILLFORT sites.
An enclosure created by constructing one or more lines of ramparts across a promontory which projects into the sea.
An early form of castle consisting of a flat-top steep-sided earthen mound, supporting a wooden tower, and a bailey.
An imprecise term used to describe large Iron Age settlements of town-like proportions.
A hillfort enclosure with defences composed of more than one bank and ditch.
A landing and taking-off area for military aircraft. Often includes ancilliary structures and buildings for the maintenance and storage of aircraft, etc.
Roman coastal forts fortified with large walls and a ditch, introduced to cope with raids from across the English Channel and North Sea.

A building or tower used to communicate information to shipping or other stations using signals such as flags, fires or lights. Roman signal stations took the form of a stone tower surrounded by a ditched enclosure and were used to warn of Saxon raids.
An excavation used as a means of concealment, protection or both.
A coastal gun/watch tower built as part of the anti-invasion defences during the Napoleonic Wars.
Any military base where the depot battalion of a regiment is based. Depot battalions maintain the stores and records of a regiment and train new recruits.

A tower situated above the rampart walkway and in between the angle towers along a defensive structure, such as a castle wall. They were used as lookout towers, roofed strongpoints or platforms from which missiles could be discharged or artillery fired.
A temporary overnight camp enclosed by a shallow ditch and palisade, constructed by Roman troops on campaigns or manoeuvres.
A permanent Roman fort enclosed by a number of ditches and ramparts, used to house a garrison of auxiliaries.

A system of fortifications constructed along a national frontier to contain the local population, as well as keep out undesirable raiders eg. Offa's Dyke. Use with more specific monument type where known.
A fort with projecting bastions, which came into use from the 16th century onwards.
A small outlying farm building, especially common in southern England, used to store ash (which was used as a fertilizer).
A building for the weighing or testing of metals, eg. at a mine site.
A building housing a boiler, often connected to a steam engine house.
A chapel attached to or founded by a college.
A type of engine house creating power by means of compressed air, typically associated with collieries where it is used for raising coal.
An accounts office, especially within an industrial or commercial complex.
A multi-purpose commercial building, used primarily as a trading place for merchants, but also incorporating shops, public offices, guildhalls, etc.
A purpose-built dwelling for the supervisor of a factory, mine or other industrial complex.
A bone or antler point with rows of barbs, usually on one side only.
A type of helmet with a hinged visor.
A gaming implement usually used in conjunction with a ball.
A long seat usually without a back.
A rough table usually for working upon.
A cage for containing birds.
A material resulting from the smelting of iron ore.
A belt used to confine a hawk's wings.
A collective name for the pans and fire bars used in the making of salt through evaporation.
A mould in which bullets or musket balls are cast.
A narrow flake which is the by-product of making a burin.
A measuring container to measure dry goods.
A war trumpet, usually Iron Age.
Ash and partially fused residues from a coal fired furnace or fire.
An item used to fasten a cloak either to another garment or to itself.
A mould used to cast coins.
A device with a spirally twisted shaft, pointed end and handle for removing corks from bottles.
A machine for freeing the cotton from the plant.
An iron bar used as a lever.
A small shallow cup used in assaying gold or silver.
A container in which  dice are shaken and from which dice are thrown.
A form of dagger.
A container used with an alembic as part of the distilling process.
An object used to catch fish. The line is tied in the middle of the fish gorge which then lodges in the throat after the fish has swallowed it.
An axehead of flint or other stone commonly used for Neolithic types.
An instrument for letting blood.
Any form of fastener used to fasten a girdle together.
Weight used for weighing specific quantities and qualities of gold.
A metal grid, usually iron, used to support pots over a fire.
A small, handled axe.
A stand or tray for ink bottles and or pens
A kind of stone used in making ink.
A cage specifically designed to hold insects.
A kind of scourge.
A bowl for the washing of hands, often in a religious institution.
A fishing spear with two heads to grip fish between.
A shackle for the hand.
A polished reflective surface.
A vessel to contain the wafers used in the Eucharist.
A clasp on a cope.
A flat based stone used in conjunction with a grinding stone
A bowl for the ritual washing of hands.
The blade or sharp-pointed head attached to the end of a spear's shaft.
A type of spur which ends in a point, blunt or sharp, which is used to aid control of an animal eg a horse.
A type of spike, often on candlesticks.
A tool for smoothing objects.
One or more ropes or straps attached to an animal's head to provide guidance and control.
Use most appropriate term.
An Egyptian religious statuette.
A by-product usually from the smelting process.
A gun using an explosive propellant to fire sharpened metal shafts, usually fired through water.
A tool, possibly for cleaning mud from parts of a plough.
The fittings or parts on a strap.
A small round shield.
An African cloth garment.
A chisel ended flaked axehead common in the Mesolithic.
A clay cone, part of a furnace.
A medical container for collecting urine for study.
Items which are used in clothing but which are not necessarily a separate item of clothing.
A general tool used to beat objects with.
A vessel for collecting tears.
A container used in the preparartion of food.
A two pronged spear for catching eels.
A set of shelves.
An object used in the lighting of an area.
Tools used to maintain a fire.
A marker used to represent a gambling stake.
An intially worked object, prepared to be made into a final product.
The spanning of an opening without the use of a lintel.
Fragments of a structure, usually material that has been worked.
An instrument, usually consisting of a disc and pointer, formerly used to make astronomical measurements, especially of the altitudes of celestial bodies and as an aid in navigation.
A village laid out systematically with spacious and garden-like surroundings.
A machine producing mechanical power by the internal combustion of gas.
A factory, works or structure used for the manufacture and purification of gas.
Storage tank for coal gas and possibly other types of gas .
Use both terms.
A small building used by a gatekeeper.
A non-specialist hospital dealing in general medical and surgical treatment.
A shop selling a variety of goods and merchandise.
A specialist hospital where the elderly receive medical treatment.
An ornate public house that developed in the 1830s after the passing of a law to encourage the drinking of beer in alehouses licensed for the sale of beer only.
A building in a zoo or wildlife park used to accommodate giraffes.
Use appropriate term.
An artificial mound of earth outside a ditch or wall intended to deflect or absorb cannon fire.
An enclosure or pen for confining geese.
A tower used to store grain in.
Use both terms.
A barn belonging to, or associated with, a grange.
A modern fodder store on a farm.
Wooden board marking a grave.
A shelter for the parson during the burial service.
A place of worship for members of the Greek Orthodox Church, the national church of Greece.
A storehouse for components used in the manufacture of gunpowder.
A shop which sells vegetables and fruit.
A heavy framework of parallel beams used to support a ship in dock.
An open grating of wrought iron, bronze or wood, forming a screen to a door, window or other opening, or used as a divider.
A building for the crushing of stones and minerals.
Use both terms.
Cottage provided for guests to a country house.

TERM: Guild Of The Holy Cross Chapel

SCOPE_NOTE: A processing house where surplus water is removed from gunpowder after incorporating.
Also known as "Demi Lune", another type of outwork associated with the bastion system.
A dock with gates which open for access for some hours before and after high water.
Use COMMEMORATIVE MONUMENT with the relevant     hall type.
A wall used in the game of handball.
Disused term: A place where physically and mentally handicapped children are cared for.
Workshop for placing handles on mugs, teapots, etc.
A shop selling ironmonger's goods, household tools and utensils.
The residence of health workers. Includes single dwellings of doctors, nurses etc. but not multiple dwellings eg.NURSES HOSTEL
A type of carriage house, usually in a churchyard, for storing a hearse.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of heart disorders and diseases.
A cast iron hammer used for shingling iron or making heavy forgings.
A building used for the storage of rope made from the fibrous stems of the hemp plant.
A series of cages in which hens are confined for intensive egg laying.
A distillery for the manufacture of perfumes from herbs.
A workshop or factory for casting metals.
A building on a river or canal in which the water levels are controlled.
Traditionally, the hall of a crafts, trade, or merchants' guild. Nowadays, often used to describe a TOWN HALL.
A stable used for riding horses or those used to pull coaches, gigs, etc.
A round or polygonal building containing a HORSE ENGINE. Commonly found on farms next to the threshing barn, where it is used to power the machinery.
A medieval hospital for lepers, usually consisting of a church and individual shelters for the lepers.
A type of guildhall belonging primarily to the London livery companies, but also found elsewhere in the country, so called because of the livery worn by members of the guild.
A purpose-built dwelling for the manager of a factory, works, textile mill, etc, often found within the complex itself.
A non-conformist minister's house.
A type of late 19th century tenement block for tenants of a higher social status - usually reflected in the more ornate facades.
A planned village or settlement, usually developed by a philanthropic industrialist , to house workers. Most include facilities for the education and betterment of the workers and their families.
A meeting hall, sometimes equivalent to a GUILDHALL, but also associated with some early mining industries.
A building for the storage and drying of hops, often including a hop drying kiln. Usually built as part of a farm.
A shelter in a public park.
An office for the payment of wages, especially in industrial or commercial complexes.
The public house was a 19th century development, distinctive from the earlier BEER HOUSE by its decorative treatment and fittings.
A depot for the transfer of town refuse to river barges before transportation to the REFUSE DEPOT.
A factory for processing rubber or manufacturing rubber goods, such as tyres.

A type of warehouse found in naval victualling yards, used for the storage of rum, a ration of which was given on a daily basis to members of the Royal Navy, up until the 1980s, when this practice ceased.
A hospital for convalescents or consumptives.
An ancilliary building within a larger works, as distinct from a SMELT MILL.
A platform for storing winter fodder.
Distinctive clerestory-roofed building, used for the drying and storage of military parachutes.
A manufacturing complex where the hides of animals are turned into leather, consisting of buildings for fleecing and drying, as well as treatment pits.
A storehouse associated with rope manufacture (eg. in naval dockyards).
A gentry house in a town or city, either detached or in a terrace.
A stable associated with a horse-drawn tramway system.
A combination of obstructions, used either to stop enemy forces or force them off the road.
A structure associated with forges, watermills, water-powered factories, etc.
A factory for the assembly of components. Usually associated with the manufacture of vehicles: cars, lorries, etc.
A type of back to back house built on a hillside, of four storeys and with entrances at different levels.
A terrace of BACK TO EARTH HOUSES.
A service building to a country house, farm, etc, used for baking. If commercial premises use BAKERY.
A room designed or suitable for dancing.
A platform or other structure for the use of a band of musicians.
A round hut, similar to a CHARCOAL BURNERS HUT, associated with forest industry. The bark was later used in the tanning process.
A mill manufacturing bobbins for the textile industry.
A factory complex consisting of PRINTING SHOPS, COLOUR HOUSES, DYE HOUSES, etc, in which patterns are printed onto calico.
A factory concerned with the commercial manufacture of cider, as opposed to domestic production.
A building, or part of a building, for the milling and pressing of cider apples to produce cider (or pears for perry) and for storing the drink in barrels.
A building found in conjunction with a WATERMILL, used for the drying of corn after harvesting, with a slatted drying floor set above a kiln.
A site containing a forge for the manufacture of cutlery.
A purpose-built fisherman's house, eg. a house with a first floor dwelling and ground floor fish store, or a house with a watch tower for spotting shoals.
A building or site where bloom iron or cast iron is forged into wrought iron.

An early warning structure built during and after WWI along the south and east coasts of England. Sound detecting acoustic dishes and walls could detect the sound of approaching enemy aircraft at a distance of 8 to 15 miles.
Usually a small, two or three man trench, dug as an isolated fieldwork rather than as part of a defensive system. A WWI and WWII feature.
A workshop for testing guns, incorporating louvred sheds to serve as firing ranges.
A kiln for drying hops in a brewery or maltings complex, as distinct from the OASTHOUSES found on farms.
A residential home for older people or people with physical and/or mental disabilities who need care provided by registered nurses.
Floatable vessel used as a floodgate in docks.
Usually made of iron, this bound the end of an axle and was perforated to allow a linch pin to pass through the axle and keep the wheel in place.
A rod or spindle, either fixed or rotating, on which a wheel or group of wheels is fixed.
A distinguishing emblem or mark, often worn to signify membership, achievement, employment etc.
A cylindrical container, usually bulging outward in the middle and usually held together by metal hoops.
A container made of interwoven strips of pliable materials, such as cane or reed, often carried by a handle.
An ornament made of thin plates of gold or silver, with repousse ornament.
A strip of lead holding small pieces of glass (quarries) in a window.
A vessel for keeping the ashes of the dead after cremation.
An object which perforated the axle cap, passing through the axle and so keeping the wheel in place. Usually made of metal, though can be made of wood or antler.
A perforated strip of metal for shoeing the bifurcated hoof of an ox.
An overshoe with a thick sole or set on an iron ring to raise the wearer's foot out of the mud and so protect normal shoes.
An object originally created to communicate a particular personal belief, achievement, status or membership. It includes articles of adornment or clothing worn primarily for their symbolism.
An object belonging to, used by, or related exclusively to one person and normally carried or kept privately by that person.
A nail of distinctive form, specifically used in the shoeing of animals, eg horses, donkeys, oxen.

A blade attached to a shoe to glide on ice. It can be made of bone, and examples are known from at least as early as the Bronze Age. Metal blades have progressively replaced bone skates since the sixteenth century.
A crosspiece fastened over the necks of two or more animals, often oxen, and attached to the plough or cart to be drawn.
A frame shaped to fit around the neck and shoulders of a person for carrying buckets. Usually made of wood.

Animal, vegetable and mineral remains including edible materials, drink or residues and unworked imported objects which have been retrieved from archaeological contexts. Also soil samples taken for environmental analysis.
Objects used for the preparation of medicines or the diagnosis and treatment of ill health or disease.
Objects used or associated with religious, ritual or funerary activities.
Objects used or associated with sport and games, eg gaming piece. This class includes toys.
Use both terms.
A hospital where Royal Naval personnel and their families receive medical and surgical treatment.
An establishment where books, periodicals, music, etc, are produced from original manuscripts and distributed to booksellers, dealers and the public.
A hospital department concerned with the reconstruction or repair of parts of the human body using transferred tissue, either in the treatment of injury or for cosmetic reasons.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the control, accommodation, service and testing of aircraft.
A factory where aircraft engines are assembled.
A monument commemorating an animal.
Buildings and structures associated with the use of animals to generate power.
Buildings and structures associated with educational and artistic recreational activities.

Court where sessions were held periodically in each county in England, for the purpose of administering civil and criminal justice. Presided over by itinerant judges acting under certain special commissions. Abolished 1971 and in 1972 replaced by Crown C.
A bridge that incorporates one or two spans that tilt at the abutments, to move up and out of the way of shipping. The most famous example of which is Tower Bridge, London.
An inclined concrete ramp on which cars can move from one level to another.
A factory where carpets are manufactured.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production of cement.
A site where clay pipes used for drainage are manufactured.
A factory where tobacco pipes made of clay are manufactured.
The residence of a cloth cutter.
Buildings and sites associated with the manufacture of clothing.
A stable found at a coaching inn where horses are housed.
A stall where a cobbler mends shoes.
A usually large school providing courses for children of all abilities, between the ages of eleven and sixteen.
An office, particularly at a seaport, at which customs are collected.
An educational establishment where dentistry is taught.
A free-standing house, not joined to another on either side.
A club or cafe where popular music is played for dancing.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the engineering industry.
An educational building where examinations are held.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the preserving of food.
The residence and sometimes workplace of industrial workers.
A school where young children, usually under the age of seven, are taught.
A chapel for followers of Benjamin Ingham after he left the Moravians prior to joining the Sandamanians.
A building in London belonging to one of four legal societies having exclusive right of admitting persons to practise at the English bar.
A historic term for an institution caring for people with mental illness.
A sewer or irrigation channel designed to avoid blockage.
A type of calcining kiln used in the processing of iron ore.
An area within a hospital used for the isolation of patients. Patients were isolated if they had an infectious disease or suffered from a psychiatric illness.
A hostel for packhorse teamsters.
A building where jazz music is performed. Often situated in small venues to afford the intimacy of the musicians performing in close proximity to the audience.
A burial ground for followers of the Jewish faith.
A place where jockeys live.
A school attended by children between the ages of seven and eleven.
A castle without a motte.
An edging of stone forming the kerb of a path.
A small gate swinging in a U or V-shaped enclosure, which allows only one person to pass through at a time.
A building used by visitors at a health resort.
An employment exchange for unemployed labourers, servicemen, etc.
A simple, lean-to structure, such as those built by the dock companies to provide shelter for dock workers waiting for work.
Buildings, sites and structures associated  with the manufacture of lace.
An educational establishment, often privately funded, for young women.
A chapel dedicated to our Blessed Lady, often placed to the east of the High Altar, sometimes in other positions.
A decorative building in the form of a dairy, used for recreation.
For the storage and recharging of battery-powered miners lamps.
A large drainage channel used for improving the land.
Areas of land used primarily for agriculture. See also GARDENS, PARKS AND URBAN SPACES.
A house to receive boat landings.
A place where vessels can land passengers and goods.
A wash room. Use with wider site type where known.
A place, hall or chamber in which justice is administered.
Accommodation in a monastery for new monks.
Buildings or sites used in the preparation, treatment and working of raw animal hide into leather products such as gloves or saddles, etc.
A workshop used for the small-scale production of leather goods.
A small house in which leeches were bred for medical purposes.
Structures used for the lifting or hoisting of goods, machinery, vehicles, people and livestock.
A water pond in which lilies are grown.
A walk or path lined with lime trees.
A substantial house in a town or the country (particularly associated with medieval London). Use more specific monument types where known.
An isolation hospital for infectious diseases and leprosy, sometimes known as a Pest House; commonly situated on the edge of a town.
A building to house waterwheels, attached to a WATERMILL or water-powered factory.
A purpose-built or adapted structure intended as a headquarters for an air raid precautions warden.
A complex of buildings and earthworks constructed for the storage of bombs and pyrotechnics.
A nonconformist church for the followers of Edward Irving.
A building with first aid facilities to deal with accidents and other medical emergencies.
A building used for the treatment of victims of chemical, gas or other forms of contamination.
A wall, usually of reinforced concrete, designed to obstruct the progress of a tank or armoured vehicle
Use both terms.

An upright, or originally upright, stone featuring a hole which is often large enough in diameter for a person to pass through, eg. Men an Tol, Cornwall. Do not use for perforated portable stone artefacts.
A building or structure used for the storage of sugar.
A detached fort covering a strategic point.
A defensive bank and ditch, circular or oval in plan, surrounding one or more buildings.
A place of residence and worship for Anglican monks.
A place of worship for followers of Sikhism.
A large building where iron is stored.
A raised platform or walkway connecting two buildings or a ship with the quay, etc.
Use both terms.
The residence of a herder.
A place of worship for followers of Hinduism.
A share or portion of land, allotted to a person, often used for growing, vegetables, fruit, etc.
A building for the storage and processing of grain crops and for housing straw, farm equipment and occasionally livestock and their fodder. Use more specific type where known.
A receptacle used as a home for bees, traditionally made of thick straw-work in the shape of a dome, but sometimes made of wood.
A building or group of buildings used for the making, processing, storing and selling of milk and other dairy products.
A building, or part of a building, used to house doves and pigeons, usually placed at a height above the ground, with openings and provision inside for roosting and breeding.
A tract of land, often including a farmhouse and ancillary buildings, used for the purpose of cultivation and the rearing of livestock, etc. Use more specific type where known.
A yard or enclosure attached to a farmhouse, usually surrounded by other farm buildings.
An area of land, often enclosed, used for cultivation or the grazing of livestock.
A private garden established primarily for growing vegetables and herbs for domestic consumption.
A bank formed at the end of a field by soil which, loosened by the plough, gradually moves down slope through a combination of gravity and erosion.
A building with malt kilns for the malting of grains and with other similar equipment for brewing work.
A piece of land used to grow vegetables to be sold at markets.
An area of arable land with common rights after harvest or while fallow. Usually without internal divisions (hedges, walls or fences).
A place where oysters are bred for consumption.
An enclosure for pigs that includes a covered pen and yard.
A series of long, raised ridges separated by ditches used to prepare the ground for arable cultivation. This was a technique, characteristic of the medieval period.
A place where sheep are washed in a chemical bath to control  the parasites of sheep. To conserve the poisonous chemicals the bath is usually small and are not allowed to enter any watercourse.
A pen or enclosure used for containing sheep.
A farm where stallions and mares are kept for breeding.
A place where swans are bred and reared.
An area of a barn, paved or boarded, on which corn was threshed by hand flailing. Use broader site type where known.
An area of land and associated buildings where vines are cultivated. The grapes produced are then used to make wine.
A cultivated plantation of watercress, usually situated near springs or small running streams.
A chair fixed to the end of a plank, in which scolds or dishonest people were tied and ducked in water as a punishment.
A place where people were put to death. Use narrower monument type where known.
A structure used for execution by hanging. Usually two uprights and a cross-piece, from which the offender is suspended by the neck.
An upright post with projecting arm from which the body of a criminal would be hung in chains after execution.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of ear, nose and throat disorders and diseases.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of eye disorders and diseases.

TERM: HOSPITAL FOR FISTULA AND RECTAL DISEASES
SCOPE_NOTE: A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of fistular and rectal disorders and diseases.

A 19th century establishment for the provision of work for the unemployed poor of a parish; later an institution administered by Guardians of the Poor, in which paupers are lodged and the able-bodied set to work.
A hospital where people with learning disabilities receive medical treatment.
A specialist hospital where medical and surgical dental treatment takes place.
A place where people can recover from illnesses or health problems through controlled eating and programmes of exercise, etc.
A hospital block where pregnant women are accommodated and receive medical treatment before and after child birth.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the processing of foodstuffs.
A street lamp in which the light is produced by the burning of coal gas. More recently natural gas has been used.
A building in which apparatus registering the amount of gas consumed is housed.
A turbine driven by gas flow or the gas from combustion.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production of glass.
A factory where gloves are manufactured.
A place where students live, sometimes on a college campus.
A place where graphite is extracted.
A path covered in a layer of water-worn or pounded stones.
A shop selling tea, butter, flour, sugar, spices, tinned foods and miscellaneous household stores.
A purpose-built area of hard material of indeterminate use.
Buildings and structures associated with good health and recreation.
An artificial, sometimes temporary, platform on which helicopters can take off and land.
A playing area for the game of hockey. May be a grass or artificial surface.
A barn used to store hops.
A specially marked ground used by children for the game of hopscotch.
An educational establishment where the art of garden cultivation is taught.
A large building used for the accommodation of paying travellers and guests.
An item that cannot be identified. Use more specific term, if possible.
A decorative piece connected to the altar.
A square, wooden drinking vessel.
Glass which has been coloured and decorated by painting.
Curved, interlocking roof tile of S-shaped section usually made of clay or concrete.
An object which has words inscribed, engraved carved or written upon it.
Buildings in London formerly used as hostels  for law students.
A court of summary jurisdiction established, following legislation, in 1908 for the trial of offenders below the age of legal reponsibility.
A metal, stone or wooden projection with a flat upper surface to support a shelf, arch, statue etc.
A bead used to create a space or interval within a necklace.
A mounting or fitting attached to a chariot.
A site where limestone is extracted.
A factory where lace is manufactured.
Use more specific term where available.
A collection of objects deliberately grouped together and hidden.
Use both terms
An enclosure where ewes are kept at the time of lambing.
Steps found at a landing point.
An establishment with automatic washing machines available for public use.
A small shovel for adding or placing coals onto a fire.
A pair of tongs used for placing coals onto a fire.
A place where a yearly or half-yearly court of record is held by lords of certain manors.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the enactment and enforcement of public law.
The residence of an employee with the duty of maintaining a section of a railway or road.
Establishments authorized to sell or allow the consumption of alcoholic liquors on their premises.
A small shelter used by a man employed to carry links (torches) to light people along a street.
A weight made to be hung from a steelyard.
A place where railway engines are kept.
A place where manganese ore is extracted. Use with other ores extracted and MINE where relevant.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the construction and repair of ships and boats.
A place where meat is displayed for sale.
A place where people meet for entertainment, discussion or assembly. Use more specific type where known.
An oval or circular structure with seats rising in tiers around a central open space. Used for religious ceremonies, entertainment, training and armed combat contests.
Grassland fertilized by allowing floodwater to cover it in winter.
A steep-sided pit formed by, and for, the extraction of gravel.
The residence of a lacemaker.
A place of worship for military personnel.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the drainage and/or ventilation of mines.
Buildings and structures associated with lifting and winding at the site of a mine.
Baths containing water impregnated with mineral substances in which patients bathe for medicinal purposes.
Buildings and sites associated with the production of materials made from minerals.
A small container for holding oil, vinegar, salt etc for use at the table.
A place where the science of historical and comparative language is taught.
Buildings, sites or structures used for the manufacture of linen and/or flax.
A factory where linoleum is manufactured.
The space enclosed between the gates and side-walls of a lock.
A hospital for the treatment of venereal disease.
A small house built out of rough logs.
A mill used to process logwood, the inner red wood of a South American tree used widely in dyeing. Imported in the form of logs and cut and ground into dye by a mechanical process.
A waterwheel where water enters below the axle but above the bottom of the wheel.
A historic term for a hospital ward treating patients with mental illness.
A building housing machinery.
A machine used to raise and lower miners to and from the pit bottom.
Use both terms.
A place where marble is extracted from the ground.
A dock or basin, often inland, used for mooring yachts and other small pleasure craft.
The residence of a sailor.
The residences of people associated with the sea.
A building from where marine operations are directed.
A stone erected to mark a particular spot in the landscape. Can be used for various reasons.
Use both terms.
The residence of a marsh keeper.
The residence of a master ropemaker.
A building at the entrance to an factory manufacturing explosives where a person was searched for matches, prior to entering the workplace.
A self-contained establishment (out-patients) where pregnant women receive check-ups, counselling and medical treatment.
A hospital for the reception of women during their confinement.
A building used by an organization or society instituted to promote the study of mathematics through lectures, research, etc.
A piece of grassland, often near a river, permanently covered with grass which is mown for use as hay.
An establishment where the theory and practice of medicine is taught.
Use both terms.
A dwelling-house with outbuildings and land assigned to its use.
A post or pillar set up alongside a road to mark the miles from or to a place.
A burial ground for military personnel.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the defence of the coastline from foreign invasion.
A building used as the command centre of a military operation.
A hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of military personnel and/or their families.
A road used primarily, but not exclusively, for the rapid transport of military vehicles, equipment and personnel.
A building where milk is deposited and stored before it is despatched to the consumer.

A northern term for water reservoirs at steam powered industrial sites that are part of the steam raising plant and are used for recirculating condenser cooling water. The lodge had to be large enough to supply the condenser with cool water for a day.
Use both terms.
A shaft, separate to the main working shaft, used to pump water out of the mine workings.
A building used for the dissemination to the public of such items like tourist brochures, travel maps, guide books and other documents, etc.
A wooden frame with holes, through which the head and hands of an offender were thrust, in which state they would be exposed to public ridicule and assault.
The office or headquarters of a local police force, or of a police district.
An establishment where offenders are confined. Use more specific type where known.
A site where acts of corporal and capital punishment were carried out.
An instrument of punishment, in which the offender was placed in a sitting position in a timber frame, with holes to confine the ankles and wrists between two planks.
A large building used for the transaction of the public business of a town, the holding of courts of justice, entertainments and other activities.
A building, structure or landscape created to commemorate a person or event.
A sepulchral monument erected to commemorate a person or persons buried elsewhere.
A tall, tapering pillar with a pyramidal top, generally square on plan. Used in England from the late 16th century as a public, funerary or garden monument.
A structure found on lighthouses, piers, etc, capable of emitting a loud noise to warn shipping in foggy weather.
A building, department or shop where postal business is carried on.
An office or central station of a local telephone system where the various lines are brought to a central switchboard and communication between subscribers is achieved.
A house devoted to the shelter of the poor and endowed by a benefactor for this use.
An institution, sometimes attached to a hospital, where patients may receive treatment or health checks.
A building for the care of the sick, aged, infirm and poor. Use narrower monument type if possible.
A hospital for the treatment of diseases of the nerves and nervous system.
A hospital devoted to the curing or correcting of physical deformities.
A department devoted to the curing or correcting of physical deformities.
A hospital department which treats patients without keeping them in overnight or for a longer period.
A building where the study and practice of preparing, preserving, compounding and dispensing drugs is performed.
A medicinal or mineral spring often with an associated building.
A room or office at a general practitioners' or veterinary practice, where patients or animals are seen and medicine dispensed.
A hot steam bath introduced from the East, in which heavy perspiration is followed by soaping, washing, massage and cooling.
A pit for the reception of night-soil and refuse.
A covered tank in which rainwater is stored for use when required.
A drainage structure that extends across and beneath roadways, canals or embankments.
A barrier of concrete or earth, etc, built across a river to create a reservoir of water for domestic and/or industrial usage.
A shallow pond, often artificial, fed by the condensation of water from the air, occuring on high land which has no other adequate water supply.
An artificial channel for draining water or carrying it off.
The gate of a sluice which can be opened or shut to let out or retain the water.
A point where water issues naturally from the rock or soil onto the ground or into a body of surface water.
A tower serving as a reservoir to deliver water at a required point.
Buildings, engineering constructions and machinery, used for the purpose of supplying a town, etc, with water distributed through pipes.
A dam constructed on the reaches of a canal or river designed to retain the water and to regulate its flow.
A shaft or pit dug in the ground over a supply of spring-water.
A small carved figure, usually female in appearance, probably representing  fertility charms, found on Romanesque churches in the West of England, eg. Kilpeck.
Upright stones engraved on the edges with a Celtic script consisting of lines or notches.
A North country memorial imitating a wattled hut decorated with formalized bears or snakes.
A small Anglo-Saxon cross-slab buried on the breast or beneath the head of a corpse.
A grave or sepulchre including a monument. Use specific type where known.
A place where beehives are kept.
A column set on a pedestal and decorated with the bows of warships to celebrate naval victories. Originally a Roman form, it was revived in 17th and 18th century decoration.
A terrace house sharing a common wall with its neighbours.
A room or suite of rooms used as dwellings, eg. in private houses, hotels or tenement houses.
A building used to house members of the armed forces.
A barn in which a pair of curved timbers form a bowed A-frame which supports the roof independently of the walls.
A house in which a pair of curved timbers form a bowed A-frame which supports the roof independently of the walls.
A laundry situated within the estate of a manor or country house.

Nowadays a hospital where patients suffering from psychiatric disorders receive medical care and treatment. Traditionally they were often places where psychiatric patients were kept confined away from society receiving minimal medical care or attention.
A hospital block from where patients are discharged after an operation or other treatment.
A building where patients or inmates of a hospital or workhouse were disinfected and their clothes washed or burnt to prevent the spread of infectious diseases or other ailments.
A place where ambulances are serviced and maintained.
Originally partially covered baths shaped somewhat like a slipper, now usually a number of single baths of the modern domestic style installed for hire at public baths.
A factory or complex containing machinery for the manufacture of printed materials.
A building, in a garden, park or open space, either housing a fountain or the machinery which powers one.
A complex or network of earthwork or cropmark linear ditches, banks or other features. Use specific type where known.
A multiple, parallel arrangement of linear earthwork ditches, usually accompanied by banks, and often of considerable territorial extent. Usually of later prehistoric or Roman date.
A circular shaped area of land enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.
An area of land, in the shape of a D, enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.
An area of land, roughly shaped like a polygon and enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.
A rectangular shaped area of land enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.
An area of land, roughly shaped like a trapezoid and enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier.

A settlement consisting of several hut circles, either grouped together or dispersed. Characteristic of the later prehistoric period. Use specific forms where supported by the available evidence. For isolated hut circles use HUT CIRCLE.

A settlement with evidence for several hut circles but clearly lacking an obvious boundary. Where it is not certain whether a boundary existed or not, use HUT CIRCLE SETTLEMENT. Characteristic of the later prehistoric period.
A site where household rubbish and other waste products can be disposed of. May take the form of a pit, rubbish tip, landfill site or incineration plant.

A site consisting of, usually two, sub-circular enclosures linked by a linear ditch running tangentially to the enclosure boundaries. Characteristic of the later prehistoric period in the Wessex region.
An area of land enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or other similar barrier. Use specific type where known.
A form of floating, moveable pier designed for use in open water.
A residence for a member of a religious community eg. Abbot, Prior, Manciple etc. For multiple occupancy use more specific term eg. DORMITORY.
A house or shelter used by drovers, herders or shepherds during the seasonal moving of livestock from the highlands to the lowlands. Use more specific type where known.

A section of the water channel on a canal or river shut off above and below by lock gates provided with sluices to let the water out and in, and thus raise or lower boats from one level to another. Use more specific type where known.
An enclosure, usually within a zoo, designed to represent the natural environment for bears, including shelter. For bear baiting enclosures use BEAR PIT.
A building, site or structure associated with the playing of racket sports.
A building, site or structure associated with the playing of ball sports.
A building, site or structure associated with various racing sports.
An area of grass, marked out for use in the game of cricket.

A hospital ward block, completely open on the south side apart from a low railing and sun blind. It was thought beneficial for the recovery of wounded soldiers as well as those with diseases of the chest.
A stone-faced enclosure, with entrance closed by a floatable caisson or by gates, which can be pumped dry for inspection, maintenance, or repair of the hull or underwater fittings of a ship or ships.
A floating structure consisting of two walls standing on pontoon tanks, the latter of which can be flooded to receive a vessel and then pumped out until the pontoon deck and the ship are dry.
Small revolving wooden chalets that could be turned with their backs to the prevailing wind so that hospital patients could recline in them on long chairs in all weathers.
A building of unknown purpose found at a military site. Use more specific type where known.
A place where photographs are taken of people or things on a commercial basis.
A structure of iron or wood, open below, running out into the sea and used as a promenade and landing stage.
The hull of a dismantled ship used as a prison.
Buildings, sites and structures used by mariners for purposes of navigation.
An establishment open at night for refreshment and entertainment.
An object used in the Eucharist.
A place of worship for members of Protestant sects dissenting from the established Church.
A complex of buildings producing power derived from nuclear energy.
A large cross designed to be carried in a procession.
Buildings and structures associated with the mining industry.
Buildings and sites associated with the manufacture of motor vehicles.
A car park, on two or more levels.
A figurative or decorative object made of corn, used as a charm for luck or to ward off evil spirits.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the manufacture of plaster.
The office of the body controlling a harbour and docks.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the collection, distribution, sending and reception of mail.
A building used to house apes and monkeys.
A cast of a person's face taken after death.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the generation and transmission of power.
A stone used to cover a grave.
An object placed to mark the site of a grave.
A stone placed over or at the head or foot of a grave, or at the entrance to a tomb.
A cross connected to a reliquary or containing a relic itself.
A sheet or cloth used to lay the corpse out in for burial.
A grave or sepulchre including a monument.
A box used for divination.
A figurative representation used in divination.
A stone used for divination.
A tray used in divination.
A piece of bone used for divination.
A die used in divination.
An image of a deity used as a focus for worship, usually used for non Christian images.
A bowl used to contain and burn incense.
A container for incense.
A small shovel used with incense.
A container for incense.
A box to contain the dowry which is a gift or endowment given to or on behalf of the wife.
An object fashioned in the image of a penis.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production and use of paper.
A vessel, usually made of stone, which contains the consecrated water for baptism.
A coin-operated meter receiving fees for parking a vehicle in a street, and indicating time allowed.
A school for the teaching of poor children, often the recipients of Poor Law relief.
A building containing celestial telescopes in which astronomical or meteorological phenomena may be observed.
A site where petroleum is drawn.
A building where onions are laid out to dry.
A necklace holding charms or being itself a charm.
An object which contains or is inscribed with spells against disease, witchcraft etc, or providing luck to the wearer.
A site where peat (vegetable matter decomposed in water and partly carbonised), used for fuel, is cut.
A fuel store for the storage of dried peat.
A bead or group of beads used in prayer.
Sites and structures associated with pedestrian transport.
A string of beads used to aid the memory in reciting a set of devotions.
A flail used for the mortification of the flesh.
An item with both secular and religious signifigance.
A staff used for ceremonial purposes, often highly decorated.
An encircling ornament for the head, usually denoting sovereignty.
A band worn around the head to denote sovereignty.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the construction and maintenance of railways and rolling stock.
Buildings and structures associated with the manufacture of rope.
A seat of state, often highly decorative, used by monarchs, bishops, etc.
A stone inscribed or marked with runes.
A tablet, often made of lead, on which curses are written. Sometimes the tablet is transfixed with a nail.
The residences of people involved in transport work.
A container used to hold and or pour a liquid in honour of a deity.
A container used to hold and or pour a liquid in honour of a deity.
A utensil used to pour a liquid in honour of a deity.
A grotto or shrine dedicated to the nymphs, composed of fountains designed to imitate a natural grotto.
A centre where treatment and rehabilitation training is given to patients recovering from injuries or accidents.
A kiln that is octagonal in plan. Use with functional kiln type where known.
An internal combustion engine powered by the combustion of vapourized oil.
An electricity-producing power station fired by oil.
A historic term for a charitable institution caring for destitute, older people.
An early to mid 20th century school designed to effect maximum ventilation and sunlight for its pupils.
A form of blast furnace. Steel is smelted in an open hearth while the waste gases are used to preheat the air blast.

A room where surgical operations are performed. Originally in the form of a room with a raised table surrounded by tiered seating from where students could watch an operation or disection be performed.
An establishment for the testing of eyesight, making up of optical prescriptions and the sale of spectacles.

A forcing house used for various types of fruit which first appeared in the 19th century. Lean-to houses were used for wall-grown fruit and free-standing houses for fruit grown in pots or for trees planted in the ground.
The residence of a storekeeper of naval ordnance.
A storage area usually for naval weapons and stores.
A plant incorporating a range of ore processing operations such as buddles.

A historic term for temporary accommodation offered to foreign sailors employed by British shipping companies but destitute while awaiting their next ship. The 'Strangers' Home for Asiatics, Africans and South Sea Islanders' opened in London in 1857.
A bridge built to enhance or compliment the surrounding landscape. Mainly found on estates or in parkland and usually 18th and 19th century.
A school for parentless children.
Use both terms.
A hospital department for the medical and surgical treatment of teeth disorders.
A place of worship for followers of the Orthodox Catholic Church. Use only where the specific denomination is unknown.
The outlet or mouth of a sewer where it dispenses into the sea, lake, etc.
A multi-purpose farm building in an outlaying area of a farm.
A building in which oxen are accommodated.
An ancillary building in a factory or other industrial complex where manufactured goods are packaged.
An enclosed field for horses.
Originally a fence against which trees and shrubs were grown. Later used to describe a row of trees and shrubs forming a hedge clipped into a green wall.
A building, usually circular, or containing circular rooms, for the exhibition of panorama paintings.
A school serving or supported by a parish. Usually teaching religious as well as conventional education.
A hospital department where research and treatment into the causes and nature of diseases or abnormal bodily conditions is carried out.
A detached block within a hospital complex used as sleeping accommodation for patients.
A small paved area attached to a building.
Detached block comprising one or more storeys of wards.
A pawnbrokers shop or place of business.
A building used for the sorting of peas.
A building used to house peacocks.
A foot tunnel, often running beneath a road.
A pond storing water to supply a HAMMER POND.
A savings bank where a sum as low as a penny may be deposited.
A cutting through a wood to open up a view or establish an allee.
A place where perfume is sold, as well as manufactured.
A separate residence for guests, a house on a private estate or a monastery building specifically for receiving visitors.
A building for human habitation, especially a dwelling place. Use more specific type where known.
A room or building where clothing and other fabrics are washed, mangled, steamed and ironed.
A small building, often inhabited by a gatekeeper, gamekeeper or similar. Use specific type where known.
A hall in a village used for meetings and other functions.
The place where a house stood or had once stood, often adjoining a garth or croft.
A settlement where previous house sites are now unoccupied, but often visible as earthworks, crop or soil marks.
A collection of dwelling-houses and other buildings, usually larger than a hamlet but smaller than a town with a simpler organisation and administration than the latter.
A town for citizens of Roman or Latin status with a constitution governed by charter, which if possessing only Latin rights could be promoted to the status of a colonia.

Traditionally a mew was a building housing hawks when they were moulting, however since the C16th the term has been used for a series of stables grouped around an open yard or alley, often with rooms above. Use only for stables otherwise use FALCONRY.
A large barn used to store the tithe (a tenth part of the annual produce of agriculture etc.) which was paid by the tenants of ecclesiastical lands.
A group of buildings in which local sewage is filtered and purified in large rectangular or circular tanks.
A controlled point with warning lights and gates or barriers where a road crosses a railway line.
A mechanized gate or barrier at a level crossing used to prevent road vehicles crossing a railway line when a train is approaching.
A building in which works of art are displayed, permanently or temporarily.
A weekend retreat for Royal parties and others, when hunting in the Royal forests, or as a viewing station for the chase.
A small timber one-roomed dwelling where holiday makers could rest after a day spent sunbathing, swimming and playing on the beach.
A wooden, stone or iron post for securing things to or for preventing vehicular access to pedestrianized areas.
A small metal bar for the cleaning of dirty footwear before entering a house, etc.
A piece of sculpture usually representing the head, shoulders and breast of a person.
An 18th century garden with a Chinese layout and ornaments.
A circular range of houses dating from the 18th century, eg. John Wood's Circus at Bath.
An uncovered area, surrounded or partially surrounded by buildings.
Structures erected on or near a public highway.
A row of houses whose facade in plan follows the concave arc of a circle or ellipse, eg. The Royal Crescent, Bath.
A circular, metal or wooden cover, covering a hole in the pavement where domestic coal deliveries were dropped into a store below.
A freestanding public call box, containing a telephone and usually operated by inserting coins.
A mechanical device consisting of a system of signal lights operating in sequence, placed at road intersections and pedestrian crossings to regulate traffic.

An artificial aperture from which water springs. The water supply usually came from a lake or reservoir higher up in order to ensure the necessary flow and pressure. More recently fountains have been powered by pumps.
An enclosed piece of ground devoted to the cultivation of flowers, fruit or vegetables and/or recreational purposes. Use more specific type where known.
A large discharge pipe with a valve for drawing water from a water main. Used to help extinguish fires.

A metal, wooden or concrete box containing a telephone for use by the public, limited accommodation for use as a temporary cell, and a lamp on top that could be used to attract the attention of a passing patrol.
A tall wooden pole used to support telegraph wires.
Grounds, usually associated with a country house, laid out so as to produce the effect of natural scenery
A stone set up on a road or path to mark the miles from or to a place.
A gallery or building in a garden, usually south facing, used for the growing of oranges and other fruit.
A tall, polygonal structure with ornamental roofs at each storey, based stylistically on a Buddhist temple but adapted as an eyecatcher and pavilion in the 18th century in England.
A greenhouse used for growing palms and/or tropical plants.
A light, sometimes ornamental structure in a garden, park or place of recreation, used for entertainment or shelter. Use specific type where known.
A sculptured, carved or moulded representation of an imaginary creature with a human head and breast combined with the body of a lion.
An open space or area, usually square in plan, in a town or city, enclosed by residential and/or commercial buildings, frequently containing a garden or laid out with trees.
A representation in the round of a living being, allegorical personage, eminent person or animal, etc, sculptured, moulded or cast in marble, metal, plaster, etc.
A table made of stone, found in streets, parks, etc.
A labyrinthine garden feature, common during the 16th and 17th centuries, created by cutting shallow pathways into deep lawns.
Buildings or sites used in the production of items derived from the parts of animals not used for consumption.
A building or site used for the production of acids by a range of chemical processes.
Buildings, structures or sites used for the production of chemicals used in agriculture, such as fertilizers and weed killers.
A building or site used to produce alkaline chemicals by controlled reactions.
Buildings and plant used for the extraction and purification of arsenic oxide into various forms of pure arsenic.
Buildings and sites used for the production of inorganic and organic dyes, pigments and paints.
A site used for the production of dyes from natural ingredients.
A site used for the production of dyes from controlled chemical reactions. In use from the mid 19th century onwards.
A site used for the separation of oil into its constituent parts by heating in an enclosed vessel(s).
A kiln used for the production of any of the soda group of alkalis by the heating of plant remains or salt.
One of a line of blocks on the floor of a building slip on which the keel of the ship to be constructed is laid. Also used in dry docks to rest a ship when a dock is pumped dry.
A prominent structure situated on land specifically as a guide to navigation for travellers or as an aid/warning to sailors out at sea.
A building providing accommodation, dining and recreational facilities for commissioned naval officers.
A building for the storage of all stores supplied for naval service other than victualling and armament.
A form of Neolithic burial monument comprising a large circular stone or earthen mound, with a low and narrow entrance passage leading to a wider and higher stone built chamber.

A rectangular or trapezoidal earthen mound of Neolithic date, usually accompanied by flanking or encircling ditches, and normally associated with human remains. Mound construction and associated features vary considerably in type and complexity.
A megalithic tomb of Neolithic date comprising a chamber bounded by large upright orthostats, often only three or four in number, which support a large capstone.
Objects associated with the care and use of animals.
Objects associated with cultivation, the rearing of livestock, gathering, hunting, fishing, horticulture and the primary processing of foodstuffs.
Objects forming fragments or parts of a building's fabric, structures and associated services, eg drain pipes. Where an object is a fixture or fitting use the separate class.
A style of dressing including all the clothes, accessories etc worn at one time, as in a particular country or period.
Soft coverings and associated objects for walls, furniture, floors and windows. Also items such as chairs, beds, and cupboards.
Objects used or associated with the movement of goods or people.
The remains of any part of any animal. Use specific term where possible.
Use for the remains of an egg whether from a bird, reptile or amphibian.
Use for the remains of any part of a fish.
Use for the remains of any part of a human.
Use for the remains of any part of an insect.
Use for the remains of any part of a mollusc. Use more specific term if known.
The remains of the shell of an oyster.
A ball of chalk found on Neolithic sites.
Use for the remains of any part of a bird.
A tube through which missiles are blown.
A bow, fixed to a stock, with a mechanism to fire the bow.
A short stabbing weapon with a pointed blade. In Medieval period daggers served a dual function being also used as knives.
A holder for arrows.
A single edged sword.
A long shafted weapon with a pointed head used for thrusting or as a missile.
A fencing sword often used for recreational purposes.
A flag or military symbolic representation on a pole.
A container used to hold ammunition.
Protective covering for the body.
A sash or belt worn over the shoulder to the hip for carrying a sword.
A large bolt or arrow fired from a ballista.
A type of shield, usually wooden and circular.
The case containing the charge for a firearm.
A two edged broadsword.
A flexible armour designed to protect the torso.
A small narrow pointed missile that is thrown or shot.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the disposal of domestic and industrial waste.
An object used to hold offerings to a deity.
A container to hold and or pour a liquid in honour of a deity.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with water transport.
A stick inscribed with a prayer or prayers for use in praying.
A scroll containing prayers.
A dedicated or consecrated offering.
A bottle for the confinement of evil spirits.
Equipment used on a bird of prey for hawking.
A type of spur with the goad in the form of a rotating disc.
An object for touching or pricking an animal's sides to increase control of it, usually used with horses.

A form of bronze axehead of middle or late Bronze Age date in which narrow, high flanges on both faces are hammered over to enclose the axe haft. Some types feature a side loop to further assist hafting.
A discoidal flint tool often has a ground edge.

A bronze axehead of earlier Bronze Age date the sides of which are raised, either by casting or hammering, to form flanges on both faces which aid hafting. Some types also feature a raised bar or stop between the flanges.
An axehead of early Bronze Age date, made of copper or bronze, which is flat on both sides and generally lacks side flanges or other hafting aids.

A bronze axehead of middle or late Bronze Age date in which the side flanges and the bar/stop on both faces are connected, forming a single hafting aid. For palstaves with side loops use looped palstave.
The residence of a keeper of a royal park etc.
The residence of a person entrusted with the management of a great house or castle.
The residence of a teacher, often on the site of a school.
A library where books may be consulted but not taken away.
The principal Roman Catholic church in a diocese in which the cathedra or bishop's throne is to be found.
A pit where domestic waste material is deposited.
A factory where boots and shoes are manufactured.
A rod, often of antler, with a hole through it and decorated.
A place where letters and parcels are sorted before being distributed. Usually found at a large general post office.
An area of prepared ground on which a sport is played. Use more specific type where known.
A group of coins deliberately deposited together.
Characteristic waste flakes struck off in the production of axes.
Use both terms.
A specialised fitting for Roman armour. For a part of a garment use APRON.
A machine for creating bails of straw.
A piece of iron cut from blooms and lengths of bar, probably for transportation, which were then reworked.
A wheeled open box for carrying loads.
An object constructed to allow birds to bathe in it.
An object designed to hold food for birds.
An object used in the preparation of a body following death. It was used to plug the orifices of the body.
The stem or handle of a brush designed to hold the head of the brush.
Flint which has been burnt. It is not necessarily worked.
A three dimensional representation usually done in wood, ivory or stone.
Waste products ensuing from the casting process.
The piece of stone or flint remaining after flakes have been produced. This is a by-product of tool manufacture.

A flint blade with negative impressions of removals on one side of the dorsal surface, creating a crest. These constitute part of a previously worked striking platfom or result from preparing the flaked surface on a core before detaching flakes or blades.
A guard or cover put in front of a fire to prevent embers or flames setting fire to a building.
A metal or ceramic cover for an open fire or hearth.
A tool for creating holes in the ground in which to plant seeds or plants.
An object of Bronze Age date, usually of gold, with an unknown function.
A piece of metal in front of a fire to stop embers rolling onto the carpet.
Knapped or ground stone/flint tool where the specific type is unknown. Use more specific type where known.
Part of the glass making process, the frit is broken up into a crucible and heated to create glass.
A fan designed to fan the coals of a fire to increase the oxygen around the coals and thus to help the fire burn.
A small rake used to move the embers of a fire.
A pumping station for draining a mine or colliery.
A depot for the storage of various minerals.
Sites where minerals are extracted from the ground.
A pit in the ground from where minerals are dug.
A factory which produces artificial imitations of mineral water, such as soda water.
A specialist hospital where water treatment is given to patients suffering from muscular-skeletal complaints, etc.
Hut or crude shelter for miners.
A building for miners to change their clothes.
A small-scale garden.
A type of stock exchange for tin which replaced the stannary courts in the mid 19th century.
An apartment in a monastery where monks were able to eat and drink.
A site for the storage, preparation and launching of missiles.
A bed or border in which different species and colours are mixed.
A cemetery containing more than one burial type eg cremations and inhumations.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
A factory built as a pattern for improved design.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms. Use specific type of monastery where known.
An often light and airy garden building in the Moorish style used for recreational purposes.
A place of worship for Protestant followers of Hussite doctrines which accept the Bible as the only source of faith.
A long, low-rise building consisting of rows of attached individual suites of rooms used for overnight accommodation by motorists.
A building where motor cycles are assembled.
A building or room where motor vehicles are exhibited for sale.
A workshop used for the production of pottery moulds.
A kiln in which the contents are protected from the fire, usually by a lining of tiles or refractory bricks.
A mill for the manufacture of low grade cloth made from ground-up heavy woollen rags.
A building where documents such as title-deeds, charters, etc, were kept as evidence of rights or privileges.
A building for the storage of ammunition and other military stores.
A building or school where music is taught.
A factory where musical instruments are manufactured.
A mill where mustard is produced.
A small work shop for nail manufacture, most commonly situated at the back of a nailer's dwelling.
A terrace or row of dwellings, with a NAIL SHOP attached to each house.
Use appropriate term.
The residence of a Royal Navy or Merchant Navy officer.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of kidney disorders and diseases.
A prepared area used for the game of netball.
A building or site producing nitrogen-rich fertilizer.
A building used for services by a nonconformist protestant sect, especially by Quakers and Presbyterians.
A type of factory building, often single-storey, designed so that windows incorporated into the vertical faces of its saw-tooth roof can allow the maximum amount of natural light into its interior.
A reinforced concrete structure, often sited underground, used as a shelter from the threat of nuclear attack.
Use both terms.
A school for pre-Infant school children, usually 3-5 years old.
An establishment for the theoretical and practical training of nurses.
The outer boundary of an airfield.
An area of common grassland in a village used for grazing cattle, recreational purposes, etc.
A small building used as a shelter by a constable of the watch responsible for patrolling the streets at night to safeguard life and property.
A garden incorporating fountains and pools in which aquatic and other water-loving plants are grown.
A tract of land with trees, sometimes acting as a boundary or barrier, usually smaller and less wild than a forest.
A building adjacent to a monastery where alms were distributed to the poor.
An elevated table or podium on which to place or sacrifice offerings to the deities.
A tomb or memorial, resembling an altar, often with a recumbent effigy on top.
A freestanding building, or a room or recess serving as a place of Christian worship in a church or other building. Use more specific type where known.
A building used for public Christian worship. Use more specific type where known.
An area of ground belonging to a church, often used as a burial ground.
A chest made of stone, wood or lead, used to enclose a dead body.
A vault, often located under a chancel or chancel aisle, containing an altar and usually used for burial.
A place of burial. Use more specific type where known.
A stone placed over or at the head or foot of a grave, or at the entrance of a tomb.

Circular or sub-circular enclosure defined by a bank and (usually internal) ditch, with one or two (rarely more) entrances. Of ceremonial/ritual function, they contain a variety of internal features including timber or stone circles.

A well or spring, possessing religious or otherwise ritualistic significance, around which a structure, such as a niche, wall or shelter, has been constructed. In the case of the water source being a natural spring, double-index with SPRING.
A cross erected within a town, usually funded by the inhabitants.
A horizontal stone placed across a grave.
A place where worship is offered or devotions are paid to a deity or saint.
A cross, erected on a highway or in an open place, at which monks and others used to preach.
A muslim temple or place of worship.
A building or room used for holding, viewing, identifying or examining dead bodies prior to burial or cremation.
An iron frame placed over a coffin or at the entrance to a grave to act as a deterrent against resurrectionists.

A confusing and baffling network of winding and intercommunicating paths, often bordered by high hedges or walls. Some early examples are believed to have had ritual uses. Use more specific type where known.
A high pole, painted with spiral stripes of different colours and decked with flowers, erected on an open space, often the village green, for merrymakers to dance around on May Day.
A covered gateway, at the entrance to a churchyard, where during a funeral a coffin could be set down until the vicar arrived.
An area or site used for the landing and take-off of aircraft, often including associated buildings, equipment and other installations.
A hangar for the storage and maintenance of dirigible motor-driven balloons.
A passageway or lane between buildings.
An artificial water channel for carrying water over long distances. Use also for bridge-like structures that carry the channel or canal across a valley, river or other obstacle.
A structure of wood, stone, iron, brick or concrete, etc, with one or more intervals under it to span a river or other space. Use specific type where known.
A structure providing protection against the weather at bus stops.
A building used for housing, and protecting from the weather, carts, waggons and farm implements, often open-fronted.
A road or pathway raised above surrounding low, wet or uneven ground.
A large, metal or wooden structure, used for raising, lowering and moving heavy objects. Use more specific type where known.
A road or track specifically used by drovers or herders to drive their animals to market.
Gates that can be opened or closed, to admit or exclude water, especially flood water.
A shallow place in a river or other stretch of water, where people, animals and vehicles may cross.
A mechanical lift or elevator, used to lift goods, etc.
A way, path or road through a cutting.
A mole or pier-like structure situated at the entrance of a harbour, or running out into lake or the sea, so as to defend the harbour or coast.
A platform, sometimes floating, for the landing of passengers and goods from vessels.
Stones placed in the bed of a stream or on wet ground, to enable crossing on foot.
A set of steps or a framework of bars and steps for crossing over a fence or wall.
A circular building for housing and repairing railway locomotives.
An inclined plane connecting two different levels, used to accomodate the movement of vehicles, wheeled apparatus,livestock etc.
An embankment or cutting on a railway system, surfaced at a uniform gradient, up or down which materials were hauled by rope.
A line or track consisting of iron or steel rails, on which passenger carriages or goods wagons are moved, usually by a locomotive engine.
A gate which allows water to pass into a dock, etc, at flood tide, and by which it is retained during the ebb tide.
A defensive or protective covering for the head.
Armour designed to protect the foot.
A small explosive device, usually hand thrown.
Armour used to protect a horse.
Armour made up of interlaced metal rings.
A form of handgun.
A short stabbing weapon.
A container to provide a set amount of gun powder.
A rigid holder for a bladed weapon.
A protective piece of armour carried in the hand to protect the bearer from weapons.
A small shield.
A weapon with a long shaft and a three pronged head.
A handheld weapon that fires missiles by means of explosives.

A convex, usually round, piece of metal or other material mounted at the centre of a shield. Originally serving  a practical purpose in deflecting blows and providing a mounting for the grip, it later developed into an ornamental feature.
A stamp, made of clay or stone, used to mark bars of eye ointment.
An instrument showing the direction of magnetic north and bearings from it.
A case or container for an amulet.
One of a set used in pharmacy to measure volume or weight for dispensing.
A strip of cloth used for binding a wound.
A small containment for drugs which can be ingested.
Equipment used to perform circumcision.
A knife that is used for circumcision.
A pair of scissors used in circumcision.
A plate used during circumcision.
A staff to support a lame or legless person.
A container, usually glass, used for storing medicinal substances.
A pointed two-edged surgical knife.
A vessel used for medical purposes.
A bottle used for the storage of medicine.
An instrument using lenses to magnify the object being viewed.
A jar for the storage of ointment.
A small bottle for liquids.
An instrument for holding back a part of a body eg an organ.
A cylinder containing a piston by which fluid can be ejected or sucked in.
A scale or index of a sextant, astrolabe or similar instrument.
An instrument for measuring height above sea level.
Weight used with any kind of balance.
A portable timepiece capable of being worn on the wrist or carried in a pocket.
A weight used for the measurement of wool.
An instrument for measuring time.
An instrument for measuring angles, usually in the form of a graduated semi-circle.
A body suspended so as to be free to swing, especially one regulating the work of a clock.
A dial for showing the hours of the night by the moon.
A sandglass that runs for an hour.
A measuring rule graduated in feet.
A system of communication used in a house to summon servants or on board ship to transmit orders to the engine room.
A bound collection of paper or other materials.
Mountings, often decorative, attached to a book.
