A broad design of sword used for cutting and slashing.
A weapon for shooting arrows.
A piece of armour designed to protect the arm or a part of the arm.
An object worn on the head.
An object originally created to be worn on the human body or on clothing for ornamentation rather than for protection or as a body covering.
A ring shaped brooch, commonly Anglo-Saxon and medieval.
This includes all articles created to be used for personal care, hygiene, grooming and cosmetic activities.
An object used with cosmetics.
Objects used for looking after hair.
A brush used to apply soap to the body when shaving.
Corrosive, dense, oily acid, usually in aqueous solution, used in the chemical industry.
A multi sided object usually used to obtain a unique value in games of chance.
An enclosed chair for carrying a person, usually carried by two people.
A raised carving.
An instrument with curved arms for measuring difficult or awkward shapes.
A scraper with retouch at right angles to the bulb of percussion.
Equipment used to bore a hole in a solid object through the use of a twisting, drilling action.
Equipment used primarily to bring percussive force onto an object.
Equipment used to scrape and smooth objects.
Equipment used to sharpen other objects.
Equipment used in the making of tools.
Includes equipment for the consumption of food.
A handled tool with two or more prongs used for digging, cultivation etc.
Metalwork attaching or attached to a harness.
A device allowing a variable amount of air through in a single direction which varies the note produced.
The part of an organ or similar instrument into which air is pushed then is emitted through the pipes.
A device fitted and locked onto the head of a woman as a form of punishment, featuring a metal plate that fits into the mouth to impede speech..
A boundary post for the payment of tax or duty.
A defensive or boundary earthwork.
Use for drain or other water-filled ditch.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of ear disorders and diseases.
A hospital department for the medical treatment of ear, nose and throat disorders.
The principal Eastern Orthodox church in an area.
A burial ground for followers of the Eastern Orthodox church.
For commercial or non commercial use. See narrow terms in each class.
An office which administers the affairs of the church.
A stall where eels, either raw or cooked, are sold.
A device with a funnel-shaped entrance designed for catching eels.
A sculptured likeness, portrait or image, often found on a tomb or other memorial.
A refractory lined furnace in which an electric arc is struck between the electrode and the metal to be melted.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production of electricity.
A school in which elementary subjects are taught to young children.
A monument consisting of parallel banks, normally accompanied by ditches, which appears to mark out an approach to another monument or monuments.
The residence and office of an ambassador.
Emergency Medical Scheme Hospital (WWII). For epidemics use INFECTIOUS DISEASES HOSPITAL.
Use for blocks in Emergency Medical Scheme hospitals (WWII).
The residence of an engineer.
A building situated within the estate of a manor or country house.
Use both terms.
A purpose-built model village for the workers on a country house estate.
Use both terms.
A site used for the production of anaesthetic gas.
A building or a room for accounts.
A government office used for the collecting of excise tax/duty.
A courtyard in a prison or workhouse for the inmates to take exercise.
A pavilion used for exhibitions, e.g. the exhibition pavilions at the Great Empire Exhibition, Wembley, 1925.
A house built using experimental building techniques and materials.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of eye and ear disorders and diseases.
A hospital department for the medical treatment of eye disorders and diseases.
Use wider site type where known. Only use term where no other part of original building survives.
Use both terms.
A modern small factory or workshop, often in the form of a prefabricated shed.
A pulley block and metal ring used to guide a line or rope and cause it to run easily without chafing.
Use INFIRMARY with ABBEY or PRIORY.
A building where animals are deliberately fattened before being killed for their meat.
A textile mill where felt is produced.
An establishment where the art of sword fencing is taught.
A group of buildings, or part of a works, housing apparatus used in the process of fermentation.
Area of a garden for the cultivation of ferns.
A glasshouse for the cultivation of ferns.
Building used for field studies and outdoor pursuits in the countryside and in an urban context.
A greenhouse for the growing of figs.
A carving, often a bust or full-length figure, originally found above a ship's cutwater. Use as an external feature only.
A building or complex of buildings where cinematographic films are produced.
A component of another building, often a house, used for storing nets.
A wooden stake fence, often associated with deer hunting.
A strong, fortified dwelling, of between two and four storeys. Occupied only in times of trouble built mainly in the border country of the North from the mid 14th to the 17th century.
Timber or metal structure consisting of upright and cross members designed to support climbing plants.
A stone on which plague victims placed vinegar-disinfected money to pay for food left for them by the townspeople.
Form of dam, usually associated with ponds supplying water for blast furnaces.
A kiln used for the slow burning of vegetable matter to produce potassium carbonate.
A mine from which potash is obtained. Potash is a deposit of potassium carbonate: the only example of a potash mine in the country is at Boulby in Cleveland.
A tower built on a prominent part of an estate to provide panoramic views of the surrounding countryside.
A mill in which sets of rollers were used to roll metal to set thicknesses or shapes such as rails, beams or rods.
An isolated building, circular in plan, generally consisting of one apartment with a domed roof, eg. Mausoleum at Castle Howard, Yorkshire.
A covered trench, often in a zig zag form, made for the purpose of approaching a beseiged place under fire of the garrison.
A small protective fortification, such as an earthwork.
A mill used for the preparation of raw fleece etc, for spinning by a coarse form of carding.
Pit for the depostion of ore sediment from waste water collected from ore washing.
A furnace constructed as a shaft with the fire at the bottom and the fuel and ore added from the top.
A tower in which shot is made from molten lead poured through sieves at top and falling into water at bottom.
A mill with machinery used to cut slabs of metal into rods, or thin sections, for use in nail making or wire drawing.
A manufacturing complex incorporating furnaces, calciner and condenser flues. Use SMELTERY for more modern type of plant.
An underground chamber, store room or passage.
Mushroom-shaped stones used to raise the floor of barns, granaries etc. above ground level, to prevent vermin gaining access to stored grain and fodder.
A waterside depot for coals brought from the collieries for shipment, furnished with staging and chutes for loading vessels.
Pit for soaking animal hides as part of the tanning process.
A water channel leading from a water wheel.
Field or area of ground where washed new cloth is stretched out to dry.
Early form of powered hammer, usually wooden, used primarily in the iron industry.
Pond for storing cut lengths of timber to prevent them becoming seasoned.
Open-air area often terraced on which a range of ore processing operations are carried out.
Used for boiling sections of willow for basket making, etc.
A metal structure supporting high powered lights.
A factory in which is ink is prepared from pigments and additives.
An area for the testing of rockets and guided missiles. Includes all structures associated with both the firing and testing of rockets and missiles.
A site available to the public for the pursuit of leisure and recreational activities.
The subsoil traces of prehistoric cultivation, presumed to have been caused by the use of an ard to till the soil.
A specially prepared track used for fast motorcycle racing.
An area of the northern Indian Ocean bordered by India, Bangladesh and Myanmar.
Use for miniaturized monument type. Index with actual monument type where possible.
A chair fixed to the end of a plank which was pivoted to allow the incumbent of the chair to be ducked into water as a punishment.
A form of whip or lash, often used for self mortification.
A chain used to inhibit a slave's freedom.
A collar, usually metal, used to signify slavery and to inhibit freedom, usually with a chain attached.
An instrument of torture used to compress one or both thumbs.
An instrument where the note is made by air being blown over an edge.
An instrument in which air is made to vibrate by a cane reed, which may be single or double, and may or may not be contained in a reed cap.
An instrument in which air is made to vibrate by the player vibrating their lips and blowing into a mouthpiece.
Part of a musical instrument.
A simple instrument where two pieces of material are manipulated to knock together.
A specific type of hand held  hollowed wooden clapper, known in Europe from medieval times onwards.
A hollow instrument containing material that produces sound when shaken.
A musical instrument which produces its sound by being scraped.
A flake or blade with retouch along one or more edges.
An instrument whirled to produce sound by a piece of flexible wood hitting against a ratchet wheel.
An instrument made by inserting a stick through a membrane stretched over a hollow vessel then played by rubbing the stick.
A framed instrument, in which strings are plucked or hit, operated from a keyboard.
An instrument played mainly by bowing the strings. Use narrower terms where known.
An instrument in which strings are vibrated by an internal wheel cranked by a handle.
An instrument with a series of pipes at different pitches, the air being produced by bellows, and pipes selected by keyboard or sliders.
A composite instrument in which air is forced through one or more drones and chanter from an inflated bag or bladder.
An instrument which has a cupped mouthpiece and may have a straight, bent or curved tube. It includes slide trumpets like the trombone.
A trumpet type of instrument made from or in imitation of an animal horn.
Use both terms.
Soft coverings and associated objects used within buildings.
Soft items used to make a bed ready to be slept upon.
A mat used on the floor as a covering.
Any vehicle/craft used for transportation on water.
An object used to prick holes on each side of a manuscript page to mark the postion of the horizontal lines.
A diagram or drawing made by projection onto a horizontal plane, often of a building.
A roll of paper or parchment, especially with writing upon it.
A piece of wax, lead, paper etc, with a stamped design, attached to a document as a guarantee of authenticity.
The object used to make impressions in wax as seals.
Two or more tablets of wood attached by a string or leather thong, with a raised border one side of which was filled with wax to write upon. Thin wooden tablets with ink writing are also known.
A plasterer's tool for smoothing the surface of plaster.
A container to receive milk during the milking process.
Containers identified by function rather than by form.
Containers used to serve food and drink. Use appropriate term.
A container used to serve food from.
A container used to serve drinks and liquids.
A container from which liquid is drunk.
Containers in which food and or drink is gathered or processed.
Containers used for cooking.
A container used in growing plants, either to contain or for use in their cultivation eg watering cans.
This does not include food or liquid storage.
A building or area where processes like bleaching, dressing, etc, are conducted under one roof.
A series of steps designed to enable fish to ascend a fall of water or a dam.
A large building where fish are stored before sale.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the farming of fish.
A crane fixed to a quay, used for the unloading of ships cargoes.
A battery mounted in the flank of a bastion from which flanking fire is directed across a curtain wall.
Small tower projecting from a castle wall, or other fortified wall. Allows defenders to fire along the length of the wall.
A building used to dry flax.
A street market.
A workshop, associated with a tannery, in which the fleece is removed from the skin prior to the tanning process.
A mill for shredding cloth, for use in flock paper, etc.
An outdoor or indoor place where flowers were sold.
A bridge for carrying a road or railway over another.
A system of petrol burners, pipework and pump houses on an airfield used to 'burn' away fog so that aircraft may take off and land safely.
Use both terms.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the large-scale production, processing and preserving of food and drink.
Terms included here are for small scale agricultural production. See also FOOD AND DRINK INDUSTRY SITE grouping in INDUSTRIAL class.
A room with special ventilation used for the slow drying of foodstuffs.
A specialist hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of foot disorders and diseases.
Use both terms
The residence of a ford keeper.
The court or enclosed space at the front of a building or structure.
A medieval court established for the administration of forest law.
Use both terms.
The dwelling and workshop of a framework knitter.
A school where no fees were charged.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
An indoor or outdoor market where fruit and vegetables are sold.
Includes sites associated with extraction.
A cable railway with ascending and descending cars counterbalanced.
An educational establishment primarily for children aged 16-18 years old but can provide education for more mature students.
A chapel in a church for penitents.
Buildings where gambling takes place.
An establishment used for gambling.
A place where gardening tools, plants, etc, are sold.
Use both terms.
A decorative or ornamental structure purposefully situated in a garden. Such as sculptures, sundials, bird baths, gnomes etc.
A path in a garden.
Use both terms.
Ornamental wrought iron screen associated with gate lodges or entrance lodges.
Stone, brick or wooden steps or stairs found in a garden.
A town laid out systematically with spacious and garden-like surroundings.
A table found in a garden, often made of stone.
A site where small electrical goods such as radios, lamps and heaters are manufactured.
A shelter for the storage of bicycles.
A place where furs are made into finished products.
A structure used for music, dance, ceremonial or civic events.
An office for the issuing of government stamps and receiving of stamp duty.
An educational establishment where law is taught.
The residence of a person employed in the textile industry.
A garden or collection of potted plants on the flat roof of a house or other building.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
A building in which the lay sisters resided. Lay sisters were not nuns and as such weren't bound by any vows. They could leave the convent and even marry if they wished.
An explosive-proof vaulted chamber used for the storage or ordnance.
A large store for the temporary accommodation of goods awaiting transportation to or from the sea.
A building where sugar is stored.
A slate situated at the end of a terrace for a coal company employee to wake the miners for their shift. The slate had the time of the shifts written on it.
A system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used during WWII to provide a counterfeit target for enemy aircraft.
A monument featuring a bank or mound constructed primarily of stone. Use specific type where known.
A roughly hemispherical mound constructed primarily of stones, normally containing or covering one or more human burials. The mound may be surrounded and partly retained by a low stone kerb.
A low, wide, circular ring or bank of stones surrounding an open, roughly circular area which is (or was initially) free of cairn material. The inner and outer faces of the bank may be kerbed.
A circular bank of stones and turf, sometimes accompanied by a ditch, surrounding a natural outcrop of rock, usually a tor, or an earthfast boulder.
A group of cairns occurring within close proximity to each other. Use for instances where the majority are clearance cairns. Also index specific types where known.
A group of cairns in close proximity which are predominantly funerary or ritual in nature.
An irregularly constructed, generally unstructured, mound of stones. Often, but not necessarily, circular. Normally a by product of field clearance for agricultural purposes.

A stone circle featuring four upright stones standing at the corners of an irregular quadrilateral. The monument may feature more than 4 stones, overall, but the corner stones are often the most prominent.
An approximately circular or oval setting of spaced, usually freestanding, upright stones. More than one circle may be present, arranged concentrically.
A monument consisting of parallel lines of standing stones, which appears to mark out an approach to another monument or monuments.
A house in a terrace built on top of another, with access at high and low level to either side.
The residence of a lifeboatman.
A building associated with the legal administration of a forest, eg. Forest of Dean.
A post, made of wood, metal or other material, erected to mark a particular spot in the landscape. Can be used for various reasons such as measurement, calibration etc.
A chapel for the use of travellers and pilgrims.
A public recreational complex centred around an open-air swimming pool. Use SWIMMING POOL as a component of LIDO.
The residence of a glover.
A factory where biscuits are manufactured.
A house of Roman Catholic nuns or canonesses.
A usually south-facing wall used for the cultivation of fruit plants.
An area attached to a house, or part of an estate used for pleasure and recreation.
Place where food or money was handed out to the poor.
A building for the storage of unbleached, untreated fabric.
Artificial mound of earth, turf and/or stone, normally constructed to contain or conceal burials. Use specific type where known.
A round barrow in which the mound and ditch are separated from each other by a berm. The ditch may be accompanied by an external (or occasionally internal) bank.
A form of round barrow intermediate between the Bell Barrow and the Disc Barrow. Only use where it is not possible to determine specific type.
A very fast small warship, armed with small calibre guns and torpedoes. Used for attacking enemy vessels, escort duties and anti submarine duties.

A short wide-beamed Dutch craft, often used as a fishing vessel or, in the 17th and 18th centuries, a privateer due to its manoeuvrability. Fitted with a ketch rig or variations thereof. Used extensively in the North Sea.
A heavily armoured capital ship with an armament composed entirely of large calibre guns and powered by stem turbines. In effect any battleship constructed after 1908.
A craft used to deepen shipping channels, harbours and other water courses.
A fishing boat using nets which are free to move with the tides and currents.
Cargo vessel specially constructed to carry bulk items such as grain. Does not include liquid cargoes.
A civil vessel disguised as a warship.
Name given to a vessel of the East India Company. Usually large, well built and magnificently decorated.
A passenger vessel equipped to carry a large number of emigrants usually with large third class decks and plenty of cargo space.
A warship used to provide an escort to other warships or merchant ships against attack.
A vessel used for inspecting vessels entering port during wartime.
A craft built with the intention of demonstrating or advertising a novel design feature.
A vessel with equipment for processing dead marine life whilst still at sea.
A vessel designed for the transport of persons and goods from one place to another an a regular schedule of sailings. Use specific type were known.
A tug equipped with water tanks and pumps for fighting fires at sea or on the shore line.
A vessel equipped with water tanks and pumps for fighting fires at sea or on the shore line.
A small vessel used to attack other vessels and setting themselves and then the enemy alight.
A vessel for policing fishing grounds and fishing vessels.
A vessel or craft used for catching or harvesting marine life by a variety of methods, use specific method where known.
A vessel for carrying messages between warships.
Large submarine intended to operate with a surface fleet at sea.
A small stem powered warship with its hull protected by iron plates. Used to bombard targets onshore, especially in the Crimean War.
Flat bottomed, two-masted Dutch coastal vessel of the sixteenth to nineteenth centuries. Sometimes used as an English term for fluit, also a flat-bottomed vessel.
A single decked cargo vessel carrying the majority of its cargo on deck.
A medium speed anti submarine escort vessel built from World War II
A three masted fully rigged warship armed with 24 to 38 guns on a single gundeck.
A vessel carrying square sails on all masts and having three or more masts.
Warship or trading vessel, three masted with a low forecastle.
Oared fighting ship with ancillary sails.
A small galley or Dutch trading vessel similar to a barge in construction.
A dredger with a grab hung on ropes or chains giving it unlimited depth of excavation. they can lift solids or pieces of wreckages and can work close to ships or to a dock wall.
A small sailing vessel armed with guns.
A small warship built to operate close to the shore or in river estuaries. Used for shore bombardment and patrol duties.
Craft used to maintain, supply or assist larger vessels whilst in harbour.
First practical submarine design. The first to use a combination of battery power and internal combustion engines.
A vessel used to carry away mud etc from a dredging machine and discharging it elsewhere.
A dredger which can act as its own hopper and can thus transport the mud which it picks up to dump it at the desired place.
A ship used for treating patients or moving them between a battle zone and a safe area.
A boat used as private or domestic living accomodation.
Small coastal vessel.
An old ship converted for a variety of uses for which it is not required to move under its own power.
Flat bottomed vessel used for coasting on the River Humber.
Warships constructed of iron plate or with wooden hulls covered by iron plates. Used as a generic name for the first examples of armour plated warships.
Flat bottomed vessel used for loading colliers in the north east, similar to a lighter.
A vessel with two masts, rigged as a ketch, used for coastal trading.
Inshore craft used for carrying troops and military equipment used either for beach landings or as a ferry. Use specific type where known.
Small landing craft often armoured, designed to carry infantrymen and their equipment ashore from larger vessels offshore.
Thin flexible sheets made from the pulp of wood or other fibrous matter.
External decorative plasterwork often incised or modelled with ornamental patterns. Usually applied to timber-framed houses, especially during 16th and 17th centuries.
Part-decomposed vegetable matter formed under waterlogged conditions into a firm, brown deposit resembling soil. Used as a brick for infilling in timber framed walls.
Rock fragment (diameter 4-64mm) larger than gravel and smaller than cobble, combined with other material e.g. flint, for decorative effect.
A render with small washed stones added as aggregate. Popular in the early 20th century.
Hard, fine grained, blue/grey coloured sandstone. Quarried in South Wales and the Bristol area and commonly used, throughout the country, as a stone roofing material (stone slate).
Use both terms.
Coarse grained, dark coloured granite, quarried in the Peterhead and Cairngall areas of Scotland, but used throughout the North.
Use both terms.
Wood of a coniferous tree native to Scotland and Scandinavia.
Use both terms.
Rammed earth or clay of a low moisture content used to make floors or walls, or found between shuttering.
Any tree, shrub or herb of cellulose form, normally subsisting in soil and producing its food through photosynthesis.
Lime plaster, consisting of lime and sand, is the oldest type of render. Applied externally to walls or onto laths for infill panels and usually limewashed.
Any of large class of polymers based on synthetic resins or modified natural polymers which may be moulded, extruded or cast while soft or liquid, which then set rigidly or slightly elastic in form.

Structural board comprising a core of thin layers of wood bonded together, which is faced on one or both sides with a sheet of metal, usually galvanised steel or aluminium. Mainly used for external wall cladding.

Thin layers of wood, bonded together to form a structural board. The grain of the adjacent layers lie across one another to give structural strength. Produced since mid 19th century for use in interior joinery, since 1930's for exterior use.
Very tough transparent sheeting often used for security glazing.
Compact, grey/green/brown/white-speckled coloured igneous rock, peculiar to Cornwall. It is easy to carve and readily takes a polish, hence its similarity to British marbles.
A type of thermoplastic polymer which is versatile and cheap, often referred to as PVC. This includes plasticized PVC and unplasticized PVC (uPVC).
A form of cement originally named since it was said to be like Portland Stone in appearance.
Fine to coarse grained, cream to green/grey coloured oolitic limestone. Quarried since Roman times, it is one of Britain's best building stones, hence its use throughout the country.
Concrete, containing bars or wires, which is compressed to greatly increase its strength.
Conglomerate consisting of rounded flint pebbles held together in a natural silica and sand cement.

A patented manmade rock invented by James Pulham and Son of Broxbourne. Pulhamite was used to join natural rocks together or crafted to simulate natural stone features. It is an artificial form of sandstone.
Use both terms.

Collective name for the oolitic limestone quarried in the Isle of Purbeck region, geologically classified into two main groups. Firstly, a fine grained whitish variety, Purbeck Portland, secondly a fossil-rich cream/gold to grey variety, Swanage Stone etc
Hard, transparent, often coloured mineral. Can be found on its own as crystals and veins but also as a major constituent of rocks such as granite. Often used decoratively.
Medium grained, hard, white/grey coloured stone consisting of quartz and often silica, produced by the metamorphosis of sandstone.
Stonemason's term for any coarse/hard stone that is not easily worked. Index with specific stone type where given. Not to be confused with Kentish Ragstone.
The tall, straight stalks or stems formed by plants found in the wetland areas, particularly The Fens. Used as a roofing material, the reed is laid with the ends forming the exposed covering surface.
Soft, medium grained, green/grey coloured, highly calcareous, cretaceous sandstone. Mined (more frequently than quarried) since pre-Norman times from the Reigate area of Surrey.
Aggregate, cement and mortar combined with structural elements of iron or steel mesh or rod reinforcement to form stonelike masses for load bearing, structural building work.
A building containing a range of processes for cleaning and processing metallic ores.
A component part of a treadmill crane, the shed is used to enclose the treadwheel.
A mill used for the sizing and drying of warp threads before they were wound onto warp beams as part of the power-weaving process.
A site used for the production and/or working of glass.
A hydraulically-powered crane constructed from open box girders.
A hydraulically-powered crane where the jib and windlass are mounted on a central pillar.
A site used for the production and/or working of metallic iron.
A site used for the production and/or working of metallic lead.
Monument visible as remains of former earthworks.
Monument visible on the sea, lake or river bed, either totally submerged at all times, or exposed at low tide, low water conditions etc.
A monument visible as a trace on marine survey equipment

Monument visible, usually from the air, due to the fill of features being of a different colour than the surrounding subsoil. Soilmarks show up well in ploughed fields or areas where the topsoil has been stripped.  Term derived from AN32 Glossary

Term derived from EH RSM Form list
Term derived from EH RSM Form list

Term derived from EH RSM Form list
A maritime monument where the remains of a vessel are known to exist but where no detailed information is available.
A maritime monument where the hull of a vessel is mostly in one piece, with large pieces of the superstructure intact.
A maritime monument where the remains of a vessel are scattered over a wide area.
An object lying on the sea bed detected by marine survey equipment that emits and receives high frequency sound waves.
An object projecting out of the sea bed detected by marine survey equipment that emits and receives high frequency sound waves projected sideways from a boat or towed array.
An object in the sea bed detected by marine survey equipment that shows the contours of the sea bed beneath a vessel.
A maritime monument where the fabric of a vessel has collapsed, leaving the hull structure flat on the sea bed but not widely dispersed.
A stone which has a socket for an unknown function. Use specific term where known.
A specialist hospital treating patients with chest disorders and diseases, can be pre sanatoria.
Large inshore craft with a retractable loading ramp in the bow. Used to carry tanks ashore for a beach landing or as a tank ferry.
Small ocean going vessel fitted with loading doors in the bow. Used for ferrying tanks or other fighting vehicles to beach landings.
Craft intended for recreation and not intended for any commercial use.
A cargo vessel constructed in the U.S.A. during World War II from prefabricated sections by welding.

A boat specifically designed for saving lives at sea, they can be either: a boat carried on a larger vessel for use in emergency evacuation of crew and passengers in the event of shipwreck or a boat built for the purpose of shore-to-sea rescue missions.
Large warship with no armour and a high speed. Used for reconnaisance and raids on enemy merchant shipping.
Unpowered flat bottomed vessel, used for carrying cargo from ship to shore or as a working platform.
A small vessel used to carry supplies and personnel to lighthouses.
Normally an unpowered vessel, moored in places where the construction of a lighthouse is impractical.
A ship belonging to a shipping company which carries passengers on a scheduled route usually applied to steam ships only.
A designed for the carriage of livestock usually cattle or sheep.
A boat fashioned out of a section of tree trunk.
A vessel with a lug sail rig. A lug is a four sided sail set on a lug or yard.
The class term, use more specific terms.
Small submarine with a two or three man crew. Used for special missions such as sinking warships in heavily defended harbours.
A vessel used for carrying mines between warships and supply depots.
A submarine built or adapted to carry mines and lay minefields.
A ship designed or modified to carry large numbers of mines and be able to lay them as a minefield.
A vessel designed or adapted to sweep and explode mined areas at sea without prior detection. (See Minehunter for vessels that detect and destroy individual mines).
A barge with a crane or sheer legs used for moving and maintaining mooring buoys.
A vessel used to put down and pick up moorings on the sea bed for large vessels.
A small fast warship powered by diesel or petrol engines. Built during World War II for coastal patrol work and anti shipping missions close in shore
Generic name for a small steam or power boat often carried on board a larger vessel.
A small warship powered by petrol or diesel engines and armed with torpedo tubes and small guns. Used for coastal anti shipping patrols and warfare in coastal waters.
A flat bottomed vessel for receiving mud and other material from a dredger.

An artificial harbour, constructed using prefabricated, concrete caissons, floating breakwaters and blockships, which were towed across the channel and assembled off the coast of Normandy to assist the allied forces after the D-Day landings in June 1944.
A vessel used to carry essential supplies, such as food and armaments, to naval ships in order to keep them replenished whilst on patrol. Use more specific term.
Small vessel built or adapted to lay and recover anti submarine nets in harbours and anchorages.
Generic term for all vessels used to supply warships with any type of fuel.
A vessel used for carrying weapons and ammunition to warships.
A sloop used for carrying weapons and ammunition to warships.

A fishing vessel which tows a dredger to gather oysters. This is an iron wedge shaped contrivance with a small net attached. Towed behind the vessel the iron wedge loosens the oysters and they fall into the net.
A fast, armed vessel, small in size, often used for despatches and mail.
A steam vessel propelled by a pair of paddle wheels amidships or a single wheel astern, driven by a reciprocating engine.
A vessel designed principally for the carriage of fare paying passengers.
A small warship engaged in patrolling coastal waters.
Diesel engined submarine designed for long ocean voyages in search of enemy shipping.
Flat bottomed vessel used as a platform for a pile driver.
A vessel used to carry a pilot to a ship.
Small square rigged ship with a narrow overhanging stern.
A small two masted craft, with oars as well as sails.
A flat bottomed boat or hollow float of which a number are used to support a temporary bridge over a river.
A vessel used for storing and issuing gunpowder, usually moored well away from the dockyard.
Demasted old ship used as a floating prison.
A private fighting ship under a letter of marque or financed by subscribers, shareholders or individuals.
A small merchant ship or warship with concealed weapons, intended as a trap for enemy submarines.
Any vessel designed for speed or endurance racing.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Narrow strips of wood which can form the groundwork for slates, panels or plaster work.
Use both terms.
Metal used primarily for roof coverings and window fittings. It is easy to work, can be worked cold and does not rust which makes it suitable for holding or repelling water.
Animal skin that has been hardened or treated by a tanning process.
Collective term for the building limestones formed during the Lower Jurassic period.
A concrete which is either aerated or made from lightweight aggregate.

Calcium Oxide obtained by heating limestone in a kiln. Used as a constituent of modern mortar, or as slaked (non-hydraulic) lime in lime putty, daub, limewash and traditional lime plaster, mortar and renders.
Use both terms.
Sedimentary rock consisting mainly of calcium carbonate. Varying in grain size, colour and hardness, quarried and used throughout the country.
Generic term for the oolitic limestones quarried in Northamptonshire, Lincolnshire and Rutland. Varying in grain size from medium to coarse, and colour from cream to pale brown.

Composed of loose uncombed lengths of harvested wheat which are formed into bundles for laying. Distinctive appearance with both ears and butts visible on the surface traditionally using hazel spars which hold the straw in place.

Permian limestones which have had their chemical composition naturally altered with the calcium content being replaced by magnesium. Fine grained and varying from yellow/brown to cream in colour, although they weather to a dark grey.
Fine earthenware with raised patterns of coloured decoration in the form of an enamel or coloured opaque glaze. Use for decorative wall facings.
A soft, grey to white coloured, sandstone formed during the Cretaceous period, whose sand grains are cemented together with lime.

A material or combination of materials manufactured by human effort, or fashioned into shape by man or a man made industrial process (excluding metal). See MAN MADE MATERIAL Class List for narrow terms.

Collective name for, in a true geological sense, a metamorphosed limestone, eg. Carrara marble, and, in the British sense any decorative stone that will take a polish, eg. Purbeck marble. In the latter's case index with specific stone type where given.
Fine grained, iron rich, liassic limestone, found in Dorset, Somerset, Oxfordshire, Northamptonshire, Leicestershire and Rutland.
A raw material determined by its form or a finished product material characterised by its end shape or form. See MATERIAL <BY FORM> Class List for narrow terms.
Tile nailed externally to a wall and usually laid in mortar designed to present a brick-like appearance.

Class of elements and alloys that are characteristically lustrous,ductile, fusible and malleable. These are extracted from ore minerals originally existing in nature and processed before becoming a recognisable metal. See METAL Class List for narrow terms
Natural inorganic substance possessing a definite chemical composition in a crystalline form. See MINERAL Class Listnfor narrow terms.

Stonemason's name for granite found lying upon the moorland surface, as opposed to having been quarried, in the West Country and the Lake District. Used, as found, since prehistoric times, in later years was often dressed and shaped.
A mixture of lime or more recently cement with sand and water used for bonding stones or bricks.
Very hard, rough medium/coarse grained, pink to grey coloured granite. Usually found and quarried in Leicestershire.
Wet soil, sand or other earthy matter combined with ballast and bonded with straw or other binding material. Walls are built in the absence of shuttering by the simple process of pitching in layers.
A native hardwood of the Beech family with hard and durable characteristics which traditionally made it appropriate for structural work.
Limestone formed during the Jurassic period. Composed of ooliths, literally small rock particles with the appearance of fish roe.
Large board used for covering the internal surfaces of a building, ie. floors, walls and ceilings. Some forms can be used as external cladding.
Curved, interlocking roof tile of S-shaped section usually made of clay or concrete.
A works where cotton waste is stored or processed.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Bridgettine order.
A site where weapons and/or explosives are tested experimentally, or are routinely tested as part of a manufacturing quality control process.
A flat floating framework of planks or other materials used for supporting or carrying persons or goods.
A training ship to which boys who had committed petty crimes were sentenced for 4 to 5 years to be reformed and trained as sailors.
A rescue tug equipped to care for survivors from torpedoed vessels and also available for towing to port ships damaged by enemy action.
A specially equipped ship designed to care for survivors of stricken vessels and offshore drilling platforms. These ships were often converted naval trawlers or minesweepers.
A single masted cutter built specifically for the prevention of smuggling and the enforcement of customs regulations.
A small warship with a shallow draught. Used for patrol duties and shore bombardment on major rivers.
A sailing vessel defined by a combination of such factors as hull design, locality and rig.
The characteristics of a sailing vessel where her type is determined by her masts and sails.
A small and powerful vessel used to assist vessels that are sinking or disabled at sea.
A vessel used for the underwater recovery of a ship and/or her contents or to assist vessels that are sinking.
Two masted ship with fore and aft sails and two or more masts.
A vessel used to maintain supply or assist larger vessels. Use more specific term.
A vessel equipped with sealed tanks for transporting sewage and dumping it in deep water.
A small light vessel with a schooner rig often used for fishing.
Old ship with a hull stripped to the water line and used as a platform for mounting the sheers used to lift masts into and out of sailing ships.
A sailing ship with a sufficient numerically large gun armament to stand in the line of battle.
A vessel with a single mast, fore and aft rigged.
Any small rigged warship below the sailing classification of frigate.
Small fishing craft used mainly for fishing, cutter or ketch rigged.
Two masted merchant vessel, rigged as a brig.
A barge with a spritsail rig commonly found on the River Thames.
A vessel with a type of rigging where the main driving sails are fixed to yards which lie square to the mast.
A demasted old ship used for storing items.
A ship in government use, used to carry naval or military stores.
A vessel designed to operate below the surface of the sea.
British 'M' class submarine modified to carry and launch a small sea plane.
A dredger that works by the use of suction.
A craft which is equipped for and performs hydrographic surveys.
A barge fitted with a large tank in its hull for carried liquid cargoes.
A ship designed specifically for the carriage of liquid cargoes, particularly oil.
An obsolete vessel used as a weapons target.
A small vessel attached to a larger vessel (usually a warship) for general harbour duties such as taking crewmen ashore or fetching supplies.
A small fast warship developed in the late nineteenth century. Armed principally with quick firing guns to destroy enemy torpedo boats.
A craft used to retrieve torpedoes after practice firings.
Vessels of various types used specifically for providing an initial training in seamanship.
A vessel used for transporting passengers or goods.
A fishing vessel specially designed to operate and trawl for the catching of bottom lying fish. Use with power where known.
Any vessel operated by Trinity house masters and brethren in the maintenance of lighthouses, lightships, buoys and other navigation aids.
A vessel used for the transport of troops, either during wartime or for garrison duties in peacetime.
A small cargo boat found on the River Severn in England, with a mast which could be taken down to allow the boat to pass under low bridges.
A relatively small and heavily built vessel equipped with large engines. Used for towing ships at sea or manouevring them in tight spaces.
A warship constructed of iron plate with its main armament mounted in a revolving turret on deck.

The British designation for any German submarine built for military purposes. U-Boat is an anglicization of the German U-Boot, an abbreviation for Unterseeboot (Undersea Boat). In German U-Boot refers to any submarine.
A vessel used to carry supplies to warships.
A ship that is built and primarily intended for war.
A small vessel used to carry fresh water to ships at anchor or in harbour.
A craft available for public hire for short journeys.
Any vessel in use by the West India Company.
A craft employed to harpoon whales and bring them in to be processed.
A ship used to process whales into saleable products.
Any vessel involved in the catching or transportation of whales.
A decked sailing vessel of shallow draft.
A general term for the weatherproof coat on the external walls of a building.
By-product or waste, resulting from an industrial process.
Fine grained, acidic, light-grey/white/ brown/red-coloured igneous rock.

Technically a quick setting hydraulic cement or lime,but term has been adapted to denote cement made from burning lumps of marl found in London clay,a technique adopted for C19th building work. Name not intended to denote a relationship with Roman period
Single lap regular shaped roof covering which can have one or more water channels. Typically made of clay or concrete. The name does not denote a relationship with the Roman period.
A render including an aggregate of gravel or stone chipping thrown rather than trowelled onto an external wall.
Use both terms.

Flexible, synthetic, polymeric organic material formed by chemical synthesis usually in imitation of a natural substance. It can be moulded to shape, extruded or formed into a sheet from solid or foam material.
Rough, unhewn, undressed building stones with irregular faces, generally not laid in regular courses. Index with type of stone if specified.
Granular material consisting of small eroded fragments of rock or mineral grains, finer than gravel used as an ingredient in mortar and other traditional building materials.

Geologically sandstone consists of particles of quartz naturally cemented together by either silica, calcium or iron. It is this geological composition that accounts for the varying colours and grain sizes found in the many building sandstones.
Extremely hard, fine grained, grey to brown silica rich sandstone. It is often found on the surface of the South Downs and has been used, as found, since prehistoric times.

Composite substance of plaster formed by gypsum, sand and lime and coloured with pigments, fixed under heat and highly polished. Used to imitate marble and popular in the 17th and 18th centuries for architectural features.
Medium to coarse grained metamorphic rock, colour being determined by its dominant mineral. Often used for floor and wall cladding.

Collective term for the Scottish Slates including the Aberdeen/Baniff and Ballachulish/Easdale groups. Fine grained, varying in colour from brown to dark grey/blue. Geologically different from Lake District, Welsh and West Country groups of slate.
Conglomerate consisting of nodules of calcium rich clay (marl). Used as a building stone from Roman times and as a key ingredient in Parker's Roman Cement, between 1796 and circa 1850.

Medium to coarse grained, green to dark red/black coloured igneous rock, mainly found on The Lizard, South West Cornwall. Due to its fragmentary structure, Serpentine is mainly used for decorative and ornamental purposes.
Soft, very fine grained, dark coloured, sedimentary rock which splits easily.
Hard, coarse grained, grey to red/brown coloured granite. Used predominantly for tombstones becasuse of its ability to take a polish, but it is also in demand for underwater construction.
Hard, protective covering made largely of calcium salts secreted by soft bodied invertebrate animals.
Wooden roof tile (traditionally oak) which is riven or sawn from good quality timber to a regular size and used as a roof and/or wall covering. Index with type of wood if known.
Fine grained, yellow/buff to grey/black coloured sedimentary rock.
A precious metal of lustrous white colour with great malleability and ductility.
One of only three 'true' British marbles, white in colour, predominantly used for sculptures and statues.
Waste material or dross separated from metals during smelting or refining.

Collective term for a hard, fine grained, dark coloured metamorphic rock, which splits easily; hence its common use as a roofing and flooring material, and a functional description for any rectangular, sheet, roofing material.
Cement/water mix often used as covering. Use this for entries including slurrying and slurried.
Use both terms.
Glass to control or reduce the effects of the sun, includes both reflective and absorpative types of glass.

Single lap roof covering made of clay. Half cylinder in profile although one end is slightly wider than the other. A Spanish tile roof covering comprises under-tiles and over-tiles, the two have the same shape, but the under-tile is slightly larger.
Any vessel propelled by sail or power and used for pleasure and not plying for hire.

TERM: FIRST RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A ship of the line mounting 100 guns or more on three gundecks.

TERM: SECOND RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A ship of the line mounting between 90 and 98 guns on three gun decks

TERM: THIRD RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A ship of the line mounting between 64 and 80 guns typically built with two gun decks.

TERM: FOURTH RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A ship of the line mounting between 46 and 64 guns

TERM: FIFTH RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A sailing frigate mounting 32 to 44 guns with the main battery on a single deck.

TERM: SIXTH RATE SHIP OF THE LINE
SCOPE_NOTE: A small warship mounting between 20 and 28 nine-pounder guns on a single deck.
A building or group of buildings, incorporating radio masts, built to intercept radio transmissions from enemy vessels and aircraft during WWI.
A place or building where animals can be washed. Often in the form of a pool with a walled funnel-like structure enabling animals to be guided into the pool.

A structure to which a net filled with mail bags is attached. Situated next to railway lines, it allows mail to be collected by a train without it stopping, the bag being 'caught' by the train as it passed. Can also be used to 'catch' mail.

A monument previously consisting of a built structure, but which has been demolished, such that only a ground plan and foundations or similar are thought to remain. Where all below ground traces have also been removed use DESTROYED MONUMENT.
A factory or plant for the manufacture of ice using mechanized refrigeration techniques.
A shallow pond, often located near an ICEHOUSE, built to provide ice during the winter.
A Monument whose presence is inferred from artefacts found in stratified below ground deposits, as distinct from surface collection or chance find.
A building used by a group of people who meet socially to participate in activities, usually related to a particular interest or occupation.
A large, luxuriously appointed hotel.
A building, or room within a brewery, where beer or cider undergoes fermentation in vats or tuns.
A fence or row of stakes, often with nets attached forming an enclosure within a river or harbour and used for catching, or holding, fish.
A lock, often containing a fish ladder, which allows fish to swim upstream bypassing a weir or other obstacle.
A firm beach or foreshore used for landing and loading of ships and other vessels. In more recent times hards have been reinforced with concrete.
A system of long, continuous banks and/or ditches dividing land into well defined areas. Possibly used for controlling livestock
Long parallel soil ridges less than 5 metres across separated by furrows, formed by using a heavy plough capable of turning the soil.
A terraced field usually found on hillsides. Comprising a flat strip of land, called the tread, and a steep, scarped lynchet or edge, called the riser.
A workshop used by a joiner; a craftsman working with wood and producing more ornate work than that of a carpenter.
Use both terms.

A mill used for the production of mortar; a combination of sand, lime and water, used to make the joints between courses of bricks in buildings. In more recent times cement has replaced lime to create a quicker drying mortar.
A structure used for the transmission and interception of radio signals. Usually composed of a number of different elements such as aerials, receiving equipment and supporting pylons.
A two masted craft which is square rigged on the foremast and fore and aft rigged on the main mast.
A small one masted craft, often using oars as well as sails.
A large ship's boat powered by oars and or an engine.
A craft with two masts.It is usually cutter rigged on the foremast and has a small mizzen mast.

A Roman under-floor heating system in which hot air heated by a stoked furnace, flowed through channels, created by either raising the floor on pillars of brick and tile or cutting channels into the concrete floor and tiling over them.
A small, walled fortlet, situated every Roman mile along the length of Hadrian's Wall to defend a gateway allowing the passage of people and as a garrison to accommodate patrol troops.
A small cargo craft, usually with two masts and a lateen rig.
A small, single-masted merchant vessel, designed for maximum hold capacity and not for sailing ability.
A broad, flat-bottomed boat.
A craft on which is a machine for the loading and unloading of grain to and from a warehouse.
A mound used to elevate buildings associated with a fishery e.g. smoke houses, above the level of a flood plain.
A structure consisting of a large, metal framework holding a skyward facing dish. Used for transmitting and receiving signals which are relayed by satellite.
A group of buildings and satellite dishes used to transmit and receive signals relayed by satellites.
A structure which allows aircraft fitted with radar equipment to 'home' in on an airfield in the dark or in poor visibility, and land safely. Radar beacons can also be used as navigation aids.
A commercial building used primarily as a trading place for breweries and hop merchants.
An alloy of iron and carbon, its strength makes it suitable for load bearing purposes. It is primarily used in structural steelwork and concrete reinforcement.
Rock of definite form and size, usually artificially shaped. See STONE CLass List for narrow terms.
Roofing material consisting of stems or stalks of wheat, rye, oats or barley separated from grain and laid flat in 'yealms' which form an overlapping surface which sheds water.
Smooth rendering applied to the exterior of buildings which may be incised to suggest coursed masonry. Made of lime and sand or brick dust, and more recently, cement.
Use both terms.
Fine grained, buff, brown to green coloured Cretaceous sandstone. Quarried at various locations in Sussex. Not to be confused with Sussex marble which is a cretaceous limestone.
Use both terms.
Hard, coarse grained, green to pink coloured igneous rock. Commonly used as a polished cladding.
Thick, viscid liquid, obtained by the distillation of wood, coal or other organic substances, chemically a mixture of hydrocarbons with resins.
Road or paving material combining crushed stone, rolled and mixed with bitumen type mixer.
Hard, unglazed, brown, versatile earthenware which can be used as a tile or moulded into statuary. Used in a structural or semi-structural context as a moulded hollow block.
Hard, fossil rich, white to deep red coloured limestone, laid down during the Tertiary period. Used since Roman times because of its good durability and weathering properties.
Squared block of glass, tile, stone or marble used in mosaic.
A woven or bonded fabric or cloth. See TEXTILE Class List for narrow terms.
Traditional roof covering consisting of materials such as reed, straw or heather layered and fastened together onto roof to form a run off to prevent water penetration.
Tablet of a uniform shape. Used as finishing or covering materials which fit together in a regular format.
Wood, cut and seasoned so forming or capable of forming any part of a structure. May be treated with preservative before use.
Malleable metal used for roofing and for alloys such as bronze.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Very light, depositional limestone formed by the precipitation of calcium carbonate rich water (Tufa). The more dense and compact form, Travertine, is formed in a similar way.
Layer of grass with earth and matted roots cut from the ground and used for earth buildings and as a covering material.
Pertaining to or deriving from a botanical living organism. See VEGETAL Class List for narrow terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.

Wooden rods or stakes which can be interlaced with twigs or branches to make walls or fences, or more commonly, to form the basis of panels in traditional timber framed buildings which are then covered with daub.
Fine grained, brown/yellow to dark grey coloured cretaceous sandstone. It is a particularly good freestone and was often used for ashlar finishes.
Length of timber boarding (usually elm, now pine) fixed horizontally or vertically to the exterior of a structure which may be 'tongue and grooved' or 'feathered' to provide external protection.
An alloy of steel.
Collective term for the North and South Wales groups of slate. Hard, fine grained, metamorphic rock, with varying dark shades.

Collective term for the slates from Devon and Cornwall. Hard, fine grained metamorphic rock. Varying in colour from dark grey/green to blueish/grey. West Country Slate is geologically different from both Lake District and Welsh Slate.
A piece of wood scored across with notches for the items of an account and then split into halves of which each party kept one.
Northern quarryman's name for any fine grained, dark grey/black to green coloured igneous rock. Index with specific stone type where given.

A device for telling the time by the sun, using the shadow cast by a gnomon, or sometimes a spot of light through a small hole. They were often used for checking the accuracy of clocks. They range from panels on the sides of churches to pocket watch size.
A jar used to store medicines, drugs or the constituent parts of medicines and drugs.
One of a set, used as standards for specific coins, often bearing stamps and other marks of authenticity.
A weight used with letter scales for weighing letters or parcels and establishing the required postal rate.

A place of worship for the Knights of the Order of the Hospital of St John of Jerusalem, a military order dedicated to the provision of hospitality for pilgrims, to the care of the sick and to the protection of the Holy Land.
A stable located at a railway station or goods yard. Horses were necessary both for freight and passengers to continue their journey beyond the railway.
A public music or dancing establishment often with facilities for gambling.
An object which is propelled by force away from a launcher, which can include from a human.
Armour designed to protect the leg or parts of the leg. For specific foot protection use FOOT GUARD
A form of armour made up of overlapping squares of protective material.
Armour made up segmentally, usually of bands of material.
A gun designed to be held in one hand. It has a short barrel length compared to long guns.
A hand held long barrelled gun.

A pistol fired by use of a flintlock.A gunflint is held in the lock which on pulling the trigger pushes back the pan cover creating sparks which set off the powder in the pan causing a flame to go through and set off the charge in the barrel.
A musket fired by a piece of burning match being held in the lock which, when the trigger was pulled, would contact with powder in the pan to set off the charge.

A musket where a wheel on the lock is wound back and when the trigger is pulled the wheel moves dragging pieces of iron pyrites over the lock tocreate sparks and set powder in the pan off and so firing the main charge.
A musket with a snaphance lock. This lock consisted of a flint and steel but the pan cover was separate to the steel unlike the flintlock.
A system of trenches dug by troops for practice purposes.

A factory used for the production of artificial limbs. They were often located within the precincts of a hospital, to enable fittings to take place and help the amputee to get used to wearing the limb.
A tool used to pound, crush or beat an object.
A method of grinding cereals where one stone is rotated on another by hand.
A bent piece of metal or bone, often with a barb, which is tied to a line and used to catch fish.
A trap designed and used to catch fish.
Line used with hooks attached to it in order to catch fish.
A long tapered flexible pole used with a fishing line and usually with a fishing reel.
A tool used for weeding and breaking up the ground prior to planting.
An object designed to float in water and to support a net.
A long handled fork with two or three long curved tines for tossing straw or hay.
A knife designed to be used for pruning plants.
A machine for cutting down cereal crops.
A hooked blade used to cut crops. All the blade is to one side of the handle rather than being on both sides as in a sickle.
A machine for mechanically separating the grain from the straw and husks.
A device for separating grain from chaff by means of a wind or current of air.
A large, flattish basket used in winnowing the chaff from the grain.
A large fork with wide spaces between its tines, used to throw grain etc into a breeze to separate grain from chaff.
A device for winding and casting a fishing line, consisting of a revolving spool with a handle attached to a fishing rod.
A weight attached to a fishing line in order to help it sink towards the bottom.
Garden comprising rockwork features including grottoes, cascades and arches, often in different architectural styles ie. Gothic, Chinese and rustic. In use from the mid C18.
A bell worn by an animal, eg sheep, goats, cows and hawks, to inform the owner of the animal's position.
A band of material, often leather, or a chain or similar worn around the neck of an animal for identification and or restraint. Where this is part of harness use the specific harness term.
Pieces of leather connected to a bridle designed to direct a horse's vision straight forward only.
Lenses worn in a frame designed to improve or protect the vision of the wearer.
The hood used to completely cover a hawk's head.
A head cover which can be attached to a piece of outerwear, eg a coat, or can be separate.
The front piece of horse armour.
Headgear for a horse, usually consisting of a series of buckled straps and a mouthpiece, bridle bit, by which the horse is controlled.
A hook on harness to help attach items.
Decorative fitting hung from harness.
A ring fixed to a vehicle through which the reins were passed.
A strap or series of straps and or bars worn over the mouth of an animal to prevent it biting.
A shaft sunk into the ground to reach the water level.
A tube for the transport of liquids and gases eg for drainage purposes.
The top stone of an arch which holds it all in place.
Stone used as a building material which has been finished, or dressed, before use.
A long vertical pillar usually of stone used as a structural support in buildings often artistically sculpted or shaped.
A structure used to dry turf on. Turves were used as a fuel and as a roofing material.

A building, similar in style to a telephone exchange but smaller. They were used to compensate for the inadequacies of 1920's and 30's equipment over long distances, by repeating the signal every 200 miles.
A settlement located on or near to the shores of a lake. Buildings associated with lake villages are usually raised on piles to prevent them from being flooded.
A building for the storage, repair and maintenance of chains for lighthouses, lightships and lightbouys.
A house which bears signs of fortification. These often include crenellated battlements and narrow slit-like windows.
A school where specialist skills, relating to a particular subject, are taught. Use specific type where known.
A building used, as a meeting place and administration block, by an organization run for the benefit of students at a school, college or university.
A crude, stone built structure, often roofless, used by tin miners to store equipment.
A buoy with a compartment into which shipwrecked mariners could climb to await rescue.
A stepped, roadside platform, usually of stone on which a sedan chair was placed to allow the porters to lift the chair without having to bend.
A site containing slipways and associated buildings used specifically for the repair of ships and larger ocean-going craft.
A crane, located in an engineering workshop or similar establishment, which can be moved on rails and thus used anywhere within the workshop.

A structure consisting of three stretches of tramline joined by points. The tram is able to go forward, reverse and then go forward again changing line each time until it has turned around completely.
Apparatus used for applying a mechanical force, or to perform a particular function. Use more specific type where known.
A school in which the funds were raised through a system of shareholding whereby parents bought shares in the school and thus paid for their children's education.
A school attended by children between the ages of eleven and sixteen offering a vocationally orientated curriculum.
A one or two storey reinforced concrete structure, usually associated with two T shaped radio masts. Term is specific to army anti-aircraft control centres operational between 1950-55.
A site or structure associated with the activities of the Royal Observer Corps. The Corps was formed on 1 January 1947 and disbanded in 1991.
A ditch associated with a palisade.
A farmyard or enclosure containing regularly built stacks of hay, corn, peas etc.
A structure, building or room within a building, used by a local authority for the continuance of local government in the event of a military or civil emergency.
A planned administrative capital for local government which provided amenities for the Roman and peregrine (non-Roman) inhabitants of the town.

A site which has produced evidence of in situ working of stone for the manufacture of tools, weapons or other objects. Such sites will usually, but not always, be of prehistoric date. Use object material where known.
A spatially discrete, though sometimes extensive, scatter of flint artefacts recovered from the surface, eg. by fieldwalking, rather than from a particular archaeological context.
An observation post for a naval officer in charge of a marine minefield.
A bakehouse built in association with a group of dwellings who shared the baking facilities. Often found in model settlements.
A basement or cellar, usually within a house, leased as a separate dwelling.

A pit lined with the bony cores of animal horns. Thought to date from the 17th/18th centuries and believed to have been used in the tanning industry although some may have been used for casting cannon.
A structure used for the production of hydraulic power. A head of water was raised at the top of the tower by means of pumps. Used for powering machinery.

A round house indicated by the presence of a low, roughly circular bank of turf, earth or stone, which formed the base of the walls. Characteristic of the later prehistoric period. Where several occur together use HUT CIRCLE SETTLEMENT.
A settlement showing evidence for one or more hut circles, enclosed by a distinct boundary ditch, wall, earth rampart or similar barrier. Characteristic of the later prehistoric period.
A fortified Roman site, usually under 1 hectare in area, strategically situated, housing small military patrols, often defended by a rampart, one or two ditches and a gate.

A small rectangular or sub circular area or areas bounded by an earthwork, ditch or similar boundary, where one side is formed by an existing linear boundary, forming a pattern reminiscent of clothes hanging from a washing line.
A monument consisting of an area of land enclosed by a ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier, where the boundary follows an irregular curving course.
A monument consisting of an area enclosed by a ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier, where the barrier follows a circular course, but is not regularly laid out.
A town founded as an act of government by charter to house Roman or Latin citizens, usually retired legionaires who had been granted land within a territorium.
An aisled timber or masonry hall, serving as the chief administrative public meeting centre and law courts for a Roman town. Usually located alongside the forum.
A tunnel running under a river or through a hill along which vehicles may travel.
The entrance to a road tunnel, sometimes of a grand construction.
A track inlaid into the road surface of a street or road, on which tram cars run for the conveyance of passengers.
An optical instrument for making distant objects appear nearer and larger, usually found at an observatory, through which astronomical or meteorological phenomena may be observed.
An optical instrument for making distant objects appear nearer and larger, often found on the promenade or pleasure pier at a seaside resort or at a site of scenic beauty.
A site containing a tennis court, changing facilities and a club house.
A modern building in which the load is carried by a metal girder framework and infilled with a light curtain wall.
A house constructed with a basic timber framework; between the members are panels which can be infilled with timber, wattle and daub, plaster, brick or other materials.
A modern building in which the load is carried by a reinforced concrete framework. Use for reinforced concrete buildings.
An area of cultivated, managed woodland producing wood which is used for a variety of purposes.
An indoor or outdoor market where leather and untreated animal hides are sold.
A large building, situated by or near a canal, used for the temporary storage of goods or merchandise awaiting transportation to or from the canal.
A large wooden structure built alongside the edge of a canal where narrow boats may lie for the loading and unloading of goods.
A post set up alongside a canal to mark the miles to and from a place.
A place where products are manufactured from wood.
An artificial area of open water, situated on a canal, enclosed by masonry and fitted with dock gates in which ships can be repaired, loaded/unloaded or berthed.
An enclosure containing a dock, boat yard, warehouse, etc, in which canal vessels are built and repaired, and all sorts of stores and merchandise for transportation brought together.
A small eating and drinking establishment or refreshment bar at a railway station for the use of passengers.
A building or room where railway tickets may be bought and administrative duties associated with a railway are conducted.
A raised floor along the side of a line at a railway station, for convenience in entering and alighting from a train.
A tunnel running under a river or a hillside through which a railway line runs.
A subscription club, usually with a library and newspaper room, established from c.1815-1860, their educational function gradually taken over by the public libraries in the later 19th century.
An inland settlement such as Runcorn, Ellesmere Port or Stourport, that combines docks and terminal facilities at the interface between land and canal transportation systems.
A supply of water used to keep canals that were vulnerable to water shortage topped up.
A small building housing a valve which controls the flow within a water regulation system.
A massive structure designed to transfer canal boats between different canal or river navigations, eg. Anderton boat lift.
A winch powered by a small steam engine used to drag barges, boats and other vehicles up an inclined plane.

A rectangular chamber of brick or stone with heavy wooden gates at either end equipped with sluices to let water in and out, thereby enabling a canal boat to be lowered or raised to a different level.
A place of meeting and worship for Brethren, a fundamentalist puritan sect founded in Ireland in the late 1820s and established in England in Plymouth in the 1830s.
A place of worship for Primitive Methodists, a group who were formed in Staffordshire and influenced by American evangelical ideas and who left the Methodists in 1811.
A place of worship for Methodists, a movement founded by John Wesley. Following his death in 1791 there were many secessions.
A place of worship for followers of the Countess of Huntingdon's Connexion, a Calvinistic Methodist sect founded in the 1740s by Selina Hastings, Countess of Huntingdon.
A place of worship for Christadelphians, a fundamentalist sect founded in America in the late 1840s who rejected the trinity and awaited the second coming of Christ.

A place of worship for members of the Congregational Church. These churches, the first of which was founded in 1616 in Southwark, practised self government. Most of them were merged to form the United Reformed Church in 1972.

A place of worship for members of the United Reformed Church, a group formed in 1972 by the amalgamation of most of the Congregational Churches in England and Wales with the Presbyterian Church in England.
A place of worship for Particular Baptists, a Calvinistic Baptist denomination who believe in predestination.
A barrier used to close an opening, usually hinged and often hung within a supporting frame.
An individual section of panelling. Can form fences, ceilings, an outer layer to a wall etc.
A thin, flat rectangular piece of slate, or  similar material, used as a roofing tile.
A thin slab of hard material, such as baked clay, shaped and used in quantity as a roofing material.
A thin piece of wood used as a roofing material.
A moveable covering, usually to a window, made up of a frame containing slats set at an angle. Allows air to circulate but limits light entering.
Glass that has been coloured by fusing glass with a metallic oxide film or by burning pigment into the surface.
A substantial piece of timber which is part of, and integral to, the structure of a building.
A slab which can be decorated, shaped, hollow etc. Used for a variety of purposes in construction.
An opening within a structure to allow air and light in and or to allow a sight outside or inside.
Glass used within a window, usually to protect from the elements, can permit a view through it or can be for decorative purposes.
An object used in combat to attack or cause damage to an opponent.
A projection on the under side of a hinged choir stall seat providing support during long periods of standing.
A form of dagger.
A type of sword often used by infantry.
A curved sword designed to cut with used by cavalry.
Articles used in charging guns and ordnance.
A long spear with a double barb where one barb is longer than the other.
A projectile fired from a bow.
The weapon end of an arrow, often shaped for particular uses.
A stone missile fired from a ballista, larger in diameter than ballista shot.
A triangular arrowhead retouched to form a central tang and lateral barbs. The sides may be straight or concave.
A type of dagger, usually used by civilians in the medieval period, with a H shaped hilt.
An axe designed for fighting could be single or double headed and used with one or two hands. Where use is thought to be ceremonial multiple index with ceremonial object.
A projectile discharged from a weapon, usually a firearm.
A heavy artillery piece consisting of a metal tube mounted on a gun  carriage.
A solid ball fired from cannons, size and weight would depend on the calibre of the cannon.
A device used to throw projectiles, can vary from a small forked stick for hurling stones to a large engine of war to hurl large projectiles.
A weapon which causes damage through exploding.
An axe used by the Saxons and Franks for throwing.
A weapon which is a blade fixed to a long handle.
A long handled weapon which has a long blade in line with the shaft, sharpened on both sides and ending in a point.
A long spear designed to be thrown in order to injure or kill a given target.
A long spear used on horseback.
A stone or metal head on a wooden shaft. Where the use is thought to be ceremonial multiple index with ceremonial object.
An object with a ceremonial or symbolic function. Multiple index with specific object where possible, eg for a ceremonial battleaxe index as ceremonial object and battleaxe.
A heavy, smooth bore, long barrelled weapon, fired from the shoulder.
A metal sphere, usually lead, fired from a musket. Often bound into a cartridge.
A weapon, usually blunt, used to strike an opponent.
A long wooden shafted weapon tipped with a metal point.
Armour formed from thin pieces of metal fastened together or on leather or some strong woven material.
A long shaft topped by an axe head. Differs from a battleaxe by the length of the shaft.
A weapon where an object is propelled away from its launcher by means of force. The launcher can be a weapon, eg a catapult, or a person. This term includes the projectiles themselves.
A long narrow two edged sword with a guarded hilt, used as a thrusting weapon.
A long barrelled firearm. The barrel is spirally grooved on the interior, which gives the bullet a spinning motion leading to greater accuracy over a longer range.
A projectile or group of projectiles fired from a weapon, usually solid rather than explosive.
A deliberately made missile fired from a sling.
A missile fired from a sling.
An object made to hurl a spear further and faster than possible by hand.

A cutting and thrusting weapon consisting of a blade and a hilt. The blade varies in length and width and the cutting edge can vary from being purely the point to being one or both sides or a combination of these.
An axe designed and weighted to be thrown.
An arrowhead which has a straight cutting edge.
A hammer designed to fight with, often has a hammer side and a spiked side.
A decorative container for serving cream.
A container used to measure liquids.
A small container for an aromatic substance, eg perfume.
An area of land enclosed by one or several boundary ditches. Double index with a term to indicate the shape of the enclosure where known.
An enclosure where the boundary consists of a line of discrete pits, as opposed to a continuous ditch. Use with a term that describes the shape of the monument.
A monument consisting of an area of land enclosed by a ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier, where the barrier consists of several straight or near straight sections.

A square shaped area of land enclosed by a boundary ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier. Small square enclosures (with sides of less than c.20m) have been interpreted as the remains of square barrows of Iron Age date.
A chamber built into the side of a covered reservoir to enable the water level to be inspected.
A beacon, firmly embedded on the sea floor, consisting of an iron mast, with ladder steps leading up to the refuge cage considerably above high-water mark, and capable of holding several people.
A ramp or incline between differing levels constructed to allow carriages access.
A building used as a headquarters and reporting centre for an Army, Navy or Air Force Group.
A decorative garden ornament, usually of stone, in the form of a wide, shallow dish.
A building associated with a spinning mill in which raw material is mechanically spun into yarn or thread.
A site where unprocessed wood is used to manufacture goods.
A cairn erected to mark a particular spot in the landscape. Can be used for various reasons.
An area of a port, dock or harbour where cargo vessels can load and unload large storage containers. May include a rail terminal for containers which have been transported to the port by rail.
An area of a port, dock or harbour where a container vessel docks to take on or unload its containers.
An open area of water, usually artificial and enclosed by dock gates or locks, lined with wharves, warehouses and berths to enable vessels to load and unload.
An area of a port, dock or harbour, often including buildings for passport control and customs, where passengers of ocean liners can embark/disembark and where supplies can be taken on board.

An area of a port, dock or harbour, often including buildings for passport control and customs, where passengers and vehicles using ferry services can embark/disembark and where supplies can be taken on board.
