An area of a port, dock or harbour, often including buildings for passport control and customs, where passengers and vehicles using hovercraft services can embark/disembark and where supplies can be taken on board.
A marker, of stone, wood or metal, used to delineate the limits of a stretch of highway, river or canal subject to a toll charge.
A complex of buildings using Radar or satellite tracking to monitor and detect enemy missile launches early enough to allow a counterattack or defensive measures to be taken.
A port situated on a river, often associated with a town or overland goods transport facilities.
A gate used to seal the entrance to a dock to prevent water escaping from a wet dock or entering a dry dock.
A college founded for the education and betterment of the working classes. Lectures usually being held after the end of the working day.
A school built and/or supported by voluntary contributions.
An inlet in the banks of a navigable river, often lined with brick and gated, into which boats can be drawn for repair etc.
A training college where workers can attend classes in vocational subjects. The classes are often day-release and sanctioned by the employer.

A lighthouse whose lantern is sufficiently high to be seen at a long range and above low lying cloud or fog. In locations where varying weather conditions occur a High Light is usually accompanied by a LOW LIGHT built alongside or nearby.
A pit which shows evidence for having been used for cooking. Often contains charcoal, burnt bone fragments etc.
A tower used as a watch tower by the coastguard. Often, though not always, built as part of a Coastguard Station.
A port, dock or harbour where ferries, hovercraft, ocean liners and cargo vessels can load and unload. May include road and/or rail terminals for transportation to the port.
A large tank where particles suspended in water, or other liquids, are allowed to sink to the bottom forming a sediment.
A small building built over the end of a water conduit or spring.
Cob type construction typical to Buckinghamshire using a local clay with a high chalk content to produce walls of notable inherent stability.
Hard, compact, unprocessed, fibrous cellulose substance. The roots, trunks and branches of trees and shrubs consist of this tissue.

A sheet or board made from a mixture of thin strips of wood and cement which are bound together through compression within a mould. Woodwool slabs are used for roof or wall cladding, providing fire resistance, and heat and sound insulation.
The oldest form of iron, it is a tough, pure form of iron that can be fashioned into decorative items or shapes by hammering, squeezing or rolling.
Use both terms.
Generic name for the fine grained, brown coloured carboniferous sandstone, quarried in the Leeds, Bradford and Halifax area.
A hard and lustrous metallic element, used for roofing, galvanising iron and a component of alloys such as brass.
Weight on the end of a graduated line for measuring the depth of water.
A pillar, rod, pin, or plate of a sundial, showing time by its shadow.
A reversible device for measuring time by the transfer of sand from upper to lower glass bulb.

A place of worship for Strict Baptists, a sect who broke away from the Particular Baptists and kept up the practice of denying communion to non members after the union of General and Particular Baptists was formed in 1891.

A place of worship for General Baptists, a movement established by John Smyth in 1603 and which grew out of the original Baptist church. They believed in free will and are often referred to simply as Baptists.
A narrow strip of land where a plough and team could turn. This usually remains higher than the ploughed land.
A pillow-shaped, flat topped rectangular mound often surrounded by a shallow ditch used to farm rabbits.
Earthworks and buildings added around a bastion to enhance protection of the bastion.
An earthwork used as a boundary marker.
An area of hardstanding to allow movement of farm transport in all weathers.
Long parallel soil ridges in excess of 5 metres across separated by furrows, formed by using a heavy plough capable of turning the soil.
A sculpted cross, or a cross incised into stone or trees, to mark a parish boundary.
A place of worship for Baptists. The first Baptist church was formed by Thomas Helws in 1611 and gave rise to the General Baptist Movement.
A place of worship for members of the Society of Friends, a denomination founded by George Fox in c.1650 who believed in passivist principles and a rejection of the sacrament.

A place of worship for Presbyterians, a movement who started off attempting to reform Anglicanism before breaking away in 1660. Sometimes referred to as moderate puritans, they joined with the Congregationalists to form the United Reformed church in 1972.

A place of worship and meeting hall for members of the Salvation Army, an evangelical sect founded by William Booth in Nottingham in 1865 and derived from Wesleyan Methodism. They rejected the sacraments and adopted a quasi-military rhetoric and style.
A place of worship for Sandemanians, a movement founded by John Glass after his expulsion from the Church of Scotland in 1728. It was spread to England by his son-in-law, Robert Sandeman.
A place of worship for followers of the Eastern Orthodox churches. This family of churches separated from the Western church in the 11th century and recognizes the Patriarch of Constantinople.
A place of worship for members of the Serbian Orthodox Church, the national church of Serbia.
A place of worship for members of the Russian Orthodox Church, the national church of Russia.
A series of arches, linked together, often made out of clipped hedges or trees with the trunks forming the uprights
A garden deliberately planted with white plants and shrubs.
An artificial stretch of water, usually rectangular in shape, used decoratively, particularly in formal gardens, eg. Long Water, Hampton Court. Occasionally used to supply water to cascades.
An often highly elaborate water fountain, usually found in parks, gardens or urban spaces.
A building, site or structure associated with the demonstration and testing of weapons and military equipment.
A purpose-built trench used to test chemical warfare weapons.
A place of meeting and worship for Exclusive Brethren, an exclusive fundamentalist puritan sect which was created when the Brethren split in 1847.
A place of meeting and worship for Open Brethren, a non exclusive fundamentalist puritan sect which was created when the Brethren split in 1847.
A place of worship for Primitive Methodists, a group founded in Manchester who broke away from the Methodists in 1806.
A place of worship for members of the Romanian Orthodox Church, the national church of Romania.
A place of worship for members of the French Protestant church of the 16th and 17th centuries.
A place of worship for Protestant Methodists, a group who broke away from the Methodists to form their church in Leeds in 1828.
A place of worship for followers of the Wesleyan Association. This group split from the Methodists in 1836 and were separate until joining the Methodist Reform Church in 1857.

TERM: NEW CONNEXION OF GENERAL BAPTISTS CHAPEL
SCOPE_NOTE: A place of worship for members of the New Connexion of General Baptists,an orthodox Baptist church which broke away from the General Baptists in 1770 when the latter became influenced by Unitarianism.
A place of worship and residence for followers of Buddha.
A hospital where patients would bathe daily in the sea or in indoor salt-water swimming baths.
A hollow ball for containing aromatic substances eg perfume.
An accessory vessel to a cremation.
A round bottomed container to be held in the palm of the hand.
A purse, sometimes of bronze, usually worn on the forearm.
A container in which weapons are put for storage and or transportation.
A container used as a lavatory by bedridden people.
A case in which a comb was carried.
Containers identified by the form they take rather than by function.
A storage container designed to contain corn.
This appears on a number of objects, use appropriate term eg, bucket, keyhole, hanging bowl etc.
A container in which plants are grown.
A box in which one or more games are stored.
A container, capable of being carried by hand, often for carrying such items as clothes, keys, money, etc.
A container which holds a set quantity of a substance, can be graduated to show quantities.
A container used to hold, store, examine or create medicinal substances such as ointments, medicines, drugs, pills, tablets etc.
A case which holds and protects a mirror.
A lockable box for holding money and valuables.
A container in which needles are held.
A container, usually square or rectangular, used in metal processing for separating metals one from another, usually silver from gold.
A container for perfume.
A container used to hold substances for dying or painting.
A container for pills or tablets.
A container for loose gun powder. Sometimes with a regulator to release enough powder for one shot.
A horn used to hold loose gun powder for recharging firearms.
A horn containing gun powder used for priming a firearm.
A container for the storage of rice.
A container designed to be difficult to get into or out of, thus ensuring the safety of objects inside the container.
A case in which a pipe would be held to protect it.
A shallow dish or plate used to serve main meals off or to serve sweetmeats, these usually being painted with devices and riddles.
A container for ointments or perfume.
A vessel for the storage and transport of wine.
A flexible container, usually leather, for the storage and transportation of wine.
A container holding materials used in writing.

A flask holding gunpowder used to prime a firearm, ie to provide a small quantity of gunpowder to be put in the pan which would be lit to set off  the main charge in the barrel. The powder would often be a finer grade than that used for the charge.
Clothes, items of attire and ornament and objects for personal use by individuals, including toiletries.
A close fitting cap covering the sides, back and top of the head.
A close fitting skull cap, usually worn under a helmet.
An appendage worn on the front of breeches.
A triangle of cloth worn by ladies to cover the shoulders, neck and throat.
A close fitting garment, usually stiffened by boning or similar and tightly laced to shape and support the wearer's figure.
An opaque, rigid sheath used to cover the penis. Not usually contraceptive and not for obvious visual display.
A pipe in which a substance is smoked.
An object for cleaning a pipe used for smoking.
An instrument used to compress a substance into a smoking pipe.
A pipe allowing the passage of water through it and designed only for this.
A brush used to disentangle hair.
A small brush used fro cleaning teeth.
A small, pierced, often spherical or cylindrical, piece of glass, wood,etc, which may be strung together with others to form a necklace.
A form of hat, usually does not cover the forehead nor have a brim, and usually worn by women.
A metal reinforcer worn on the sole or heel of a boot.
Any brooch with the pin sprung or hinged at one end and the catchplate at the other end of a curved or flat bow. Can be one or two piece construction.
A garment covering from the waist to the knees, similar to trousers but stop at the knees.

A fastener made of a metal circle connected to a metal loop fixed to an object and used to fasten to another object by means of a button or a loop. The usage of these items is unclear, could include use for animals or for dress.
A piece of material, eg metal, cloth, leather etc, added to a button to enhance or embellish it.
A covering for the head with a peak to shade the eyes.
A clay tube with a small bowl at the end used for smoking tobacco.
A voluminous garment worn over other clothing.
Covering and accessories worn on the body.
An item worn as clothing or in addition to clothes.
A building in which newly made bricks are laid out to dry.
An area where builders keep building materials such as brick, stone, planks and cement.
A railway at a dockyard used for the transportation of goods to and from the dock side.
A large building used for the storage of leather goods or processed animal skins.
A works or factory where nitroglycerine is manufactured.
A building, factory or works which was engaged in the manufacture of refining saltpetre. Often part of a gunpowder works.
A chemical works engaged in the production of Ammonium Nitrate, used as a fertilizer or for use in the explosives industry.
A chemical works engaged in the production of Ammonium Perchlorate, a product used in the explosives industry.

A chemical works engaged in the manufacture of the coal tar derivative, picric acid, often associated with the textile industry where it was used as a dye, but more commonly with the explosives industry where it was used as the shell filling Lyddite.
A works engaged principally in the manufacture of ammonal explosives.
A works engaged principally in the manufacture of the explosive bellite.
A works or factory principally engaged in the manufacture of dynamite
A factory where explosives and the components of munitions of all types are brought together for assembly.
A factory or works principally engaged in the manufacture of the explosive Gelignite.
A factory or works engaged in the manufacture of the explosive guncotton. They may be found as separate factories or form part of a cordite factory.
A factory or works principally engaged in the production of a single base propellant, using nitrocellulose without the addition of nitroglycerine.
A factory or works principally engaged in the manufacture of the mining explosive sabulite.
A factory engaged in the manufacture of small arms ammunition, especially the metal components and filling with the explosive propellant.
A works using sealed retorts to produce charcoal. Wood distillates may be produced as byproducts of this process. They may be found at separate works or comprise part of a gunpowder works.
A works or factory where shells or projectiles were machined before they were dispatched to a filling factory to be filled with explosives.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production, testing and storage of gunpowder.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the production, testing and storage of explosives.
A factory or works principally engaged in the refining or manufacture of TNT.
Use both terms.
A place where wigs, hair-pieces and hair extensions are made and sold.
A purpose-built triangulation point used for the metrical survey of Britain carried out by the Ordnance Survey.

A building or buildings ranged around a courtyard on at least three sides. They occur in the Iron Age, as well as being an influential plan type of house from the 15th century onwards. Index with appropriate period.
A market where goods are bought and sold in bulk, rather than by retail.
A water pump situated at the side of a road or track for use by travellers and their animals.
A shallow channel to collect rain water, attached to the eaves of a building.
Objects relating to the punishment and restraint of humans.
An artificial watercourse for the conveyance of water.
A place where watches and timepieces are manufactured and mended.
A place where paper, frequently printed in ornamental designs, used for covering the interior walls of buildings, is manufactured.
A device used to trap or kill animals considered to be pests, eg. rats.
An office where the administrative duties of a university are performed.
A stopping place on an underground railway system where passengers can board and disembark from a train.
A tunnel carrying a railway beneath the surface of the ground.
A sample consisting of minerals, stones etc.
A route way which passes underneath the surface of the ground.
A large space in an underground tunnel, usually wider than the tunnel itself, used for storage, etc.
A mechanism used to turn a trolleybus around.

A large hilltop or hillslope enclosure in South West England, located close to rock outcrops, and surrounded by one or more circuits of stone built walls. All are prehistoric; some are definitely Neolithic.
Equipment used in the production of textiles.
A place where tobacco is made into cigarettes, cigars, etc.
A place where processed wood is sold.
A place where ceramic tiles are manufactured.
A piece of material worn around the neck. Where it is a collar for an animal use animal collar.
A comb made up of riveting together sections between connecting plates.
An associated group of toilet articles.
Ornamentation worn specifically for formalised dancing.
A garment worn by females.
A pin worn to hold two or more pieces of material together, often when being worn as clothing.
A pad of cloth or fur for keeping the ears warm.
A thin scoop used for cleaning the ear.
An ornament for the ear, usually clipped to the lobe or fastened through a hole pierced in the lobe.
A piece of strengthened material worn projecting over the forehead and eyes to provide shade for the eyes.
A small hole for a lace, cord or hook to be passed through.
A hand held instrument for producing a current of air for cooling the user. It is both a practical and a fashion item.
A circular band, usually metal, worn on the finger for ornamentation.
Clothing worn on the foot.
Items which are part of or added to footwear.
A band worn around the leg to hold up a sock or stocking.
A precious or semi precious stone used within jewellery.
An object designed to add curls into hair.
A wig, toupee or section of extra hair designed to replace or enhance the wearer's real hair giving greater quantity, bulk or length.
A ring used to hold hair in place.
A comb or slide used to hold hair in place.
A piece of fabric for wiping the nose, face or hands.
A band of cloth or other material worn around the head, not totally covering it.
A fine net worn over the hair.
A cloth or scarf worn over the head as a covering.
Decorative ornamentation worn on the head.
A garment hook having a flat plate, often decorated, with two or more holes for attachment and a hooked projection. The term is often used for early Medieval examples.
Outerwear covering the upperbody, including the arms. Covers to the waist.
A loose piece of clothing about hip length worn over other clothes, not usually tucked in at the waist.
Pleated skirt, usua;;y of a tartan material, worn by men and women.
A small pin or stud worn in the lapel, often decorative.
Outerwear designed to protect the legs from weather.
A long narrow spoon used to remove cosmetics or medicines from narrow necked containers.
An item used as part of a manicure.
A melon shaped bead.
A set of clippers for finger or toe nails.
A piece of fabric worn tied or knotted around the neck.
Clothes worn so that they are visible, usually but not always worn over other clothes.
A light weight umbrella used as a sun shade.
A Romano-British brooch type, appearing at the end of the first century AD and developing during the second, characterized by a flat plate to which the pin and catchplate are attached at the back.
A sole held onto the foot by straps or thongs.
A band of material worn around the neck, waist or shoulder.
A piece of material worn over the head and or shoulders.
A sleeved garment worn on the upper body.
A covering for the foot not enclosing the ankle.
A metal bar to strengthen the heel and or sole of a piece of footwear.
A covering for the arm, usually attached to or part of another garment.
A decorative clasp to fix sleeve cuffs together.
A long loose fitting garment worn instead of a coat.
A garment worn on the foot and lower leg.
The part of footwear that touches the ground.
An object made of sponge used to wash or clean with.
A covering for the leg which fits closely.
A belt worn around the waist from which a sword is hung. Where worn over the shoulder use baldric.
An object designed to be the end of a lace or simimlar to aid the insertion of the lace through a loop or eyelet.
Dress designed to be worn for theatrical purposes.
A semi circular jewelled headdress for formal occasions.
An outer garment worn on the legs.
Clothing worn on the upper body.
Headwear where a band of material is wound around a cap.
A set of small pincers used for gripping and plucking.
A folding circular cover on a stick held in the hand for protection against rain.
Clothes worn against the skin and beneath other clothes.
A pipe used for smoking where the smoke passes through water.
An artifical head of hair worn to disguise baldness, for adornment, for ceremonial or theatrical use etc.
An object designed to add curls to a wig.
A band worn around the wrist as a bracelet.
A stud used for fastening an item usually used for clothing.
A sample taken from waterlogged conditions.
Use for the remains of any part of a plant.
A symbol with secular signifigance, particularly implying authority.
A building which provides the centralized market for trading in stocks and shares and for raising capital for industry.
A series of flat-topped structures, usually made of stone or wood, used to facilitate a person's movement from one level to another.
A place where stained glass is manufactured, traditionally for church windows.
A place of accommodation for a stablehand.
An object that commemorates an animal, person, location or event.
An iron bar or ingot of distinctive form with a pinched end previously thought to have been used as a medium of exchange in the Iron Age but is now believed to be a roughout for a sword.
A metal counter used in calculation of financial sums but not itself directly exchangeable for coins, goods or services.
Official currency printed or written onto paper which can be directly exchanged for goods, services or coins.
An unofficial, usually local, substitute for coinage, which could be exchanged directly for goods or services in certain areas or with specified retailers.
Silver rings believed to have been used in the Hebrides and Irish Sea regions during the Viking period, and derived from Hiberno-Viking arm rings.
Penannular objects of late Bronze Age, usually gold and too small to be worn on arms.
An object that carries the weft in a loom without the need to be passed from hand to hand. The thread is wound into the shuttle and can be used in hand or machine looms
A container designed to assist in cooling foodstuffs or liquids. Use specific type where known.
A straight sided drinking vessel, usually with a wide mouth and without handles.
A drinking vessel, usually curved in shape, fashioned out of animal tusk or horn and sometimes with bands of decoration.
A vessel with a specially adapted mouthpiece, to assist in feeding young animals and humans.
A term for a drinking vessel, although its use often implies a recognised quantity.
A device with two flat plates and a mechanism used to force the plates together, to  help solidify milk products in cheese making.
A stone or stone platform in a fire upon which cooking vessels are placed.
A device for removing the core from fruit.
Hand held instruments which assist in the holding, cutting and eating of food.
A pronged iron hook used in cookery.
A long handled scoop usually used with liquids.
An object assumed to be to pick limpets out of their shells.
A hand held device for mashing food, usually with a flat holed base attached to a handle.
A device to hold and rotate food against a heat source during cooking.
A device for containing food whilst cooking it by the action of steam.
Decorative mounts on horse harness
A stone grooved on one face thought to have been used to straighten and smooth arrow shafts.
A structure for hanging criminals, often used to suspend criminals after execution, consisting of one upright post with an arm.
A shackle for the feet.
A wooden framework with holes for the head and hands, in which the offender stood.
A wooden framework with holes for the feet, and occassionally hands, in which the offender was restrained.
A post to which the offender is tied to be whipped.
A shaft hole adze with additional hammer knob, normally polished stone.
An axehead of flint or other stone, commonly used for Neolithic types.
A graving tool used for engraving objects. Prehistoric versions are usually made of flint or other stone, later versions usually of metal.
A specially designed chisel for producing ornamental mouldings.
A tool for splitting and chopping.
A flake or blade tool with more than one notch on its edge.
A tool of flint or other stone, usually worked bifacially, and thought to be a fairly general purpose tool.
A stone tool, often only polished on the edge.
A tool used in the separation of fibres from the bark in flax working.
A tool with a curved blade and a short handle. The blade is on both sides of a line extended from the handle. If just on one side use reaping hook.
A small cutting hook on a long handle.
A tool with a cross handle at one end and a spoon shaped or gouge cutter at the other, used for drilling holes.
A flint tool for piercing holes.
A small tool for boring holes with a cross handle and a screw tip.
A tool for pounding or grinding.
A quern where one stone is rotated on another to grind grain.
A stone with a concave upper surface on which grain was ground by using a rubbing stone.
Usually a L or T-shaped tumbler lock key which allowed the bolt to be pulled across by a cord.
A form of tumbler lock key which pushes the bolt.
A lever lock key.
Use for large remains such as fruit, seeds, plant parts, buds etc.
The remains of the fine powdery substance produced by male elements of flowering plants, uniquely identifiable to the species it came from.
Use for microscropic remains.
Microscopic animal remains. Use more specific term if known.
Use for the remains of any part of a mammal, except for humans.
Use for the remains of any part of a reptile.
Use for the remains of any part of an amphibian.
An object which supports or is attached to a curtain.
An object fixed to the door or floor to limit the amount a door can open.
An object which surrounds or makes up a keyhole.
An object which does not provide light but supports or is attached to lighting equipment.
A pan for cooking fish.
A device for rotating a spit.
A tool for removing the core from an apple.
An object used to preserve fish by immersing the fish in smoke.
A cutting blade with handle used for food preparation and consumption.
Implement with a shallow bowl at the end of a handle used to eat with or to stir food etc.
A piece of furniture intended to hold drinks, side dishes etc.
A low stool for resting feet upon.
A flat surface often with drawers used for working upon.
A piece of furniture containing shelves, cupboards or drawers for storage or display.
Thick material, usually woven, used as a covering for the floor.
A piece of furniture containing a chamber pot or wash basin.
A piece of furniture with one or more doors concealing storage space.
Hanging drapery used to cover an opening eg a window, often decorative.
An article laid over the floor or ground as a protcetive and or decorative covering.
An attachment to furniture that can be detached.
Movable, usually functional, articles in a room. Use only for objects believed to be furniture where more specific term is not identifiable.
The cover for a garderobe on which a person would sit.
A bag or case stuffed or padded, designed to be slept on.
A bag stuffed with soft material used to support the head whilst sleeping.
A large piece of material used on a bed for sleeping on or under.
A small type of seat, usually without a back, set on legs.
An item designed to cover, decorate or enhance a wall.
An item hung over a window, usually can be open or shut to allow light in.
A box containing tinder, any dry inflammable material, usually also contains flint and steel for lighting fires.
A metal receptacle used for burning coals, charcoal etc to provide heat.
An object made up of a wick surrounded by wax or tallow which burns slowly to provide light.
An object in which a candle is put in order to provide light.
A tall holder for candles which stands on the floor.
A container for one or more candles.
A hanging frame with branches which act as candle holders or to which lights are attached.
An open lamp which was filled with oil then a wick floated on the oil.
An appliance that produces light by means of a liquid fuel and a wick.
A small container used to fill a lamp with fuel.
The support from which a lamp was hung.
An object which encloses a light source but allows light out through holes, glass etc.
A bar or rod, usually of metal, used to push another object into place eg to push coals within a fire.
A stone heated in a fire then dropped into a liquid to heat it.
A light made by dipping a rush in grease.
A slim piece of wood used to ignite fires, lamps, ovens etc.
A closed chamber used for heating or baking objects.
A triangular sectioned rod probably used for making sparks.
A pan with a long handle which would be filled with coals and drawn over sheets to warm a bed.
A twisted fibre which is immersed in wax, grease or oil except for one end which is lit.
A residue, primarily lead oxide, formed during refining silver
Characteristic waste flakes struck off in the manufacture of adzes.
An unfinished, roughly shaped axehead.
An object which is going to become a key. It has the shape but has not been cut to fit a lock.
An partly-worked millstone that is still to be finished.
An initially worked quern that is still to be finished.
An object that is to become a padlock key. It has the correct shape but has yet to be cut to fit the lock.
An example from which another object is made.
A pattern cut out in wood or metal to help shape something accurately or to reproduce shapes.
A shaped rod which passed through a hole in the door and was used to raise a latch or to slide a bolt.
A chemical works engaged in the production of the coal tar derivative phenol, a chemical used for the manufacture of explosives during WWI.
A by-product of the production of microliths.
A pavement walkway for pedestrian use, often raised above the level of a road or path.
A very small flint or other stone tool.
A simple, pointed implement for piercing.
A residential establishment for retired armed servicemen and women.
A leather strap for sharpening a razor.
A knife used to rub grease into a hide and to force dirt out of it. The knife is symmetrical with a handle at each end.
A knife handled at both ends used to shave wood.
A flattened glass sphere used to give linen a gloss.
A flint blade or flake with retouch on one or both ends.
A bridge, usually resting on raised arches, carrying a road across low-lying land or water.
A small semi circular scraper current in the Bronze Age.
A short blade set at an angle in a slot between two handles.
A large building, situated at a railway terminus, used for the temporary storage of goods or merchandise awaiting transportation to or from a railway.
A rod used to create repousee work on metal vessels. The rod is Z shaped.
A flat board with short spikes used to comb out the staple of wool to remove tangles before spinning. Usually used in pairs.
A comb used to comb fibre before spinning.
A flat blade used to beat the weft against the newly woven cloth in weaving.
A sign, often mounted on a post next to a roadside, giving directions or other instructions.
A place where goods and merchandise are temporarily stored before being transported to or from somewhere by road.
A place where railway trains regularly stop for taking up and setting down passengers or for receiving goods for transport.
A toothed comb used to beat the weft against the cloth in weaving.
An object used in tablet weaving to control the shed.
A short piece of track lying parallel to the main railway line enabling trains and trucks to pass one another. Sidings can also be used to park trains which are not in use.
A small store building at a railway station for the storage of equipment and other stores associated with the railway.
A tool used for digging where the blade is at right angles to the handle.
A massive hammer of wood, stone or iron.
A tool with a pointed head for breaking ground.
A pick with a point at one end and a cutting blade at the other end.
A tool used to reduce the diameter of metal rods. Consists of a pair of semicylindrical surfaces.
Hook used to support cloth on a tenter frame after fulling to dry the cloth.
A place of worship for members of Protestant sects dissenting from the established Church.
A furnace or oven used for drying items or materials. Use specific type where possible.
A container for the storage and/or transport of food and/or liquid.
A portable beehive, often made of straw.
An object related to deaths, burials or funerals.
A container, in the form of an urn, for keeping the ashes of the dead after cremation.
A staff with a bent head used by a shepherd. For a crook used by a bishop use crozier.
Use for structural objects within or connected to a place of worship, eg font. For structures, use a monuments thesaurus.
Protective covering for personal defence, objects designed to kill, injure or overwhelm an opponent or quarry, and ancillary equipment.
A place of burial for members of the French Protestant Church.

Tools and equipment with a specific function and those for which a function cannot be assigned with any degree of certainty. Where the function is known, the term is also included under the relevant Class.
Objects which cannot be assigned to any one particular class, or the function of which is unknown.
Objects used or associated with the transmission of ideas and information through the written medium.
A commemorative monument to victims of the plague.
A place of worship for members of a guild.
A hall associated with a church, used for holding functions, meetings and for conducting parish business.
A school run by a christian church.
A building in which pottery ware is made by shaping plastic clay on a spinning turntable, known as a potter's wheel or throwing wheel.
A textile building where the process of combing, a preparatory process for long wools, takes place.
A site where the process of combing, the preparatory process for long wools, takes place.
A textile factory where the process of doubling, the twisting together of two spun yarns, takes place.
An object which has been rejected eg due to being misshapen, spoilt etc.
A balance for weighing coins.
A navigational device.
An indicator of the extent of an area of land.
A measure for dry substances. A quarter of a bushel.
A measure for liquid holding two pints which is a quarter of a gallon.
A measure for liquid, usually for a quarter of a pint.
A calculating table or frame, specifically one in which balls slide upon wires. Used for the mechanical solution of arithmetical problems.
An instrument for viewing or measuring information on heavenly bodies.
An apparatus for weighing, usually consists of a beam on a pivot with a means of supporting the object to be weighed on one side and weights on the other.
A table of months and days in the year.
Instruments used within geometry, geometrical drawing and navigational mapping.
A container holding a set quantity used specifically for measuring grains or cereal.
An object used to mark each mile and to indicate distances to locations.
A graduated length of material used for measuring distances.
An instrument designed to measure temperature.
An instrument used to measure the passing of time.
An object with a broad enough blade which catches the wind and so is pushed until it shows the direction the wind is blowing in.
An object used to weigh something down or to measure the weight of another object.
A container used to catch blood during bleeding.
A ladle used for the making of drugs and medicines.
A small hand operated rotary drill used by dentists.
A long, slender, flexible tube for inserting into a body cavity for the introduction or withdrawal of fluids.
Tool used in dentistry either for examination or surgery.
A small shaped container designed to bathe the eye.
An instrument in the form of a pair of pincers used to grip and pull objects, usually used in surgery.
A piece of material, usually glass, which has been ground into shape to enhance vision or protect the eyes.
an instrument or tool used for medical purposes.
A tool used to examine or explore a cavity eg surgically for exploring the depth and direction of wounds.
A small knife used in surgery.
A flat object which is broad and rounded at one end and tapers to a handle at the other.
An instrument used for surgery, which is the treatment of injuries by instruments and manually.
Musical instruments by how the sound is produced by the instrument.
A musical instrument producing sound by air vibrating.
A musical instrument producing sound by the use of strings.
A musical instrument producing sound from a membrane.
A musical instrument producing sound from its own body.
An enclosed, round bell with a slit, sounded by a loose internal pellet.
A wooden or metal object used to provide a rhythm by striking another object.
A strung object used to produce sound usually from a string instrument eg a violin bow.
A piece of wood attached to a thong that makes a roaring sound when the thong is whirled.
A stringed musical instrument, usually played with a bow.
A stringed instrument with a fingerboard which has frets on it.
An instrument consisting of a small lyre-shaped metal frame held between the teeth, with a steel tongue plucked with the finger.
A stringed instrument with a very rounded body.
A part of a musical instrument played by the feet.
Any instrument for plucking or strumming a string eg a small piece of wood or plastic used to strum a guitar.
A medieval wind instrument.
A thin board forming part of a musical instrument and placed in a position to strengthen or increase its sound.
The part of a musical instrument in which notes resonate and increase the sound of the instrument.
Part of an instrument that is used to modify or limit the sound of a note.
A triangle of metal which, when struck, produces a note.
The peg of a stringed instrument which, when tightened or loosened, tunes the string of the instrument.
A part of a coffin that is removable eg handle, mount etc.
A stone inscribed or marked with ogham letters used for a memorial
Polished stone balls interpreted as ritual objects in the Scottish Iron Age.
An object consisting of a vertical member with a transverse member. Usually there is a religious or ritual significance to such an object.
A three panelled altar decoration that can be closed.
Each of a pair of long narrow pieces of wood, usually pointed and turned up at the front, fastened under the feet for travel on snow.
A small vessel propelled on water by an engine, oars or sails.
A building where lace was laid out to dry.

The room housing the looms in a domestic handloom weavers cottage. In general, wool loomshops were above the living quarters, whereas cotton loomshops were often below in a cellar, since the floor was usually kept damp to aid the weaving of the cotton.
A site where machine tools, machines designed to remove surplus material from a work piece by accurately guided cutting tools, are manufactured.
A kiln with a pyramid roof and capped vent in which barley is dried. Found on the site of a malt house.
A building where artisans could learn more about their craft, and the scientific and theoretical principles behind it, by attending lectures and the use of the reading room facilities.
An 18th century cottage with a pottery kiln attached.

A type of waterwheel where the incoming supply of water leaves a launder near the top of the wheel, and drops onto the paddles or buckets of the wheel which rotates in the reverse direction to that of the incoming flow.
A pit dug in the prospect of finding valuable minerals, coal, metal ores, etc, beneath the ground surface.
A machine used in a mill to remove bran scales and flour from grits or middlings.
A central office dealing with financial accounts.
A place where tree trunks were sawn into planks by hand.
A building in which silk was dried.
A furnace for holding hot steel ingots to equalize their temperature before they are hot-rolled in a steel-making or rolling mill complex.
A mill or factory in which raw cotton, wool, nylon or other material is spun into yarn or thread.
A building used to dry teazle heads in. Teazles were used to raise the nap on cloth in teazle shops.
A type of buddle used as an ore-cleaning device for seperating metallic ore from waste material by washing the dirty ore in a continuous flow of water.

A prime mover in which a central wheel with curved vanes, enclosed in a chamber, receives water directed onto the curved vanes by a ring of fixed guide vanes, causing the wheel to rotate about its axis.
A small boat of wickerwork covered by a watertight material.
A pole with a blade used for rowing or steering a boat by leverage against the water.
A load carrying horizontal structural member.
A band of leather, cloth etc worn usually around the waist to support clothing, carry weapons, pouches, tools etc or as a decoration.
A shirt like garment.
A container, typically cylindrical with a narrow neck, usually for containing liquids.
Ornamental band or chain worn around the arm or wrist.
A metal container for liquids and foodstuffs, often sealed.
A large bottle, generally protected by a basket or box, usually used for containing corrosive liquids, etc.
A container for dried foodstuffs.
A container filled with musket balls, metal fragments, nails etc. Designed to kill or maim the enemy at a close range.
A small box or chest for valuables, especially jewels.
A large pot used for boiling.
A neck band or necklace worn tightly around the throat.
A contrivance of interlocking parts used to fasten objects together.
A pan with a perforated bottom for straining or rinsing food.
A portable medieval container usually cylindrical or barrel shaped.
A container in which substances are heated to high temperatures.
Container with a handle, spout and narrow neck.
A decorative band or feature.
A long handled shallow pan used for frying.
Cloth or leather covering for the leg or ankle.
A form of belt or sash worn to hold in garments.
A container for drinking, with a base and stem but without handles.
The arrangement of straps used to control an animal and/or to attach the animal to a vehicle.
A hinged or looped clasp that fits over a staple and is secured by a pin, bolt or padlock.
A container for holding water that has been blessed by a priest and is used for symbolic rituals of purification.
An inhumation burial in which the body is covered by a shroud, placed in a coffin of stone, wood or lead and covered with gypsum, plaster or lime. Roman and early Medieval.
A Roman cremation burial in which the human cremated remains are placed inside or adjacent to a wooden casket, frequently decorated with lion-headed mounts and studs.
A high status Iron Age grave in which a two or four wheeled vehicle accompanies a frequently richly furnished inhumation burial. A barrow may overlie the grave.

A decorative design or illustration, often an anthropomorphic or geometrical image, carved into a stone surface, such as a cave wall or free-standing stone. Usually, though not always, of Prehistoric date.
A site where iron or steel bolts, and often their accompanying nuts, are manufactured. Sometimes referred to as NUT AND BOLT WORKS.
A site where cement is manufactured for the building industry.
A building housing a whim, a machine worked by a horse, used for raising ores, etc, from a mine.
A building housing a winching mechanism.
A factory, incorporating power driven machinery from the late 18th century, where cloth was manufactured from threads interlaced at right angles to each other in a loom.
A handloom weavers workshop where the weaver received yarn from a clothier and manufactured a woven piece of cloth from it.
A building or area within a brewery where barrels of ale are stored.
An engineering works producing items for the railway other than rolling stock, such as signals, tracks, points, etc.
An engineering workshop for the manufacture and repair of springs.
A non-vertical kiln where the shaft and burning zone is horizontal to the ground thereby allowing material to be fed in.
A kiln in which stone is burnt as it falls through a heated and slightly inclined steel tube.
A vertical structure, sometimes made of steel, often used in the manufacture of cement. Material is loaded at the top, burnt in the middle and removed at the bottom.
A twin-shafted kiln, circular or oval in plan, consisting of a fire chamber, pre-heater and cooling chamber.
A structure, composed of oven and hovel, used for the firing of pottery ware.
A furnace for the calcining and roasting of a mixture of sand and fluxes as a preparatory stage in glass-making.
A small, open air bowl-shaped furnace, in which the flames are fanned by bellows. Used for both ferrous and non-ferrous smelting.
A furnace used for the smelting or reheating of lead.
An enclosed furnace used for the continuous casting of plate glass.
A building which houses the administrative functions of a local authority.
A building where the administrative functions of a Trade Union are carried on.
A county judicial building where the Quarter Session and the Assizes for the County were held.
A building where samples of corn were sold or auctioned during the early to mid 19th century. When not in use, between market days, the buildings were used as public halls.

One in a chain of stations with semaphore shutters and telescopes which could relay messages according to a planned code. Used from the 1790s by the British Admiralty to speed up communications from London to the ports of Deal, Portsmouth and Plymouth.
A place of law to which debtors were taken for the recovery of monies by their creditors.
A farm building erected in the 18th and 19th century which were architect-designed rather than built in the local vernacular style.
An outbuilding used for the storage and maintenance of horse-drawn carriages.
The administrative office of a transport company who provide a service for the conveyance and transportation of either goods or people.
A structure sited within the grounds of a fire station used for drying hoses.
A building owned by a constituency political party which provides a meeting place for local political activities and also provides entertainment facilities for its members and guests.
A room in which a judge sits to hear cases and undertake other official proceedings which are not of a sufficient importance to be brought into court.
A building from which the administration of a county is carried out by the County Council. It is also, historically, the site where the county quarter sessions and assizes were held.
A building for a society formed for the promotion of some branch of learning or science.
The premises of a police officer for a parish or township who was appointed to act as a conservator of the peace within the district.
A building occupied by the corps responsible for police and disciplinary duties in the armed forces.
The official residence of the chief officer of the municipal corporation of a city or borough in England.
A vertical, pointed structure usually resembling a pyramid or cone. Use for component of a larger building type where it is now used as a freestanding ornament.
A building in which people are held in a state of imprisonment or confinement as punishment. Usually associated with military and political offenders.
A building housing the services of professionals with an expert knowledge of the law such as the offices of solicitors, barristers and lawyers.
A residence of two or three monks dependent on a foreign mother house sent to exploit a distant estate. Alien houses were officially suppressed in 1414.
A residence of two or three monks of the Augustinian order dependent on a foreign mother house.
A residence of two or three monks of the Benedictine order dependent on an English mother house.
A residence used during short visits by an official and attendants of the Knights Templars for administrative purposes on their estates.

The residence of a preceptor, officials and servants, etc, supervising the estates of the Knights Templars military order. Includes the mother house styled the Temple, London. The Order was suppressed in 1312.
Objects denoting membership and/or authority. Including objects associated with ceremonial rites or symbolising secular power.
A playing piece for the medieval game of table.
A playing piece for draughts
A circular toy which spins on a point.
A round object used in games.
A gaming piece used specifically to play chess.
A flat, oblong gaming piece marked with spots used to play dominoes.
A board marked up to play a game upon.
Pieces of bone used in a game, the pieces are thrown and then picked up between bounces of a small ball or throws of another piece.
A small ball, usually of glass or porcelain, used in games.
A small doll controlled by the operators hand either directly or with strings.
A ring, often metal, which is used to be thrown as part of a game.
A peg or upright object which is the target of a ball in skittles.
A circular toy which spins on a point. Can be kept spinning by whipping with a lash.
A metal or pneumatic rubber rim to a wheel.
A craft of uncertain function over 30 metres long.
A means of transportation.
A long handled hook used for pulling a boat to a place eg another boat, or pushing off from a place.
A thin vegetable based sheet used for writing, drawing, printing etc.
A very small spoon used to provide liquid to mix with ink on an ink stone.
A device with hooks or claws attached to a rope and used for dragging or grasping.
The cutting or chopping part of an axe.
A small tool with a shovel blade and a pick blade set at right angles to the handle.
A drill where the bit is twisted by means of a bow with the string wound around the shaft of the drill.
A key for a padlock.
A long handled heavy hammer used by two hands.
A small bobbin used in lace making.
A bobbin where thread is wound around it, used for example in spinning and weaving
A tool used to polish the surface of an artefact.
A cutting tool for shaping and carving materials, often used in conjunction with a hammer or mallet.
Scissor like object used for cutting, clipping, shearing etc.
A tool used in processing the fibres from coconuts.
A tool which combines two or more different types of tool.
The cutting part of a drill. Often bits are interchangeable.
A tool used in etching which is the use of acid to breakdown parts of a metal plate in order to create an image.
A tool, usually metal, with roughened surfaces in the form of very small teeth.
A knife with a hinged blade which folds into a slot in the handle.
A tool with a sharp, concave edge for shaping wood, stone or metal.
A revolving stone used to sharpen or polish by grinding.
A blunt headed instrument used for striking objects.
A mould in which an ingot is made.
The constituent parts of a kiln.
An instrument used to create and link loops of yarn to produce a garment.
An engraved object which when struck imparts the image engraved onto the leather.
A bar used to increase the force being brought to bear in order to move an object.
A device used to lock another object.
An apparatus worked by hand or mechanically for weaving yarn into textile.
A tool used to impart an image, impression or mark onto a surface.
A pattern used to create a consistent shape for an object, often hollow and reusable.
A thin, pointed implement used for sewing with a hole at the blunt end for threading the sewing material.
A small, sharp bladed knife for sharpening pens, originally sheathed, now the blades fold.
A tool for gripping with, often used to pinch objects together.
A tool used to smooth wood. It has a flat surface with an adjustable blade protruding through it.
A flint tool with a convex top and flat base.
A weight hung on a piece of string or twine used to show the vertical.
A tool with a sharp tapering end used for piercing materials or as a weapon point.
Polished bone used to burnish objects eg pottery.
A tool used in making pottery.
A rotating wheel, horizontal to the ground, on which pottery is made.
Equipment or tool used to compress an object into a desired form, a flatter appearance etc.
A wheel with a groove in it for a rope or cord, used to raise heavy objects.
A tool for perforating or stamping, used in conjunction with a hammer.
A toothed, handled tool used to drag objects either to gather them together eg grass or hay, or to level them out eg sand or earth.
A flake that has had small flakes removed to blunt, sharpen, refine the outline or prepare the edge of the tool.
A place where processed cloth is cut for use as garments or soft furnishings, etc.
A factory or site where wooden clogs are manufactured.
A place where shoes and boots are mended.
A place where meat and fruit, etc, is preserved by salting and/or drying.
A hoisting mechanism powered by electricity.
A site where merchandise and goods are temporarily stored before or after transportation by rail.
A building where merchandise and goods are temporarily stored before or after transportation by rail.
A building at an airport from where passengers embark and disembark from an aircraft.
A house in a terrace consisting of a double row of houses sharing a common back wall, characteristic of industrial cities in the North of England.
A factory where lengths of soft, woollen cloth, loosely woven to retain heat, used as a bed covering, were manufactured.

A building, with adjacent open areas, in which buses are maintained, usually having an extensive area free from upright columns or stanchions to permit overnight storage, repair bays, stores and an office.
A building and open area from which buses, usually those working local or regional services, begin or end their journeys.
A site where canvas, coarse, unbleached cloth, made from hemp or flax, was manufactured.
A site where wrought iron or steel chains were manufactured.
A site where traditional public shows, in which the display of exotic animals, combined with feats of agility and comedy, were held.
A circular kiln or oven used in the manufacture of bricks. Common in Staffordshire in the 18th century.

A group of four houses in quadruplex form within a single block, of approximately square plan and set in a spacious garden. Such houses were usually provided for supervisory or skilled workers within a textile factory.
A site where products containing sugar or honey, such as cakes, sweets, crystallized fruits or jam, were manufactured.
The place where metallic ores were crushed and washed to remove waste, forming a concentrate which could be used in a smelter.
A low-temperature oven for the firing of metallic-based colour onto pottery after glazing.
A form of lock on a river, which increased the depth upstream and had a gated opening.
A factory where flour was produced for use in food products.
A kiln where gypsum was dried to a state where it could be used as plaster of Paris or for the production of cement.

A type of tower mill, either with turbine-type sails able to take wind from any direction, or with sails working with shrouds to direct wind from one direction. The sails directly drove millstones set beneath them.
A house with windows and doors on one side only; often built facing inwards onto a burgage plot, or sometimes on a steep slope, with no apertures on the uphill side.
A terrace with windows and doors on one side only, often built facing inwards onto a burgage plot, or sometimes on a steep slope, with no apertures on the uphill side.

An area of land owned by a developer, whether a private entrepreneur or a public authority, and divided into plots for leasing or sale to manufacturing or commercial concerns which may share some common services.
A boarding or day school for children who had committed minor crimes or who lived in circumstances where they were likely to commit crime.
A lock at the point where two waterways join together.
A place where padlocks and rim locks for doors are made from iron and brass.

A series of parallel railway sidings on which goods wagons originating from different locations can be sorted or re-sorted into new trains before being despatched to their next destination or sorting points.
A works where crude oil is distilled into its fractions or cuts.
A factory where putty, used as a means of securing windows and for setting plumbing fixtures, is produced from a combination of whiting and oil.
A structure with semaphore arms and/or coloured lights used as a means of warning on railway systems.
A tower in a semaphore communication system. Often a three-storey building on a hill in line-of-sight, signal towers provided working and living space, usually for two crewmen with their families.
A site where sugar beet was processed before being washed and dried to form granulated sugar.

The main office of a telegraph company containing rows of tables set with Morse sounders, keys, relays and pigeon holes from where MORSE coded messages were transmitted and received and telegrams dispatched.

A building designed specifically for handling tobacco. This may be a bonded warehouse containing facilities for removing tobacco leaves from the hogsheads in which they were imported, and pressing them.
The masonry beneath a lock gate, sometimes projecting several feet from the gate.
A wide mouthed container, usually cylindrical without handles.
An object, often including gems and ornamentation, used as an adornment, usually on a person.
A container for holding or pouring liquids, usually having a handle or lip.
A piece of cloth worn over the head.
A residence of two or three monks of the Order of Tiron dependent on a foreign mother house.
A friary of the Order of the Friar servants of the Blessed Virgin Mary or Servites. The Servite Fathers came to England in 1864.
A residence used during short visits by an official and attendants of the Knights Hospitallers for administrative purposes on their estates.
A mixed house of nuns and religious men of the Benedictine order.
A site inhabited by a modern order of nuns, founded in 1900 at Lanherne, Cornwall, following Carmelite traditions.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Carthusian order.
A residence of two or three monks of the Cistercian order dependent on a foreign mother house.
A residence of two or three monks of the Cistercian order dependent on an English mother house.
An outlying farm or estate belonging to the Cistercian order.
A residence of two or three monks of the Cluniac order dependent on an English mother house.
A residence of two or three monks of the Premonstratensian order dependent on an English mother house.
A residence of two or three monks of the Gilbertine order dependent on an English mother house.
A communal residence of secular vicars whose duties included the education of choristers attached to cathedrals and collegiate churches.
A communal residence of secular priests and/or other clerics sometimes with the condition of learning and education attached.
A piece of machinery used to raise oil from a well.
A supporting structure for drilling machinery used in the extraction of or prospecting for mineral oils.
An underground structure for the storage of mineral oil.
A site, often in a woodland clearing, used for the production of pure carbon by the controlled burning of wood and other organic materials.
A crude shelter for persons engaged in the production of pure carbon by the controlled burning of wood and other organic materials.
A heated stone, brick or iron chamber used for drying corn.
A building or room where beer is decanted from conditioning tanks, into casks or barrels.
A large site specializing in the manufacture of locomotives.
An engineering workshop, often attached to an engine shed, for the running repairs of operational parts, etc.
A factory or site for the manufacture of food stuffs from raw ingredients.
A building housing equipment for the process of distillation.
A site where metal springs are manufactured.
A site containing plant and machinery for the manufacture of steel.
A building or site used for the manufacture of swords.
A site where copper ore is extracted directly from the surface of the ground.
A site where tin ore is extracted from suspended fire waste in tin mine spoil heaps.
An area of ground indicating the site of a horse or man-powered winding mechanism.
Equipment used in the grinding of cereal to produce foodstuffs.
A building or room used for the storage of pottery moulds.
Equipment used primarily to cut, slice, chop etc, using an implement with one or more sharp edges.
A site where all the processes for the production of glass and objects made from glass are carried out.
A factory where rock gypsum is ground into a powder used in the production of plaster.
Equipment used to grip an object.
Equipment used to create a mark, image or character in an object.
A factory containing machinery for processing clay for the manufacture of bricks, tiles or pottery.
Equipment used to pierce or puncture other objects through the use of a point.
A pit used for the containment of clay whilst it is mixed to the right consistency for brickmaking.
A building or structure in which bricks are made.
A site used for all the processes associated with the manufacture of roof, floor or decorative tiles.
A kiln used to calcine the component parts of cement to remove excess water and other ingredients.
Equipment used to create objects through the use of a pattern or matrix which shapes the object.
Equipment used to compress or break through compression.
A light plough used to break up the earth. It does not have a mouldboard to turn the earth.
An object used to create a blast of air.
A pointed tool used to pierce holes, usually in textiles.
A stone used as a hammer in making stone tools.
A stick for digging up roots etc. Sometimes a stone weight is attached.
A missile consisting of a number of weights joined together by cord. The bolas entangles the legs of a target causing it to fall.
A shaped stone, which could be hand held, used in combination with a saddle quern to grind or rub grain.
A tool for cutting substances eg wood, metal etc. Its blade has teeth down one edge.
Twin blades each with a sharpened edge connected together by a pivot which cut when opened and closed on an object.
A tool for scooping loose substances, usually with a handle and a curved blade partially covered at the handle end.
Scissor like tool, usually larger than scissors, used for cutting, pruning or trimming.
A mould which is used to provide the shape of a piece of footwear.
A handled tool with a broad blade with slightly raised sides used for scooping or shovelling.
An object which when hot is used to smooth fabric.
A tool used to impart heat in order to fuse two or more metal surfaces together.
A wooden rod passed through a spindle whorl. Used to handspin fibre.
A bit for an auger to scoop out material.
A tool that produces a mark on an object through the application of percussive force through the stamp.
A tool used to filter solid material from liquid by means of a mesh, net or sheet with holes.
A small cap for protecting the finger or thumb whilst sewing.
Twin bars riveted together which can open and close allowing it to grip objects, usually to lift and move them.
A small blade for moving earth, applying liquids such as plaster, smoothing etc.
A tool with a handle and curved blade designed to cut through grass sods.
An appliance for holding an object while work is done on it, usually has a pair of jaws.
An object, usually wood or metal used to force open or keep open another object. Often used to split timber by striking the thick end and forcing the wood apart.
The windlass used to wind rope around to raise and lower the bucket in a well.
A tool used to twist fibres together to create yarn.
Any form of fastener used to fasten clothing together.
A flat nail of the same thickness that tapers in width to a point.
A length of cord usually made from twisting fibres together which increases the strength of the rope.
A wheel with a series of teeth on its outside which interlock with similar teeth on another cogwheel to receive or give motion.
A type of staple used to hold two object together.
An object which has been bent and angled from which something else can be caught or suspended.
A small bar raised or lowered by a latchlifter which is used to fasten gates or doors etc.
A border put around a picture to enhance it and ususally to hold in place the picture and any covering, eg glass.
An object used to fill up a hole.
A long usually cylindrical object usually made of wood.
The point or tine of a fork.
A three dimensional representation of an object, person or animal.
A piece of pointed wood, usually to be driven into the ground.
A three sided or U-shaped metal fastener on which the ends are pointed.
Flexible, twisted fibres, joined together, for tying objects.
A sharp pointed nail with a large flat head.
A device to limit the amount of liquid coming from a pipe or hole.
An object showing signs of being worked. Use more specific term where known.
A nail adapted so that the end of the nail can be turned over and driven back into the substance through which it has passed.
A form of padlock with a cylindrical case and bolts and springs attached to spines.
A key, usually with a long stem, its terminal is generally hooked or looped, and bit set at angle to stem with radiating or looped wards.
A key usually with a long stem with bit, stem and terminal in line.
A series of connecting metal links.
A stopper made of cork used to prevent liquid escaping from a container.
A metal collar or cap to strengthen the end of tubes, sticks, shafts, etc. Use with specific object name where known eg spear and ferrule.
A piece of cast metal obtained from a mould in a form suitable for storage.
A detachable lock with hinged loop used for attachment operated by a key.
A bolt for fastening metal plates. One end is put through prepared holes and then beaten flat.
A wooden cylinder or dowel used for pinning planks or timbers together.
A tent especially one made of bark, rushes or skins spread over a set of arched poles that are lashed together.
A pointed projectile fired from a crossbow designed to injure or kill a given target.
An object used to provide heat for various purposes eg to cook or to heat a room etc.
A hook with a spiked tang which allows it to be driven into a vertical surface.
An musical instrument where the strings are played by plucking or bowing. Use more specific term where known.

A strategic food store, directly operated by, or on behalf of, the government. The stores were used to store a variety of foodstuffs. They were in operation from the end of the Second World War until the early 1990's.
A building housing a board organized to protect the interests of commerce.
A small ornamental case, usually on a necklace or chain, that holds a picture, keepsake etc.
A piece of cloth worn around the loins.
A rod used to measure the imperial measurements of a pole or a perch.
A projection which can be used to lift or suspend an object, often used as a handle.
A cylinder of fur or cloth into which the hands are placed to keep warm.
A way between different places, used by horses, travellers on foot and vehicles.
A large room or building at a school used for assembly and other activities.
A chain, band or cord, often bearing beads, pearls, jewels etc worn around the neck.
A bag containing food hung around a horse's head.
A tread-wheel by which a crane was formerly worked.
A piece of armour used to protect the armpit.
A fence made of pales.
A broad container, usually used for cooking.
A wood or metal dowel for joining objects together eg for securing roofing slates.
Equipment used in the preparation and maintenance of ground, and in the planting and maintenance of crops.
A tool, piece of equipment, container or other object used for or in fishing.
An object used in the harvesting or mowing of crops etc.
Equipment for the hunting and capture of animals.
Objects used to thresh and winnow crops.
A board or slab, often with a thumb hole in it, used by an artist to hold and mix colours on.
A long stick or rod used as an aid in walking, climbing etc. Where it is a weapon use quarterstaff or staff weapon. Where there is another use, use the appropriate term eg surveying staff.
A long staff, occasionally bound with metal, used as a weapon.
A long graduated staff used in surveying to help measure distance or height.
An item used in caring for the body for appearance and cleanliness.
An object used in washing or cleaning the body.
Object used in shaving.
Objects used to secure buildings, furniture or objects or used in the finishing and (non-structural) decoration of buildings, equipment and furniture.
An object used in lighting a fire, lamp, oven, candle etc.
A struck piece of flint or other stone where the length is at least twice the width.
A shoe fixed to an animal, either permanently or temporarily, to protect the hoof and provide improved grip.
A hospital department for the identification and treatment of skin tissue disorders.
A specimen of material to represent the whole from which the sample was taken.
A body which has been interred in boggy or marshy ground or other similarly waterlogged environment. Interment may have been deliberate or accidental.
A house with an open hall whose main span is separated by an arcade from the side aisles.
A house with a range at the end of it, at right angles to the main range.
A landing and taking off area for civil aircraft, usually with surfaced runways and aircraft maintenance and passenger facilities.
A small dwelling for the solitary confinement of a pious reclusive religious man or monk, often attached to the north wall of a church. A squint enabled the occupant to witness the Mass.
A house where the upper storeys rest on projecting floor joists and so create the effect of an overhang.
A pin or bolt, especially one on which some other object turns.
A large jug, usually rounded with a narrow neck, used for holding liquids.
A shallow, usually circular, dish on which food is served or eaten from.
A container, usually round and deep.
A small bag or detachable outside pocket.
A small bag or pouch for carrying money, especially coins.
A narrow strip of fine material, used for trimming or tying.
A device on a boat's gunwale serving as a fulcrum for an oar and keeping it in place.
A projecting starched frill worn around the neck, especially 16th century.
A piece of equipment fastened on an animal for carrying loads, including riders, or for assisting in traction.
Two discs at the end of a short shank, used to fasten shirt fronts, collars etc.
A container with a perforated bottom through which material is shaken or poured.
A three dimensional representation.
A device in the form of a loop with a flat base hung on either side of a saddle to support the rider's foot.
A large one handled drinking vessel, sometimes fitted with a hinged lid.
A low, wide, open container.
A vase-like receptacle, especially a large bulbous one with a foot.
A vessel used as an ornament, often to hold flowers.
A large container for holding or storing liquids.
A circular frame or disc arranged to revolve on an axle and used to facilitate the motion of a vehicle.
A stick or rod with an attached lash.
A building used for the education of, and as a residence for, chantry priests.
A school used by the children of settlers at a Chartist Colony.
A barbed spear head used to catch marine life, usually has a rope or line attached to it.
A frame set with teeth used to drag over ploughed fields to break down the earth clods etc.
Equipment used in the care and upkeep of animals, usually used directly on the animal.
The forms of armour used to protect various parts of the body.
Use for the function that the armour is intended for, eg parades, field use, decorative etc.
Machinery for lifting pieces of stone or loaded trucks out of a quarry.
A group of buildings where consumer goods, such as small machines and electrical components, are manufactured.
Piece of armour worn to protect the back, often permanently connected to the breastplate.
A site where scientific and technical instruments such as microscopes are assembled.
A building or room used for any type of engineering work. Use more specific type where known.
A short stabbing weapon, designed to be fixed to the muzzle of a musket or rifle, even in some cases to pistols. Some were designed to be used both fixed to long guns and independent of them.
A bayonet designed to plug into the muzzle of a musket or rifle.
A bayonet designed to fit over the muzzle of a musket or rifle, allowing the gun still to be fired.
A kiln used for the drying of wood.
A furnace for the manufacture of glass. Includes glass cones, open hearth and oil-fired furnaces.
A long hollow tube used to blow molten glass into shapes.
A furnace used for smelting or re-heating of iron, either for casting or for further working.
Armour designed to protect the chest, sometimes permanently attached to a backplate.
Four iron spikes joined together so that when the caltrop is on the ground a spike is always pointing upwards. Used to disable infantry and cavalry.
A thick heavy weapon used to strike the opponent.
Armour designed to protect the torso, and consists of both back and breast plates.
A flat heavy slightly curved blade.
Use appropriate term.
Armoured covering to protect the hand and wrist.
A shaped flint used in flintlocks to create the spark to fire the gun.
A combination of spear and axe on a long handle.
Decorative armour used for parades and display, not for combat.
A hand held weapon used to throw missiles such as stones or bullets.

A spatially discrete scatter of mixed artefactual material found on the ground, seabed or riverbed which may have been deposited over time rather than resulting from one particular event. Index particular types where appropriate.

A monument consisting of a small (generally less than 100m diameter) subcircular enclosure with a narrow approach way consisting of parallel ditches (thus banjo shaped). Believed to be associated with stock management in the Later Prehistoric period.

A poorly understood Neolithic monument comprising a very long, narrow earthen mound. They may be of single-phase construction, or represent the addition of a linear extension to the bank of an existing Long Barrow.

A monument comprising an irregularly circular enclosing ditch, interrupted by several causeways, surrounding a central circular area used for funerary activities, often concealed originally beneath an earthen mound. Index with barrow type where known.
A Neolithic burial monument comprising a stone-built chamber within a mound of stones. Use more precise term where known.
A Neolithic burial monument comprising a stone-built chamber within a mound of earth or stone. Use more specific type where known.
A stone, either in situ or part of a monument, bearing one or more small, roughly hemispherical depressions, generally created by chipping or pecking.

A stone, either in situ or part of a monument, bearing one or more small, roughly hemispherical depressions surrounded by a concentric arrangement of annular or pennanular grooves. More complex designs may also occur.

A cemetery of later prehistoric date comprising exclusively cremated human remains, some or all of which may be contained within pottery vessels. The cemetery area is partly or wholly surrounded by an earthwork bank and/or ditch.

A site used primarily for domestic purposes on at least a semi-permanent or seasonal basis, and which has been surrounded by a bank and ditch, palisade, or some other form of enclosure. Use more specific type(s) where appropriate.

A form of Neolithic burial monument primarily found in Cornwall and the Scilly Isles. It comprises a round cairn, usually with a retaining wall or kerb, and an entrance leading directly into a chamber.

A site where flint seams within chalk have been exploited by digging deep vertical shafts, often with horizontal galleries radiating out from the base. Use for Neolithic examples and for Post Medieval gunflint industry.
A late Neolithic/Early Bronze Age earthwork enclosure distinguished from a henge primarily by its larger size, irregular shape, and greater complexity of internal features.
A commercial building used for the production of detailed, often technical, drawings.
A hall used for the promotion and selling of agricultural produce and practice.
An area within a building open to the public where light meals and drinks can be purchased and consumed.
A building offering accommodation to people who are visiting a town or locality renowned for its mineral springs.
A public house offering lodgings to the passengers, and stabling for the horses of stage coaches.
An area of a building providing reading materials for the benefit of colliery workers.
A school attended by children between the ages of eleven and sixteen.
A dome shaped structure, with an aperture open to the sky, used to house a telescope.
A building used by teachers for in-service training.
A hall in which public assemblies and meetings can be held.
A building or group of buildings situated close to the sea used by coastguards to enable them to monitor the coastline.
A building or site from which a watch can be kept to prevent the illegal import/export of goods.
A hall built for the use of people living within a parish boundary.
An assemblage of public and private buildings, larger than a village and having more complete and independent local government.
A structure, often ornamental, in a garden, park or area of recreation, designed to reflect the style of Indian architecture. The most famous example of which is the Royal Pavilion in Brighton.
A fountain decorated with shells forming an ornamental feature.
A bridge decorated with shells forming an ornamental feature.
A church, sometimes circular in plan, founded by the Poor Knights of Christ and the Temple of Solomon, commonly known as the Knights Templar.
A small room or building containing a lavatory and, in more recent times, washing facilities.
A hand operated mechanism used to raise and move water, liquids, compressed gases etc.
A channel dug, or built up, to carry away surplus water from a river or waterway to prevent it bursting its banks and flooding.
Manmade constructions used to prevent water flooding the surrounding area. Often taking the form of a bank or wall but may be more elaborate e.g. the Thames Barrier.
A pool of water and associated ancillary buildings designed to accommodate sea lions.
A plate, usually of wood or metal, used to indicate the limit of an area or piece of land.
A jettied house where the overhanging upper storey runs along the entire length of one side.
A house consisting of a single storey open hall with a two storey domestic range attached at one end, forming a T shape.
A house consisting of a single storey open hall with a two storey domestic range attached to both ends forming an H shape.
A house consisting of a single storey hall with two storey domestic ranges attached to either one or both ends.
A CRUCK HOUSE where the cruck blades are truncated and joined by a collar beam, above which is a separate roof construction.
A gaming piece for the Viking game of Hnefatafl.

A place of worship for Bible Christians, a group who split from the Wesleyan Methodists to form their own church in the South West of England. They were amalgamated into the United Methodist Church in 1907.
