A lodging house for apprentices learning a trade or profession. This accommodation was often provided in lieu of wages.
A stone basin for containing holy water often set in inside walls of a church, especially near the entrance.
A factory for the production of missiles
A building where distillation, a chemical process used in the production of a range of different chemicals, took place.
A plucked string instrument in which the strings pass over the soundbox and parallel to the sides of the instrument.
An anti aircraft battery usually mounting weapons with a larger calibre ammunition such as the QF 3.75 inch (94mm) gun.
A community of Protestant followers of Hussite doctrines, first founded by Moravian emigrants in Saxony, Germany.
The bottom part of a sleeve, can be ornamental.

A musket fired by use of a flintlock. A gunflint is held in the lock which on pulling the trigger pushes back the pan cover creating sparks which set off the powder in the pan causing a flame to go through and set off the charge in the barrel.
A workshop used for the manufacture of clay tobacco pipes.
A building wherein silk worm cocoons are boiled to release the silk fibres.
An office at which the registration of marriages, births and deaths are recorded, and in which marriage ceremonies may take place.
A house, the inhabitant of which keeps an official register e.g. a registrar's house near a cemetery would keep an official record of deaths and burials.
A pond or pool with arms covered with nets into which wild birds, are allured and then caught. Monument type includes water feeder channels.
Forms of ride which are designed for entertainment.
Coarse, hard Chalkstone, light grey to white coloured, containing shell fragments.
Generic name for the hard, white/cream coloured, freshwater limestone. Quarried on the Isle of Wight.
Use both terms.
A semi solid mixture of complex hydrocarbons derived from coal or petroleum. Used as a waterproof binder or protective coating.
A material made of felted fibres bonded by bitumen. Often used as a roofing material.
Use both terms.
Hard white/grey coloured liassic limestone. Quarried on the Devon-Dorset border.
Any of the pieces of hard tissue consisting largely of calcium phosphate that make up the skeleton of a vertebrate animal.
Easily formed metal alloy composed of copper and zinc.
Sedimentary rock consisting of angular fragments naturally cemented together.

Lightweight building block traditionally made with coke breeze from gas works combined with sand and cement. Use this term generally to denote a light, modern concrete building block with man made characteristics.

Standard rectangular block or tablet bonded on mortar joints in a regular arrangement or pattern for strength or decoration. Made from clay or brick earth which may contain varying quantities of chalk, lime or iron oxide which effect colour or density.
Hard, corrosive resistant alloy of copper and tin.
Fine grained limestone, yellow or yellow/white in colour. Imported from France, mainly for ecclesiastical use.
White coloured marble. Imported from France.
An unbleached cloth of hemp, flax or other coarse yarn.
Limestones formed during the Carboniferous period. Many are cut, polished and used as marble.
Imported Italian marble varying in colour from green, blue, purple to white.
Coarse hard sandstone often coloured with iron oxide creating its characteristic brown shades.
Dating from the 15th century, it is a hard alloy of iron and carbon, melted and shaped into various moulded forms.
Durable wood from a non-native, evergreen conifer.

Originally obtained by burning limestone to produce quicklime. Now a fine grey powder made from a mixture of limestone and clay used with water and sand to make mortar or with water, sand and aggregate to make concrete.
A binder combined with various aggregates which sets and holds together into a mass which then hardens and gains strength.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Designating or pertaining to hard, brittle substances produced by strong heating of clay.
A soft, porous, white to light grey coloured limestone.
Use both terms.
A hard, silica rich rock, black or brown coloured, commonly found in nodular form.
A fine grained earth which becomes more plastic when water is added and can be moulded and dried to make bricks, tile, pottery, etc.
Large, moulded, unburnt blocks of clay type soil laid in a similar way to brick, but bedded in lime and clay 'mortar'. The walls produced are characteristically thinner than those of cob and pise.
Use both terms.
Fused ash from furnaces used as aggregate.
A hard, gritty, grey/green coloured form of chalk.
Durable artificial stone consisting of china clay, sand and finely ground stoneware cast from moulds and fired in a kiln. Commonly used for architectural ornament and facings.
Walls composed of clay, earth, straw, lime and sand, mixed with water. Constructed without shutters in layers upon a stone or brick plinth and usually covered with protective limewash.

A small, circular Late Neolithic/Early Bronze Age enclosure which bears a morphological resemblance to henges, but may belong to another category of circular earthwork-defined monuments, or is enclosed by something other than a bank and ditch.
Levelled or terraced area of ground presumed to have been the site of a house or hut.

A long, narrow, irregularly constructed and generally unstructured mound of stones. Normally a by-product of field clearance for agricultural purposes, though prehistoric examples may include burials and other deposits.

A rectangular or trapezoidal non-megalithic stony mound of Neolithic date, with human remains in cists rather than a large chamber. Mound construction and associated features vary considerably in type and complexity.
A long, narrow mound of earth or stone and of uncertain date and function. Use more appropriate term where possible.

A subrectangular earthen enclosure defined by a ditch, usually with an internal bank, assumed to have been used for the primary exposure or burial of human remains in the Neolithic period prior to secondary burial elsewhere.
Timber or stone built structure, traces of which are found within some long and round barrows, in which human remains were interred prior to mound construction.

An enclosure of Late Neolithic/Early Bronze Age date, related to henges, defined by a circular arrangement of pits, probably none of which originally held posts. More than one circle, concentrically arranged, may be present.
A spatially discrete group of pits usually containing artefactual material with little or no accompanying evidence for structural features.
A pit which appears to have been dug for, or which contains, objects apparently deposited for reasons other than storage, disposal or extraction. Index with principal object types.

A shaft which appears to have been dug for, or which contains objects apparently deposited for, reasons other than storage, disposal or extraction (eg. of stone, water, etc). Index with principal object types.
A burial monument, usually of Iron age date, comprising a small square ditched enclosure surrounding a central interment, which may also have been covered by a mound.
A cemetery comprising inhumations or cremations interred in stone cists.
A collective term applied to Bronze Age round barrows displaying more complex external morphology than the simple bowl barrow. Use appropriate specific term.
Neolithic chambered tomb featuring a passage with lateral and/or end chambers.
A place of worship for members of the Methodist Reform Church. This group was the result of a secession from the Methodists in 1849. They remained until joining with the Wesleyan Association in 1857.
A place of worship for members of the United Methodists Church, a group formed in 1907 by the amalgamation of the United Methodist Free Church, the Methodist New Connection and the Bible Christians.

A place of worship for members of the United Methodist Free Church. Formed in 1857 by the amalgamation of the Methodist Reform Church and the Wesleyan Association they later became part of the United Methodist Church in 1907.
A place of meeting and worship for Jehovahs Witnesses.
A lawn planted with camomile plants which when walked upon release a fragrant smell.
A garden seat covered in clipped, camomile plants which release a fragrant smell when sat upon.
A factory principally engaged in the  manufacture of the propellant explosive cordite.
A house with a pitched or gabled roof with a double slope and gables on two or more sides.
A place of worship for members of the Seventh Day Adventists Church. This was formed in 1843 by followers believing in the imminent second coming of Christ.
A place of worship for followers of Emmanuel Swedenborg who believed he was the medium through which the New Jerusalem would be founded on earth. The church was formed in 1787.
A place where appropriate acts, rites and ceremonies are performed to honour or revere a supernatural being, power or holy entity. Use specific type where known.
A small building used by the keeper of a castle, park, etc.
A building or room where items of pottery are manufactured. Includes handcrafted and machine made pottery.
An artificial mound, generally conical, placed within a garden or park to provide a viewing point to overlook the garden or park. It may also serve as a visual focus in the garden or park layout.
A building situated next to a horse racing course with facilities for participants and spectators.
A crane located on a quayside used for the loading and unloading of goods and materials to and from vessels.
The residence of the head or president of a chapter, or community of religious persons.
An educational establishment for the training of police cadets.
A large-scale site where medicinal drugs are maufactured.
A small artificial pond of water often found in parks and gardens, for decorative purposes.
A scientific laboratory where marine life is studied and researched.
A hospital for the medical and surgical treatment of sailors and/or their families. For Royal Naval seamen use ROYAL NAVAL HOSPITAL.
A range marker allowing bombers to locate the bombing range.
A hospital where people would pay a subscription in order to recieve treatment when ill.
A factory for the manufacture of rocket motors, both for civil and military use.

A reinforced concrete structure, usually sited underground, from where it was intended to conduct the business of government in the event of nuclear war. Date specific from mid 1980's to early 1990's.
A pit or emplacement surrounding a concrete pedestal, or 'thimble', which was used to mount a spigot mortar. Deployed by the Home Guard during WWII as an anti invasion measure.
A barn which is constructed with a timber framework; between the members are panels which are infilled with timber, wattle and daub, plaster, brickwork, stone or other materials.
A factory, where preserves such as jam and marmalade, are manufactured.
A floatable concrete vessel, numbers of which made up the main breakwater of the Mulberry Harbours used to secure beachheads during the allied invasion of Europe in June 1944.
A covered way or passage especially in a cathedral or monastic church, leading east from the cloisters between transept and chapter house.

A small prefabricated, reinforced concrete structure manufactured by Messrs Orlit Ltd for the Royal Observer Corps.  The first were ordered in 1951, most were redundant by 1955, a few remained in use in eastern England until 1965.

A small underground chamber from where it was intended to monitor radioactive fallout in the event of nuclear attack.  The majority were built between 1956 and 1964, although construction continued into the early 1970s.
A plate, usually of wood or metal, set up on a road, canal or railway to mark the miles from or to a place.
A crane powered by a treadwheel and used for lifting and lowering, dating from the Roman period. Also used in later periods to assist on building sites, at mines and in ports.

A tunnel built alongside a canal tunnel to enable a horse to be unhitched and led through the hillside to meet the barge when it emerged from the tunnel. Mainly built prior to the development of the towpath tunnel.
A site or building used for the manufacture of goods made from pewter, an alloy of tin and lead.
A crane or hoist within a building found mainly in the North of England. Can also refer to a projecting crane located above a loading slot.
A lock where the gates rise vertically. Rarely found on canals but common on navgable rivers in the Fens, particularly the river Nene.
A mechanism used for lifting and lowering weights, operated by hand.

A railway, usually by the sea, linking the beach with the cliff top. Various mechanisms were used the most common being that the cars were attached to a cable and winding drum and were balanced so that one travelled up, as the other came down.
A structure erected for the processing of shale, to extract oil through heating.
A mill which contains machinery for separating grain from the chaff.
A building where timber was allowed to dry and harden, to render it fit for use as a working material.
A mill in which strands of yarn are twisted together to produce a strong thread with a uniform thickness.

A building where fish are stored. Often taking the form of a single storey building with one room, but also may provide living accommodation for a fisherman above. Found mainly in the South West of England.
A building, often close to a churchyard, used for the entertainment of poor people on their wedding day.
A small, ornate structure in which candles were placed either during masses for the dead or to indicate the position of the cemetery at night .
A house of friars of the Augustinian order. Also known as Austin Friars
Use both terms

A prefabricated structure of a steel frame clad in corrugated iron. Semi-circular in section they were used as accommodation for the armed forces and, during WWII, as emergency housing for bombed out civilians. Also used for storage.
A chapel built on, or at the end of, a causeway.
A farm or group of buildings where Silkworms are bred. The Silkworm when changing into a pupa spins a cocoon made of silken filaments, these are then unwound and used to manufacture silk thread.

A cathedral in which the chapter was composed of canons who lived in their own houses and were not governed by a monastic rule. Nine such cathedrals existed in England between the 11th and 16th centuries.

A monument within a church or cathedral representing one of the stations of the cross. Usually images or pictures of successive incidents of the Passion, they are intended to be visited for meditation and prayer.
A mechanism through which crude coal gas is passed to remove any impurities eg Ammonia and Sulphur.
A pair of SHEER LEGS mounted on shore or on a SHEER HULK, used as a crane to hoist a mast and lower it into place on a ship.
A house having four rooms of equal height on each of two floors; in larger houses there are often two parallel and equal roofs.

A term for a type of house, with varying definitions according to period. Roman villas were high-status and usually associated with a rural estate, whereas Georgian and later period villas were often semi-detached, town houses.
All linen used at the table, including tablecloths.
A cloth or leather tunic, usually worn underneath metal armour, although sometimes worn by itself.

An astronomical instrument for telling the time at night. The date is set on the nocturnal then its pointers lined up with the Pole Star and the two primary stars in the Great Bear, thus allowing an approximate time to be read off.
An instrument for measuring the angular distance of objects, and particularly used for navigation by noting the position of the stars.
An instrument for measuring atmospheric pressure by its effects on mercury in a glass tube. It can also be used to measure altitude and depth and is especially used for predicting the weather.
An instrument for measuring the angle of slopes, usually in inches per yard, consisting of a weighted graduated wheel with movable sights.
A measuring rule used for cloth, with the imperial yard divided into quarters and nails (sixteenths), or using the now obsolete ell of 45 inches.
A graduated vessel or instrument for gauging or measuring the force or quantity of a fluctuating object, such as rainfall, tide, wind etc.
An instrument for taking measurements and describing circles, with two straight arms connected at one end by a movable joint.
A form of compass, sometimes with a screw for setting to small intervals.
An instrument for measuring or drawing angles, consisting of a quarter circle, graduated to 90 degrees, with a movable arm.
Right angled triangular plate for determining, measuring or setting out set angles.

An instrument for determining, measuring or setting out right angles, usually consisting of two pieces or arms set at right angles to each other, but sometimes with the arms hinged or pivoted to measure any angle.
An instrument for establishing the horizontal line of sight and used in surveying. It usually has an eyepiece and an air bubble in a glass tube or dome.
An indicator of the extent and or ownership of a property.
A measuring rule not graduated in feet.
A balance measuring weight by the tension of a spring.
A balance with unequal arms where the contents of a pan on the short arm are weighed by a weight or weights attached to the long arm.
A box with one transparent side within which a picture, jewel etc can be displayed.
Medium grained, dark bluish-grey stone. Quarried mainly from the Rubislaw Quarry.
Fine grained, whitish, granular variety of Gypsum. Suitable for carving.
Lightweight, strong metal with good corrosive resistance, normally used as an alloy.
Pertaining to or deriving from a living organism. See ANIMAL Class list for narrow terms.
Aluminium coated by a protective film of oxides created by electrolysis.
A rectangular sheet of roofing material created by a man made process (eg. asbestos cement slate) and made to look like, and used in the same way as, natural slate.

Synthetically manufactured stone made from natural stone aggregate or reconstituted ceramics or clay, and made to appear natural. Used as solid stone for masonry or for sculptural and architectural ornament.
Synthetic fibres and reconstituted materials imitating, or in the form of, timber created by a man-made process. Use carefully - do not confuse with mock and sham timber work.

A mineral crystal of thin, tough fibres which can be woven. Used for high temperature insulation or as reinforcement in asbestos cement building board and corrugated roofing. If used to imitate slate, use artificial slate also.
Use both terms.
A square, hewn or worked, high class freestone which can be 'freely' cut and is laid in horizontal courses with vertical joints.
Solid or viscous bituminous pitch of natural occurrence,or produced from petroleum mixed with sand or other aggregate filler, for use in roads or as a covering material
Thermosetting plastic commonly used for its properties of electrical insulation.
Tropical giant grass with hollow stem used structurally or as a covering material.
Hard, coarse grained, calcareous sandstone, coloured by iron oxide. Quarried in the Guildford and Godalming area of the South East.
Basic, black coloured, fine grained, igneous rock.
Even grained, poorly fossiliferous, light brown/cream coloured, oolitic limestone. Quarried in the Bath area.
A power station used to produce electricity, fired by coal gas.
A building in which an organization or society is instituted to promote foreign languages in England such as French and German, etc.
A building in which an organization or society is instituted to promote literature through lectures, study and research, etc.
A building used by an organization instituted to promote the needs and rights of the blind.
A building used by an organization or society to promote the study of oriental languages and history through lectures, research, etc.
A building used by organizations or societies for the promotion of a particular profession through lectures, research, etc.
A building used by an organization or society instituted to promote science through lectures, research, etc.
A building used by an organization or society instituted to promote technology through lectures, research, etc.
A place where working men could educate themselves through lectures and the use of a reading room with newspapers, etc.
A building used by the church to promote Christianity through lectures, study, etc.
A site used by a carrier to accommodate his horses and vehicles and store goods awaiting transportation, etc.
A building or room used for the practice and study of dance.
A school where theological subjects are taught.
An establishment dedicated to the study of God and religion.
A building with a regulated moderate temperature for the cultivation of plants.
An area of land, with associated buildings and targets, used for practicing the dropping of bombs and other aspects of air warfare.
A burial site for an animal, usually commemorated by a gravestone or other structure.
The principal Anglican church in a diocese in which the cathedra or bishop's throne is to be found.
The premises of an agricultural merchant where agricultural equipment, animal feed and fertilizers can be bought.
The premises of a builders merchant where building materials such as stone, cement, bricks, tiles and timber could be bought.
A channel which feeds water from a reservoir into a canal when the water level gets low.
A building where carpets and other floor furnishings were woven.

A building of basic construction, usually smaller in size than a house and constructed from a variety of materials such as mud, turf, branches, wood, brick, concrete or metal. Use more specific type where known.
A henge which contains a circle of standing stones. Use both terms.
Reformatory established under the Inebriates Acts 1879-1900 for repeat alcohol related offenders
A monument composed of plants or trees which are still extant. Especially relevant for park and garden features. For example tree avenue, orchard, rose garden and lawn.
A structure comprising two upright spars, joined at the top to form a triangle, with a hoisting tackle suspended from the apex. Used to lift cargo or other weights.

A structure comprising of two walls of stone or wood with nets or fish traps attached. Located in coastal waters, on shelving coastlines or in river estuaries they form large enclosures with a V or L shaped plan. The narrow point on the seaward side.
A hoist suspended from a girder within the roof of a building or workshop.

A crane consisting of a lattice girder carried on a lattice tower forming a T-shaped structure. A hoist is carried along the girder by a 'crab', enabling the crane to perform a variety of tasks eg loading/unloading of ships.
A building with an aisle on one side only.
A building with an aisle along one or both sides. Usually a row of posts separates the main space from the aisle.
A small monastery or nunnery of the Augustinian order dependent on a larger mother house.
A building used by members of the Womens Institute, an organization which meets regularly and engages in various social and cultural activities.
A light, ornamental building or structure situated close to the sea.

A building used as a social venue by people interested in, and involved with, the sport of rowing. An area of the building may be used for the storage of canoes, sculls etc. Often situated by a river.
A building containing a bier; a movable stand on which a corpse, often in a coffin, is placed prior to burial.
A light, ornamental building or structure built to incorporate, or in association with, a mineral spring.
A hall used by the members of a trade union for meetings and social functions.
A building used as a social venue by people interested in, and involved with, the sport of sailing. Often situated by a MARINA.
A chapel situated within the demesnes of a manor. Can be a separate building or an integral part of a manor house.

A high status building of the medieval period, consisting of a hall and attached room at first floor level with rooms below possibly for storage or living accommodation for a lower status family. The first floor was accessed by an external staircase.
A jettied house where the upper storey only overhangs the end elevation of the building.
A building or group of buildings containing equipment capable of transmitting and receiving radio signals. Use BROADCASTING RADIO STATION for broadcasting establishments e.g. BBC Radio stations.
A building, usually within the grounds of a school and often containing dormitories, used by pupils who board.
A place of worship for Welsh Presbyterians. Formerly known as Calvinistic Methodists, the Presbyterian Church of Wales separated from the established church in 1811.
A waterwheel where the water enters at the same level as the axle.

A section of the water channel of a river, shut off above and below by lock gates provided with sluices to let water in and out and thus raise or lower boats from one level to another. Often found situated next to a weir.
A dwelling cut into the rockface of a cliff or hillside, often with a built frontage. Many date from the Medieval period and are still in use in some areas of the country.
A manmade chamber cut into a rockface.
A large, decorative garden ornament resembling a vase.
A structure consisting of a large plastic pipe attached to a high tower and sloping down to a swimming pool. Water flows down the inside allowing people to slide down into the pool below.
A structure, often within a CHURCHYARD or LYCH GATE, on which a coffin could rest prior to burial.
An area of ground immediately surrounding a cathedral.
A chapel adjacent to, associated with or containing a well.
A building or room within a granary used to dry grain. Often consisting of an oven with a refractory-brick drying floor above, on which the grain was placed.
A slab of stone, either standing or recumbent, inscribed with a cross. Usually found in association with burials.
A grave lined with slabs of stone or slate and covered by a large slab of stone. Commonly found on the Isle of Man.
A lid for a well. Well covers are often ornate and can be made of various materials.

A row of houses linked at first floor level by an open continuous gallery which runs through the front of the buildings. Access to the gallery was gained by flights of steps. Commonly found in the city of Chester.

A house within a row. At first floor level a gallery which runs through the front of the building. Access to the gallery was gained by steps set at intervals along the row. Commonly found in the city of Chester.
A house with a pitched roof with a double slope and gables on the side elevations of the building.
A house with a pitched roof with a double slope and gables on the front and rear elevations of the building.
A stone slab, raised on stone or wooden piers, used for the display of fresh fish. Usually found in market places.
A room or building used for recording and broadcasting radio programmes.
Naturally occurring glacial rock fragments (diameter 64-256mm) larger than pebble and smaller than boulder.

Composed of sand, stones or other aggregate and cement mixed with water which sets in a hard mass. The material is usually associated with modern building but was developed by Romans where cement was obtained from quicklime.
Use both terms.
Sedimentary rock consisting of rounded pebbles naturally cemented together.
One of only three 'true' British marbles, green and white in colour, predominantly used in large public buildings.
Metal used primarily for roofing and ornamental purposes, being lighter and stronger than lead.
Buoyant, light material obtained from the cork tree.
Sandy, light brown (cream to golden) coloured limestone, easily worked and readily available.
Limestone formed during the Cretaceous period.
Application of earth based plaster to a backing of lath or wattle used in internal or external walls. Composite mixture which may include clay soil, dung, straw, lime putty, sand or horsehair.
Ornate or patterned decoration, carved into or moulded from plaster.
Use both terms.

Limestone formed during the Devonian period, and found predominantly between the Exe and Tamar rivers in Devon. Varying in colour from black/grey to pink/white it was often polished to imitate, and be used as, marble.
Coarse grained, dark coloured, igneous rock.
Medium grained, intrusive, black or dark green coloured, igneous rock.

Soft, often white, but may be transparent. Dolomite can be found on its own, but may also occur as a replacement mineral found in some rocks, particularly limestone, formed after action by magnesium-rich fluids.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.

Combination of organic and inorganic material cohered to form a hard solid wall or covering. Use for structures created by the excavation and piling up of earth, such as ice houses. Earth may be used in combination with other materials.
Unbaked clays and/or soil material often mixed with, or performing the function of an aggregate or binder. See EARTH MIX Class List for narrow terms.
Deciduous wood from the native elm tree, commonly used for framing or cladding of lesser timber framed structures due to its poorer weathering qualities as compared to oak.
Miner's term for fine grained, often light grey/fawn coloured porphyritic rocks. Commonly found in Devon and Cornwall.
Glazed and decorated, patterned earthenware tile combining different coloured clays which are inlaid and burnt in. Mainly used for flooring and external decoration.
A dense, high strength, low absorption brick of uniform size, employed predominantly in industrial structures such as railway viaducts.
Solid masonry slabs (tiles) of terracotta which are usually used as a cladding by bedding in concrete. Faience also refers to decorative glazed units.
Hard, often coloured, can be transparent. Found on its own as crystals and veins but also as a major constituent of all three geological rock types.
Fabric of fibrous materials consolidated by heat and mechanical action so that the fibres are matted together.

A sheet formed from wood which has been separated into its fibrous elements and reconstituted under pressure. The natural fibres produce resins which act as adhesive, but often additional adhesives are used.
Any material consisting of glass filaments woven into textiles, paper or board.
Soft sandstone stained by iron oxide often used in the Surrey area.
Hard, durable, dark grey stone, the purest native form of silica, which can either be used decoratively or as a main material. Predominantly found in East Anglia and the South East.
Any church which bears signs of fortification. Churches on the Welsh and Scottish borders were often fortified, only allowing access to the tower from a single opening in the nave.
An open area, often paved or cobbled, surrounded by privately owned buildings and inaccessible to the public.
A flat, level area of ground within a garden. Often raised and accessed by steps.
A garden building or greenhouse, containing pools in which Water Lilies are grown.
A tower containing a curfew bell. The bell was rung in the evening, as a signal that fires were to be extinguished.
A hut used by a person who makes items from wood. Often found in a woodland setting.
A house occupied by an employee of a waterworks. Usually found in association with a pumping station or waterworks.
A mill which is powered by a turbine.

A glass sphere in a metal frame standing on a small pillar. A card is placed behind the sphere which focuses any sunlight, marking the card and thus indicating how many hours of sunlight there was on that day.
A circular bank surrounding an area where burials were placed.

A stone wall, often of considerable length, built to divide an area of land. Most occur as part of extensive walled field systems. This is a regional term specific to Dartmoor and should not be used in other parts of the country.
A highly defensible gateway, usually of stone with two or more storeys, built into the defensive walls of a town or city.
A railway used for the conveyance of coal and other minerals.
A building housing electrical or electronic equipment used for communicating over long distances. Use specific type where known.
A building where people could bathe in salt water. Salt water was believed to have medicinal properties.
A structure, building or site housing equipment for transmitting radio or television signals.
An area of land, usually on a slope, which has been built up to provide a flat surface for the cultivation of crops.
An earthen mound, usually within an ornamental garden, on which a tree was planted.
A levelled area of ground, circular in shape, used as the base on which a monument was built.Sometimes raised, a platform is often the sole surviving evidence for a monument.
A levelled area of ground on which a house is built. A platform is often the sole surviving evidence for a house.
A machine used to raise and move water and other liquids, compress gases etc. and powered by a steam engine.
A site or building where silver was processed and/or worked and fashioned into objects.
A site or building used for processing shale. Shale can be fashioned into goods or, if bituminous, distilled to produce oil, naphtha or tar.

A building used for storing Sulphur, a highly inflammable chemical element used in the manufacture of matches, gunpowder and sulphuric acid. It is also used in bleaching, for vulcanizing rubber and as a disinfectant.
A small structure comprising of a 'shelf' of wood or metal sitting on pillars and erected for the benefit of porters to allow them to rest their burdens.
A small hut erected over a mine shaft.
The remains of a vessel which has either sunk or suffered structural damage to the extent where it can no longer function.
A building within a transport terminal, often associated with the registration and clearing of incoming and outgoing passengers or freight.
A levelled area of ground on which a barn is built. A platform is often the sole surviving evidence for a barn.
Soft mineral, colour varying from black/purple to yellow/green. Commonly found as a mineral vein.
Use both terms.
Collective name for a series of rocks (granite, syenite, porphry and slate) found in the Charnwood Forest of Leicestershire. Index with specific stone type where given.
The remains of living organisms preserved in stone over a long time period. This may be the internal or external moulds of, usually, the hard parts of an organism (shells, bones, etc.).
Stonemason's term for any easily worked sedimentary rock. Index with specific stone type where given.
Use both terms.
Transparent, hard substance made by fusing soda-silica which solidifies from a molten state.
Coarse grained, metamorphic rock in which the colour is dependent upon the predominant mineral.
A precious metal characterised by its yellow colour and resistance to tarnishing.
A spiny evergreen shrub of the pea family which can be utilized as a roof covering in areas of its predominance, eg. heathland.
A hard, coarse grained, durable igneous rock. Can be used decoratively or as a main material. Found throughout the country.
Use both terms.
Grains of rock fragment larger than coarse sand and finer than pebbles (diameter 2-4mm).
Geologist's term for any dark coloured, slightly metamorphosed igneous rock. Index with specific stone type where given.

Specific English quarryman's term for any limestone abundant in shell fragments. Use this term with care. When only Gritstone is mentioned, unless otherwise specified, assume it to be Gritstone (Sandstone), since this is the most common usage.

Carboniferous sandstone varying in grain size from coarse to fine and in colour from white, yellow, pink to brown. When only Gritstone is mentioned, unless otherwise specified, assume it to be Gritstone (Sandstone), as this is the more common usage.
Shelly, gold/brown, coloured liassic limestone containing large quantities of crystalline calcite.
Use both terms.

A dwarf shrub of the heath family used as an alternative to straw as a roof covering in moorland regions. Cut while in bloom and laid with the roots carefully entwined. The covering turns a characteristic black colour with age.
A strong alloy of steel.
Medium hard, green/black coloured. Found in many igneous and metamorphic rocks.
Compact grained, brown/yellow/green/grey blue, coloured liassic limestone.
Hard, fissile sandstone which weathers to a dark brown colour. Mainly used as a stone roofing material (stone slate) throughout Sussex and Surrey.
One of only three 'true' British marbles, pale green and white in colour.
A malleable, ductile ferromagnetic metal widely used for structural and decorative purposes.
Collective name for any stone that has become impregnated with iron oxide. Index with specific stone type where given.
Use all terms.
Limestone formed during the Jurassic period. Provides many widely used building stones.
Hard, white/grey coloured liassic limestone. Quarried near Somerton in Somerset.
Sandy, rough blue to green/grey coloured limestone. Quarried in Kent and widely used throughout the South East.
Cornish miner's term for slates formed during the Carboniferous and Devonian periods.

Collective term for the Burlington (Silurian period) and Borrowdale (Ordovician period) groups of slates from the Lake District and parts of Cumbria, Lancashire. Hard, fine grained metamorphic rock, varying in colour from green/olive to black/blue black.
A place of worship for followers of the Wesleyan Reform Union, a movement formed in 1859 by those members of the Methodist Reform Church who did not join the Wesleyan Association.
This is the top term for the class. See GARDENS PARKS AND URBAN SPACES Class List for narrow terms.
This is the top term for the class. See RELIGIOUS RITUAL AND FUNERARY Class List for narrow terms.
Buildings and structures associated with the performance of musical, oratory and dance events.
A settlement whose plan suggests the aggregation of several formerly distinct settlement nuclei into a single settlement.
An extant settlement which shows evidence of a shift in focus, eg. towards a new road, generally in the form of abandoned buildings or earthworks on the margin furthest from the new focus.

The site of a deserted settlement in cases where there is evidence that it has deliberately been relocated in a single planned action, eg. to remove a settlement from an enclosed park, or to create a model community, as opposed to gradual abandonment.
An area of land which retains distinctive large-scale rectilinear land divisions characteristic of Roman agriculture. Generally aligned with the course of a Roman road.
A burial vault built to contain the remains of members of a single family, household or dynasty.

A funeral rite in which the human body is burnt, usually on a pyre, leaving fragmentary charred or completely combusted remains. Often found buried, occasionally in a container associated with grave goods.

Inhumation rite in which charcoal is included with the buried corpse, possibly in an attempt to preserve the body. Thought to be associated with high status burials of the early medieval and medieval period.

An area used for the deposition of human remains where the principal funeral rite is the burial of the corpse complete. Generally indicated by the discovery of articulated human skeletal remains, occasionally with evidence of coffins and/or grave goods.

A built structure, generally below ground, designed for the interment of several burials over a period of time. Usually constructed with a door or sealed entrance to allow reopening for further burials.

A pit used for the re-burial of disarticulated human remains from many individuals, occasionally displaying sorting of remains, eg. grouping of skulls or long bones. Distinct from mass burials which contain articulated skeletal remains.
A pit over which a  corpse has been cremated on a pyre into which the remains and debris, and sometime grave goods, collapse and are buried. Generally confined to the Roman period.
An iron, stone or concrete tower built up from the bed of a reservoir. From it the control valves of the pipes which draw off water at different levels are operated.
A road surface made out of wooden blocks or planks. It was much used in English cities before 1940, but the cost of wooden blocks eventually made it uneconomical.
An unsocketed earthenware or porous concrete pipe laid end to end unjointed so as to drain the ground.
A river canalized for shipping.
A place where shale, a laminated clay or silt which has been compressed by the weight of the rocks over it, is extracted from the ground.
A channel for taking a rapidly flowing stream of water away from a canal lock, or away from the canal itself.
A coal-burning power station where domestic electricity for an area is produced, eg. Battersea Power Station, London.
A complex of buildings where electricity is produced using steam-powered turbines.
A device for converting one voltage of alternating current to another voltage.
A chapel attached to, or inside, a church, endowed for the celebration of Masses for the soul of the founder.
A factory producing metallic aluminium by an electrolysis process.
A group of buildings containing machinery for the production in bulk of butter or related dairy products.
A building containing a machine tool for boring out large cylindrical holes in items such as steam engine cylinders, pump barrels, etc.
A kiln used to reduce the shells of shellfish to calcium carbonate.
A building containing apparatus for the removal of large pieces of detritus from a water supply.
A dockside crane with a solid curving jib made out of rivetted iron plates.
A structure used for the drying of food using an indirect source of heat.
A group of buildings, or part of a works, housing apparatus used in the process of distilling.
A pond used as a water supply for the operation of a furnace or blast furnace.
A site used for the extraction of metallic zinc by a variety of processes.
An artificial mound of earth indicating either the former site of a windmill or built as the base of a post windmill.
A site where millstones have been cut to shape and/or fabricated from smaller pieces of stone.
A crane mounted on wheels and/or rails, used for the unloading of ships' cargoes.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Any vessel which has been hired or impressed for use by the Admiralty.
Use both terms.
A small, fast boat used for carrying orders between sailing vessels.
A major warship equipped with a clear flat deck to provide a landing and taking off place for aircraft.
A vessel fitted with a catapult for launching an aircraft.
Shallow draft vessel used to carry ammunition.
A vessel (often small obsolete cruisers or pleasure steamers) equipped with batteries of anti aircraft guns as its main armament.
A small warship (often adapted from a trawler or drifter) used to hunt enemy submarines.
A vessel used for carrying cargoes, fitted with defensive weapons. Use with specific type and form where known.
A fishing vessel employed exclusively on the Grand Banks cod fisheries.
Shallow draft cargo vessel, often broad beamed and flat bottomed, powered by engine and or sail.
A sailing vessel, generally with three masts, square rigged on the fore and main mast.
Sailing vessel generally with three masts square rigged on the foremast only.
A vessel used as a platform for flying a barrage balloon from.
A capital warship lightly armoured but with the same gun armament and stem turbine propulsion as a DREADNOUGHT BATTLESHIP.
A capital warship, often steam driven, heavily armoured with armament of large calibre guns deployed in turrets.
A small coastal fishing vessel peculiar to Kent, cutter rigged.
Single masted east coast trading vessel, ketch rigged or single masted.
A hulk or obsolete vessel filled with cement or similar material and scuttled to block an entrance to a port or anchorage, usually as a defensive measure.
A sailing warship armed with one or more heavy howitzers or mortars and used for bombarding shore positions. The modern equivalent is the MONITOR.
A vessel for maintaining the buoys, hawsers and netting of a boom defence.
Two masted vessel with a square rig on both masts.
A self propelled vessel for deepening harbours using a continuous chain of buckets
Large cargo vessel specially built and equipped for handling large quantities of ore.
A small vessel with a cabin as an integral part of its construction.
A ship used for laying cables (often telephone cables) along the sea bed.
A small open boat, usually a very light craft propelled by a paddle.
Small two or three masted ship used as trading vessels in the medieval mediterranean.
A craft used for the transportation of cargoes. Use specific type where known.
A three masted vessel with a square rig on the fore and main masts and lateen rig on the mizzen mast.
Generic term for fast sailing ships with schooner rig and fine hull lines.
Old ship converted to a floating coal store.
Small cargo vessel used for short coastal voyages carrying a variety of cargoes.
North European medieval merchant vessel.
A vessel for carrying a cargo of coal in bulk.
A small craft of wickerwork covered with waterproof material.
A small anti submarine escort vessel built in World War II
A flush decked sailing warship with a single tier of guns.
All vessels, use more specific type where known.
A shallow draft vessel used to carry a crane.
Open decked vessel used for sight seeing or pleasure voyages.
A passenger vessel equipped with recreational facilities for long voyages for pleasure and sight seeing.
Large warship equipped with turret mounted guns. Intended for independent action for trade protection, reconaissance and fire support for amphibious operations.
A small vessel used as transport for customs officers.
A vessel used for the laying and removal of buoys and other navigational markers.
Ketch or yawl rigged vessel with a large mizzen sail used in the west country.
A vessel, usually a merchant vessel, altered to resemble a warship or another vessel.
A vessel containing equipment for reducing the magnetic structure of a ship's hull making it immune to magnetic mines.
A ship acting as a base for smaller vessels and or submarines.
A monument where the evidence that defines the type of the monument derives from the nature of surface markings. Examples include graffitti on quarry walls.
Maritime monument identified as a ferrous object lying on the sea bed detected using marine surveying equipment that detects localised anomalies in the Earth's magnetic field.
Monument whose presence is inferred by discovery of unstratified artefacts, for instance in plough soil.
An inn, with an integral courtyard, for the lodging and entertainment of travellers. Often with open galleried wings overlooking the courtyard.
Thick, black liquid distilled from bituminous coal, and containing many organic chemicals.
Powder produced by grinding cacao beans, used as the main ingredient for the drink Cocoa.
Large, brown, hard-shelled seeds of the palm tree Cocos nucifera, the flesh and liquid contained within the shell can be eaten.
Large fish, native to the North Atlantic and adjacents seas which has been fished since the Middle Ages.
The beans, or powder resulting from grinding the beans, of shrubs of the genus Coffea. The powder is used to make the drink Coffee.
Pieces of metal money usually small in size and circular in design. Manufacture from a variety of metals including gold and silver but more recently manufactured from base metals and alloys.
Building material made by combining gravel, cement, water and sand. When hard it forms a stonelike surface, used for paving and building.
A factory or complex of buildings where creosote oil is produced. Creosote oil is distilled from coal tar and used as a wood preservative.

A temporary structure used for the firing of bricks or tiles. Unfired bricks or tiles were stacked upon a layer of fuel (usually wood) and then surrounded by a wall of old bricks and covered by a layer of mud or clay. The clamp was then fired.
A building or site where the carcasses of whales were butchered and rendered into by products such as oil, fenk and whalebone.
Materials used for the construction of buildings, vehicles or other objects.
Receptacles, including boxes, barrels etc., designed to contain something. Nowadays used specifically for a large, metal boxlike container used for the transportation of goods by road and sea.
People who have been convicted of criminal offences. Traditionally criminals, even those convicted of petty offences, were transported from Europe to penal colonies in the Americas and Australia.
Solid bars made from pure Copper metal.
A mineral containing high quantities of Copper.
The Supermarine Company was formed in 1912 and specialised in producing sea-going aircraft, including several Schneider Trophy winners. Taken over by Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd., in 1938.
Aircraft grouped according to their manufacturer.

A single-engine dive-bomber, the JU87 was very successful during the invasions of Poland and France but suffered heavy losses during the Battle of Britain. Withdrawn from NW Europe in 1941 for use in the Mediterranean and on the Eastern Front.

The main German, medium bomber of the war, the HE111 first saw action during the Spanish Civil War. HE111s took part in the Battle of Britain and from 1944 onwards were used to launch airborne flying bombs against London.

Developed as a long range, heavy day-fighter, the ME110 found its niche as a night fighter. It saw service over Southern and Eastern England during the Battle of Britain but lost out in the daytime to the faster British fighters.

Twin-engined bomber. The Whitley was the first 'heavy' bomber to be built in quantity for the RAF and made the first bombing attack on Germany in May 1940. It was later used for convoy protection and reconnaissance.
Aircraft grouped according to their physical form.
Aircraft grouped according to their function.
A light, high-speed aircraft designed to engage in aerial combat.
A large, powerful aircraft, usually with two or more engines, designed to carry a payload of bombs.
A light, high speed aircraft designed to engage in aerial combat and also equipped to carry bombs.
An aircraft with a single wing, or plane, either side of its fuselage.
An aeroplane with two wings, or planes, placed one above the other either side of the fuselage.

A streamlined, twin-engined bomber, the DO17 entered service in 1937 with the Condor Legion, having started life as a high-speed mail and passenger transport aircraft, a role for which it was ill-suited due to the narrowness of the fuselage.
A progressive development of the DO17, the twin-engined DO217 entered service in 1941. The DO217 saw service as a bomber over the UK and took part in the 'Baedecker' raids of 1942.
Generally understood to mean aircraft whose normal loaded weight is less than 2750kg (6060 lb).
American twin-engined medium bomber and ground-attack aircraft that entered service in 1941. A small number were delivered to the RAF under the British designation Mitchell I.
British three-seat, single-engine light bomber. All metal in construction, this monoplane had a 1000 lb bomb load.
Goods manufactured from processed cotton.
A building used for the finishing, drying and storage of lace.
A works used for the production of parchment from animal skin.
A large house dating from the 16th century onwards, built as a symbol of the wealth and status of the owner but not intended to be defensible unlike the castles and manor houses it replaced.
Double index with DEMOLISHED BUILDING plus EXTANT BUILDING or RUINED BUILDING or STRUCTURE as appropriate.
Double index with DESTROYED MONUMENT plus EXTANT BUILDING or RUINED STRUCTURE or STRUCTURE as appropriate.
A reinforced concrete structure, usually sited underground, from where it was intended to conduct the business of government in the event of nuclear war. Date specific late 1950's to early 1970's.

A structure, often sited underground, from where it was intended to conduct the business of government in the event of nuclear war. Sub RSGs were introduced between the RSGs and local authorities to allow the RSGs to focus on strategic direction.
A building, usually part of a hospital complex, in which contaminated clothes, bedding and utensils are disinfected.
Traditional term for any fine to medium grained igneous rock, containing large crystal fragments.
A dump for wasters; pieces of pottery spoiled in the manufacturing process.
Steel coated in zinc, giving good protection against weathering.
Iron coated in zinc, giving good protection against weathering.
A building used for broadcasting radio programmes for public entertainment. Often includes recording studios, transmitters and offices. Use RADIO STATION for non-broadcasting uses eg. Military.
A small, defensive settlement, usually consisting of one dwelling and ancillary buildings, surrounded by a palisade.

A high status, walled, Roman burial ground containing cremations and/or inhumations in mausolea, tombs, barrows, coffins or cists. Dating from the late 1st to the 4th Century AD. DO NOT USE for cemeteries of later dates which are walled.
A building where the upper storeys rest on projecting floor joists and so create the effect of an overhang.
This is the top term for the class. See MONUMENT <BY FORM> Class list for narrow terms.
The homestead of a farm consisting of a farmhouse and working farm buildings, with yards, other working areas and usually a garden to the house.
A rustic building of picturesque design, often associated with a model farm, country house or estate. Although ornamental in design they are intended to be functional.
Use only for features assumed to be archaeological but which cannot be identified more precisely without further investigation .Use more specific term where known
A structure which can be an area within a building, a separate building within a complex or a detached architectural component of a building
A shop which dispenses medicinal drugs and other health-related items. Can include an area for the preparation and manufacture of medicines and other drugs.
A market consisting of stalls erected in the street and selling a variety of goods.
A warehouse used for the storage of fruit and/or vegetables.
A booth, shed or stall erected at the side of a road, canal, bridge or gate where a toll must be paid.
Traditionally the chief residence of a land owner. Now used specifically to describe the residence of the Lord Mayor of London.

An anti aircraft battery armed with 3 inch rockets with a ceiling of 22,000 feet. Both single and multiple launchers were designed. Single launchers being used to defend vulnerable points such as coastal batteries with multiple launchers defending town.
A site where a body of troops is temporarily or permanently lodged, with or without entrenchments and fortifications.
A searchlight battery, which points out to sea, used to locate enemy shipping
A tower, containing a gate, built into the walls of a town, castle or similar fortification.
A building in which a parliament meets and conducts the business of government.
An area of a garden with a semi-circular backdrop formed by an ornamental, architectural structure or a natural feature grown to the required shape eg. a hedge
A large bath used for Jewish ritual ceremonies.
A column, in the form of a female figure, used to support an entablature.
An area within a hospital where patients receiving privately-funded medical and surgical treatment are accommodated. Often includes separate rooms.
An area within a hospital where patients with contagious diseases are isolated from the rest of the hospital.
An area within a hospital where children are accommodated during the period of their medical or surgical treatment.
Seed of the cotton plant from which edible oil is extracted.
Stone which has been crushed for use in the construction industry.
Products, such as cheese and butter, manufactured from milk.
Fish which has been preserved by drying.
Fruit which has been preserved by drying.
A high explosive, manufactured by absorbing unstable nitroglycerine in a material such as kieselguhr, a soft, earthy material.
The large, pointed teeth, made of ivory, which are specially developed to protrude from the mouth of elephants.
Manufactured goods, including shells, dynamite etc., containing substances which can be made to explode.
Machinery including tractors, ploughs, harrows etc, which are used on farms.
Soft, pear-shaped fruits of the Ficus carica tree. They can be eaten fresh or dried.
Any of a large group of cold blooded vertebrates who live exclusively in water. Also can refer to the flesh of fish which is eaten.
Equipment used to catch fish
The fibrous stalks of the plant, Linum usitatissimum, which can be processed and used to manufacture linen.
Stone consisting of nearly pure silica, which can be used as a building material or knapped to produce flint objects.
A soft, powder used in the manufacture of bread and foodstuffs, obtained by grinding wheat or other grain.
The edible product of a plant, usually consisting of the seed and its sweet, juicy envelope.
Materials or substances, including petrol, firewood etc., used as a source of heat or power.
Grains of cereal used as food.
A smooth, flammable liquid, produced naturally or from plants or animals, and used for a variety of purposes.
Materials or goods which have been produced wholly or in part from oil, e.g. petroleum.
The plant, Allium cepa, whose bulb is used, usually for culinary purposes.
Citrus fruit of a distinctive orange colour.
An unprocessed mineral, collected for the extraction of metals or other substances contained within the mineral.
A liquid used to provide a protective or decorative cover to a surface.
Oil derived from palms, used for a variety of purposes.
Thin sheets of material used for a variety of purposes such as writing on, painting on, or printing on.
Flat stones used to create flat surfaces, e.g. pavements.
Use for cargoes which are not specified.
An alcoholic beverage distilled from grain or malt and usually flavoured with juniper berries.
Hard, transparent, brittle substance manufactured by fusing soda or potash with other ingredients. Used for glazing windows and in the manufacture of drinking vessels.
A yellowish, tarnish-resistant precious metal used to make jewellery and coins.
Collective name for the seeds of various cereal grasses.
A granular, crystalline, hard rock often used as a building material.
Blocks carved out of granite and used as a building material.
Small fragments of waterworn stone used in the construction industry.
The excrement of seabirds and bats used as a fertilizer.
A powder made from charcoal, sulphur and potassium nitrate and used as an explosive in fireworks, flintlock guns etc.
An aircraft, either whole or in part. Aircraft often survive as commemorative monuments, gate guardians or crash sites.
A site or building where ore is processed to obtain metal.
A substance secreted by some plants which hardens upon drying but is soluble in water.
Weapons including portable firearms and large artillery pieces.
A herbaceous plant grown for its fibre and marijuana, a drug derivative. The fibres are used in the manufacture of rope.
People who leave their native country to settle in another, often for financial or religious reasons.
Waste material resulting from industrial manufacturing processes.
A magnetic metal found abundantly in certain ores and widely used for the manufacture of tools, machinery etc. Iron is also a chief component of  steel.
Goods, including machinery, manufactured from iron.
Fibres obtained from plants and used in the manufacture of ropes, sacking, canvas etc.
A fatty substance derived from the fat of animals used in cooking.
Narrow strips of wood used in the building industry.
A soft, heavy, malleable metal, often obtained from the mineral galena. Traditionally used in the construction industry for roofing and plumbing.
Ore containing high levels of lead, eg. galena.
Animal skins which have been treated by tanning or similar.
The hard, heavy wood obtained from plants of the genus Guaiacum.
A white, caustic solid obtained by heating limestone and used in the preparation of mortar and cement.
Stone composed mainly of calcium carbonate, used as a building material and in the production of cement.

Fish which have been caught and kept alive. Fish were kept alive on ships in earlier centuries to ensure they reached their destination as fresh as possible. In more recent times exotic fish have been kept alive to sell as pets.
Railway engines designed to travel under its own power and to draw railway carriages and rolling stock.
A large room within a hospital set aside for emergency patients.
A building used by an association of persons for social and recreational purposes or for the promotion of some common object.
A room or building used as a store, usually for documents, works of art, books etc.

A multi-storey, fortified hall house with one of the crosswings being raised in the form of a crenellated tower. Permanently occupied, they date from the mid 14th to the 17th century and are found mainly in the border counties of the North of England.
A residence for military personnel.
Use most appropriate term where known. If uncertain use both terms
Oil used to lubricate moving parts, particularly in machinery.
Apparatus used for applying a mechanical force, or to perform a particular function. Use more specific type where known.
Fortified wine produced on the island of Madeira.
Hard wood, reddish-brown in colour with a fine-grain often used in the manufacture of furniture.
Letters and parcels transported on behalf of the dispatchers by the postal services.
Grain, especially barley, prepared for brewing, distilling or vinegar making.
A flat slab of stone used to provide a level surface from which to measure the height of racehorses at a meeting, as part of the handicapping and anti fraud systems.
Collective name, in a true geological sense, for a metamorphosed limestone eg. Carrara marble. In British sense, any decorative stone that will take a polish, eg. Purbeck marble.
Long poles or spars, usually set vertically, on sailing boats and ships to support the sails.
A powder made by grinding the edible part of various grains, and used as a foodstuff.
A building or site used for the production of both chemical and organic fertilizer.
A building housing an economizer, a machine designed to preheat water for boilers.
A building used to store fertilizers.
A bridge, often over a canal or road, allowing access between two parcels of land.
A small dwelling for the solitary confinement of a pious reclusive religious woman or nun, often attached to the north wall of a church. A squint enabled the occupant to witness the Mass.
WWII secret bases, sometimes partially underground, intended for use by the British resistance in the eventuality of a foreign invasion.
A site or structure on which a signal, especially a fire, could be placed as a warning or means of communication. Use for beacon sites or surviving beacon structures.
Sites and structures associated with the manufacture of bricks and tiles. Includes sites associated with earth extraction and preparation.
A building for housing deer overnight.
A building in which raw pottery is finished by dipping it in glaze.
A building, usually associated with a hospital, where doctors live. Include blocks of self-contained flats.
A mine in which access is gained by a straight entrance driven on a constant downward slope. Use with product(s) extracted and MINE where known, eg. COAL MINE.
A building or site used for the production of bricks and other items, from a clay with refractory properties.
A building, room or suite of rooms where books, or other materials, are classified by subject and stored for use by the library's members.
Term used by the RAF to describe an open walled structure built of concrete, brick or sandbags which enclosed one or more machine-guns mounted on pintels for light anti-aircraft and ground defence.
A monumental burial place, usually for a single person or family.
An excavation open to the sky, caused by the extraction of coal, stone or similar. Use with product type where known.
A gun battery used to signal warnings to ships during bad weather.
A complex, comprising a workshop and a storage yard, used by a stonemason.
A missile base armed with the Bristol Bloodhound surface-to-air missile. Bloodhounds were deployed to defend the launch sites of Thor Intermediate Range Ballistic Missiles.
A missile base armed with the Thor Intermediate Range Ballistic Missile. Thor Missiles were deployed in Britain under joint British/US control between 1959 and 1964.
A house provided for the treasurer of a cathedral, palace or similar.

A pit in a road or trackway covered with a grid, usually of metal poles (but can be of wood or stone) with sufficient space between the poles to prevent animals from crossing, without restricting access for vehicles and people.
An underground room or building with an arched roof, often used as a burial chamber. Use wider site type where known.
Sites associated with the manufacture and engineering of vehicles.
A tower-like structure of wood or brick with a wooden cap and sails which are driven around by the wind producing power to work the internal machinery. Use with product type where known.
The flesh of animals, either raw or cooked, used as food.
A heavy, metallic element, which is liquid at room temperature. Used in thermometers and medicinal preparations.
Any material, including gold, silver, copper, tin etc. which is ductile, malleable, usually lustrous and a good conductor of heat and electricity.
Equipment, including uniforms, small arms and field pieces, used by the armed forces.
Vehicles owned or used by the armed forces. Includes tanks, armoured vehicles as well as civilian vehicles in use by the military eg. ambulances.
An ore containing sufficient quantities of a mineral as to make its extraction profitable.
Naturally occuring substances eg. coal and salt, obtained by mining.
Explosive devices, usually of metal, placed in the ground or floating in water with the purpose of endangering enemy personnel or shipping.
Unable to identify actual place from documentary sources alone.
Scotland
An uncrystallized syrup, produced as part of the sugar refining process. Used as a food additive and in the production of rum.
Human beings. Use more specific type where known.
A dark, viscous liquid, obtained from the ground, which is refined for use as a fuel for motor vehicles and in generators to produce light and heat, and as a solvent.
Goods, usually foodstuffs, which have been sealed inside canisters, usually made of tin or steel, to preserve them.
Salts or organic derivatives of phosphoric acid, especially compounds of Calcium or Iron found in cereals and minerals.
Domesticated animals, derived from the wild boar, kept as a source of ham, bacon and pork products.
Softwood obtained from trees of the genus Pinus, often used for the manufacture of furniture.
A fine white clay used specifically for the manufacture of clay tobacco pipes and for whitening leather.
A dark, viscous substance obtained, from the distillation of wood tar or turpentine, and used as a sealant for caulking the seams of a ship or boat.
Hard semi-translucent ceramic material made out of kaolin, quartz and feldspar which is biscuit fired at around 1000 degrees Celsius and glaze fired at around 1300 degrees Celsius.
The flesh obtained from pigs eaten as food.
A strong, sweet fortified wine made in Portugal.
The edible tubers of plants of the family Ipomoea Batatas eaten as a vegetable.
Traditionally any food preserved by boiling with sugar, salting, pickling etc. Nowadays used specifically for fruit which has been preserved with sugar.
Equipment and parts used in the manufacture of railway tracks, locomotives and rolling stock.
A grain, obtained from the grass Oryza sativa, eaten as a staple in many parts of the world.
Carriages, locomotives and other vehicles used on a railway.
Thin plates of slate, usually rectangular in shape, used as roofing tiles.
A cord manufactured by twisting strands of material, such as flax, cotton, nylon etc., together to form a strong line.
A fine, soft fibre produced by silkworms and used to make thread for textiles. Also the cloth made from this thread.
A precious metal, lustrous white in colour. Used for the manufacture of coins and other valuable items.
A building or room for the storage of vegetables, particularly root vegetables, for human consumption.
People who are considered to be the property of someone else and who are bound to obedience.
Mud, which has often been dredged from the beds of rivers.
Wood which is soft or easily cut, particularly the wood of coniferous trees.
People who serve as members of an army.
Aromatic vegetable substances, either in their natural form or ground, used to add flavour or scent to food.
Alloys of iron which have great strength, malleability and which are able to be tempered to different degrees of hardness. Used for the manufacturwe of tools, machinery etc.
Rock or hard minerals used as a building material and for carving etc.
A sweet, crystalline subtance obtained from sugar beet or sugar cane and used in cooking, brewing etc.
Weapons used for cutting and thrusting, consisting of a blade and a hilt.
Items of crockery and cutlery which are used whilst dining, either to eat with or for table decoration.
A fatty substance rendered from animal fat and used in the manufacture of soap, candles and for dressing leather.
A thick, viscous, black liquid obtained by the destructive distillation of coal or other organic substances used for preserving wood or rope and for covering road surfaces.
Dried leaves from the plant Camellia sinensis, which is used to make a drink by infusing the leaves in boiling water.
Threads of material used to form cloth.
Items made from cloth, wool etc used as a covering for the human body.
A ship or brig peculiar to the Mediterranean.
French coasting vessel
A lustrous, malleable metal, which is resistant to corrosion. Tin is used in alloys such as pewter and used in the manufacture of cans for the storage of food.
Solid bars made from pure tin.
Sheets of iron or steel coated with tin.
The dried leaves of the plants, Nicotiana tabacum or Nicotiana rustica, which are smoked (in pipes, cigars or cigarettes), chewed or taken as snuff for their relaxing properties.
Manufactured objects and devices used to apply a force to an object or perform a particular mechanical function.

Clothes which are distinctive in cut, colour and fabric and worn by members of the armed forces, emergency services or civilian organizations to help to distinguish their members form other organizations.
Any plants which are grown to be eaten. Includes parts of plants, especially roots and leaves.
A sour tasting liquid, produced from wine and other liquors, used as a preservative, in pickling, or as a flavouring for food.
Oil obtained from the rendered blubber of whales, used as a fuel in old oil lamps.
The hair from the coat of goats and sheep, made into yarn and used in the manufacture of woollen cloth.
Ceramic vessels produced out of wet clay which is shaped ad dried or fired to harden. In some cases other materials like sand are added to the clay.

SCOPE_NOTE: A fine grained rock which splits easily into plates. Used for the manufacture of roofing tiles etc.
The seed of the flax plant pressed into cakes and used as cattle fodder.
The top layer of earth consisting of humus and rock particles.
Woven or felted fabric used in the manufacture of garments, tablecloths, towels etc.
Solid bars made from pure lead.
Pipes manufactured from copper used for a variety of purposes, especially plumbing.
General merchandise and saleable commodities. Use more specific type where known.
Merchandise wrapped in canvas and tightly bound with cords or hoops to form bales.
Small fish, Sardina pilchardus, common to European waters and eaten as a food fish.
Plain, white, cotton cloth often unbleached.
Wood from the elm tree.
Timber from trees of the genus Juglans, used for the manufacture of furniture
The bony outgrowths found on the heads of mammals used for display or combat used for a variety of purposes.
Flat, rectangular piece of material, traditionally of wood but now of any material, used in the construction industries.
Materials used to equip and fit out a ship. Includes masts, spars, rigging etc. Use only where evidence is less specific, otherwise use most relevant term.
Various flavoured aromatic and savoury substances, such as herbs, salt etc, used to impart flavour to food.
Includes all forms of paper and any products manufactured from it.
Includes all trees, flowers, vegetables etc. and any products manufactured from them.
Gold fashioned into coins for use as currency.
Silver fashioned into coin for use as currency.
Metal, either precious or base, in the form of bars and coins. Use more specific type.
Articles, usually woven from coarse fibres or made from hard wearing materials (eg. rubber or cork) used to protect the floor or for lying, sitting or kneeling on.
Iron, usually unworked, in the form of bars.
Previous name for Chennai.
Bordered by the continents of Africa, Asia and Europe, the Mediterranean covers some 967,000 sq miles. It is linked to the Atlantic Ocean by the Straits of Gibraltar.
Mistranscription of 'Morlaix'.
Transcription/transliteration from Cyrllic alphabet to Latin alphabet.
Generally used as a synonym for the South Pacific Ocean.
Netherlands
Continent.
The land mass comprising, the continents of North and Central America and South America. Use more specific type.
Bordering the continents of Africa, Antarctica, Europe, North and South America the Atlantic is the second largest of the oceans, covering 31,736,000 square miles.
A heavy grating, often made of wood or iron, usually lowered vertically as a defensive barrier at the entrance to a gatehouse or barbican.
That portion of the Atlantic Ocean which stretches from the Arctic Ocean in the north to the Equator.
That portion of the Atlantic Ocean which stretches from the Equator in the north to Antarctica.
A building used for the safe storage and public display of jewellery, eg. the Jewel House at the Tower of London.
A sea within a sea, the Arabian Sea consists of the northern part of the Indian Ocean bordered by India, Pakistan, Iran, Oman and Yemen.
A sea within a sea, the Adriatic consists of that part of the Mediterranean which separates Italy from the Balkans and Greece.

A factory or group of buildings engaged in the manufacture of acetone. A variety of processes may be used to manufacture acetone including the use of destructive distallation of wood and fermentation technology.
A long, narrow, rectangular plot of land used for the manufacture of rope. Usually walled, it may include small buildings and awnings at each end. Often attached to a warehouse.
A mill used for the production of wadding, as opposed to yarn or cloth. Often associated with steam or water power.
Use for the historic region of Flanders only
A purpose built pit, usually below a gatehouse or barbican, into which the counterweight of a drawbridge could be lowered, thus enabling the bridge to be raised.
Country bordering the Black Sea.
That portion of the Pacific which stretches from the Arctic Ocean in the north to the equator.
That portion of the Pacific which stretches from the equator to Antarctica.

Bordering the five continents of Antarctica, Asia, Australasia, North and South America, the Pacific is the largest of the world's oceans, and covers more area (63,838,000 square miles) than that of the combined seven continents.
The ocean which surrounds the continent of Antarctica, and includes the most southerly regions of the three largest oceans, the Pacific, Atlantic and Indian.
A chemical works engaged in the production or refining of toluene, a substance extracted from coal tar or specific types of crude oil, and used in the production of explosives during WW1.
An armoured fighting vehicle. Often survive as commemorative monuments, targets and coastal wrecks.
A factory used for the processing of isinglass, a product obtained from the swim bladders of sturgeon and used in the brewing industry as part of the  process for clearing wine and beer.
A works producing gelatine from animal products for use as a culinary setting agent and in the photography, dyeing, brewing and glue industries. For explosives use GELATINE WORKS (EXPLOSIVE)
Drinks containing alcohol, an intoxicating substance found in fermented or distilled liquids.
Military provisions, traditionally of all types but now used specifically for projectiles and propellants such eg. bullets and gunpowder.
Hair taken from animals and used in a variety of manufacturing processes.
Products derived from the carcasses or hides of animals. Includes bone and ivory products, blubber and grease but not meat.
Animals and products made from the carcasses and hides of dead animals.
The round, firm fleshed fruit of the apple (Malus Domestica) tree. Grown in numerous varieties throughout the world.
The powdery residue resulting from the combustion of a substance eg. wood and used for various manufacturing processes.
The outer layer of tissue on a tree or woody plant, often used in the dyeing and tanning industries.
Containers of cylindrical form, traditionally made of curved wooden staves bound together by hoops of metal. Also includes modern plastic and metal barrels.
Seeds of any of the various related plants of the leguminous plant Vicia faba.
An alcoholic drink made by the fermentation of malt and flavoured with hops or other bitters.
Containers filled with high explosive, which can be fired from artillery pieces, thrown, dropped by aircraft or placed by hand and detonated in various ways.
Alcoholic drink distilled from wine or fermented fruit juice.
Originally a metallic alloy of copper and tin or zinc, now used solely for an alloy of copper and zinc.
A staple foodstuff made with flour, water and usually yeast, which is kneaded and then baked. Can include unleavened (no yeast)  varieties.
Construction blocks manufactured using clay which is then fired or sun dried.
Dairy produce obtained by churning cream and used in cookery as a source of fat.
A body of wax or tallow, usually formed into a long, thin, cylindrical shape enclosing a wick and burnt to produce light.
Meat precooked and then sealed in cans made from steel, tin or aluminium plate to preserve it.
A piece of military ordnance, of sufficient size to require mounting and used for firing projectiles, traditionally cannon balls but more recently high explosive shells.
A strong unbleached cloth manuifactured from hemp, flax or similarly coarse yarn. Used mainly in the manufacture of sails, tents and for painting on.
Large mammals of the genus Bos, domesticated to provide milk, beef and materials eg. leather. Use only for live animals.
Dried produce especially, hay, straw etc. used to feed cattle.
Powder mixed with water and applied as a paste for binding stones and bricks or for forming floors, walls etc.
Any of the plants of the grass family, Graminae, cultivated for their edible seeds, especially corn, wheat etc.
A crude, stone-built shelter for persons involved in lime production and the processing of lime burning.
