Substances, either natural or man-made, used to make soil more fertile.
Includes chemical and natural fertilizers and waste products. use more specific term.
Steel, usually unworked, in the form of bars.
Sweet red peppers.
Porous black residue of partly burnt wood, bones etc. used as fuel or, in the form of charcoal pencils, as a tool for drawing.
Dairy produce formed from the curds of milk, coagulated by rennet and pressed into a solid mass.
Substances, including acids, alkalis etc. obtained by or used in a chemical process.
Clay used in the manufacture of fine ceramics especially porcelain.
A type of Red Wine from Bordeaux in France.
Fine grained earth which becomes more plastic when water is added. Mainly used in the manufacture of bricks, pottery and other ceramics.
Hard, black, carbonized plant matter, usually found in seams below the earth's surface and used as a fuel and for the manufacture of gas.
A joint which has a splay interrupted by a step
A joint with each timber ending in a cut slanted across its length.
The point or block from which an arch or vault starts. The block generally has a horizontal base and sloped top.
A triangular or wedge-shaped timber cocking-piece attached to the upper face of a rafter near its foot  in order to reduce the slope above the eaves. Such eaves are referred to as being sprocketed.
One or more arches built across an angle between two walls to support a polygonal or circular structure.
An aperture cut obliquely in a wall, usually of a chancel, affording a view between the high altar and the aisles or side chapels.

A short, tapered, vertical stone supporting a rough stone disc so resembling a toadstool, often forming one of several uprights on which a timber structure, such as a granary  rests, protecting the building from damp and vermin.
Glass that has been coloured by fusing glass with a metallic oxide film or by burning pigment into the surface.
A tower, normally forming part of a larger structure, housing a staircase.
A small or subordinate tower, normally forming part of a larger structure, housing a spiral or winding stair.
A flight of steps leading from one level to another.
A room which contains, wholly or partly, a staircase.
A small hole filled or vacated by a stake, normally driven into the ground.
A series of water or engine-driven crushing machines used in ore dressing.
A room or group of rooms usually reserved for use by the monarchy or government.
A steam engine working at a fixed location.
A crane deriving its power from steam generated from solid fuels.

A power source deriving its energy from solid fuel, which is used to boil water in an almost closed vessel, producing steam which moves one or more pistons in tight fitting cylinders, the energy being transmitted by a piston rod to a diversity of devices
A pump driven by steam power generated by solid fuels.
A steam motor in which rotory motion is produced by steam impinging directly upon a series of vanes upon the circumference of a revolving cylinder or disc.
A steam-powered machine used for raising materials such as ore or water from a pit or shaft.
A collective term embracing a church tower's entire structure, including its spire.
A compact, free standing steam engine introduced circa 1810 and built mainly in small sizes.
A series of flat-topped structures, usually wooden or stone, on which a person places their feet when ascending or descending, facilitating movement from one level to another.
A room for higher-ranking servants.
An arch where vertical piers raise the springing line.
The hole through which the fuel for a fire is put to start and maintain the fire.
A projecting, sometimes decorated, finish to a moulding, chamfer, label, hood-mould or string-course.
A joint which has a splay with a short perpendicular section at each end.
A room set aside for the storage of goods or valuables. Use more specific term where known.
A fixed basin, containing Holy Water, positioned near the entrance of a church, usually placed within a niche, on a wall or pier, or freestanding upon a pedestal.
An arch whose purpose is to arrest or prevent structural movement in a building.
A transverse timber in aisled construction, joining aisle posts below tiebeam level, to allow rearing of pairs of posts.
A feature found during an archaeological investigation which implies the presence of a monument, building, structure or human activity.
A sloping timber in a staircase holding the ends of treads and risers.
A horizontal, moulded band, usually projecting, running across a wall, often indicating the position of a building's interior floor.
A part of a building or structure that is an element of the construction.
A plan form of a structure or building.
A member whose purpose is to keep two other members apart, so acting in a state of compression.
A block in the position of a tiebeam.
A subsidiary member, usually vertical, in a framed  wall or partition.
A planked or battened door, with large nails or pegs with projecting heads keeping it intact.
A room for private work, reading etc.
A building plan in which the rooms are symmetrically placed.
A building or structural plan shaped like a T.
A recess for holding the Holy Sacrament.
A compact steam engine of moderate power in which the steam cylinder was placed vertically on a table with the crosshead and guides mounted immediately above.
A room for storing and maintaining the equipment used in riding, eg saddles, bridles, reins etc.
A pole projecting to the rear of a post mill to allow the sails to be moved into the wind.
A horizontal, stationary steam engine with two cylinders in line, one behind the other, the steam passing through each cylinder in turn.
In a truss, a rafter used to stiffen the principal rafter by doubling it.
A ceiling beam aligned with the length of a building.
A plan of a building which consists of two or more cells where the chimney is placed on the axis of the building between two rooms and midway between the lateral walls.
A purlin that is joined to the back of a principal rafter.
A staircase for the use of servants, tradesmen or individuals not permitted to use the main part of a building or establishment.
A machine used in the worsted industry for cleaning woollen slivers after gilling and cording.
A plan featuring a doorless entry to a lobby in front of an axial chimney-stack.
A small semicircular moulding.
Defences or an external wall surrounding a castle's motte or keep. Also a castle's outer court, or a court within a castle's walls.
A room for baking.

A platform projecting from the surface of a wall of a building carried on brackets, consoles or columns, usually placed before windows or openings, and protected by a railing or balustrade. It can also be a gallery in an auditorium.
A canopy suspended, or on pillars, over a throne or altar.
A decorative ball usually used to ornament a bench end, canopy, gable, pinnacle or spire.
Decorative ornamentation in the form of a ball enclosed within petals.
A hand operated machine for winding cotton and linen thread into balls - invented in 1802.
A room for holding receptions particularly balls.
An upright member supporting a coping or handrail in a balustrade or staircase.
The structure consisting of a series of balusters supporting a rail or coping, and sometimes a base and pedestal, on a parapet, balcony or staircase.
A column in which the shaft is interrupted by stone bands.
A flat band carrying a motto.
An open area within a bank where financial transactions take place.
A hall normally reserved for holding feasts on special occasions.
A building, or part of a church, used for baptismal rites, usually containing a font.
A joint in which a dovetailed timber's surface is proud of the receiving member on one side.
A joint in which the tenon retains one or more of the original sides of the timber.
A board fixed at the gable end to purlins, often decorated.
A semi-circular or pointed vault uninterrupted by cross vaults, the ceiling bearing a resemblence to a tunnel or the inside of a barrel.
A small auxiliary engine to help start up a large steam engine - invented 1866.
A small turret that projects from the top of a tower or parapet.
The lowest part of a structure, such as a pier, or the section of an order on which the shaft of a column sits.
A small outer courtyard, or service-yard.
A cruck, forming the main upright of a wall but whose blades are truncated by a transverse member.
The bottom storey of a building, often below or partially below ground level.
A plan type, usually for a church, having a rectangular core with one apsidal end wall.
An arch consisting of a segment of a circle connected to other segments with smaller radii.
A Byzantine bell-type capital, ornamented with carving resembling wicker-work or basket-weave.
An outward projection from a defensive wall allowing the defenders to attack the flanks of any force attacking the wall.
A container for holding water in which to bathe.
A room intended to contain a bath and often other toilet facilities.
A small timber fixed to a wall to support items such as cladding. Also a strip of timber fixed across two or more parallel boards to join them together or conceal their join.
A door with a planked outer face and spaced horizontal members such as battens or ledges on the inner face.
An indented parapet consisting of raised parts, called merlons, separated by gaps, or crenelles.
A regular structural subdivision or compartment within a building, defined by dividing walls or the positions of the principal supporting members.
Bay-leaf shaped decorative ornamentation, usually adorning mouldings or friezes, often depicted in a garland arrangement.
A window that forms a projection from the body of a building, extending down to ground level, forming a bay in the wall's interior.
Decorative ornamentation consisting of alternating bead shapes with small, elliptical forms resembling reels
A decorative moulding depicting an animal or bird head with a tongue or beak that overlaps the moulding set below it.
A main load-bearing horizontal member.

An engine which operates machinery via a pivoted, horizontal beam with a piston located at one end and a reciprocating pump beneath the other, resulting in a rocking, seesaw-like motion. Variations featured the steam piston placed above the beam.
A small self-contained rotative Beam Steam Engine.
A timber placed horizontally in a cob or stone wall to support the foot of a post or cruck blade.
A small moulding on the top of the architrave in the Doric order.
A purlin that is joined to a principal rafter by a tenon joint.
An inward radial-flow reaction turbine developed by James Thomson.
A purlin that is threaded through a hole in the principal rafter.
A depressed arch formed around three arcs: two struck from the springing line with one centrally placed arc struck from below it.
A building plan consisting of three rooms placed in a straight row.
A machine for beating out or separating grain from corn.
An improved water frame spinning machine which differed from the water frame in mechanical details, being larger and operating at a much faster speed.
A building plan in which a passage crosses the axis of the building, often at one end of a hall, with an external door at each end.
A purlin that passes a principal rafter
A joint in which the tenon passes completely through the receiving timber.
A machine used in the silk industry for applying the final twist  to silk threads to make them suitable  for weaving into a fabric.
A major horizontal timber spanning a roof space to connect a pair of principal rafters and prevent them spreading.
A vertical cladding consisting of tiles hung in overlapping rows.
An early form of powered forging hammer, featuring a cast-iron hammer head fixed to a pivoted wooden arm, introduced circa 1500 and used primarily in the iron industry.
A room containing a toilet, water closet etc..
A grave or sepulchre enlosed or covered by a memorial.
A large, convex moulding, sometimes ornamented, set at the base of a column and above its plinth.
A tall structure of any form, high in proportion  to its lateral dimensions, often rising in stages, freestanding or part of another building, often used in fortifications and churches.
A window which has its head beam decorated with elements of tracery.

An arrangement by which panels, screens, vaults or windows are divided into parts of different shapes or sizes by means of moulded stone bars or ribs, called form-pieces or forms in the Medieval period.
A small mobile steam engine.
A large division of a building which lies across, and at right angles to, its main axis, such as the arms either side of the crossing in a cruciform church.
A beam that runs the width of a building.
A rib which spans a vault passing from springer to springer at right angles to the axis of the vault.
A crane, usually used in engineering workshops, that can be moved from place to place, often by means of rails.
A crane, usually used in engineering workshops that can be moved from place to place by means of overhead rails..
A large wheel, often of timber construction, rotated by the walking action of people or animals placed within it usually to provide a power source for another machine or device.
A crane operated by a treadmill turned by the walking action of men placed within it.
A plan featuring three foils or lobes radiating outwards from a central point.
A window in the form of a three-leafed clover.
A purlin that sits in a trench cut in the back of a principal rafter.
A grooved block placed in series, alternating with the metopes, in a Doric frieze.
A short timber supporting end of joists or rafters to facilitate an opening, such as a door or dormer.

A design of steam engine in which either three cylinders, in the case of vertical engines, or four cylinders on horizontal engines, permit steam to be expanded three times as it passes through the installation.
The junction of two timbers at right angles which involves chamfers or mouldings meeting on a diagonal line and where the timbers meet on the 45 degree line of the chamfer or moulding junction.
A steam engine in which the pistons are long relative to their diameters, and there are no piston rods and crossheads.
A combination of timbers to form a frame placed at intervals and carrying the purlins.
Decorative ornamentation in the form of an upright, stalked trefoil used in Tudor architecture.
A decorative feature in the style of a formalized rose.
A motor in which rotary motion is produced by motive power, usually of water, steam or gas, impinging directly on a series of vanes upon the circumference of a revolving cylinder or disc.
A small tower, usually round or polygonal and attached to a structure. When a separate building, treat as a monument.
An arch of the Tuscan Order.
A base of the Tuscan Order, featuring a square plinth supporting a large torus with a fillet above.
A capital of the Tuscan Order featuring a square abacus.
A column of the Tuscan Order featuring a plain, unfluted shaft.
A moulding on an entablature that is between the frieze and the corona.
A small projection designed to allow space for a bed.
A room intended to contain a bed.
A roof with a bow-shaped, segmental timber truss which has the space between its members filled by a lattice of crossing diagonal rods.

The tower, generally attached to a church or other building but sometimes separate, where bells are hung and from which sound is emitted. Also applied to the upper chamber where bells are hung, or the wooden structure supporting them.
The core of a capital.
A capital which is circular and has several mouldings but no foliage.
A high tower, attached to or detached from a building such as a church, with a belfry stage containing bells.
A housing for one or more bells, usually gabled or roofed.
A turret on the side of a house providing views across the surrounding countryside.
A series of billet mouldings forming a decorative band of small, regularly placed squared or rounded blocks.
A joint in which the end of one timber is cut in V- form and rests on the edge of another timber, frequently found between common rafters and wall plates.
A principal member in a cruck truss.
A room dedicated to the drawing or letting of blood, a procedure once thought to possess medicinal properties.
A succession of arches on shafts with no openings, attached to and used to enliven a wall.
A series of columns in a straight line supporting an entablature with no openings or glazing.
A small piece of timber occupying the angle between two other timbers.
An Italian cornice consisting of a bed moulding, a row of plain block corbels or modillions, and a corona or cornice.
A column whose shaft is interrupted by square blocks.
A steam engine driving a reciprocating air pump to provide air for a blast furnace.
A steam generator comprising a pressure vessel, and/or rows of tubes arranged to receive heat from a firegrate.
A moulding which projects beyond the face of a panel or frame, usually found in panelling or in doors.
One of the rolls forming the sides of an ionic capital, joining the volutes of the front and rear faces.
A carved, convex block, often richly decorated, at the intersections of vault-ribs, beam-junctions or terminations of mouldings.
A small, finely-furnished room, traditionally where a lady could retire to be alone or entertain intimate friends.
A window set within a curved projection from the face of a wall.
A private room or parlour usually at the same level as the hall.
A roof constructed of horizontal tiebeams and curved trusses.
Timber framed construction where a box of horizontal and vertical members is created to support the roof.
A complete cross-frame from ground level to ridge in a box-framed building.
An inclined timber used to support and provide rigidity to roofs, partitions etc.
A small support designed to help support a weight, such as that of a projecting member.
A decorative moulding cosisting of two ogee-forms with joined faces.
A room for the storage of bread, biscuits, flour etc. Often part of a buttery in medieval times.
A room where meals, particularly breakfast are partaken.

A waterwheel in which the incoming water is directed onto the periphery at approximately the same level as the axle, the water being kept in contact with the floats, or buckets, by breastwork of masonry, timber or iron.
A joint consisting of a projecting tongue fitting into an open housing in a scarf joint or the apex of a rafter.
An octagonal spire atop a square tower, the transition between structures effected by partially pyramidical masonry forms called broaches.
Decorative motif in the form of an ox skull.
A feature which forms part of a building and has a specific functional usage or decorative form.
An early type of steam engine, similar to a Cornish Engine, designed by Edward Bull.
An oval window placed with its long axis horizontal. The term is often applied to similar round windows.
The pit in which human or animal remains are placed for interment,which may be either an inhumation or cremation.
A treasury, often the bursar's room in a college or university.
A nineteenth century plan where two or four wings of a house are constructed at an angle to the core, usually at approximately 45 degrees to the wall of the core building.
A room for the storage of food and drink.
A mass of stone or brick built against or as part of a wall to provide additional strength to it.
A small room used as a study for the preservation of papers etc. Generally use for any small room appended to a larger one.
A decorative moulding shaped to resemble a length of cable or twisted rope.
The hot room in a Roman baths.
An entablature of the Tuscan Order consisting of a plain architrave, frieze and cornice without decoration or enrichments..

A biggest and plainest of the classical architectural orders, based upon a simplified version of the Doric Order. Sometimes called the Gigantic order, though not to be confused with the Colossal or Giant Order.
A building or structural plan with a U shape.
An underground, or partially underground, vault or crypt beneath a church or other building.
A waterwheel where the inflow of water strikes the paddles, or floatboards, below the axis of the wheel.
A steam engine in which steam flows in one direction only at each stroke, as opposed to the commoner contra-flow engines.
A cruck with its feet sitting on a ceiling beam on the first floor.
A brace extending from a vertical to a higher horizontal timber.
One of a pair of inclined struts that meet at the bottom to form a V shape.
A room or space with an arched ceiling or roof, the depth of which exceeds its span.
A gap which allows air to circulate.
A shaft constructed to allow the circulation of fresh air, into a mine, building etc.
A rafter set outside a gable to carry the roof beyond the wall face.
An engine in which a vertical piston rod supplies energy via a crankshaft directly to the flywheel suspended above the cylinder.
A room used in a church to store vestments and for the clergy to dress in.
A decorative, spiral scroll form, thought to have been based upon the shape of a ram's horn, employed in consoles, modillions, the capitals of orders such as the Ionic, Composite and Corinthian etc..
A wedge shaped stone or brick forming part of an arch or vault, with its radiating sides coinciding with the radii of that arch.
A roof consisting of a series of rafters and arch braces set closely together to give the appearance of a continuous, uninterrupted arch or curved plate.
A clear area in a church covered by the transepts and crossing.
A structure, usually of brick, stone or timber, that encloses or defines a space or room.
A wall mounted, hydraulically operated crane or winch, sometimes used to operate lifts.
A two dimensional image using paint applied to the surface of a wall.
A longitudinal timber set on top of a timber frame, brick or masonry wall on which roof-trusses or rafters rest.
A post, usually carrying a tiebeam, which forms part of a wall in a timber framed building.
A room intended for, and usually equipped to aid, the performance of ablutions.
A device for hoisting, or operating pumps, using water displacement as a lifting and balancing medium.
A machine used for spinning cotton powered by water.
A pump used to move water.
A steam engine, often used in the 18th century, which drove a pump to return water back to a waterwheel so that it could be used over and over again.

A prime mover in which a central wheel with curved vanes, enclosed in a chamber, receives water directed onto the curved vanes by a ring of fixed guide vanes, causing the wheel to rotate about its axis.
A wheel turned by water to generate mechanical power.
A piece of cladding in the form of a length of timber fixed horizontally to the building.
An external wall cladding consisting of overlapping horizontal  boards.
A platform scale set within, and flush with the surface of, a roadway, for weighing vehicles, cattle etc.
A machine used for weighing objects.
The west end of a church made up of a tower, entrance hall and upper room, usually with an altar.
A circular window with tracery or shafts radiating from the centre.
A small hinged opening within a large door.
A high speed, single acting compound steam engine with centrally placed piston valves controlling the distribution of steam.
A diagonal or arched member placed across rafters to stiffen and support a roof structure.
A simple, wind-driven water pump, also known as a windpump.
A staircase that rises  through only one storey and has treads and risers framed into square studs, one of them often on one side of a door-frame; it usually occupies a rectangular space.
An engine used for directly winding up coal from deep mines, dating from the 18th century.
An opening in a wall, roof, door, etc to allow light to enter. Usually used to include all component parts.
A lintel over a window.
A part of a building joined to the core of the structure and at an angle to it.
An early power loom in which  the shedding actions of the machine were controlled by tappets, or wipers, which received their motion from a rotating cam shaft positioned at one side of the loom.
A representation of the crucifixion of Christ or related scenes as a sculpture, etc.
A place in which brewing and sometimes baking took place.
An H-sectioned strip of lead used to hold panes of glass in position in stained-glass windows or other leaded lights.
A private bed sitting room.
A suite of rooms.
A slope, usually with rails, by which a boat can be transferred from one level of waterway to another.
A sculpted female figure carrying a basket on her head.
A room intended for the taking of refreshments, usually containing a counter from which they are served.
The top part of a column, often decorated.
A large stone laid horizontally to form the roof of a chamber.
An enclosure or niche in a library or cloister used for study.
A decorative, framed tablet, usually bearing an inscription or coat of arms, in the form of a scroll or curving piece of parchment.
A female figure used instead of a column, usually supporting an entablature.
A chamber built into a wall in a defensive structure.
A hollow moulding, often enriched, similar to a scotia or cavetto, used in Gothic jambs and cornices.
A window where the sash is hung vertically and the window opens outwards or inwards.
A decorative moulding depicting an animal or bird head, similar to a beak head moulding but with a shorter, cone-like tongue or beak overlapping the moulding set beneath it.
A roof with one side longer than the other, continuing at the same pitch over an extension to a building. Commonly found in New England Colonial architecture.
The lesser stalks springing from the principal stalks, or caules, within the decoration on a Corinthian capital.
A concave moulding where the profile is a quarter of a circle.
The surface of a room which conceals overhead structural members.
Term used to indicate the basic unit of accommodation in the plan of a building. It does not necessarily relate to the structural divisions within a building.
A room that is underground or partially underground. Primarily used for storage.
A temporary support placed under a vault or arch to support them during construction.
see axial chimney plan
A plan in which a chimney containing back-to-back fireplaces heats two rooms simultaneously by being placed within the dividing wall.
A plan in which the staircase is placed at the centre of the building.
A decorative moulding in the form of a chain.
An early design of pump featuring a series of pistons, or sometimes bundles of rags, passing through a barrel on a continuous chain, forcing water upwards.
The choir and sanctuary in the liturgical eastern part of a church appropriated for those who officiate during services.
An arch at the liturgical east of the nave, carrying a gabled wall above, separating nave from chancel.
A chapel, often attached to or screened off inside a church, endowed for the celebration of masses principally for the repose of the founder?s soul.
A building, room or area, often within or attached to a church or other building, serving as a place of  worship. Where a monument, use the Thesaurus of Monument Types.
The area that contains the ambulatory, apse and chapels. Usually found in larger churches, monasteries and cathedrals.
A three-dimensional decorative ornamentation composed of a series of Vs forming a zigzag.
The flue or channel that funnels smoke from a fire.
A stone or brick structure that projects into, or out of, a room and contains the flue.
A covering of metal, stone or pottery set on a chimney breast above a fire to prevent smoke entering the room and instead directing it up the chimney.
A cylindrical, polygonal, or square element of brick, metal or terracotta fixed on top of a chimney stack to extend the flue and improve the extraction of smoke.
A very high chimney, though more often a chimney stack containing only one flue.
A masonry or brickwork structure projecting above a roof and containing several flues.
A room decorated, and furnished, in the style of the Chinese.
Part of a large church, east of the nave, appropriated for singers and clergy.
A machine that presses apples to extract juice for the production of cider.
The plan on which a circular building is constructed.
A non-structural covering, such as tile, slate, wood etc., applied to an exterior wall.
A horizontal, riven board, tapered in section, used for external cladding.
A purlin that rests against the lower surface of a principal rafter and is supported by a queen post, collar or raking strut.
A buttress which encases the corner between two walls.

The upper parts of walls carried on arcades or colonnades in the nave, choir or transepts of a church or hall, rising higher than the lean-to roofs of the aisles and pierced with windows to allow light to penetrate.
A beam steam engine, reciprocating or rotative, powered by two steam cylinders side by side.
A short timber linking two pieces of timber.

Twin-engined monoplane that served the RAF as an advanced trainer and flying ambulance. Mk. I featured a gun turret and served for gunnery and bombing-crew training. Subsequent versions used for pilot, radio and navigation training.
Twin-engined, single-seat fighter-bomber. Flown by USAAF fighter groups from 1942, excelled as a ground-support fighter. Could carry two 1600 lb bombs or rocket projectiles.
Single-seat fighter-bomber with a single, midships engine and tricycle landing gear. After proving a failure as an air-combat fighter, was used mainly in the ground attack role.
Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber. Fitted with eight fixed forward-firing machine guns in the wings, plus two 1000lb bombs or six rocket projectiles.

Single-engine, single-seat, long range fighter originally designed in 1940 to a British requirement. Outstanding low-level speed and range resulted in its assignment to the ground support (Army co-operation) role.

Single-engine navigation trainer and communications aircraft. Constructed of tubular steel and duralumin frame, with a duralumin and canvas covering, 500 were delivered to the FAA, serving from 1944-5.

Single-engine, single-seat carrierborne fighter: a Spitfire VB fitted with an arrester hook. Modifications on later versions included folding wings, rocket-assisted take-off gear and conversion for photo-reconnaissance duties.
Single-engine fighter/dive-bomber. The Fleet Air Arm's first operational monoplane, and its first aircraft to shoot down an enemy during the war.

Single-engine, single-seat interceptor fighter developed from the race-winning Schneider Trophy seaplanes. One of the most famous of all combat aircraft, entered RAF service in 1938 and was still in use in the 1950s.

Seven/eight-crew, heavy night-bomber. The first four-engine bomber to join the RAF, with a bomb load of 14000 lb, entered service in 1940. Superseded as a bomber by the Lancaster and Halifax, later versions served as transports and tugs.
Single-engine, three-crew torpedo-spotter, reconnaissance and anti-submarine biplane. Entered Naval service in 1936, designed for operation from aircraft carriers and equipped with folding wings.
Three-crew, single-engine carrierborne torpedo-bomber. Entered service in 1942, first seeing action during the Battle of Midway. Served with the US Navy until 1956.

Single-engine, single-seat fighter-bomber developed from the Typhoon and the abandoned Tornado. Entered service in 1944 with its greatest success being in destroying V.1. flying bombs. One of the fastest World War 2 aircraft, with a top speed of 436 mph.
Single-engine, single-seat fighter-bomber. Designed to replace the Hurricane as an interceptor, excelled as a rocket-projectile-firing ground-attack fighter. Entered RAF service in 1941.

Canadian-built, single-engine, high-wing transport and communications aircraft converted from a civilian model. Metal-framed with fabric covering, saw service in 1944-5. Was capable of being equipped with wheels, floats or skis.
Single-engine aircraft designed as a dive-bomber. Found to be inadequate in this role, a number of those delivered to the RAF were used as target tugs. Entered service in 1941.

Twin-engined air/sea rescue and anti-submarine patrol aircraft. Originally developed from the Wellington and intended as a bomber, entered RAF Coastal Command service in 1943. Fitted with a Leigh Light and ASV radar.

Six-crew, twin-engined medium night-bomber. Entered service in 1938 and was the RAF's principal bomber until 1943, participating in the first bombing raid of the war. Later versions served as torpedo and reconnaissance-bombers, transports and trainers.
Single-seat carrierborne jet fighter. Originally conceived as an RAF land-fighter, entered Fleet Air Arm service in 1951 and was the first jet fighter to be standardised in first-line squadrons.

Twin-engined, seven-crew, coastal reconnaissance, biplane flying-boat. Designed to the same specification as the Saro London, entered service in 1937. Also serving in an anti-submarine role, was replaced by the Consolidated Canso (Catalina) in 1943.

An aircraft lifted by gas bags, containing hydrogen or helium, but propelled by engines. Also known as a dirigible balloon, firm and streamlined in shape and incapable of high speeds. Used extensively during World War One.
An aeroplane with the capability to land at sea, the underside of its fuselage shaped like the hull of a sea-going vessel and designed to make contact with the water.
An engineless aeroplane, designed to be towed aloft, that travels suspended by upward air currents.

An aircraft designed to land on water. They can be divided into 2 types: Flying boats (designed with a hull allowing the aircraft to land directly on water) and Floatplanes (where the undercarriage was replaced by fixed floats).
An aeroplane featuring three wings, or planes, placed one above the other either side of its fuselage.

Four-engine, long range heavy bomber. Developed from the Lancaster, and originally designated the Lancaster Mk. IV, it was larger in size, bombload and fuel capacity. Never used operationally in World War Two.

Chance Vought Division of the United Aircraft Corporation. Was reconstituted as a separate division in 1943, after being part of the Vought-Sikorsky division, to concentrate on the production of combat aircraft.
A room in which cloaks, coats, hats etc may be left and often including coathooks, hat boxes and similar fixtures and fittings.
A tall structure, high in proportion to its lateral dimensions, often rising in stages, free standing or part of another  building, surmounted by a clock.
A covered ambulatory, usually arcaded, arranged around three or four sides of a quadrangle in a monastic or collegiate establishment.
In timber framed buildings this is the division of a wall into narrow panels by vertical studs.
A truss in which spaces between timbers are filled, as between rooms and at the ends of a building.
A small chamber or private room.
A pier made up of several columns clustered together. They can be attached through their whole length or only at top and bottom.
Loading machinery tipping coal into railway wagons, usually at a pithead.
A crane used for moving coal during the refuelling of coal-powered vessels or locomotives.
A series of recessed, ornamental panels decorating a ceiling.
A joist that has its end resting in a recess in a transverse beam.
A horizontal member connecting rafters or cruck blades at a point between their feet and the apex of the roof.
A horizontal timber that joins the collars of a series of roof trusses.
A small shaft or column.
A row of columns that carry arches or an entablature.
A colonnade where it is exposed to the air on two sides.
An order in which the columns rise more than one storey in height from the ground or plinth.
A vertical, circular member, usually load-carrying. Where separate, use monument type.
A machine used for combing wool. Use more specific term where known.
A room where a committee meets to discuss matters put before them.
A rafter of uniform size placed at regular intervals along the length of a roof.
A roof consisting entirely of common rafters, without the use of principals, in pairs but not connected by collar-beams.
A pair of common rafters with a collar.
A room in general use for persons to meet, often found at institutions such as colleges.
A lancet arch designed in the composite style.
Bases of this order are often referred to as spira and have a double astragal in the middle.
An ornate version of an eight-voluted Ionic capital known as an angular capital or Scamozzi under which are added two tiers of acanthus leaves.
A detached, sometimes monolithic vertical structural element usually circular, square or polygonal bearing an ornate eight-voluted Ionic Capital.
The horizontal assembly of architrave, frieze and cornice carried upon columns and pilasters in the Composite order; and so containing elements of the Ionic and Corinthian orders.
An order composed of elements of the Ionic and Corinthian orders.
A pier made up of several shafts against it. The shafts can be attached or detached.
A doubled rafter, separated by cleats, spacers or distance pieces.
A steam engine that uses the same steam successively to drive pistons in high and then low pressure cylinders.
A brace halved to the inside of studs, and so not visible from outside.

A steam engine in which the spent steam leaving the cylinder passes to a condenser instead of being exhausted to the atmosphere. The condenser creates a partial vacuum which increases the pressure drop across the engine, so raising its efficiency.
A recess or chamber near the altar which holds a relic. A feature of medieval churches.
An extension to a building usually made primarily of glass, for growing plants.
An S-shaped ornamental bracket with a greater height than projection.

The common design of steam engine, where steam enters the cylinder at one end, and after it has pushed the piston to the other end, its direction of flow is reversed as the piston returns, the steam leaving  the cylinder through the exhaust ports.
A room in which actions are checked, verified and approved.
A cantilevered block projecting from the face of a wall and supporting a structure such as a parapet, beam or arch.
A slender and elegant base usually of Attic type with two tori, two scotiae and two astragals.

A capital with two rows of eight acanthus leaves rising above an astragal;from between the leaves of the upper row rise eight stalks,each surmounted by a calyx from which emerge volutes carryingthe corners of the concave sided abacus and central ornaments
A vertical structure usually with an Attic base or spira with slender and elegant design, with a capital decorated with acanthus leaves and an entablature rich in carved ornament.

An entablature often of great magnificence with bead and reel between fasciae of the architrave, frieze ornamented with continuous sculpture and cornice, with ornate coffers and richly carved modillions.
A classical order having a bell shaped capital that is decorated with laurel, olive or acanthus leaves from which CAULICOLI emerge. The shaft is usually fluted and the base is often an Attic base.

Single-engine, single-seat fighter. Entered service in 1943 as a land-based fighter. Converted to a carrierborne fighter in 1944 for use by US Navy and Fleet Air Arm. Mostly saw action in the Pacific and Far East.
An aircraft, usually towed or radio-controlled, designed for use as an air-to-air, or ground-to-air, gunnery target.
An aircraft, often fitted with cameras, intended to fly over enemy territory to ascertain its strategic features and/or the position and strength of any military presence.
An aircraft used for the transportation of troops, supplies or vehicles.
An aircraft used for the training of pilots, sometimes fitted with dual controls for use by the instructor.
An open pit from which coprolites or phosphatic nodules were extracted. Commonly found in the Fens and East Anglia coprolites were ground up and used as fertilizer.

Airspeed (1934) Ltd. registered in 1934 when associated with shipbuilders Swan, Hunter and Wigham Richardson Ltd.. Acquired by de Havilland in 1940, maintaining own identity and changing name to Airspeed Ltd. in 1944.

Sir W. G. Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft, Ltd. formed in 1921. Controlled by the Armstrong Siddeley Development Co., Ltd., a subsidiary of the Hawker Siddeley Aircraft Co., Ltd. from 1935. Pioneers in the development of all-metal aircraft.

A. V. Roe & Co., Ltd. formed in 1909. A subsidiary  of the Hawker Siddeley Aircraft Co., Ltd. from 1935, having formerly been a member of the Siddeley group. Produced such notable aircraft as the Lancaster, the York and the Anson.
Blackburn Aircraft, Ltd., founded by Robert Blackburn, who produced his first aircraft in 1910. Specialised in the production of torpedo-carrying aircraft.
Boulton Paul Aircraft, Ltd., formed in 1934 to take over the  Aircraft Department of Boulton & Paul, Ltd.
The Bristol Aeroplane Co., Ltd.. Founded in 1910 by Sir George White, a pioneer of electric tramways. The company had previously been The British and Colonial Aeroplane Co., Ltd..

The de Havilland Aircraft Co., Ltd., founded in 1920 by Sir Geoffrey de Havilland, C.B.E., A.F.C., F.R.Ae.S. Originally developers of commercial aircraft, were responsible for such notable wartime aircraft as the Mosquito and the Tiger Moth.
The Fairey Aviation Co. Ltd., established 1916 by Sir Richard Fairey. During WW2 formed a group production scheme with Blackburn Aircraft, Ltd. and Boulton Paul Aircraft, Ltd..

Formed in 1936 as British Marine Aircraft Ltd. to construct civil flying-boats. In 1937, with the arrival of H P Folland, formerly Chief designer for Gloster Aircraft Co., became Folland Aircraft, Ltd..
Gloster Aircraft Co., Ltd. formed in 1917, later became part of the Hawker Siddeley Group. First British or American company to design, build and fly a jet-propelled aircraft.
Hawker Aircraft, Ltd., established 1933 to succeed the H. G. Hawker Engineering Co., Ltd., which had been formed in 1920 as the result of the voluntary liquidation of the renowned Sopwith concern.
Miles Aircraft, Ltd., originally known as Phillips & Powis Aircraft Ltd.. Formed in 1935 as a public company to take over aircraft manufacture from Phillips & Powis Aircraft (Reading) Ltd.
The Percival Aircraft Company was formed in 1932 and re-organized as Percival Aircraft Ltd. in 1937, when the works moved from Gravesend to Luton.

Short Bros. (Rochester & Bedford), Ltd. founded by Eustace and Oswald Short in 1898, originally manufacturing spherical balloons. In 1936 became Short & Harland Ltd. in collaboration with Belfast shipbuilders Harland and Wolff.
Vickers (Aviation) Ltd. formed in 1911, as the aviation division of Vickers Ltd., and took control of Supermarine Aviation Works Ltd. the same year. Taken over by Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd. in 1938.
Westland Aircraft Ltd., formed in 1935 to take over the aircraft branch of Petters Ltd., previously known as the Westland Aircraft Works.

Formed in 1935 by Lawrence D. Bell, Ray P. Whitman and Robert J. Woods, who left the Consolidated Aircraft Corporation when it moved its factory from Buffalo to San Diego. Sub-contracted work before its first original design, the XFM-1, in 1937.
The Boeing Aircraft Company, established 1916. A subsidiary of The Boeing Airplane Company. Notable aircraft produced include the B17 Flying Fortress and the B29 Superfortress.

The Brewster Aeronautical Corporation was founded in 1932, taking over the plant, equipment, designs and goodwill of Brewster & Co., Inc.'s aircraft division. Initially manufacturing seaplane components, later designed and produced complete aircraft.
The Consolidated Aircraft Corporation. In 1943 merged with Vultee Aircraft, Inc. to form the Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation.
The Douglas Aircraft Company, Inc., established in 1920, reorganized in 1928. Produced such notable aircraft as the Dakota.
The Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation founded by Leroy R Grumman and incorporated in 1929.

The Lockheed Aircraft Corporation. Founded in 1916 by Allen and Malcolm Loughead. In 1926 the company moved to Burbank and changed its name to The Lockheed Aircraft Company, and was then incorporated in 1932.

The Stinson Division of The Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation. Originally the Stinson Aircraft Division of the Aviation Manufacturing Corpn., who were taken over by Vultee Aircraft Inc., who merged with the Consolidated Aircraft Corpn. in 1943.
Vultee Aircraft, Inc.. In 1943 merged with The Consolidated Aircraft Corporation to form The Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation.
A church, usually found in East Anglia, of early Medieval and/or Medieval date with attached or detached round tower.
A building or group of buildings designed for the breeding and rearing of animals, including fish and birds. Often include incubators and heated rooms.
A building, or group of buildings, deliberately designed for rhinos.
A spheroid produced predominantly by birds, though also produced by some animals, which encases the young creature providing a place for it to develop.
A fluid substance. Use for unspecified liquids only, where known use more specific type.
A living thing that is not an animal. Use for unspecified plants only. Use a more specific type where known.
The latex of plants tacky in its normal state and elastic after treatment. Used for a variety of purposes.
A material in a granular form that is smaller than gravel and created by the erosion of rocks.
Small stones which have been rounded usually by the action of sea water.
Shaped material used for covering buildings, usually as a roofing material though can be used on walls or floors. Often of fired clay they can be of other materials particularly stone.
A malleable water repellant substance created by animals or as a coating to parts of plants.
Items that have been through a manufacturing process. Use specific type where known.
Coiled substance, usually metal or plastic, used to absorb shocks or in timepieces since it can stretch and return to its original shape.
A three dimensional representation of a figure, whether animal or human, produced by carving, casting sculpting or similar.
A mineral of copper, iron and sulphur and is the main ore of copper.
Partially decomposed granite used to produce a glaze for porcelain.
A mixture of coals that have been formed into briquettes or blocks. This fuel took its name from the fact that it was under patent in the late nineteenth century.

A twin-engined, multi-role aircraft built by Junkers. Originally designed as a medium bomber with the speed of a fighter, but its adaptability allowed it to fulfil the roles of night fighter, torpedo-bomber, anti-tank aircraft and photo-reconnaissance.

Single-engine, single-seat fighter manufactured by Messerschmitt. First used as part of Germany's Condor legion during the Spanish Civil War, the 'one-o-nine' was the Luftwaffe's most widely used fighter seeing service throughout World War II.
Founded by Professor Willy Messerschmitt as the Bayerische Flugzeugwerke. Reconstituted in 1938 as the Messerschmitt A.G..
A man made terrace, often constructed in concrete, built to allow spectators a view of organized outdoor events or activities.
A barrier, usually of wood or chain, stretched across the entrance to a harbour, port or anchorage, to control entry and/or limit the effect of the weather on the wave action.
A building designed to house insects.
An enclosure for wild cats such as Lions and Tigers
A platform on which corpses are placed and allowed to decompose in the open air, so as to leave only the bones for subsequent burial.
An underground cell, or group of cells, used for imprisonment.
An underground cell, usually hidden and accessed only through a trapdoor, in which a prisoner was confined and then allegedly forgotten about.
A building used for the testing of steel.
Buildings, sites and structures associated with the retrieval, refining, processing and storage of petroleum oil.
A manmade barrier built across a river in order to increase the depth of water.
A short, horizontal brace set between a tiebeam and a wall plate to strengthen the structure.
The upper part of the classical entablature. Also a moulded projection crowning a door, wall, window etc.
A beam steam engine originating in Cornwall, first used for raising water from mines.
Decorative ornamentation in the form of a horn filled with fruit etc.
A vertical faced projection in the cornice.
The main body of a structure not including wings etc.
A passageway within a building providing access to rooms.
A assembly room or rooms in which a collection of nominated persons meet to transact business of relevant purpose.
The apse at the west end of the nave in a double-ended church.
A low bank on the edge of a defensive ditch on the side away from the main rampart.
A roof in which pairs of rafters are fixed to the ridge piece and the wall plates without any collars or tiebeams.
The place, hall or chamber in which justice is administered.
An enclosed area, often surrounded by walls or buildings.
A plan of a house where the buildings are around at least three sides of a quadrilateral courtyard.
A large concave moulding.
A passageway or corridor beteen two areas which is covered.
A machine used for lifting materials.
The openings between the upright blocks, or merlons, of a battlement.
A capital which is decorated with stylized leaves similar to small volutes.
The entry to a hall through opposed doorways, but without a passage formed by a wall or partition.
A gable supporting a roof, placed at right-angles to the main part of the roof.
A method of floor construction in which sections of joists run at right-angles to one another.
Entry to a hall through opposing doors with a partition screening the hall and forming a passageway.
The transverse portion of a cruciform church, or the arms on either side of the crossing, often with chapels at the east sides and possibly with aisles as well.
Two intersecting beams set on the ground to support a post, usually for a post mill.
A vault created by the intersection of two other vaults set at right angles to each other and of equal size.
A window with a single mullion and a single transom.
A wing joined to the main body of the building with the roof at right angles to the main roof.
The intersection and space between the nave, chancel and transepts in a cruciform church.
A plate in a crown post roof, supported on crown posts and bearing the collars.
An upright timber standing on a tiebeam to support a collar or purlin. Once used as an alternative to king post, this term is now restricted to the shorter post ending at collar level.
A steeple in which the spire resembles a crown.
An upright timber similar to a crown post, but not supporting a plate.
A gable with sides shaped like a flight of steps.
A building plan in the shape of a cross.

A pair of timbers, or blades, usually curved, rising from a place at or near ground level to a point at or near the apex of a roof, forming an approximately triangular frame on which the subsidiary structure rests.
A short timber connecting a cruck's timber, or blade, to a wall plate.
A stud on the outside of a cruck blade and attached to it.
A horse-powered apparatus, for the crushing of commodities such as ore or cider apples, consisting of a stone wheel running over a circular iron or stone bed.
A wholly or partially underground chamber, often beneath a chancel, equipped for religious services and usually containing tombs.
A small dome on top of a larger dome, roof etc.
A wall connecting two pavilions, bastions, towers etc..
A cube-shaped capital with its lower corners rounded to facilitate the transition from the circular shaft below to the square abacus it supports.
The wedge shaped end of a bridge pier designed to break the current of water.
A decorative S-shaped moulding, usually placed at the top of a cornice, with a convex lower half and a concave upper half.
A decorative S-shaped moulding, usually placed at the top of a cornice, with  a concave lower half and a convex upper half.
The top of a cornice in an entablature.
A raised platform at the end of a hall on which the high table sat, though sometimes used to describe the table itself.
A decorated beam, above the dais or high table, attached to the partition at the upper end of a hall.
A framed canopy suspended above the dais or high table at the upper end of a hall.
An early washing machine used in bleaching works for washing calico and other textiles.
A communal living room.
A chamber where discussions of issues take place, often found at universities.
The Consolidated Vultee Aircraft Corporation. Formed in 1943 with the merging of The Consolidated Aircraft Corporation and Vultee Aircraft, Inc..
Vickers-Armstrongs Ltd.. In 1938 took over Vickers (Aviation) Ltd., which itself had taken control of Supermarine Aviation Works Ltd. in 1928.
Focke-Wulf Flugzeugbau G.m.b.H.. Founded in 1924 and amalgamated in 1931 with the Albatross-Flugzeugwerke G.m.b.H.. Converted to a G.m.b.H. in 1937.
Ernst Heinkel A.G.. Formed in 1922 by Dr. Ernst Heinkel, previously Chief Designer with Hansa-Brandenburgische Flugzeugwerke, where he produced many notable seaplanes during World War One.

Junkers Flugzeug und Motorenwerke, A.G.. Formed in 1910 with Professor Junkers being granted a patent for an all-wing aeroplane. Produced first successful all-metal aeroplane, the Junkers J1, in 1915.

The Waco Aircraft Company, established in 1921. One of the largest pre-war producers of civil aircraft in America, Waco specialised in the production of troop and cargo carrying gliders during World War Two.
A light, high speed aircraft equipped specifically to engage in night combat.
Originally the Zeppelin Werk Lindau G.m.b.H., developed metal aircraft from World War One under the guidance of Dr. Ing. Claude Dornier, changing its name to Dornier-Werke G.m.b.H. in 1922.
Handley Page, Ltd.. Founded by Sir Frederick Handley Page, this was the first limited company to be incorporated in Great Britain for the purpose of aircraft manufacture.
Long-range, usually four-engined, bomber designed to carry a large bomb payload.
High speed, short to medium-range bomber, usually powered by two engines.
A camera-equipped aircraft intended to fly over enemy territory and gather photographic evidence of strategic features and/or the position and strength of any military presence.
A large cargo vessel, either purpose-fitted or converted, for the transportation of slaves.
The Sopwith Aviation Co., Ltd.. Established in 1911 by the noted aviator Mr T. O. M. Sopwith. Produced many notable aircraft, including the Camel and a Schneider Cup-winning seaplane.

The Glenn L. Martin Company, established in 1909 by Glenn L Martin. Produced the first successful American-designed twin-engined aeroplane, the Martin Twin, which was then converted for use as a passenger aircraft.

Noorduyn Aviation Limited. Formed in 1934 by Mr R.B.C. Noorduyn as a successor to Noorduyn Aircraft Limited, which was formed in 1933. The company's most notable production aircraft was the Norseman transport.

The Republic Aviation Corporation. Developed from the Seversky Aircraft Corporation, founded by Alexander P. de Seversky in 1931 after the collapse of his previous company, the Seversky Aero Corporation, in the 1929 stock market crash.

The English Electric Company Limited. Formed in 1918, but didn't move into aircraft production until 1938, at the Government's request. Continued to develop aircraft after the war and in 1948 produced the `Canberra', Britain's first jet-propelled bomber.
Marine Aircraft Experimental Establishment, RAF Felixstowe. Developed seaplanes and flying boats until World War Two, when the establishment moved to Helensburg, Scotland.
A single-seat, pusher prop, escort and patrol-fighter. Used in the UK in a Home Defence role until superseded in 1917.
A single-seat fighter which began service with the RFC's fighter squadron in 1916. Some short-term success in dealing with new Fokkers but was withdrawn from service in mid-1917.

A two-seat, single-engine bomber. Fast, versatile and well armed, but with a fuel tank poorly placed between pilot and gunner, was considered to be the best day bomber of the First World War. Later entered civil service.
The DH5 was an attempt to give a tractor-type fighter a good forward view. However it suffered from unpleasant flying characteristics and, as a result, had a short service career.
Originally designed as a trainer but relegated to use by the RNAS in a Maritime Reconnaissance and anti-submarine role when the Avro 504 became the standard trainer.
Developed from the DH4, featured the pilot and gunner cockpits in closer proximity, but suffered from engine reliability problems. Also known as the Ninak, saw service from 1918 to 1931.
A two-seat, reconnaissance biplane developed from the FK2 with a more powerful, but heavier, engine. Primarily used for training in the UK.
Single-engine, two-seat tractor bomber and reconnaissance aircraft. Entered service in 1916 and, during 1917 and 1918, equipped nine RFC squadrons in its reconnaissance role.

An important two-seat, tractor biplane, initially used by the RFC in a reconnaissance role and by the RNAS as a bomber. Later converted to a single-seat Home Defence fighter and ultimately used as a trainer.

Highly successful, two-seat, biplane fighter and reconnaissance aircraft with both forward and rear facing guns. Designed to replace the BE2, it entered service with the RFC in mid-1917 and remained in service until 1932.
Large, single-engine, eight passenger airliner biplane.
A distribution of artefacts indicating the presence of former presence of a monument.

Single-engine, two-seat, light, biplane, elementary-flying trainer. Adapted from a civilian design, and constructed from tubular steel and spruce with plywood and fabric covering, entered service in 1931 and was available in land-plane or seaplane forms.
Post-World War Two, single-engine, high-wing utility transport. Manufactured by De Havilland Canada, was also produced in a seaplane version. Known as the U6A from 1962.
A component part that is designed deliberately for decorative purposes.
One of a series of small, rectangular blocks arranged like a row of teeth, projecting from the lower part of a cornice in many classical orders.
A machine for hoisting or moving heavy weights, consisting of a spar or boom set up obliquely, with its head steadied by guys, and furnished with suitable tackle and purchases.
A buttress placed at the exterior corner of a building, forming a 135 degree angle with the walls it supports.
A mullion of square section set diagonally.
A principal that has been reduced to the same thickness as a common rafter where the roof has clasped purlins.
A room, furnished with tables and chairs, where meals and refreshments are served and consumed.
A plan in which entry is directly into a room without being situated opposite a fireplace.
A hydraulic engine patented in 1830 comprising a large specially shaped cast-iron outer casing enclosing a close-fitting but separate solid globe.
A staircase divided into two parallel flights joined by a landing with no well between the outer strings.
A decorative moulding featuring a repeating star-like motif carved in relief.
A roof, circular in plan, usually semicircular in section, over a circular, square or polygonal base.
The entrance to a building, apartment or any enclosure consisting of a movable barrier, usually lockable, of wood or other materials.
A lintel over a door.
A vertical upright on either side of a door.
The space in which a door is placed, allowing passage through.
A base of the Roman Doric order with a torus, an astragal and a fillet.
A capital with an abacus, ovolo, neck and astragal.
A column that is equidistant, with intercolumniations, even at the corners, with two or more triglyphs over each  intercolumniation.
An entablature with a plain architrave or principal beam over which are the frieze and cornice.
A classical order with metopes and triglyphs in the frieze. Greek Doric has no base and a fluted column but Roman Doric does have a base and may or may not have a fluted column.
A chamber usually used for sleeping.
A projecting vertical window in the sloping roof of a house.
A sleeping apartment usually containing a number of beds and sometimes partitioned into cubicles.A room for sleeping in, usually for a number of beds.
A truss in which two pairs of arch braces form a continuous curve from the wall-heads or below to meet  in the centre of the collar.
Two linked quadrangular open areas surrounded by walls or buildings.
A plan in which the building is two rooms deep but has no central corridor.
An English seventeenth century house plan consisting of a rectangular block two rooms deep, the rooms sometimes separated by a passage.
A joint in which the end is shaped like a dovetail.
A brace running from a vertical to a lower horizontal timber.
A horizontal member cutting through the corner formed by two walls to act as a support to a hip rafter to support jetties on two adjacent sides of an upper floor.
A horizontal brace linking tiebeam and wall plate, or adjacent wall plates at the corner of a hipped roof.
A wooden bar sliding from a long channel at one side of a doorway into a socket in the other jamb so as to bar the door.
A hand-operated loom on which figured cloth could be woven, also known as a drawing engine.
A room to withdraw to from the dining room.

A room, particularly in a house or theatre, intended for dressing or changing one's clothes and furnished with wardrobes, dressing tables and other facilities for the application of make-up, styling of hair etc.
A pointed, two centred, arch whose span is greater than its height.
A transverse ceiling beam set below wall-plate level in order to increase head room within the roof space; it carries knee principals, or the struts or braces of an interrupted tiebeam truss.
A chamber for the incarceration of one or more prisoners.
A type of direct-acting, twin cylinder steam driven water pump.
A transept in which the two wings that extend beyond the walls of the nave are lower than the nave and the crossing of the church.
A plan type of a hall with two wings and a central porch.
A wooden commode containing earth, which was used to cover and absorb human waste. An alternative, and rival, to the water closet.
The edge of a roof that hangs over the wall.
A board on the lower edge of a sloping roof which protects the top of the external wall.
A feature formed by water falling from the roof of a building and creating a linear or curving indentation in the ground.
An ovolo moulding below the abacus of a Doric or Ionic Capital.
A rounded or convex moulding, such as an ovolo or torus.
A raised platform from which an officer can address or review his troops.
A structure indicated by the presence of post holes and of uncertain interpretation.
An institute provided by a regiment for the improvement of the soldiers and to reduce excessive drinking.
Purpose built accommodation for members of the armed forces and their families.
A trough or gutter for conveying liquids such as water or molten metal. It can be cut in the surface or formed of wood or other materials.

Four-engine, ten-crew, long-range maritime reconnaissance and anti-submarine aircraft. Developed from the Short C-class Empire airliner. All metal in construction, entered RAF Coastal Command service in 1938.
British single-engine, two-seat night fighter. Originally intended as a day fighter, but withdrawn and converted in August 1940, this was the first fighter to incorporate a power-driven gun turret.
An aircraft used for the towing of targets.
A subsidiary of Lockheed.
A radio-controlled target tug version of the Tiger Moth used for target practice. 380 were built for the RAF.
Twin-engined fighter-bomber. All metal in construction, entered service in 1940. Supported bombing operations and participated in attacks on France, but not widely used due to engine faults.

Single-engine, two-crew multi-role aircraft designed for RAF Army co-operation. Entered RAF service in 1938. Noted for its role dropping agents into Europe, also served as a night-fighter, day ground-attack aircraft and target tug.
Decorative ornamentation consisting of alternating oval and V-shaped motifs, used to enrich ovolo mouldings.
An arch which is half an ellipse.
A decorative moulding featuring a geometric pattern suggesting the crenelles and merlons of a battlement.
A cruck blade, sometimes jointed, set in the centre of a gable wall, usually of a cruck-framed building.
A medieval plan with the hall situated at one end of the main range.
A plan featuring a lobby entry, situated at one end of a side wall, which provides access to one room only.
A column that is attached to or partly sunk into a wall or pier.
A piece of machinery used to convert energy of one sort (for instance steam) into motive energy.
In the Classical Orders, the horizontal assembly of architrave, frieze and cornice carried upon columns and pilasters.
A passage between two rooms in a house or leading from the door to the hall.
A place of entry into a site, monument or building.
The passage, area, lobby, room or vestibule into which a building's main entrance opens.
An arch whose height is equal to its span.
A decorative feature of a shield for armorial bearings.
A semicircular niche or recess in a wall.
A yard intended for the purpose of taking exercise, for example within the grounds of a prison.
A space or area that is outside a building.
A flight of stairs, situated on a building's exterior, extending to an upper storey.
A compound steam engine with provision for bleeding off some steam after it has passed through the high pressure cylinder and before it enters  the low pressure cylinder.
The outer curve of an arch or vault.
The external face or elevation of a building, especially the principal front.
A joint in which the side, or face, of a timber has been squarely cut away to fit into a corresponding cut-away in the side of another member.
A specialised form of crane, usually employed on a dockside, featuring a curving, solid jib.
A mechanical testing machine used to carry out pioneering tests on various materials, particularly cast-iron beams, to determine practical data on their strength and other properties.
An arch built by corbelling or cantilevering in from both sides with horizontal joints.
A gable without a roof behind it.
A transverse timber resembling a hammer beam but without a hammer post above, being braced to a principal or collar instead.
A truss with a transverse timber like a hammer-beam, but braced to a principal or collar without a hammer-post.

A bladed wheel attached to the rear, and at right angles to the main sails, of a windmill.  Connected to winding gear, the fantail would catch the wind when it changed direction, allowing the mill to move automatically into the wind.

One of two or three bands on a classical architrave, each projecting slightly beyiond the one below, often separated by enriched mouldings. Also a vertical band or board, such as that over a shop front on which its name is painted.
An item used to fasten, bind or join one item to another.
An archaeological component which cuts, overlies or abuts other features such as ditches, pits and building foundations.
An area in a church, sometimes defined by screens, containing a shrine. Also a shrine, usually portable, containing religious relics.
A plain, narrow moulding or area, sometimes projecting, separating two decorated mouldings or features such as the vertical grooves on a fluted column.
The shaped projection on the top of a newel post or at the apex of a gable.
A small window placed to cast light upon a fireplace.
The opening at the base of a chimney stack.
A stationary winding steam engine positioned at the top of a railway incline for hauling up trains and locomotives.
A crane that is fixed to a quay and used for the loading and unloading of cargo.
Accessories used in furnishing and embellishing a building or structure.
A spire, or spirelet surmounting a roof, especially over the crossing of a French Gothic Cathedral.
A gable with curved sides and an identifiable pediment.
Decorative ornamentation of a formalized lily.
Decorative ornamentation of a flower or leaf.
A composite beam of timber strengthened by an iron plate, or plates, used in the construction of 18th and 19th century timber framed mills and warehouses.
A mobile crane which floats on water.
The lower, horizontal surface of a room on which people walk. Can also mean a storey of a building.
A decorative feature in the style of a flower or plant. Use more specific term.
A duct or channel for hot air to travel through.
The use of knapped flint applied to a wall to form a decorative pattern.
A concave groove or series of grooves.
A plinth or pedestal, sometimes decorated, and sometimes supporting statuary, placed at the apex and lower extremity of a pediment.
A series of concentric mouldings decorating the curved face of an arch.
A flat, horizontal strip, block or moulding, sometimes decorated, on a facade or interrupting an architectural feature such as a column.
A continuous series of ornaments within a horizontal moulding.
An arched, or bow-shaped, segmental timber truss with its ends tied together by a straight or cambered member.
A bowstring truss with the space between its members filled by a lattice of crossing diagonal rods.
A plain stone course, sometimes projecting, above a cornice and counterbalancing the cantilevered sections of stone, or at the base of a building.
An enclosed, high-sided seat, sometimes entered through a door, usually found in churches as one of a series of box-like compartments.
A pediment with a gap at the centre of its base.
A ceiling that is curved or vaulted, sometimes employed to give a space the appearance of a vault.
A building, sometimes polygonal in plan, attached to a cathedral, church, abbey etc. and used for the assembly of chapter or brethren, often to address official business.
An ornamental foliation in panels or tracery so called because it is arranged around five intervals, known as foils or cusps, that describe the outlines of five leaves or petals.
A booth, cubicle or recess, often enclosed, in which a priest, usually screened from view, hears confessions.
A protective covering applied to the top of a wall, chimney, gable etc., usually curved, sloping or ridged to prevent rainwater settling.
A projecting wall or structure, such as a parapet or battlement, supported by a series of corbels.
A recess, often containing shelves and usually fitted with a door or doors, used for the storage of items.
A wall-mounted moulding defining the upper edge of the dado, intended to protect the wall's surface from damage caused by chairs being pushed against it.
An unengaged, or free-standing, column.

A decorative, repeating geometric pattern, utilizing motifs such as lozenges, leaves etc., applied to a wall or panel, or incorporated into brickwork by laying different coloured bricks in a series of squares, diamonds.
A semi-circular opening or window divided, by two mullions, into three sections, the central section being wider than those either side of it.
The wood, stone or brick framework, lining a doorway, from which the door is hung.
A moulding that projects from a wall above an exterior opening and is shaped to channel rainwater away from it.

Impressed civil, twin-engined airliner converted to a military transport. Thirty were ordered for military use, though only eleven were actually built. Entered service in 1940, with the last being scrapped in 1950.
An aircraft used in the assistance of ground-based military operations.
Emperors of the Roman Empire.
Emperor of Rome (30BC to 14AD).
Emperor of Rome (14-37AD).
Emperor of Rome (37-41AD).
Emperor of Rome (41-54AD)
Emperor of Rome (54-68AD)
Emperor of Rome (68-69AD).
Emperor of Rome (69AD)
Emperor of Rome (69AD)
Emperor of Rome (69-79AD).
Emperor of Rome (79-81AD).
Emperor of Rome (81-96AD).
Emperor of Rome (96-98AD).
Emperor of Rome (98-117AD)
Emperor of Rome (117-138AD)
Emperor of Rome (138-61AD).
Joint Emperor of Rome (161-169AD). Emperor of Rome (169-180AD)
Joint Emperor of Rome (161-169AD).
Emperor of Rome (180-192AD)
Emperor of Rome (193AD)
Emperor of Rome (193AD)
Emperor of Rome (193-211).
Rival Emperor of Rome (193-194AD).
Rival Emperor of Rome (193-197AD).
Joint Emperor of Rome (211-212AD). Emperor of Rome (212-217AD).
Joint Emperor of Rome (211-212AD).
Emperor of Rome (217-218AD).
Emperor of Rome (218-222AD).
Emperor of Rome (222-235AD).
Emperor of Rome (235-238AD)
Joint Emperor of Rome (238AD)

A buttress set away from the structure it supports, joined to it by an arch.
A device patented in 1733 for speeding up the weaving of cloth.
A receptacle to hold water used in baptism usually found in a baptistery or nave of a church.
A room in which food is prepared.
An enclosed area in front of a structure.

A pointed arch which, on a plan, is shown to be constructed around four arcs: two centred below and two centred upon the springing line, which is the level at which the vertical sides of the arch begin to curve.
A machine for making paper in a continuous length.
An outward radial flow reaction water turbine.
A mixed-flow reaction water turbine, developed in the USA in 1840 by James Bichino Francis, in which water enters the runner radially and leaves axially.
A casement  window, carried down to floor level, and opening like two-leafed glazed doors to a garden, veranda or terrace.
A two dimensional image using paint applied to plasterwork whilst the plaster is still damp.
Decorative ornamentation of a key pattern
The middle section, between the architrave and the cornice, of an entablature.
The part of the wall that supports a pitched roof at the end of the roof.
A plan of a building where the entrance is in the gable wall.
The commonest type of roof with sloping sides meeting at a ridge and with a gable at each end.
A small gable above a hipped roof. Also used ornamentally, such as on a buttress or over a niche.
A lobby or chapel at the western entrance of a church. Sometimes a place of burial, an area reserved for women, or a place where monks could meet female relatives.
A long room for recreation, often on an upper floor.
A store for undressed meat, usually for keeping grouse, partridge, pheasant or rabbit in a cool environment.
A room in which board and table games are usually played.
A latrine built into, or projecting beyond, the wall of a medieval castle featuring a stone or wooden seat situated above a pit or the castle moat.
A projecting spout to throw water from a gutter away from the wall, frequently decorated with grotesque figures to spew out evil away from the House of God.
An apartment contained, wholly or partially, within the roof space of a house.
An internal combustion heat engine which uses gas as its fuel, and acts as a prime mover or power source for driving other machinery.
A heat engine prime mover in which hot gases or hot air expand as they pass through and rotate vanes attached to a central shaft, enclosed in a chamber.
A movable barrier, usually external, within an opening in a wall, fence, hedge or similar.
A pier which supports a gate.
A form of entrance closed by a gate.
A beam that is part of a frame in a wall.
Also known as a half-beam engine, named for the characteristic nodding action of the overhead beam which is supposed  to resemble the action of the rear legs of the grasshopper.
An apartment for the use of people of high status, often the owner of the building. Also a room adjoining, or close to, a hall and used as a drawing room or venue for private functions.

A large communal room often occupying the full height of the building, used for functions such as meetings, entertainments etc. Traditionally found in medieval buildings but also found in later buildings emulating medieval architecture.
A room where usually materials or consumables are processed into tools or meal, for example in a workshop or mill.

A classical ornamentation featuring foliage, fruits and, unlike Arabesque, human and animal figures, sometimes fantastic or mythological in nature. The term may have originated from the fact that many examples of such ornamentation were found in grottoes.
A room frequently in a military building where sentries guard and protect the premises.
A decorative ornamentation of interlaced bands in the form of a plait.
A usually shallow cut linear feature often used for drainage.
A room for storing guns.
Small 'drops' or conic projections under the mutules (a repeating block motif) and triglyphs (rectangular blocks embellished with vertical grooves) in a Doric entablature.
A building plan that features a hall lying between, and at right-angles to, two projecting wings.
A short bay, usually in a hall, commonly as a smoke bay or for a cross-entry.
A beam which is half the width of a main beam, usually supporting joists.
A roof whose ends are partly gabled and partly sloped.
The principal room in early houses, which occupies the entire height of the building.
A common plan form of large medieval and sub medieval houses, with a hall range flanked by two wings; also found with only one wing.
A joint in which both timbers are reduced in thickness.

Single-engine, testbed monoplane built to Air Ministry Specification 43/37. Only twelve were produced, the first of which tested the Sabre I engine in 1940, and were used throughout the war. The cockpit could seat two observers behind the pilot.
Four-crew, twin-engined, general reconnaissance flying-boat. Entered service after World War One, becoming the RAF's standard flying-boat until replaced by the Supermarine Southampton in 1925.
Second World War allied patrol-bomber built by Lockheed Vega, a Lockheed subsidiary. This aircraft was a military development of the Lodestar, USAF designation B-34.
The face within a pediment, as enclosed by the cornices, or the solid infill of an arch above an impost, sometimes embellished with sculptural or relief ornament.
Prior to 1822 a vessel used by the customs department involved with the prevention of smuggling.
A man-made passageway, which is built through a sea- or riverbed.

Component part of a mungo and shoddy mill, where non-wool fibres from shredded material are destroyed by either soaking rags in an acid solution or rotating them in drums in a hot acidic gas followed by heat. The result is an all-wool product.
