Emperor in Britain (293-296AD).
Joint Emperor of the Roman Empire (West) (305-306AD).
Joint Emperor of the Roman Empire (East) (305-311AD).
Rival Emperor of the Roman Empire (West) (306-312AD).
Joint Emperor of the Roman Empire (West) (306-324AD). Became Emperor of the Roman Empire (324-337AD) with his defeat of Lucinius.
Joint Emperor of the Roman Empire (East) (307-324AD).
Joint Emperor of the Roman Empire (East) (308-313AD).
The first English Civil War fought between Parliamentary forces and the King's Army (1642-1646).
The second phase of the English Civil War fought between Parliamentary forces and the King's Army (1646-1648)..
The third phase of the English Civil War fought between Parliamentary and Royalist forces (1650-1651).

Fought between the Covenanter/Royalist army led by David Leslie and the Parliamentary army led by Oliver Cromwell on the 3rd September 1650.  The Covenanter army was destroyed and as a result Cromwell seized Edinburgh.

Fought between the Royalist army led by Charles II and the Parliamentary forces commanded by Oliver Cromwell on the 3rd September 1651. The battle was a decisive victory for Parliamentary forces which destroyed the Royalist army.

Fought between the Scottish/Royalist forces led by the Duke of Hamilton and the Parliamentary forces led by Cromwell on the 17th-19th August 1648. The Royalist were routed and Cromwell's army became the dominant power in the country.

Fought between the Royalist army led by Charles I and the Parliamentary forces led by the Earl of Essex on 23rd October 1642. The battle was a tactical victory for the King but was won by only a narrow margin.

Fought between the Royalist forces led by Prince Rupert and the Parliamentary forces led by Sir Philip Stapleton on 18th June 1643.  Whilst attempting to return to Oxford after a raid, Rupert ambushed his pursuers, then charged and routed them.

Fought between Royalist forces led by the Duke of Newcastle and Parliamentary forces led by Lord Fairfax on 30th June 1643. The Parliamentary army was destroyed by a larger force leaving Yorkshire under Royalist control.

Twin-engined, medium bomber with a 1200 mile range and a bomb load in excess of 10,000 lb. Entered service in 1940, but engine faults resulted in retirement in 1942 with its design later modified into the acclaimed four-engine Lancaster bomber.

Fought between the forces of Edward III of England and Philip IV of France, 26th August 1346. Edward III's army although heavily outnumbered destroyed the French forces with the efficient use of disciplined infantry and longbowmen.

Fought between the English forces of Edward the Black Prince and the French forces of John II of France 19th September 1356. A crushing English victory which saw the capture of the French King. Another victory credited to the longbow.

Fought between the forces of Henry V of England and Charles d'Albret, Constable of France, 25th October 1415. The English made good use of longbowmen in a defensive position. A major victory which cost France half her nobility.

Fought between the forces of King Harold of England and William of Normandy, 14 October 1066. Although in a good defensive position with a strong shield wall, Harold's forces eventually succumbed. William went on to be crowned King of England.

Fought between the English forces of King Harold and the Norwegian forces of King Harald Hardrada, 25th September 1066. Harald Hardrada was killed and the English won a strategic but were poorly placed to deal with the subsequent Norman Invasion.
Single-engine, single-seat biplane seaplane built for the 1924 Schneider Cup Race.
A joint in which one timber is reduced in thickness.
A short beam that projects into a roof space from the foot of a principal rafter to receive a hammer post and, often, an arched brace.
A truss with transverse timbers, like a tie-beam from which the middle section has been removed, supported on braces and carrying hammer-posts and braces that carry the open structure of the roof.
A vertical timber resting on a hammer beam and forming a triangle between it and a principal.
A type of slender support carried on a corbel.
A room where fittings such as saddles and harnesses for horses are usually kept.
A part of an arch between the apex and the springer.
A loft for the storage of hay.
A plan in which the chimney stack backs onto the cross passage between a building's two entrances.
A door divided horizontally into two parts, independently hinged.
A machine for combing the fibres of cotton, worsted, flax etc to remove short fibres, clean out extraneous matter, and lay the fibres more or less parallel to each other.
A roof with four sloping sides, rising from four gables, joining at the apex like a pyramid.
Studding in which the studs are at an inclined angle to the posts.
A rotative beam steam engine patented in 1790.
A building or structure with a six-sided plan.
A dining hall for the use of seasonal labourers.
A movable joint, usually consisting of two plates joined by a pin, that fastens a door, gate, window etc. to its frame and allows it to open and shut.
A rafter set at the corner of a hipped roof, to take the upper end of a common rafter.
A ridged roof that slopes on all four sides.
A wool combing machine for very fine wools.
A spandrel that is sunk below the surface of the arch.
A steam engine in which the cylinder, crosshead and crankshaft lie in a horizontal line, as opposed to vertical designs.

A device or engine powered by one or more horses or donkeys walking around a circular track and harnessed  so as to turn a large toothed wheel, either in the same plane or above, which turned smaller  wheels operating machinery.
A timber, horse-powered device consisting of a large, rotating drum around which a rope would be wound, hoisting material from a quarry pit, mine shaft etc..
An arch, either pointed or round, which broadens above the springing line, creating a horseshoe shape.
An engine which uses air or the products of combustion as its working  medium.
A box crane which uses hydraulic power
A crane using hydraulic power.
An engine, introduced in Germany 1748 for use in mines, worked by high pressure water.
A hydraulic machine used to magnify the stroke of a hydraulic piston. The pulleys and chains of a crane or other device are attached to the jigger.
A hydraulic machine used to drive a pillar crane.
A machine that uses liquid pressure to exert a large force on two platens so that items placed between them are pressed to a shape, compressed, or forced together.

A device in which a large quantity of low pressure water is made to pump a small proportion of itself to a greater height than its source or to a higher pressure; achieved by using the pressure rise resulting from suddenly interrupting the flow
An hydraulically powered machine that tips coal into railway wagons, usually situated at a pithead.
An underfloor heating system.
A design of vertical steam engine patented in 1802.
A grand staircase where the lower flight splits into two upper flights.
A decorative style on a block or band from which an arch springs.
A machine used to burn and desiccate rubbish.
A slope, usually with rails, along which a vehicle can be moved between two relatively flat stretches of railway, or by which a boat can be transferred from one level of waterway to another.
A room or group of rooms for healing the sick. Where it is a monument use the Thesaurus of Monument Types.
An area within a large fireplace where it is possible to sit.
An inner defensive area within a castle.
Romanesque overlapping  arcades, producing a series of pointed arches.
An area or space within a building.

An engine or prime mover, in which a mixture of air and fuel is ignited inside a closed cylinder, and the resulting explosion drives a piston to the opposite end of the cylinder, its movement turning a crankshaft via suitable mechanical parts.
A tiebeam whose central section is omitted to increase head room; its inner ends are held by a slip-braces or struts rising from a dropped tiebeam and can be used in end frames.
The lower, or inner, curve of an arch
A type of steam engine in which the steam cylinders are placed above the crankshaft supported on a robust frame.
A base embellished with horizontal reeds and other mouldings.
Single-engined fighter, developed from the Camel. Entered service in 1918 and became the RAF's first mainstay peacetime fighter.
Twin-engined, four-crew bomber. Wooden framed, with linen covering, entered service in 1924, equipping several RAF squadrons.

Interbellum, twin-engined, five-crew, biplane flying-boat with a characteristic triple tail-fin. Entered service in 1925 and used for general reconnaissance duties. The Mk.I had a wooden fuselage, whilst the Mk.II's was metal in construction.
Large, three-engined, long range reconnaissance flying boat. Wooden hull and frame construction, with linen covering. Entered service in 1930.
Prime Minister of Britain (1721-42).
Ruler of the provinces of Gwynedd (844-878), Powys (855-878) and Seisyllwg (872-878).
Ruler of the province of Gwynedd (878-916).
Ruler of the province of Gwynedd (916-942).
Ruler of the provinces of Dyfed (c.904-950), Seisyllwg (c.920-950) and Gwynedd (942-950).
Ruler of the province of Gwynedd (c.1023-1039).

Prince of Gwynedd (1240-1246). Towards the end of his reign he assumed the style 'Prince of Wales'.

A Capital with a rolled up cushion-like form on either side creating distinctive volutes.
A column of the Ionic Order, set upon a base and characterized by its slender form.
An entablature consiting of an architrave, usually a frieze and cornice.
A classical order with an Attic base and fluted column. The cornice has dentils and the capital volutes.
A kiln in which Iron ores were heated before smelting in order to drive off the impurities such as sulphur.
A machine for the final reduction in cross sectional area of a cotton sliver into a fine roving preparatory to spinning high counts of yarn.
A shortened common rafter that runs between ridge and a valley rafter, or between eaves and a hip rafter.
An 18th century hand-operated machine capable of spinning several yarns at once, invented in circa 1767.
A projecting part of a building that overhangs the wall below it.
The bracket under a jetty bressumer.
The sill beam of the jettied upper floor resting on projecting ends of joists or on jetty brackets.
The wall plate of the lower storey on which the joists of a jetty rest.
A crane consisting of a vertical tower or similar structure from which projects a movable boom, or jib, fitted with a mechanical hoist.
A pulley running on the outside of a belt to improve the effectiveness of a drive.
A junction whereby two members or elements of an artificial structure or mechanism are joined or fitted together, whether rigidly or hinged.
A cruck truss whose blades are composed of two pieces of timber joined near the wall head in a variety of ways.
Horizontal timbers laid parallel to each other on which flooring is laid and to which a ceiling is fixed.
A joint used to secure the end of a joist
A parallel or axial-flow reaction water turbine invented in France in 1843, in which water descends through fixed curved guide vanes which direct the flow sideways onto curved vanes on the runner.

A room in the house of a Justice of the Peace in which cases were heard. Houses after 1848 contained these for prestige purposes since the practice of hearing cases at home was made illegal at that date.
A curved moulding with a sharp edge running along its centre. So named as its profile resembles the keel of a ship.
A room that serves as a combined living-room, kitchen and workshop.
A stone edging on a footway dividing it from a carriageway.
A truss with two curved kerb-principals, which are the short principal rafters rising froma tiebeam to a collar, placed either side of a crown strut.
A piece of wood of square or rectangular section driven through a scarf joint to tighten it
Classical decorative motif of interlocking right-angled and vertical lines, usually applied as a continuous pattern.
The wedge-shaped block placed at the crown of an arch to consolidate the structure. Sometimes employed as a decorative feature.
A mullion which divides a window with four or more lights and is larger than the mullions either side of it, often sharing the dimensions of the frame?s members.
A vertical timber in a truss, descending from the ridge, and projecting below the lower transverse timber, normally used  with scissor beams.
An upright post set on a tiebeam or collar and used to support a ridge piece.
A vertical timber set on a collar or tie-beam extending to the apex of a pitched roof.
A room in which food is prepared.
A very short brace between post and tiebeam, or post and wall plate.
A principal that has a short, angled section, resembling a knee-joint, at one end.
A large approximately triangular stone at the foot of a gable, cut to have a horizontal bed and a top conforming, wholly or in part, to the slope of the gable.
A communal sleeping room in medieval houses for male servants.
Decorative ornamentation in the form of interlacing ribbons or cords, usually in an intricate pattern.
A house plan with a hall and a single wing.
One of a set of windows placed vertically and linked either decoratively or by aprons extending to the lintel below.
A chapel dedicated to the Virgin, usually east of the chancel.
A semi-automatic loom developed  in Lancashire. Although it is self-acting, it has to be stopped to recharge empty shuttles.
A pointed, two-centred, arch whose height is much greater than its span.
A tall, narrow window with a pointed arched head.
A small structure, often polygonal or circular, on top of a roof, dome, tower etc. featuring apertures to light or ventilate the building it adorns.
A joint in which the dovetailed member is proud of the receiving member and is not finished flush with it.
A joint in which one timber is applied to the surface of the other.
A room in which food, usually meat, is kept.
A buttress attached to a corner of a structure, seeming to be a continuation of one of the walls.
The smallest piece of timber (2-5cms) across used in building, employed on rafters to support the roof covering or in a partition as a base for plaster or external render and wall covering.

Component part of a Flint Mill where flint is calcined before it is brittle enough to be ground in the mill. Ground, burnt flint is used in the production of earthenware pottery, which whitens and strenghens the body.
Ruler of Cantref Mawr (11971-1201).
Ruler of Cantref Mawr (1204-1234).
Ruler of lands in various parts of Deheubarth (1216-1231).
Ruler of the province of Powys (c.1116-1132).
Ruler of Powys (1132-1160).
Ruler of Southern Powys (1160-1195).
Ruler of Southern Powys (1195-1208).
Ruler of Southern Powys (1240-1286). Out of possession (1257-63) and (1274-77).
Ruler of Northern Powys (1160-1191).
Ruler of Northern Powys (1191-1236).
Ruler of Northern Powys (1236-1268).
Self-proclaimed Prince of Wales who led a rebellion against Henry IV, established a Welsh Parliament and fought for Welsh Independence.
The dissolution of the monasteries.
A torpedo-bomber and reconnaissance biplane in service with the Fleet Air Arm 1935-1938. Rendered obsolete after 1938 by the Swordfish and withdrawn from service.
Aircraft designed for the carrying and dropping of torpedoes.

Aircraft Manufacturing Co., Ltd. Established in 1912 by Mr G. Holt Thomas. In 1914 secured the services of Capt. Geoffrey de Havilland as designer-in-chief, who went on to lend his initials to a number of highly successful machines.

A two-seat, general purpose biplane. The first to be designed specifically for an Army Co-operation role, it entered service in late 1927. Ended its service as a communications and advanced trainer aircraft.
Single-engine, single-seat biplane day fighter developed by Siddeley. Variations included an all-metal, fabric-covered Mk.III, which became the RAF's main fighter in the 1920s.
A single-engine, heavy, long range, three to five-crew day bomber. Served only with 99 Squadron RAF, 1924-5.
A biplane, reconnaissance aircraft with a crew of 3 or 4 which equipped 3 and 22 squadrons RAF before passing to the Fleet Air Arm. Produced in two variants.
A two-seat trainer chosen to replace the Avro 504. 380 entered RAF service with many finding their way onto the civilian market at the end of their careers.
Originally designed as a light bomber but diverted for use as a high speed target tug to replace out-dated biplanes.
A fighter version of the SKUA fitted with a four-gun turret. The majority were converted to target tugs for use by the RAF and Fleet Air Arm.

Twin-engined, four-seat torpedo-bomber designed to replace the Vildebeest. Entered service with RAF Coastal Command in 1939. Later versions incorporated a remote-controlled machine gun with periscope sight.
An engineering works that produces machinery specially for use in shoe making.

Six-crew, medium-range, twin-engined reconnaissance flying-boat. Entered service with 209 Squadron in 1939 but, due to design and operation problems, saw little action and was not produced in large numbers.
Miles M.14 Magister. Single-engine, two-crew training and communications aircraft. Spruce and plywood in construction, with open cockpits and a fixed landing gear, served between 1937 and 1945.

Single-seat, single-engine biplane fighter. In operational service from 1939 to 1941, this was the last, and believed to be the best, biplane to be flown in the RAF. All-metal in construction with fabric and aluminium covering.

Three/four-crew, single-engine, shipboard observation and air/sea rescue amphibian seaplane. Entered RAF service in 1936. Also employed for gunnery spotting, anti-submarine and convoy protection duties.
A factory where packaging products, such as cardboard boxes, are produced.
A type of concrete bridge, developed in the 20th century, that consists of reinforced concrete deck slabs that sit on the supporting bridge piers and/or abutments.
A room for washing and cleaning linen.
A room with apparatus for washing the hands and face, now often combined with a water closet.
An archaeological unit of soil in a horizontal plane which may seal features or be cut through by other features.
A pilaster without base or capital.
A place set apart to contain books for reading, study or reference.
A tertiary vault rib, usually employed for decorative purposes, that links one intersection of the main ribs to another.
A section of a window between mullions; thus for example a three-light window.
A horizontal member spanning an opening and providing support to the wall above the opening.
A machine for combing out wool, mohair and alpaca, removing short fibres and any extraneous matter, and laying  the long fibres more or less parallel  to each other.
A room for general daily use, usually in a family dwelling.
A small room communicating with one or more apartments.
A plan in which the front entrance opens into a lobby opposite to an axial chimney stack.
A parlour in a monastery.
A joist which rests on top of a beam.
Space used for storage in the roof.
A long, high-ceilinged room, usually extending the full length of an Elizabethan or Jacobean house and often occupying an upper floor, used as a promenade, place of entertainment etc..

A machine for weaving cloth. A traditional loom comprises a framework with a horizontal back roller, the warp beam or warp roller, around which closely spaced warp threads have been wound parallel to each other, stretched horizontally onto a front roller.
An opening in a wall that is usually narrow on the outside but widens internally to allow a defender to stand and shoot through the loophole.
A room where the public can sit, often in hotels and airports.
An opening in the ridge of a roof intended to provide ventilation or an outlet for smoke; also the hood on such an opening that prevents rain entering.
An opening normally in a door or window filled with diagonally set slats to provide ventilation.
A window that is lower than others in the chancel side wall.
A decorative moulding in a diamond shape.
A window in a spire, often in the form of a dormer.
An opening through which missiles or combustible materials could be dropped upon attackers. Usually through the roof of an entrance way or in a projecting parapet.
A single piece of apparatus that uses mechanical power for a particular function.
Apparatus using mechanical power for a particular function.
A device for raising miners individually from a shaft consisting of two rods, raised and lowered alternately, fitted with small platforms and powered by a waterwheel or steam engine.
A twin cylinder compound steam engine introduced in the 1870's which combined a horizontal and vertical configuration in the same machine.
A curb-roof with curved or steeply pitched lower slopes and a hipped or pitched roof above. Named after the French Classical architect F. Mansart.
The non-diagonal joint at the right-angled meeting of two stone mouldings.

A powerful machine comprising a pair of heated cylinders revolving inside a chamber, and used for converting raw rubber into a soft plastic mass by being 'chewed' between knives or teeth projecting from the cylinders.
Machines for automatically feeding fuel onto the fire of steam boilers and other furnace plant, introduced at the beginning of the 19th century.
An oval or circular decorative feature often bearing an illustration or portrait in light relief.
A room intended, and often furnished accordingly, as a venue for the holding of meetings.
The solid, upright part of a battlement separating the openings, or crenelles.
A thin, rectangular panel, sometimes enriched with sculptural relief, placed between the triglyphs in a Doric Order frieze.
A storey of lesser height than those above and below it.
A machine tool capable of creating a variety of forms and surfaces in materials by way of a spinning cutter positioned over a movable table.
A steam engine working an underground cable haulage system in a late 19th century coal mine.
A projection from the bottom of a church stall designed to provide some support for a person standing in long services.
A small moulded bracket found on the Corinthian and Composite orders, and in plain form in the Ionic.
The most common form of joint between two timbers meeting at right angles or at an oblique angle, the mortice being a socket cut in one timber to receive the tenon projection of the other.
A surface made up of small pieces of hard material such as stone or tile, often in a decorative pattern.
An ornamental contour given to the angles or features of a building, whether a projection or a cavity, such as a cornice, an architrave or an astragal.
A mobile crane.
A mobile crane usually found on a marine or inland quay.
A machine for spinning cotton yarn.
A vertical member dividing a window into two or more lights.
Periods which relate to technological or cultural change
Periods which relate to a specific timespan. This covers centuries and events which took place during them.
Periods defined by the reigns of emperors, monarchs or parliaments.
Use for any site or object which is definitely pre-Roman but which cannot be more closely dated. In the UK this covers the period c.1000000 BC-43AD.

The period from the earliest evidence for human activity (eg. tool making) to the final retreat of glacial ice at the end of the last Ice Age. In the UK this covers the period c.1000000 BC - 10000 BC.

The period from the end of the last glacial phase to the start of the Neolithic, though neither start nor end are well defined. Characterized by the use of microlithic technology for tool production. In the UK c.10000 BC - 4000 BC.

Final phase of the Stone Age, characterized by the spread of agriculture, the first use of pottery, the first monuments (eg. long barrows, causewayed enclosures), as well as by the use of ground and polished axes etc. In the UK c.4000 BC - 2200 BC.
The earliest phase of the Palaeolithic, characterized by the use of bifacial tools, such as handaxes. In the UK c. 1000000 BC - 150000 BC.
The final phase of the Neolithic, associated with the construction and use of henges, and increasingly diverse (and regional) styles of pottery, lithics, etc. In the UK c. 2900 BC - 2200 BC.
The earliest phase of the Iron Age characterized by artefacts influenced by the continental Hallstatt Culture. In the UK  c. 800 BC - 300 BC.
The second phase of the Iron Age characterized by artefacts influenced by the La Tene Culture. In the UK c 300 BC - 100 BC.
The final phase of the Iron Age. Usually deemed to have ended in the UK with the arrival of the Romans in 43 AD, although cultural traditions continued. c. 100 BC - 43 AD.

The period characterized by the increasing Romanization of the indigenous British tribes. Romano-British culture survived the departure of the Romans and probably continued into the 6th Century. c. 43 AD to 600.
Use most appropriate term.
The period following the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain up to the Norman invasion in 1066. c. 410 AD - 1066.
The Medieval period or Middle Ages begins with the Norman invasion of Britain and ends with the dissolution of the monasteries (1066-1540).
Periods which can be defined by the artistic style of architecture.
Container for the storage of unspecified materials.
A large, vertical revolving wheel with passenger cars or pods on the periphery used to give a bird's eye view of the surrounding area.

A coin which has been struck in relief on one side, usually the obverse side face down on the anvil die, and incuse on the other side, due to a previously struck coin sticking to the upper or punch die.
A primitive musical instrument.
A metal disc before it is stamped to become a coin.
An earth based plaster the mixture of which may contain clay, dung, straw, lime putty, sand or horsehair.
Several strands of string twisted together to form a strong thin rope, or thick string, though it has been used in the past as synonomous with rope particularly for ropes on ships.
An area of ground which has been cleared of plants and other obstruction.
An open flat gound where the sport of shooting with bow and arrows is pursued. The ground can be equipped with targets mounted on butts and various fixed distance marker.
A military dining room where members of the armed forces eat and take recreation.
The premises of a coal merchant where coal and other kinds of solid fuel can be bought.
A recreation ground with usually permanent structure. It usually contains rides such as ghost trains, helter skelter and roller coasters.
A complex of buildings with the purpose of providing and storing food and drink supplies (esp. for the navy).
An artificial pond or pool constructed for the purpose of watering  livestock, particularly in prehistory.
A bracelet or necklace formed by hammering gold onto a triangular-sectioned bar and twisting the metal to form a spiral pattern.
A fragment of a vessel, or hollow object, usually of ceramic or glass. If known, use specific vessel type.
A fragment of the rim of a vessel, or hollow object, usually of ceramic or glass. If known, use specific vessel type.
A fragment of the base of a vessel, or hollow object, usually of ceramic or glass. If known, use specific vessel type.
A fragment of the body of a vessel, or hollow object, usually of ceramic or glass. If known, use specific vessel type.
A grooved ring holding a gem or semi-precious stone.

A small notebook formed from two tablets usually made of wood, bone, ivory or metal. They were given as commemorative gift by a consul on his installation and often decorated with the image of the consul.
An object used for counting, keeping count or marking the position of a player in a game, usually in the form of a small circular-shaped piece of bone, metal, wood, plastic or other material.
A flat, circular object often made from metal, wood, bone or ivory and of unidentified purpose.
A hinge composed of two parts: a u-shaped hinge attached to a door which slotted over an L-shaped staple in the door jamb.
A flat stone, often sandstone, used for paving.
A chain used to inhibit a prisoner's freedom.
A piece of armour worn to protect the throat.

A small, metal, crescent-shaped object, often highly decorated,  worn across the upper part of the chest by military personnel as a badge of rank and as a symbolic representation of the former piece of armour (see GORGET (ARMOUR).
A net worn over the hair to hold it in place.
The part of an object by which it is held when in use, being moved or carried.
The part of the bridle that fits around the horses head.
A device for holding a lamp in a fixed position. These could take many forms from a simple bracket fixed to a wall to an onrate candelabra.
A tall, thin pillar of wood, stone or metal on which a lamp could be fixed.
A boat fashioned out of a section of tree trunk.
A window divided into lights by mullions.
A small slab in a Doric cornice.
A decorative feature in the form of small pyramids in a continuous line.
A transverse vestibule at the west end of a church.
An antechurch which is transverse to the axis of the church and is covered or enclosed.
The central division of a church, extending from the west end to the chancel or transepts.
A plain area situated between the top of the shaft and the capital of a Renaissance Tuscan or Doric Order column.
A moulding on the neck of a column.
A steeply pitched spire whose base is significantly narrower than the tower on which it sits.
A single acting, non-rotative beam engine worked by atmospheric pressure.
The post at the centre of a winding staircase from which the steps radiate; or the post, supporting the handrail and string, at the angle of a square staircase.
A staircase where the vertical members are placed at the ends of flights to support the strings, handrails, trimmers and bearers.
A shallow, ornamental recess, often arched and semicircular in plan, set in a wall or pier and usually containing a statue or ornament.
A staircase, usually leading from a dormitory, used by monks to enter the transept of a monastic church.
A machine for combing out wool, cleaning out extraneous matter and short fibres and laying the combed long fibres more or less parallel to each other as required for Worsted spinning.
A steam engine from which the spent exhaust steam either passes out to the atmosphere and is lost, or in some cases is used as process steam in a factory.
A patented design of twin-cylinder, inverted vertical steam engine, which can be started irrespective of the position of the crank.
A window usually spanning the full width of the north side of a roof allowing the maximum amount of direct and indirect light to enter.
A roof design, common to weaving sheds, featuring a sawtooth profile with unequal slopes forming each ridge and  lights on its northern side.
An automatic power loom invented by James H Northrop in 1894.
A lap joint which has a notch cut in one side.
A decorative moulding featuring a series of small, projecting, dome-like shapes each resembling a halved nutmeg.
A plan of a structure which has eight sides.
A circular or oval window or panel. Also the circular opening at the top of a dome.
The area where the act of Offertory, where bread and wine are placed upon the altar, takes place.
A room in which commercial or administrative activities are carried out.
A decorative form consisting of two upright S-shaped curves positioned opposite one another with their concave sections placed at the top.
A pointed arch in which the arcs comprising it are centred on points both outside and inside the arch so that the point takes the form of a double S, or ogee.
A brace which is cut to a double curve.
An oil-fuelled internal combustion engine, developed in the late 19th century, and usually made as a stationary, horizontal unit.
A hall, or main living-room in a medieval house, open to the roof.
A hearth, normally placed clear of the walls, without a chimney stack or hood above.
A building plan where space is unconstrained by partitions.
A truss which does not subdivide a space, as in the centre of a hall of two bays or in an undivided building such as a barn.
A staircase, usually rising through more than one storey, with a space at its centre around which the stair is carried by strings and newels.
A small private chapel in either a house or church.
An area normally below a stage or dais occupied by an orchestra or musical group  for performances and entertainment.
A style of construction following an established set of criteria, based around the conventional use of a type of column.
A musical instrument that produces sound through the passage of air through a number of pipes controlled by stops, pedals and keyboards.
A bay window, supported by corbelling, cills or brackets, projecting from an upper storey of a building.
A large vertical stone forming part of a structure. If the structure is roofed, the orthostat will stretch from the floor to the roof as a single slab.
A compact design of steam engine which eliminates a connecting rod by having the piston rod directly attached to the crank.
A narrow hand loom.
A hidden dungeon entered through a trap door from the room above it. Also a similarly concealed pit into which prisoners would be cast.
A large defensive area that usually has to be crossed before entering the inner bailey of a castle.
An extension to a building, though sometimes contemporary with it, housed under a lean-to roof.
A waterwheel turned by the weight of water discharged into buckets placed around its circumference from an outlet positioned above it.
A Classical convex moulding, often decorated with egg-and-dart or similar motifs.
King of England (1087-1100).
King of England (1100-1135).
King of England (1135-1154).
King of England (1154-1189).
King of England (1189-1199).
King of England (1199-1216).
King of England (1216-1272).
King of England (1272-1307).
King of England (1307-1327).
King of England (1327-1377).
King of England (1377-1399).
King of England (1399-1413).
King of England (1413-1422).
King of England (1422-1461).
King of England (1461-1470) and (1471-1483).
King of England (1483).
King of England (1483-1485).
King of England (1509-1547).
Queen of England (1558-1603).
King of England and Scotland (1660-1685)
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1714-1727).
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1760-1820).
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1901-1910).
King of England (1066).
King of Norway (1047-1066).
The name given to the style of architecture popular during the reigns of Charles I and Charles II.

The style of architecture prevalent during the reign of James I and VI (1603-25) being a more complex development of the Elizabethan style. Later Jacobean architecture was influenced by the works of Inigo Jones.
The style of Gothic architecture which was prevalent in England between c.1250 and c.1350.

A fleet of 130 ships sent by King Philip II of Spain to invade England. After indecisive fighting the fleet was dispersed by fireships off Calais. A major engagement of Gravelines followed which led to the defeat of the Armada.
The union of the parliaments of Scotland and England in 1707.
A large, powerful, hand-drawn bow, usually 6 ft (1.8m) in length and traditionally made of wood.
A strap from the reins to the girth of a horse, preventing it from raising its head too high.

A long, thin cane of glass made by layering glass of various colours in a mould and pulling the soft glass until the cane was of the desired thickness. When cut and viewed in section the cane has a mosaic like appearance.
A object fitted to an item or garment for the purpose of display or decoration.
A shrine often including representations of a god or gods or other holy relics which could be carried by worshippers whilst travelling.
A finger ring with a brief motto or inscription.
A maritime fitting for spacing rigging elements and preventing entanglement.
Use most appropriate term.
A small container used for dispensing table salt for seasoning purposes.
A finger ring bearing a signet.
A tubular orifice to assist in pouring......
A decorative fitting of mid to late 11th century date, exclusively of copper alloy, and mostly zoomorphic. Arranged in pairs, on each stirrup either side of the footplate.
A decorative fitting of mid to late 11th century date, mainly of copper alloy, often traingular or trapezoidal in shape. Mounted at the junction of the stirrup and stirrup strap.
A decorative tile incorporated into the front of a tile stove.

A metal, often decorative, hinge constructed with a single large strap attached to the surface of the moving part wiht a loop in the end which fits over a pintle attached to the adjacent stationary frame.
A weight used to hold down thatch.
American-built, twin-engined flying-boat designed for maritime patrol and reconnaissance. Entered US Naval service in 1936 as the PBY-1; christened the Catalina by the RAF, who used it from 1939 on.

Also known as the C-47 Skytrain, this twin-engined, military transport was developed from the DC-3 twenty-eight-seat commercial airliner and was the most extensively employed transport of the Second World War.
A building with small observation ports used for plotting mines dropped by parachute.
Originally a light day-bomber, the Boston II, re-christened the Havoc, was adapted for night-flying in the fighter-intruder role. Was capable of a top speed in excess of 300 mph.
Transport version of the four-engined Lancaster bomber. Serving from 1943 to 1951, and all metal in construction, this aircraft was used extensively during the Berlin airlift.

Originally designed as a wood and steel bomber-reconnaissance aircraft, subsequent variations served as special transports, glider tugs and paratroop carriers. Featured a tricycle-style undercarriage.

A biplane torpedo-bomber designed to be flown from aircraft carriers. Equipped with foldable wings for ease of storage. Joined Fleet Air Arm service in 1940, intended as a replacement for the Swordfish.
British multi-purpose, single-engined monoplane that served as a torpedo-bomber, dive-bomber, reconnaissance aircraft and in other roles. Equipped with folding wings for use aboard aircraft carriers.
General Aircraft Limited.
Single-engine, spruce and plywood, fabric-covered training and communications low-wing monoplane. Served from 1939 to 1950.
A British aero- and marine-engineering company based on the Isle of Wight specializing in the construction of flying boats.

Originally ordered as land based dive-bombers, with 950 being delivered to the RAF, none are known to have flown operationally, instead apparently serving as target tugs. Bermuda was the name given to the Brewster SB2A Buccaneer in RAF service.
American, all-metal-construction, fighter. Entered service in 1941. 209 were delivered to RAF/FAA, most of which were used in the Far East.
The Curtiss-Wright Corporation, Airplane Division, established in 1910. Notable aircraft produced include the Kittyhawk.

American troop and supply-glider constructed from steel tube and fabric-covered wood, with a hinged nose to allow loading and unloading of troops or light vehicles. Also known as the Haig, this was the only US glider to see combat service.
Export version of the DO17.
British two-seat, twin-engined night fighter. Also used for roles such as long-range escort fighter, ground-attack and anti-shipping strike aircraft, bomber, torpedo-carrier and rocket fighter.
British twin-engined light/medium bomber developed from the model 142 civil transport. Noted for its speed, this three-crew monoplane had an all-metal, stressed skin structure and a 1000lb bomb load.
Four-crew, twin-engined monoplane designed as a torpedo-bomber and reconnaissance aircraft for RAF Coastal Command. Withdrawn from operations in November 1940 and downgraded to a trainer.
A timber set on the back of a cruck blade to carry a purlin.
A short timber laid across the top of a masonry wall to carry a wall plate or the foot of a common rafter.
A stone block set into a wall to support a truss or beam.
A room in which servants slept.
A defined portion of a surface, often a wall lining or door, usually rectangular, which may be recessed, level with or proud of its surrounding surface and may be framed by mouldings or channels.
A door adorned with panels, usually arranged in pairs.
A series of panels, usually of wood, combined to line a room.
A circular plan with a series of cells around a central core, often used for prisons.
A room used for storing food.
An atrium or open court, surrounded by porticoes, at the west end of a church.
A brace, parallel to another, in wall framing or arcading, or in trusses between post and tiebeam; also referred to as a duplicate brace.
A barrier, usually in the form of a small wall, set to prevent people falling over the side of a bridge, balcony, roof etc.
Ornamental plasterwork applied to the exterior of a building, especially timber-framed houses of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries..
Originally a reception room where visitors come come to talk especially in a closed establishment such as a monastery or school. Later used to refer to any room used for entertaining guests.
A space usually in front of a church entrance but can include the space surrounding a church.
A narrow means of access, often internal.
A narrow aisle that pierces an internal buttress.
A long straight timber, halved across  other roof timbers, especially running from a wall post or aisle post across the tiebeam to the opposing rafter.
A windbrace that bypasses one purlin to be jointed into the next  purlin or principal.
A flat oval or circular ornamental feature decorated in relief, often with flutes or floral motifs.

A section of a building distinguished from the rest either architecturally or as a separate structure joined to the main building, often intended for entertainment, specialised functions or ornamental purposes.
A plan form in which pavilions lead off from a spiral corridor.
A base on which a statue, column etc. stands.
A triangular gable usually above an entablature.
A wooden nail, round or square in section, used to fix a joint.
A decorative piece descending vertically from the bottom of a newel on a staircase, or from the junction of barge boards  at the apex of a gable.
A spandrel which supports a dome and aids the transition between the dome and its square or octagonal base.
A lean-to or monopitched roof, or a projecting canopy over a door, window, or stair.
An internal combustion engine which uses a mixture of air and petrol as fuel, the combustion of which is by an electric spark.
The principal storey of a building, containing the main reception rooms, when not situated on ground level.
A solid support of masonry to sustain vertical pressure and frequently each of the pillars from which an arch springs.
A detached external pier by which an arch or vault is prevented from spreading.
A window cut through a single slab of timber or stone.
A flattened rectangular version of a column of one of the classical orders.
A form of pilaster without base or capital.
The equivalent of a colonnade but using pilasters.
A type of foundation in the form of a post sunk into the ground to support a building platform.
A vertical member standing without support.
A water-drain connected to a stone bowl within a niche in the south wall of a chapel, used to receive  the water in which the priest washed his hands and rinsed the Chalice.

A waterwheel where the incoming supply of water is introduced at the top of the wheel and drops onto the paddles, or buckets, of the wheel which rotates in the reverse direction to that of the incoming flow.
The element or elements that make up the different parts of a structural plan.

A machine tool for producing large flat surfaces on metal objects. It comprises a large work table which slides backwards and forwards along a substantial guide bed, passing under a stationary bridge containing a fixed tool.
A door made up of vertical planks on the outer face and horizontal planks on the inner face.
Plans of structures, particularly ground plans, and divisions or elements of structures that form part of these plans.
A general term given to all horizontal timbers laid on walls or posts in order to support other timbers.
A room for children to play in.
The skirting or projecting base of a wall.
An arch produced by two curves, usually each with a radius equal to the span, which meet at a point.
A room for temporary imprisonment and detention at a Police Station.
An inwards, radial flow reaction water turbine developed by Jean Victor Poncelet (1788-1867) in France in 1826.
A twin-engined development of the JU88, the JU188 had a higher service ceiling and greater maximum speed. JU188s operated over the UK from 1944 onwards as night intruders and reconnaissance aircraft.
A type of seaplane, with one or more slender pontoons (known as "floats") mounted under the fuselage to provide buoyancy.
The course or channel of a river or stream preserved as a geological feature.
An installation used to store ammunition and equipment ready for the mobilization of armed forces in the event of a war.
A racing track, often within a permanent stadium, for racing dogs, usually greyhounds and whippets.
A factory for the manufacture of heels for the shoe making trade.
A building, usually part of a textile mill complex, where warp yarn is sized prior to weaving. Sizing is the application of a starch solution to warp threads to add strength and protection.
A manufacturing site producing weaving shuttles for the textile industry.
A building or buildings where electronic components or devices are designed, developed, manufactured and assembled.
A technological and cultural phase of the Palaeolithic marked by the appearance of more elaborate bifacial tools, notably handaxes. Use LOWER PALAEOLITHIC.

A technological and cultural phase of the Palaeolithic marked by a technology dominated by flakes. Overlapping in time with the Acheulian, this is the phase generally associated with Homo Neanderthalensis in Europe. Use MIDDLE PALAEOLITHIC.

An early cultural phase of the Bronze Age centred around the use of Beaker pottery, and based on an assumption that this pottery was introduced by a distinct group of people - the 'Beaker Folk'. Use EARLY BRONZE AGE (or LATE NEOLITHIC if appropriate).
A former cultural grouping of Bronze Age sites and objects focused around the use of Deverel-Rimbury pottery styles. Use MIDDLE BRONZE AGE.
King of Scotland (1406-1437).
King of Scotland (1437-1460).
King of Scotland (1460-1488).
King of Scotland (1488-1513).
King of Scotland (1513-1542).
King of Scotland (1371-1390).
King of Scotland (1390-1406).
King of Scotland (1306-1329).
King of Scotland (1329-1371).
King of Scotland (943-954).
King of the Scotland (843-60). He was king of the Scots of Dal Riata from 841 and king of the Picts from 843 and created the combined kngdom of Scotia.
King of Scotland (860-863).
King of Scotland (863-877).
King of Scotland (877-878).
King of Scotland (878-889).
King of Scotland (889-900).
King of Scotland (900-943).
King of Scotland (1005-1034).
King of Scotland (954-962).
King of Scotland (962-967).
King of Scotland (967-971).
King of Scotland (971-995).
King of Scotland (995-997).
King of Scotland (997-1005)
King of Scotland (1034-1040).
King of Scotland (1040-1057).
King of Scotland (1057-1093).
King of Scotland (1093-1094) and (1094-1097).
King of Scotland (1094).
King of Scotland (1097-1107).
King of Scotland (1107-1124).
King of Scotland (1124-1153).
German single-engine, four-seat maritime patrol and reconnaissance flying-boat. In production between 1934 and 1940, the DO18 was replaced by the three engined DO24.
German three-engined air/sea rescue and transport flying boat. Entered service in 1940 as a replacement for the DO18.
American, single-engine fighter designed for operation from US Naval aircraft carriers. Produced between 1940 and 1945, Wildcats provided to the British Fleet Air Arm were renamed Martlets.

American, single-engine fighter designed for operation from US Naval aircraft carriers. The Hellcat was a more powerful version of the Wildcat, a total of 1000 being provided to the Fleet Air Arm under Lend-Lease.

Fleet Air Arm fighter and torpedo-bomber, designed for operation from aircraft carriers. All-metal in construction, it entered service in 1944 and was rendered obsolete after the war by the advent of the jet aircraft.
A single-engine, photo-reconnaissance fighter designed for operation from aircraft carriers. Later adapted as a night fighter, it entered service in 1943 and remained in production until 1956.

Single-engine, two-crew fighter, also used for convoy escort and reconnaissance. Designed to operate from aircraft carriers. Entered service with the Fleet Air Arm in 1940 and remained in use until 1945.
Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber and ground-attack aircraft. Entered service with the Luftwaffe in mid-1941. Approximately 20,000 were constructed between 1941 and the end of the war.

Long-range, four-engine reconnaissance-bomber. Initially produced as a transport, converted and used against Allied convoys in the Channel and the Atlantic. Also served as a VIP transport, one of which was the Immelmann III: Hitler's personal aircraft.

Four-engine, seven-crew heavy bomber. Entered service with RAF Bomber Command in 1940, becoming one of the twin sources of bomber strength along with the Lancaster. Also used for transport and glider tug duties.

Wood and fabric transport glider, twenty of which were produced with twin Bristol Mercury engines. Fitted with a hinged nose for loading and unloading, this was the largest glider used by the RAF and could accomodate a 7-ton tank.

Three-seat, twin-engined minelaying, torpedo-bombing and reconnaissance twin-float seaplane. First flown in 1936, in 1938 it set eight world speed records for its class in various range and payload categories.

Twin-engined, six-crew, heavy bomber. Conceived as a rival to the Lancaster and Flying Fortress, the HE177 was dogged by mechanical and structural problems. Of a thousand produced, only about two hundred saw action.
Twin-engined, four-seat medium bomber. A re-engined variant of  the Hampden, less than 200 were built but never became operational due to engine unreliability. Some were converted to Hampdens.

Troop and general transport glider. Almost entirely wooden in construction, many were manufactured by the furniture industry. Mk I featured a a door-ramp on the port side whilst the Mk II was fitted with a hinged nose.
Principal glider-pilot training glider fitted with tandem seats. Spruce and plywood in construction, the Hotspur served with the Glider Pilot Regiment between 1941 and 1945.

Twin-engined maritime-reconnaissance bomber adapted from pre-war American airliners, the A-28 and A-29, evident from the row of portholes along its fuselage. Entered service with RAF Coastal Command just before the outbreak of World War Two.

Single-engine, single-seat fighter, also adapted as a night-fighter, fighter-bomber, rocket-projectile fighter and tank-buster. The first monoplane to enter RAF service with 14,000 being produced between 1937 and 1944.
Three-seat tactical support aircraft. Entering service with the US 9th Air Force in 1944, the Invader had a bomb load of 4,000 lbs and was later used as a conventional medium bomber.

Two-crew, twin-engined bomber. Entered production in 1934 and designed for dual use as a high-speed commercial transport. Technical problems hindered its use as a bomber and led to conversion to high-altitude reconnaissance.

Single-seat, single-engine fighter-bomber: Curtiss P40 Warhawk, known to the RAF as the Tomahawk, later renamed Kittyhawk. Serving from 1941 to 1942, control difficulties in dive attacks impeded bombing accuracy, resulting in use for larger targets only.

Twin-engined jet-fighter. The first British aircraft to exceed Mach 1 in level flight, later to exceed Mach 2. Entered service in 1960. After 13 years was superseded in its primary defence role by the Phantom, though remained in RAF service until 1988.
Single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer. Spruce and plywood in construction, entered service in 1939, continuing to serve as a trainer, and also a target tug, until 1950.
Single-engine, advanced-pilot trainer used in secondary flying training schools. Serving from 1939-50, was also used as a target tug for gunnery practice.

Two-seat, twin-engined fighter/fighter-bomber designed as a replacement for the Bf110. Of the 600 or so produced, only 258 reached the Luftwaffe due to serious design faults. The ME210 was superseded by the ME410 Hornisse.

The RAF's first jet fighter, flown operationally during 1944-5, with later versions serving for a further ten years after the war. The Meteor's first active operations were in the interception and destruction of V.1. flying bombs.

Two-seat, twin-engined light/medium bomber celebrated for its speed and versatility. Entering service in 1941, was also adapted for duties as a fighter-bomber, Pathfinder, mine-layer, transport, trainer and photo-reconnaissance aircraft.
An interior or projecting shelter surrounding an entrance to a building.
A frame to a structure formed by precast concrete beams placed in pairs.
A porch which is sufficiently large enough to allow a vehicle beneath it.
A porch with columns and pediments.
A substantial vertical member, usually a component of a main framework.
A truss comprising principal rafters and wall-posts secured by knee-braces or sling-braces, but lacking tiebeams.
A hole occupied by a timber post or the void remaining after its removal, usually with packing.
A pad on which a post rests to support part of a structure.
The space occupied by or left where a post has been.
A small room off a bedroom, usually in eighteenth century houses, in which a person would have their wig powdered.
A power driven cloth-weaving machine.
A part of the chancel of a church where the altar is situated.
A structural member that supports a purlin. Use PRINCIPAL RAFTER where the principal is also a common rafter.
A structural member that supports a purlin and is also a common rafter.
A roof made up of common and principal rafters.
A pair of principal rafters with a tiebeam, usually with a collar.
A principal with a curved lower end that continues down the wall for a short distance.
A room for detention and imprisonment within a prison.
A room for personal rather than public use.
A latrine.
A private chamber usually in a Royal residence.
An arch associated with the portion of the stage between the curtain and the orchestra.
A room in a church to receive the congregation's offerings.
A capital with a half figure projecting from each corner
A raised structure from which a priest can preach.
A frieze that has a convex section.
A power driven machine or device for raising a liquid or forcing it along a pipe, or for compressing a gas.
A horizontal timber set in the plane of a roof's slope and supporting common rafters.
A vault where the bay is divided by diagonal and transverse ribs into four cells or webs.
A piece of machinery for lifting stone, or containers loaded with stone, from a quarry.
A diagonal brace running from an end of a cross tree to the vertical post to support this.
A plan with four foils radiating out from a central point.
A window either in the shape of a four leaf clover or circular with four foils enclosed.
A crane usually found at a marine or inland quay.
One of a pair of posts, placed symmetrically on a tie beam,  supporting a collar purlin or plate.
A truss with paired vertical posts set on the tie-beam and supporting collar purlins or plates.
A strut which is part of a pair which support the collar and are supported by the tiebeam.
A stone or brick used on a corner to reinforce it and also as decoration.
One of a series of chapels which project symmetrically from an apse or ambulatory at the east end of a church.
An inclined member used to support laths under a roof covering. Normally one of a pair.
A timber running obliquely across a series of common rafters.
A horizontal member of a wall frame between posts or studs, also the horizontal member in panelling, a panelled door or a window.
A barrier consisting of a horizontal rail supported by uprights.
A slope, usually with rails, along which a vehicle can be moved between two relatively flat stretches of railway.
An elevator used to raise locomotives.
A signal usually mounted on a gantry, be it mechanical or electronic, to provide guidance to traindrivers on access to sections of track.
A rotating circular platform operated by machinery to turn a steam locomotive around.
A cruck which is set in solid masonry above floor level but stretching a long way down the wall.
A cornice along the sloping edge of a pediment or gable.
One of a pair of straight or curved members set at an angle on the tie-beam and framed into a principal rafter, often supporting a purlin.
A protective earthern mound.
A prime mover which is rotated by the reaction from forcing a moving fluid to change direction.
A rectangular recess along the edge of a timber to receive a shutter, door or window.
A decorative feature, or non-heraldic badge, representing the name of a person connected with a building, often in the form of a graphic pun on the name.
A room intended for the pursuit of recreational activities.
A plan in which a four-sided figure has all its angles at right angles and its opposite sides equal and parallel.
A dining hall, usually in a monastery or college.
A room within a church or cathedral in which holy relics were kept.
King of Scotland (1153-1165).
King of Scotland (1165-1214).
King of Scotland (1214-1249).
King of Scotland (1249-1286).
Queen of Scotland (1286-1290).
King of Scotland (1292-1296).
King of England (1066-1087).
Use most appropriate term.
King of England (1485-1509).
King of England (1547-1553).
Queen of England (1553-1558).
King of England and Scotland (1603-1625). King of Scotland (1567-1603).
King of England and Scotland (1625-1649).
King of England and Scotland (1685-1688).
King of England and Scotland (1689-1694) as joint ruler with his wife Mary II and (1694-1702) as sole ruler.
Queen of England and Scotland (1689-1694) as joint ruler with her husband William III.
Queen of England and Scotland (1702-1707). Queen of Great Britain and Ireland (1707-1714).
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1727-1760).
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1820-1830).
King of Great Britain and Irleand (1830-1837).
Queen of Great Britain and Ireland (1837-1901). Empress of India (1876-1901).
King of Great Britain and Ireland (1910-1922). King of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (1922-1936).
King of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (1936).
King of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and North Ireland (1936-1952).
Queen of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland (1952-Present Day).

The period marked by the increasing use of Iron, rather than bronze, as the main material for tools and weapons. The Iron Age ends in England with the Roman Invasion of 43AD. In the UK c. 800 BC - 43 AD.
The period associated with the use of copper and bronze as the main material for the manufacture of tools, weapons and ornaments. In the UK c. 2600 BC - 700 BC.

A phase of the palaeolithic characterized by a technology dominated by flake production, including extensive use of the 'Levallois' technique. In Europe, it is the phase associated with Homo Neanderthalensis. In the UK c. 150000 BC - 40000 BC.

The final phase of the Palaeolithic, associated with the appearance of modern humans. Technologically, it is characterized by the production of narrow blades struck from cores. In the UK c. 40000 BC - 10000 BC.

The earlier, post-glacial phase of the Mesolithic, characterized by the use of broad blade industries, and showing clear continuity from the preceding final stages of the Upper Palaeolithic. In the UK c. 10000 BC - 7000 BC.

The later phase of the Mesolithic, characterized by the use of narrow blade industries, with smaller and more varied microlith forms. During this phase Britain was physically separated from continental Western Europe. In the UK c. 7000 BC - 4000 BC.

The first phase of the Neolithic, associated broadly with the first long barrows, megalithic tombs, causewayed enclosures etc. and the appearance of plain and decorated bowl pottery. In the UK c. 4000 BC - 3300 BC.

The first phase of the Bronze Age, associated with the more widespread use of round barrows, and the first manufacture and use of copper and bronze tools, weapons and ornaments. In the UK c. 2600 BC - 1600 BC.

The phase of the Bronze Age traditionally characterized by the use of palstaves rather than flat or flanged axes. Also characterized by the first clear evidence of enclosed settlements and field systems. In the UK c. 1600 BC to 1200 BC.
The final phase of the Bronze Age, traditionally characterized by the use of swords and socketed axes. In the UK c. 1200 BC - 700 BC.

A former cultural grouping of Bronze Age material focused around the use of gold objects and other 'valuable' items as grave goods in southern England. Use EARLY BRONZE AGE or MIDDLE BRONZE AGE as appropriate.

Cultural period associated in Western Europe with the first widespread use of iron, among other developments. Hallstatt phase C is the first for which analagous material culture appears in the British Isles and equates broadly with the EARLY IRON AGE.
Cultural period in Western Europe grouped arounf particular forms of material culture, notably new styles of metalwork. Use MIDDLE IRON AGE or LATE IRON AGE as appropriate.
King of the West Saxons (802-839).
King of the English (978-1016).
Queen of Scotland (1542-1567).

King of the West Saxons (839-858). Visited Rome in 855 dividing his kingdom between his two sons. On his return Aethelbald refused to give up his power and Aethelwulf was confined to the eastern half of his kingdom until his death in 858.

King of the West Saxons (858-860) . Aethelbald was placed in charge of the western part of the Kingdom of the West Saxons by his father when Aethelwulf set off for Rome in 855. On his father's return Aethelbald retained some control.
A simple, single cylinder vertical steam engine with its cylinder mounted directly on a baseplate, driving an overhead crankshaft which is supported by two A-shaped frames
A strut with a reflecting counterpart that forms the letter A on either side of a king post.
The flat slab at the top of a capital.
Solid masonry placed to counteract the lateral thrust of a vault or arch.
A long much indented leaf usually curled over at the tip which is a standard form of foliage in classical decoration.
A display or depiction of authorised armorial bearings, such as the elements of a coat of arms, livery and personal badges and flags, mottoes etc..
A passage, usually horizontal, leading into a mine to allow for access or drainage.
Originally, the inner sanctuary of a Greek temple from where the oracle was delivered. Now used for any private chamber or sanctuary.
An opening or shrine, usually containing a statue, framed by a pair of pilasters or columns supporting an entablature and pediment.
The framing of a door or window with two columns piers or pilasters which support a lintel,entablature etc.
The area of the Basilica, especially in the early church, in which the altar resides.
A keystone decorated with a relief sculpture, usually a cartouche
A half gable or half pediment concealing the lean-to roof of an aisle.
A pump for removing condensed steam from the condenser of a steam raising plant.

The side compartment of a building, usually a church, hall or barn, separated from the main body of the building by an arcade; or a passage allowing access to rows of seats in an auditorium or church.
A horizontal member along the length of an aisle wall to receive the ends of rafters.
A roof truss supported by arcade posts in an aisled building.
A recess within a wall or room.
A room in a monastery from which alms were distributed; or the residence of an almoner.
An elevated table or podium on which to place, or sacrifice, offerings to a god or gods.
A rail or balustrade that separates the altar from the rest of the church.
A partition or wall behind an altar, often separating the choir and altar from the ambulatory and east chapel.
A walkway around the parapets of a castle or the roof of a church.
The consecrated ground immediately surrounding a tomb or grave.
A reading desk usually placed near the west end of the choir.
A path or area for exercise, usually taken in the form of walking. Can be partially or totally covered.
An aisle within a chancel providing access to, and around, the High Altar and surrounding cells.
A representation of a winged boy who represents Cupid or Love.
Use appropriate term.
A simple type of hinge used for large gates.
A beam the end of which is fixed beyond the upright it passes through.
A room over the vestry of a church, often thought to have been where anchorets lived.
A projection left on a stone block to allow it to be hoisted into position.
An ornamental bracket on either side of a doorway supporting a cornice.
The corner upright bar of a polygonal sash.
A bracket that is shaped to form an angle.
Two buttresses which meet at a right angle at the corner of the structure they are supporting.
A capital at the corner of a colonade or portico in the Ionic Order in which the volutes are splayed outwards at 45 degrees.
A chimney placed at an angle with the walls so that there is an obtuse angle with each wall.
A column at the corner of a structure.
A diagonally set modillion placed at a cornice's external corner.
A principal rafter below a hip rafter that supports the ends of purlins under a hip.
A rib placed at an angle to support timbers.
A vertical piece of wood fixed on corners of walls to help the fixing of plaster and to protect against damage to the plaster.
A strut which is at an angle between the principal rafter and tiebeam.
A projection from the inner angle of a building around a court or with advancing wings, usually containing a staircase and often crowned above the roof line with an ogee dome.
A type of Ionic diagonal capital where all four sides are the same and with therefore eight volutes.
A niche in the corner of a structure.
A structure, or building, forming a supplementary and subsidiary part of a main complex.
A circular moulding.
A term used to describe a vaulted roof where the vault goes from either the newel of a staircase to a wall or from one wall to another where the walls are circular in plan.
A column joined to another by a band or ring.
An arch built into a wall above another arch or lintel to relieve it of some of the weight of the structure above.
Components within a religious, ritual or funerary site directly connected to the sacred practices involved at the site.
A decorated screen behind an altar.
A shelf that is behind an altar.
A room used for sleeping or resting in. Use more specific term.
The space between the high altar and the east wall or chapel in a large church, and often the area west of a Monks' choir.
A moulding on a flat or vaulted ceiling, suggesting a structure or forming a pattern derived from vaulting..
The horizontal timber running the length of a roof and positioned at its apex.
A semicircular crypt below the apse of a church.
A gulley in the form of a circle for holding vertical posts in the walls of iron age round houses.
A gauge for measuring the volume of water flowing from a river to machinery using the water for motive power??
A plain moulding of semi-circular section.
A loft or gallery supported on a covered, vaulted structure and projecting over the rood screen proper, occassionally used by minstrels or singers.
A timber screen, often richly decorated, placed in front of a chancel to support a rood loft.
The exterior upper covering, and its supporting structure, of a building.
An enclosed compartment within a building intended for a purpose other than as a thoroughfare.
A circular window containing tracery.
A circular stylised ornament, essentially a patera with floral enrichment, associated with classical architecture and occurring on the soffits of coffers, and as the fleuron of the Corinthian abacus.
An engine in which the oscillating motion of the beam is translated via gearing to a rotative motion.
A steam engine which produces rotary motion.
A room in a church where vestments and sacred vessels are stored.
A short timber set on top of two cruck blades.
A thin timber, usually sloping on both sides, fixed to the floor between the jambs of a doorway.
A device, usually wooden, or fabric on a timber frame, designed to catch, and be driven by, the wind in order to power a windmill. For maritime uses see the Thesaurus of Maritime Archaeology.
A large, high-ceilinged room, usually in a great house or palace, serving as a principal reception room; also a room used by the public for a specific purpose; or a drawing room in a house.
The part of the chancel, between the altar rail and the eastern wall, containing the high altar.
A window with a frame for holding the glass, capable of being raised and lowered in vertical grooves.
A device for receiving and sending radio-transmitted signals into the atmosphere.
An elementary steam engine working on the atmospheric principle; often used downstream of an overshot waterwheel.
A roof truss used for small spans with a saw-tooth overall shape braced by vertical and diagonal members.
A type of cushion capital with the lunette on each face cut into a series of truncated cones to form a scallop shell-like decoration.
An ornamental moulding whose curved, segmented form resembles that of a scallop shell.
A joint between two timbers meeting end to end.
A truss with braces crossing and fixed to each other, thus tying a pair of rafters together.
One of a pair of crossing braces halved or lapped across each other, tying a pair of rafters together.
A wheel, usually steam driven, used for raising water by means of buckets attached to its circumference.
A housing, normally of triangular section, in a post to take the end of a prop, to hold the post upright during construction.
A compact design of engine in which a connecting rod is dispensed with, giving a short baseplate.
A deeply concaved moulding, with a projecting lower edge, that sits at the base of a column between two torus mouldings.
A vertical partition used to separate one area from another.
A passage that runs axially across the end of a hall with a screen between it and the hall and doorways to service rooms on the other side.
A joint in which the end of one timber is shaped to fit around the moulding on another.
The junction of two timbers at right angles, with chamfers or mouldings meeting on a diagonal line, where one timber is cut to fit around the chamfer or moulding of the other timber.
A room, or part of a kitchen, for the cleaning and storage of kitchen utensils.
A figurative or abstract design in the round or in relief and can be of various materials. For freestanding sculptures see also Monument Types Thesaurus.
A machine for cleansing flax, hemp or cotton and forming the fibres into a continuous wide lap or sheet in preparation for carding.
The inner rafter of a compound rafter.
A truss of slighter construction between principal trusses in an elaborate roof.

King of the West Saxons (860-865). Placed in charge of the eastern part of the kingdom by his father when Aethelwulf went to Rome in 855.  Acceeded to the whole kingdom on the death of his brother Aethelbald who held the western part until his death.
King of the West Saxons (865-871).

King of the West Saxons (871-899). Prevented the Danish conquest of England by defeating Guthrum and his army at Edington (878). He built a navy to prevent further attacks from the sea and did much to revive learning, translating Latin texts into English.

The period of military occupation or political control by the Roman Empire, which flourished in Europe and the Mediterranean basin between late first century BC and the fifth century AD. In the UK c. 43AD to 410 AD.
A site used for the manufacture of lasts, shoemaker's models of the foot for shaping and repairing footwear. Lasts can be from a variety of materials, such as wood or iron.
A law court builidng established during the 1970's accommodating offices and courtrooms fro the Crown and County Courts.
A local civil court first established during the 17th Century by local Acts of Parliament to deal with minor cases of debt. Based on a model established during the reign of Henry VII.
A building housing court rooms and associated offices and cells, in which the Quarter Sessions were held.
A court of summary jurisdiction formally recognized by statute in 1848. Renamed Magistrates Court, following legislation, in 1949.
A magistrates court sitting for the purpose of holding trials for children and young people. Replaced the juvenile court, following legislation, in 1991.
A distinctive magistrates court established by legislation in 1980, dealing with civil family proceedings.
A small, flat band or fillet around a shaft or column.

A pilaster terminating the side walls of a temple whose capital and base differ from those of its associated columns. Such an arrangement, where the columns do not project beyond the faces of the antae, is said to be 'in antis'.
The partially enclosed western part of a chapel, leading to the chapel proper.
Part of a church in front of the choir and usually enclosed by tombs, screens etc.
An addition to the west end of a church which is similar to a porch or narthex but usually consists of a nave and aisles.
The first court which is before the principal court.
A decorative tile on the end of the cornice or eaves of a building to conceal the ends of tiles.
The hall before a great hall.
A porch in front of the solid wall of a cloister.
A room before a larger room which is often used as a waiting room.
A stylised, leafy decorative feature reminiscent of, and sometimes referred to as, honeysuckle
A room or group of rooms in a building.
The top stone in a gable end.
The undressing room in a bath house or similar.
The outward curve at the top or bottom of a column where it joins the base or capital.
A storeroom for valuable goods, such as wine, oil and spices.
Found in early churches this was a part of a church on the south side of the chancel where there were bookshelves and storage for vestments.
A beam that has been applied to a wall face.
An engaged column, that is one attached to a wall.
A classical order in which the columns or pilasters are applied to a wall.
A shaped or decorated raised panel below the sill of a window or a niche.
A polygonal or semicircular recess projecting from an external wall, often with a rounded vault.
A chapel that radiates from an apsidal end of a cathedral or church.
A small apse.
A type of water pump used in the Wigan coalfields in the late 18th and 19th centuries.
A style of decorative design consisting of intertwined, geommetrical patterns of leaves, branches, tendrils etc. Often defined as being devoid of human or animal figures.
A series of arches.
A timber running above vertical posts, in the place of a wall-plate, within a timber-framed building.
A curved construction, spanning an opening, formed from wedge-shaped blocks supported by mutual pressure; they can also be formed from moulded concrete and cast metal.
The part of a rib or arch visible below the general surface of the vault.
A curving, upright timber brace used in roof construction, found in pairs, forming an arch.
A wedge shaped brick used to construct arches.
A buttress shaped like an arch and springing from a pier in arched form to the wall.

The lowest of the three main parts of an entablature. Also the lintels, jambs and mouldings surrounding a door, window, panels or niche; or the ornamental mouldings around the exterior curve of an arch.
An opening in a structure which is arched.
An arched or vaulted recess, within a tomb or catacomb, intended to contain a coffin or sarcophagus.
Areas and spaces within a monument or site.
The body of a church or chapel as opposed to galleries.
A metal binding or ring fastened around the top of a pile to stop splitting.
A room where weapons and armour are stored.
A triangular piece of wood used to raise slates next to a wall or similar.
A V-shaped gutter.
An inclined timber running from a rafter to the inner face of a wall, forming a triangle.
Short vertical timbers which go from the rafters to the inner plate on a thick wall.
An Ionic base with a lower disc with horizontal fluting or reeding, above which is a torus, also reeded.
A large room for large numbers of people, eg for balls, meetings etc.
A moulding which is small, convex and circular.
Describes a Classical interior, exterior or facade without pilasters or columns.
A whole male figure used in place of a column to support an entablature.
An early steam engine using steam at atmospheric pressure. Chiefly employed in mine pumping. sometimes known as a vacuum engine.
A court in front of a church, usually open.
A central area within a building.
An area partly or fully within the roof space of a building.
A column base featuring a hollow, concave - or scotia - moulding between two tori, which are projecting, convex mouldings.
A square pillar.
A room where a monarch or similar would meet people, usually in a palace or similar building.
A room or hall designed for an audience to listen and view, as in a theatre, concert hall, lecture hall etc..
Circular or almond-shaped halo surrounding the figure of Christ, the Virgin or a saint.
A bridle joint which is invisible from all sides of the timber.
A joint with a notch cut into its invisible inner face.
An arch made up of part of a circle, the centre of which is below its springing line.
A room for servants, particularly where they would eat.
The part of a house frequented by servants when not performing their duties.
A room usually set aside for the provision of materials used in a household.
A staircase normally used by servants and tradesmen.
A wing of a house used specifically for the storage of household materials and victuals.
A buttress that is set slightly away from a corner. Usually one of a pair.
A decorative pattern, as used in tracery or a Gothic arch, featuring six lobes, or foils, separated by cusps.
The part of a column between the capital and the base.
A moulded ring around a shaft.
A machine tool for producing flat surfaces and slots on small work pieces by cutting away surplus material.
A flat arch or lintel with quadrants on the corbels rising from the jambs.
A fereter or repository for relics or any building containing such a repository, or any place or structure where worship is offered or devotions are paid to a saint or deity.
A hinged, sliding or rolling door placed over a window's exterior or interior.

A design of beam steam engine introduced circa 1800 in which, instead of a single overhead rocking beam, there are two beams positioned alongside the cylinder, one either side, giving a lower overall height.
A building plan in which the principal fireplace is positioned on the side wall.
The horizontal piece of timber or stone forming the bottom of a window, doorway or other opening, usually and properly designed to throw off water.
A horizontal timber positioned at the bottom of a framed wall into which posts and studs are tenoned.
A horizontal timber usually at the bottom of a timber framed wall into which posts and studs are tenoned.
