A form of tandem compounding of early beam engines, with a high pressure steam cylinder mounted on top of a low pressure one, introduced in Cornwall the 1840s by James Sims.
A simple, one-roomed structural plan.
A glazed opening in a roof or ceiling.
A machine for applying protective size to yarn intended for warp
A wall cladding consisting of slates hung in overlapping rows.
A wall, usually perforated to allow free passage of air, supporting the ground-floor joists of a building.
A brace, running from a post to a principal, stiffening an interrupted tiebeam.
A joint with a loose tenon morticed into two touching pieces of timber
A machine tool similar in general appearance  to a shaping machine but in which the head or ram carrying the cutting tool moves in a vertical plane.
A machine for further attenuating a sliver of cotton after it has been through a draw frame.
A bay in a two storeyed house open to the roof to allow smoke to escape.
A framed fireplace hood built on a bressumer and extending from one outer wall to the other or to a spere.
A cleansing or separating machine used in a corn mill for removing smut from grain before it is ground.
The under surface of an arch, lintel or projecting architectural feature.
A first-floor chamber, often serving as a parlour, bedchamber or private room, in a medieval house. Also a loft, rood-loft or garret.
A horizontal member supporting the posts in a timber framed structure.
A short timber set across the top of a wall to take the foot of a rafter and an ashlar piece.
A straight brace from rafter to collar in a common rafter truss.
The quasi-triangular area between, and defined by, the upper sections of a pair of adjacent arches, or between the curve of an arch and the angle of a surrounding frame or structure.
A short timber set diagonally in the spandrel of an arch brace, between the brace and the corner of the main frame.
A general name given to a series of machines which successively reduce the diameter of rovings before  the final spinning into yarn.
A screen, with a wide central opening, or multiple narrower openings, spanning the lower end of a medieval hall, screening the cross entry and defining the screen, or cross, passage.
The structure across the lower end of a medieval hall containing the spere, its supporting posts and tie-beam.
A machine used for drawing out and twisting together short fibres to make a yarn or thread. Use more specific term where known.
A column whose shaft is scuplted to give it a contorted or twisted appearance, sometimes referred to as a barley-sugar column.
A decorative feature, usually Norman, in which fluting takes a spiral rather than vertical form.
A staircase, circular in plan, that winds around a central newel.
A tall, circular, polygonal or square structure rising from a roof, tower, turret etc., tapering to a slender point.
A small form of spire.
A building used in the Second World War to co-ordinate action against enemy air raids.
A roomspace within an abode which combines the specific functions of several of the more traditional roomspaces into a singular unified space.
Second World War defence work usually consisting of securinng points for a boom defence, associated gun, and searchlight, emplacements
Buildings and structures used to monitor the accuracy of bombs dropped on a bombing range
A centre used by the Territorial Army, the volunteer reserve of the British army.
A storage facility used for the accommodation and dispersal of military vehicles.
Beaches used for the departure of troops and equipment for the D-day landings.

Special concrete loading ramps nicknamed 'hards' had been constructed along river banks, beaches and inlets to enable organised embarkation onto various types of landing craft to take place, irrespective of tides.
Site or building constructed or adapted for indoor and/or outdoor leisure and sport activities, for example archery, team-building and "outward-bound" activities based on military training.
A structure, usually of earth and concrete, and usually, although not always, subterranean, designed for protection against explosives
Non-specific building type associated with an airfield.

Protective equipment, usually made of metal, to protect parts of the body, e.g. helmets, breastplates, or full suits of armour, to protect troops or individuals in warfare. Most examples date from the Middle Ages, obsolete from the 17th century.
The plant, Allium sativum, whose bulb is used for culinary purposes.
Vegetable matter decomposed in water and partially carbonized to form bogs, whence slabs are cut out to use as fuel.

An establishment used for the manufacture of reeds and healds, which are components of a textile loom with related functions, in that they move and control the threads, and similar wire-based construction.
An establishment used for the manufacture of jacquards and dobbys, which are textile loom components that control the weaving of complicated or figured patterns.
A calciner dating from the early 17th to early 20th centuries, usually made of brick and without moving parts, consisting of a reverberatory furnace, and used for the extraction of arsenic.
A device used to remove pollutants from gas or smoke produced during industrial processes such as burning high-sulphur fuels.
A calciner used in arsenic production from the 1820s to the 1950s featuring a distinctive, slowly rotating hearth.
Buildings and structures associated with the acquisition of electronic signals for the purpose of intelligence gathering.
A building housing computers and information technology equippment e.g. for a business, factory or other instituion.
A room where letters and parcels are sorted prior to dispatch
A factory or works which has been temporarily turned over to the manufacture of goods for the war effort.
School built by the local Education Authority to provide residental schooling at the seaside for children from urban communities.

A calciner commonly used between 1870 and circa 1900 for extracting arsenic from mined ores  and featuring a slightly inclined rotating iron tube with a firebox at the bottom and an ore feed at the top.
A site from which troops could be embarked onto transport vessels prior to the D-Day landings can also apply to muster/departure points from which troops embarked for their journey to the Front.

6 Type DFW 55373s placed in a 3X2 rectangular plan. Each projector was separated by 31-34m. Hardened personnel and ammunition shelters located midway between each projector, but ammunition stored outside the perimeter.
A site used by the Air Raid Precautions network. Use more specific term.
A seperate wing of a large house provide accommodation for guests.
A short or long term residential home for people not requiring medical intervention or nursing care, usually for older people.

A solid concrete or stone base on which a machine (often an engine and therefore called the engine bed, forming part of an engine house) was mounted to power an industrial process. Dates from the 19th century.
An apparatus used for the process of condensing: the conversion of vapour into a liquid.

Part of the WWII air defence radar system, whereby in 1939 a chain of radar stations were established along the south and east coast of Britain. The equipment was based upon apparatus developed for ionospheric research.
Use for unspecified musical instruments.
A raised platform or stage for public speaking or conducting an orchestra. Also a platform for supporting cameras during filming.
A flat-topped, often elongated, construction at which customers are served by staff in a commercial establishment such as a bank, shop, inn etc.
The lowest part, or base, of a structure, sometimes built into the ground, on which the weight of the whole rests.
A narrow timber board or moulding lining the base of an interior wall as a finish between it and and the floor.
A foreshore structure to prevent barges from sinking in the river mud. Made by placing chalk on fascines of brushwood, which is in some cases retained by a timber revetement.
A sports arena with a steeply banked oval track for bicycle racing. There are outdoor as well as indoor velodromes.
A pipe or channel to carry water outwards from a gutter or behind a parapet. If decorated with grotesque heads it is called a gargoyle.

A decorative feature of wood, plaster or carved masonry, often used in low relief on ceilings, panels or screens and resembling interlacing leather straps. Popular in the late 16th and early 17th centuries.
A moulded bar or baton dividing the panes of glass within a window light.
An enclosed area of land of varying size and shape which shows traces of defence.
A horizontal door within, and usually flush with surface of, a floor, ceiling or roof.
An inscription or illustration carved into the surface of a stone wall or other architectural element.
An inscription on illustration applied to a wall by carving into its plaster to reveal a different colour beneath.
A light porous acid volcanic rock used for scouring and, in powdered form, as an abrasive and for polishing. Also used to make lightweight concrete.
A demasted ship used exclusively for the storage of grain.
Objects designed to be played with, often a model or miniature replica of something and especially for a child.
Two-wheeled vehicles for personal transport with pedals for propulsion by the rider.
A light, usually encased and mounted upon brackets, often used outdoors.  It may be powered by gas, electricity or house a candle.
A hollow, cylindrical structure or tube made of clay, lead, steel, wood etc. through which gas, oil, water or other liquids can be conveyed.
A large structure, usually associated with power stations, in which hot water undergoes a process of cooling before being re-used .
A metallic rod attached to a high point on a building and leading to the earth for the purpose of conducting lightning away from the main body of the building.
A pedestrian passageway, often elevated, connecting two buildings or sections within a building.
A vessel, purpose-built or requisitioned, used for patrolling inland or coastal waters, e.g. Coastguard and Customs vessels.
A framework of crossed or parallel wooden or metal bars placed over an opening to prevent access but allow the passage of air, light, water etc.

A panel, board or device bearing an inscription, symbol or image, usually describing a function, name, location, instruction, or otherwise distinguishing the object or structure on which it is placed.
A position or place that allows a wide or favourable overall view of a scene or situation.
A cutting, bank or block positioned against the wall of a trench, fort, parapet etc. to allow riflemen to shoot over the crest of the wall or parapet from a standing position.
A subsidiary tower or projection attached to the front of a keep containing access to its first floor entrance.
Term applied to both the pit trap itself, and the walled enclosure containing pit trap(s).
A firing step from which standing defenders could fire over the crest of a high parapet.

Standard dwelling of the non-ruling classes of Japan until the mid twentieth century. Minkas are timber-framed houses with mud-plastered panels and thatched roofs. The design varies from region to region. Minkas served as home as well as workplace.
Cut human hair, usually intended for wig-making.
Mark 10 or the tenth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Mark 11 or the eleventh variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
A disc-shaped plate brooch.
An enamelled plate brooch, dating from the second and third centuries AD, depicting an animal often with religious significance, such as hares, birds, fish and horses, sometimes with rider.

Imported Roman brooch with a wide, highly arched flat backed bow, one end rolled forward onto the head to form a hinge for the the pin. Named for the head inscription assumed to be a maker's name. Dated to first half of 1st entury AD.
A Roman brooch dating from approximately 50 to 150 AD. Derived from the earlier Aesica Brooch, and fitted with a hinged pin, the body widens to a triangular plate below the bow.
Anglo-Saxon two-piece bow brooch, dating from the 8th to 9th centuries AD, so named for the distinctive bow shaped like the arching body of a caterpillar.

A first century AD one-piece bow brooch, one end of which is drawn out to form a spring and pin, characterized by its long, narrow, tapering bow, a small crossbar in front of the spring and a forward hook which holds the spring chord.

Roman bow brooch, dating from the third to fifth centuries AD, with a P-shaped profile and a characteristic crossbar, often adorned with knobs at its end and on the head. Shown in contemporary illustrations as being worn by high ranking males.
An Anglo-Saxon brooch type dating from the 5th to 7th centuries AD and influenced by the Crossbow brooch, featuring a sprung pin and a head plate.
An Anglo-Saxon cruciform Long Brooch, often ornamented with knobs across and terminating its crossbar and head, and frequently with its foot shaped into a zoomorphic motif.

Roman, mid-1st century AD two-piece Bow Brooch, derived from the Colchester Brooch, with a winged, transverse head  protecting a spring mechanism held by a rear facing hook over the chord, its profile evoking a leaping dolphin.

Roman mid-first to third century AD S or reverse-S shaped brooch. Often enamelled, with its central section expanded for decoration, the brooch depicted stylised creatures derived from Celtic art. The pin was looped over the neck of the brooch.
A two-piece Bow Brooch, derived from the Colchester Brooch, dating from the later first and second centuries AD and so called due to the decorative stud on the upper bow.

Roman, mid to late 1st century, hinged  Bow Brooch, related to the Aucissa Brooch, with side knobs on the upper bow, the curvature of which is confined to the brooch's top half, the lower half being straight. Frequently tinned to give a silver appearance.
A Roman Bow Brooch dating from the mid-second to mid-third centuries AD, characterized by the pronounced curvature of the bow, resembling a knee. Usually used by military personnel.

A two-piece Bow Brooch dating from the early to mid-first century AD in Britain, originating in Gaul. Featuring a wide flat reeded bow, this and the Thistle Brroch were the first to conceal the spring mechanism with a cylindrical or semi-cylindrical hood.
A simple, one-piece Bow Brooch with a spring of four coils, sometimes  less, its chord tucked beneath its head and variations to bow and catchplate. Dating from the first century AD.

An Anglo-Saxon disc brooch featuring an upturned rim. Usually decorated with zoomorphic or geometric designs either chip-carved directly on the face or applied to a thin bronze plate affixed to the brooch's floor.

A highly decorated Anglo-Saxon Long Brooch, often made of silver or bronze, worn by women. Contemporary with the Cruciform Brooch, it features a large, square head plate and usually three rounded foot-terminals.

Early to mid-1st century AD Bow Brooch with a P-shaped profile, a cylindrical or semi-cylindrical spring cover and a round or lozenge-shaped centre plate with a short bow above and a flat leg below, both of which are reeded like the Langton Down Brooch.

A Roman Bow Brooch, dating from the later 1st and 2nd centuries often worn in pairs with a linking chain. Characterized by its distinctive head, sometimes enamelled, and resembling the mouth of a trumpet.
A Mark 6B aircraft which has undergone further modifications to enhance performance or armament.
One of a pack, or deck, of cards used to play games, each distinguished from the others by markings on its face.
A case or border, usually wood or metal, enclosing a picture, painting or photograph.
A Mark 1E aircraft which has undergone further modifications to enhance performance or armament.
Mark 12 or the twelfth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
A structure, often sunk into the ground, for the purpose of allowing total bodily immersion in mineral sprinwater or similarly beneficial substances.
Mark 14 or the fourteenth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Mark 7 or the seventh variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Mark 4 or the fourth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Room within a building or complex used by a porter.
Room in a building or complex in which the master of an establishment, such as a workhouse or a school, is accommodated.

A nineteenth century stone calciner, similar to a lime kiln, used for extracting arsenic from mined ores, consisting of a solid structure with a central shaft and a drawing-hole at the base for calciner waste.
An industrial building, plant or site where crude substances, such as sugar, metal, oil etc., are purified or refined.
A marine survey in which a multi-element transducer provides many (30-150) individual soundings of the water depth and echo strength for each ping.
An establishment used to serve ice cream to the general public.
A building from which the firing of torpedoes can be controlled and evaluated.
A prepared area of ground, featuring a 'mini' golf course with obstacles, used to undertake the leisure pursuit of miniature golf or 'crazy golf'. Often popular at seaside resorts.
Site used for the maintenance of aircraft.
A building, usually housing electrical or electronic equipment, used for gathering and disseminating information. Use specific type where known.
Partly subterranean operations rooms for the lighting arrays of the various types of bombing decoys in use during the Second World War.

A building, often with underground rooms, used to receive all reports of aircraft locations, to assimilate and assess this information in order to provide the most accurate possible picture to the Operations Room of a fighter or bomber Group.
Bed coverings, usually of woollen or similar natural or artificial fabrics.
An observation tower is a structure used to provide panoramic views of the surrounding area. They are often used as attractions at seaside resorts e.g. Blackpool Tower.
A site equipped for passive or active defence against an airborne enemy assault.
A site equipped for active defensive action against an airborne enemy assault.
Sites, buildings or structures involved in passive air defence, usually by forcing hostile aircraft to fly high or drop their bombs on the wrong targets. Use more specific term.
A site comprising a system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used during WWII to provide a counterfeit target for enemy aircraft. Use more specific type where known.
A large vessel, sometimes large enough to accomodate several gallons, often made of leather and richly decorated, for storing and serving liquor.

Sites used for the accommodation, welfare and recreation of servicemen, especially those serving in the Royal Air Force. Use only for sites associated with military installations. For non-military sites use DOMESTIC class and its narrower terms.
A type of light fixture affixed to a wall in such a way that it uses only the wall for support, and the light is usually directed upwards.
A building or room where nets are made
Paper, often decorated with a printed pattern, painted or embossed design, and usually provided in rolls and used to line the interior walls of a building for decorative purposes.
Construction works for the production of rigid or dirigible airships.
A kiln principally used in brick making which gives a continuous operation.
Accommodation and facilities for aircrew away from the main RAF airfield.
A quoin, usually of stone, with a concave rebate at one corner forming the surface against which the rounded edge of a canal lock gate turns, making a kind of hinge.
A room used for the ritual cleaning of the body prior to burial
A large tract of land covered with trees and interspersed with open areas of land. Traditionally forests were owned by the monarchy and had their own laws.
An arrangement of railway tracks, stations and other buildings that together form a railway transport system.
A plug to keep out dust, moisture etc.
An area of a building or complex specifically housing the kitchens, sculleries and services.
A well with a superstructure, either partially or wholly enclosed with an access door, designed to protect the water source.
An open area of prepared ground used for practising putting with golf clubs.
A low lying area of land that is usually waterlogged at all times and is flooded in wet weather.
A field covered with herbage for the grazing of livestock.
A site used for the manufacturing of steel. Use more specific type where known.
A strategically placed aperture in the wall of a fortification through which guns and cannon can fire upon an invading force.
A structure, part of a structure or area consisting of plain masonry.
A route across a river, or lake. Use only for small inland ferries and index with LANDING POINT/STAGE/STEPS or PIER where known.
17th century Dutch vessel built for naval or East India service, with a relatively flat bottom and narrow hull; sometimes rendered into English as `fly-boat'.
A form of thatching straw composed of stems that have been combed mechanically to remove grain and extraneous waste material without crushing the stem.
An enclosed, defensible passageway, equipped with gun ports, extending into or traversing a dry ditch.
A fixed seat, often enclosed, usually found within an ecclesiastical building and frequently arranged in series to accomodate a congregation, choir or clergy.
Room in a building or complex, such as a workhouse, in which work is carried out.
A room in which domestic appliances and facilities for cleaning are stored.
A pavilion ward in a workhouse, used to accommodate inmates
A room within a building or complex, such as a workhouse, used for purifying objects with smoke.
A room within a building or complex used for storing clothing.
A photo- reconnaissance variant of the Boeing Superfortress, used from 1944, initally deployed in the Pacific war, later for Cold war duties over Europe.
The fine, keratinized, flexible filaments that grow from follicles beneath the surface of the skin in mammals.
A part of a building or complex where administrative duties are undertaken.
An area or wing of a hexagonal plan workhouse or prison from where the supervision of the inmates is carried out.
Mark 16 or the sixteenth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
An umbrella-shaped pavilion, Indian in origin, constructed over a funerary site. Can also refer to a funerary monument or cenotaph constructed in this style.
A ward in a workhouse for vagrants
A ward for receiving new paupers upon entry to a workhouse. They had to remain there until checked by medical officer.
A depression in the ground caused by the impact of a falling object, such as a crashed aircraft.
A building forming part of a complex or larger establishment, such as a workhouse, that serves as an entrance equipped with facilities associated with procedures undergone by new arrivals.
An area of a building functioning as a hospital.
A Mark 3 aircraft which has undergone slight modifications to enhance performance or armament.
Garden associated with a crematorium where the ashes of the deceased are scattered or buried.
US Navy version of the four-engined, six-crew B24 heavy bomber. Modified for long-range reconnaissance duty and used as a patrol-bomber against shipping and submarines.
A Mark 2 aircraft which has undergone slight modifications to enhance performance or armament.
A tank used for the storage of water, usually found as part of an institution like a workhouse or hospital complex
Residence for retired people, often in the form of an apartment complex, differing from a nursing home as the residents live independently.
Housing provided for refugees. Similar to refugee camp but with the reuse of existing buildings rather than a temporary camp.
Carved stones used for marking a grave.
Intended for personal decoration, objects made of precious, semi-precious or imitation metals and gemstones.
Coastal base for the docking, launch and maintenance of submarines.

A single engine two seat cabin monoplane tourer, first flown in 1933 as a successor to the Puss Moth. Impressed into military sevice in WWII by the RAF and the Fleet Air Arm as a liaison and communications aircraft, also used by training units.
Plaster which has been painted either for decorative purposes or to protect it.
A tall, hollow pipe, usually cast-iron, resembling a lamp-post. Used to ventilate sewer systems.
An archaeological unit of soil in a horizontal plane which may seal features or be cut through by other features.

Type of furnace used in the glass industry to pre-heat glass in crucibles, prior to the main melt. This may have been a separtate structure, or may have been part of the main furnace. All periods from the Roman onwards.
The position of a fire in a wood-fuelled furnace. All periods from the Iron Age  to the 17th century.

In the glass industry, a furnace of Lorraine Type, comprising a central rectangular melting furnace with ancillary structures at each corner, adjacent to the fires. Post-Mediaeval until superceded by coal-fired furnaces.
In the glass industry this is bench-like structure within the melting-furnace on which crucibles are placed.

This is a pit used in the glass industry for the production of cylinder glass. The only surviving examle in England is at the Hartley Wood Glasworks, Sunderland. It is a feature of 19th century and later glassworks
A building or site used to assess the mechanical state of a vehicle.
An area of a site or building providing a stable base for the firing of artillery pieces.
A vehicle or aircraft placed at the entrance to a site as a symbolic guardian.
Mark 6 or the sixth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
A Mark 2A aircraft which has undergone slight modifications to enhance performance or armament.

A bomber designed to operate with medium bombloads over medium distances.The medium bomber was generally considered to be any design that delivered about 4,000 lb (1.8 t) over ranges of about 1,500 to 2,000 miles (2,400 to 3,200 km).
A shop housing the business of a grindery dealer. Grindery are the tools and materials used by shoemakers and other leather-workers.
A track of two parallel ruts deliberately cut in the ground or living rock for the guidance of two-wheeled carts when the way was obscured by darkness or water.
A site where cementstone nodules are extracted under ground.
A site where cementstone nodules are extracted.

Single-engine, two or three-crew pre-World War 2 biplane fighter and general purpose aircraft. First flown in 1931, the Seal was a Naval variant on the Fairey Gordon and a forerunner of the Swordfish.
An aircraft used to facilitate communications, for example in a military context.
An area of a building or complex, such as a workhouse or hospital, for isolating new residents before admission into main building, used to prevent spread of disease
Use VAGRANTS WARD as it is meant to shelter wandering vagrants overnight rather than the permanent inhabitants of a workhouse.
Three-seat, single engine, high wing braced monoplane designed for civil use and first flown in 1929. Saw military service in World War 2 in an Army co-operation and communications role.
Part of textile mills.
A site or factory where waste slag from ironworking if further processed for use in manufacturing.
An area of a building or complex, such as a workhouse, hospital or prison used to house infirm inmates suffering from fever.
A building providing business premises to companies or individuals, sometimes for short periods, in exchange for a membership fee.

Bow Brooch derived from the Colchester type in the mid to late 1st and 2nd centuries AD. Typically the spring is held in a semi-cylindrical crossbar with closed ends and holding the axial bar and a hook or lug on the head to hold the chord.

1st or 2nd century Bow Brooch derived from the Colchester. It typically has a pin hinged on a bar held in a cylindrical crossbar, the bow tapering and commonly decorated. Developed examples often have a headloop and enamelled panels.

Derived from the Colchester in the mid to late 1st century, particularly in south and east Britain. Characterized by the attachment of the separate spring and pin through two holes in a lug behind the head, which projects to form a crest atop the bow.
A mid-1st century AD brooch influenced by the Thistle type, commonly with projections on the upper bow and widening to a triangular plate, often described as a fantail, below.
A small, often of about two inches or less in length, version of the Long Brooch usually made of less expensive materials than other brooch types and frequently worn in pairs.
The official residence of an abbot.
A cupboard set into the eastern wall of a synagogue, facing Jerusalem. The Torah scrolls are kept in the Ark.

An offshore station, equipped with a fixed electronic radio navigation and positioning system such as Hyperfix. The transmission principle are pulsed and phase comparisons systems. Superceded by Global Positioning System in 1994.
A piece of forest land converted into arable.
An aircraft equipped to deploy explosive mines.
Buildings and structures associated with the processing and storage of natural gas.
A concealed passage or room for the purpose of hiding and protecting a (Roman Catholic) priest during times of religious persecution.
A boat, ship or other vessel either whole or in part. Watercraft often survive as commemorative monuments or have been reused as floating restaurants, museums, hotels etc.
An area off the coast where ships anchor.
A boiling vessel used in the direct boiling process, or the sleeching process, used for the manufacture of salt. For evaporating features associated with SOLAR and PARTIAL SOLAR sites use SALT POND.
A panel of often decorated wrought-ironwork forming the arch between two gate-piers or standards or above a gate. Also used for an arched support for a lamp-holder between two standards.
A piece of animal bone roughly shaped with grooves in which pins are laid and held whilst being sharpened.
A depot or warehouse for the storage, distribution and repair of shoe making machines.
A 19th century structure of various shape or material for the protection of troops in an emergency.

A World War One German three-crew, twin-engined, long range heavy bomber biplane manufactured by Gothaer Waggonfabrik A.G..  Entering service in 1917, this aircraft incorporated a ventral tunnel allowing the gunner to shoot downwards and to the rear.
An arcaded upper aisle, wall passage or blind arcade, usually occurring in large Romanesque or Gothic churches, above the aisle and below the clerestory.
Gothauer Waggonfabrik A.G., based in Gotha, Thuringia (Germany). During World War 2 produced mostly training and light commercial aircraft and troop and freight-carrying gliders.
A type of large steel framed aircraft hangar introduced by the Royal Air Force in its Expansion Period with a number of designs between 1934 and 1939, to accomodate heavy bombers.
A place for sharpening metal objects like tools and weapons.
Use Grinding House for a place material is crushed and Grindery for a place where metal objects are sharpened.
A place where two artificial waterways meet each other.
Site associated with the testing of nuclear material or its containers.
A building or site used for the production of frameworks of beds.
A site which has produced evidence of in situ production of items derived from antler.
A trench dug in order to receive the foundations of a structure such as a stone wall etc.
A pit filled with rubble, etc., into which rain or waste water flows in order to disperse into the surrounding soil.

A type of temporary military aircraft hangar introduced in 1940; of steel welded and bolted construction typically clad in galvanized corrugated iron sheets. The T2 became the standard temporary hangar for the RAF in World War Two.

A type of military building associated with military airfields, where air crews were briefed for missions. The room could be a seperate building or part of an operations block and are built of varying types of temporary brick or nissen hut constructions.
A chamber attached to the sewer of a building to facilitate the removal of any blockage.
A wheeled device supporting a windmill's fantail that moves around a trackway thus turning the windmill into the wind.
A slaughterhouse for horses.

A type of transportable aircraft hangar patented by Miskins and Sons in 1939. The arched hangar was constructed of steel or wooden ribs and generally clad in steel sheets. The hangar did not require any foundations and could be anchored by iron stakes.
A mechanism within a windmill, attached to the striking rod, allowing the opening and closing of the shutters or vanes of patent sails.

A large type of military repair hangar mainly used on WWII bomber bases, constructed using steel stanchions and clad in corrugated iron. B 1 hangars were part of a series of prefabricated buildings intended to supplement existing hangars on bases.
A building of varying designs intended for directing military aviation operations. Normally associated with military airfields.
A four-armed metal coupling, positioned at the centre of a windmill's sails,  connected to the front of the striking rod and the shutter bars of all the sails, causing the shutters to open and close.
A functioning clock designed to serve also as an ornamental feature or sculpture.
A fighter-bomber designed to deploy its bombs during the latter stage of a diving manoeuvre, thus increasing the accuracy of its targetting.
A prefrabicated home sited in parks where a pitch fee is charged. Although technically mobile they usually only make one journey before being permanently installed.
An aircraft engaged in rescuing persons in danger at sea.

Any form of arms or ammunition whether from a formal organized military context or as a general cargo. Use specific terms - e.g. swords, bombs, where known; otherwise use this term primarily in contexts where the arms are unspecified or ancient.

Any unspecified items without utility or function and prized for personal or domestic decorative value. Examples might be unspecified metal objects from the Bronze Age or Victorian Staffordshire china dogs.
An alloy, principally of copper or tin, but which may also include zinc and/or lead.
Instruments for determining position at sea, e.g. compasses, sextants.
Holders for one or more candles, usually of metal or pewter.
Use most appropriate term.
Use most appropriate term where known.
Man made structure, usually sub-terranean, built to contain water for the purpose of immersion of people for sport and leisure.
Man made shallow pool, usually made for children to play in rather than swim.
Manmade feature to contain water for the purpose of floating miniature boats in it. Different to BOATING LAKE as lake can be naturally occuring park feature and can be used for full sized boats.
Man made structure to contain tidal waters, often part of a LIDO, bathing or swimming complex at the sea edge.
A swimmin pool restricted to the use of men only.
A swimming pool restricted to the use of females only.
An open floor surface for dancing.
Swimming pool, usually part of a larger LIDO or SPORTS CENTRE complex. Medium size pool, between large pool and paddling pool, used primarily for learners.

A unenclosed feature, usually sub-terranean, constructed to contain water for public or private recreation and sporting activities. Sometimes part of a LIDO complex. Use INDOOR SWIMMING POOL for pools within a covering structure.

An unenclosed feature, usually sub-terranean, constructed to contain water for public or private recreation and sporting avtivities. Sometimes part of a LIDO complex. Use INDOOR SWIMMING POOL for pools with a covering structure.

An enclosed feature, usually sub-terranean, constructed to contain water for public or private recreation and sporting activities. Often a component of a larger SPORTS CENTRE. Use OUTDOOR SWIMMING POOL for unenclosed pools.

An enclosed feature, usually sub-terranean, constructed to contain water for public or private recreation and sporting activities. Often part of a larger SPORTS CENTRE. Use OUTDOOR SWIMMING POOL for unenclosed pools.
A priest's private entrance into a church, usually found on the south side of the chancel.
A club where predominantly rhythm and blues style music is played, analagous to a jazz club.
A venue, with a boxing ring and associated facilities, which is used to train for and undertake amateur or professional boxing.
A small transportable hangar built by the Teesdie Bridge and Engineering Company. Mainly used on RNAS airfields for folding wing aircraft.
Similar in design to the FROMSON HANGAR but designed to drawing number 3752/43 and used for storing aircraft with small wingspans.
A plastic covered tunnel designed to protect vulnerable plants from the weather and allow vegetables to be grown out of season
Similar in design to the Callender Hangar but with a reduced height of 17ft. Built to Air Ministry drawing number 17346/40.

A cable repeater station for the undersea telephone and telegraph cables. Repeater stations compensated for the inadequacies of 1920's and 30's equipment over long distances, by repeating the signal every 200 miles.
A building or complex in which visitors to a prison can meet with the inmates under the supervision of the prison staff.
A two-storey watch office similar in design to drawing number 1959/34 but constructed completely from concrete. A large, almost square, ground plan with a central observation tower.
A hospital which has been built either wholly, or partially, underground in order to protect it from attacks by enemy aircraft.

A secure, bomb-proof, undergound complex designed to be used by the government in the event of a national emergency such as nuclear war. Usually equipped with communications equipment, emergency rations and water and air filtering plants.
A radio station set up to broadcast signals aimed at 'bending' or altering German navigation transmissions

A curved military aircraft hangar produced in 1939. The frame is steel which is then clad with steel sheeting and reinforced concrete and typically covered with a thin layer of concrete, earth and turf.
Tyne and Wear

The first transportable aircraft hangar developed by the RFC/RAF, which comprised a kit of timber and canvas that could be assembled in 48 hours. The canvas doors open one end only. Also known as Type H hangar.
Scotland
Argyll and Bute

A mill for the processes of grinding, balling, couching, drying and packing of woad. The mill can be demountable, enabling it being located close to the fields, as woad crop has to be rotated and move to new fields as soon as the ground is exhausted.
Site where fossils where mined for use as artificial fertilizer. Use both terms
Saxon rectangular burial chamber comprising a large sunken 'room' lined with wood. 6th and 7th century AD.
A surface interpreted as a buried cultivation layer, for example an agriculturally cultivated field.
A steel framed transportable hangar similar in construction to Type T2 but about half the size. Designed in 1941 and 1942.
A light porous cellular rock, consisting of consolidated volcanic ash ejected from vents during a volcanic eruption.
A mixed earthy substance consisting principally of clay mixed with calcium carbonate and sand in very variable proportions.
A widening in a canal to allow boats to turn around.

Accommodation given rent-free along with or as part of a corrody, which is a provision of an annual allowance of food and money by a religious house to an individual, usually in return for service or by purchase. Term used until mid 16th century AD.
A monument consisting of an area enclosed by a ditch, bank, wall, palisade or similar barrier, where the barrier follows an almost rectangular course.
Tyne and Wear
Northumberland
A vault with a ceiling or undersurface subdivided by ribs into bays or webs.

A six oared rowing boat which originated in Cornwall in the 18th century. Originally used as a pilot vessel, useage adapted to include cargo vessel and lifeboat. Today gigs are used in sporting events.
Scotland

Medieval Fenland ditched field system where the land is divided into strips for agricultural production. The strips are separated by hand-dug wide shallow drainage ditches with the spoil thrown up to create a dryer ridge.
Term used in particular in Lincolnshire instead of Darland Field System.
An inhumation burial in which the corpse is laid on a wooden bed, often surrounded by a collection of grave-goods. Anglo-Saxon rite of 7th century AD.
An area of agriculturally used land, which is divided into small, elongated, rectangular fields running parallel to each other.
A small concrete turret placed on top of a standard 4 ft. diameter concrete pipe sunk into the ground. Intended for use in defending road junctions, airfields and beach exits.
The limit line of an area pertaining to a medieval manor.
The limit line of a medieval local administrative unit of a hundred.

A type of aircraft hangar from the closing years of WWI either of steel or wood utilising a type of lattice work roof support known as a Belfast Truss, which features diagonally interlaced pieces of thin pine. The roof appears as a smooth curve.
A climbing plant (Rubia tinctorum) which was formerly cultivated for the reddish-purple dye obtained from the roots.

A modern building system in which both steel and concrete are utilized together to carry the load in ways that neither material predominates over the other. There are many varieties e. g. a steel frame surrounding a concrete core.
Netherlands
A railway yard with associated buildings used for the maintenance and storage of locomotive engines and rolling stock.
A reservoir or tank used to hold a supply of water for fire-fighting purposes in the event of the main supply being damaged or cut off.
The principal longitudinal member or spine of a windmill sail, extending from the stock and supporting the sailbars.

A type of steel framed transportable British military aircraft hangar developed from 1941onwards. The hangar had a steel frame, some versions used commercially available sheeting for cladding. It was similar to but smaller than the arcraft hangar type T2.
Twin-engined, four-crew German seaplane. Entered service in 1932 as a torpedo bomber and naval reconnaisance aircraft, though by World War 2 those still serving were used mainly for air sea rescue.
Essex
East Friesian Islands, Germany
Germany
Zeeland

A building that houses material that can be used to facilitate the study of a site, landscape or an historical event/period. Such centres are often found in close proximity to the sites and/or landscapes that they seek to encourage the study of.
A type of temporary transportable aircraft hangar designed in 1936 by N.S. Bellman. It was designed for ease of installation, and was composed of light rolled steel sections.
A building used for a variety of administrative purposes, usually at a naval dockyard.
A camp where people who fled from danger or problem whithin their country or across international borders and who are in need of international protection are temporarily placed.
A camp for the temporary accommodation of uprooted civilians or foreign ex-service personnel, who had fought for the British forces during WWII (e.g.Polish).

A circular or octagonal building at the base of a post mill to provide storage space and to give protection to the superstructure. The roundhouse is not attached to the mill itself. Some roundhouses were later converted for domestic purposes.

A permanent military RAF aircraft hangar type, designed in 1924. It features a steel frame (with longitudinal ridge and valley trusses for the roof) reinforced concrete and brick infilling for the walls. Typically 122 foot span by 249 foot in length.
North Carolina, USA
North Carolina, USA

The earliest side-opening standard type of aircraft hangar designed in 1913 and used in WWI. Originally constructed from wooden trusses and struts, some examples have steel frames. It comprised a single or coupled shed with rear workshops.
Northumberland
North Carolina
Early name for aircraft hangar (up until around 1940), when the term hangar was only used for a tent construction.
Early name for aircraft hangar (ca. up until 1940), when the term hangar was only used for a tent construction.
A place where dead animals are buried.
A pit where calcium oxide (Quicklime) has been hydrated to produce calcium hydroxide, known as slaked lime.

The earliest side-opening standard type of aircraft hangar designed in 1913 and used in WWI. Originally constructed from wooden trusses and struts, one example has steel frames. It comprised a single or coupled shed with rear workshops.
A mill where china stone is grinded.
A building or buildings used for the manufacture of crucibles.

A large steelframed military aircraft hangar designed in 1939, intended for aircraft maintenance on operational stations. It includes side annexes for workshops and offices, provided with a large number of windows. The annexes are of brick or concrete.
Hut along the coast, which provided shelter for lookouts known as "huers", who kept watch for the pilchard shoals that passed by the coast. Built of stone or wood. Particular common to Cornwall.
A wall structure built to direct a current into the desired channel in a harbour, river etc.
A site where iron oxide and iron sulphate is extracted.
Dutch galliot-rigged vessel used mostly for river trade in Holland but sometimes also for coasting or short sea-going voyages

Building block (often a temporary brick structure or Nissen hut) comprising office accommodation for flight commanders and flight sergeants as well as pilots' rest rooms, storerooms and locker rooms. Some flight offices have central corridors.
An area, with fixed defences, designed to act as a focal point for a defending force.
Sites, buildings and structures associated with the prevention of an invasion by a hostile force.
A designated area, usually sited at a strategic crossroads, with fixed defences such as pillboxes, anti tank ditches and gun emplacements, designed to act as a rallying point for defenders.
A pair of cannon balls joined by a solid bar.
A fortified river or river bank forming part of the anti invasion infrastructure.
A pair of cannon balls joined by a chain.
Cube-shaped shot.
A type of chain shot characterized by a number of chains attached to the main shot, causing maximum damage. Sometimes known as a Spider shot.
A number of small iron balls, each about the size of a cricket ball, often numbering nine, wired together and bound in a canvas bag.
A solid, spherical projectile, originally made of stone but later iron.
A fitting of unknown function. Use more specific type where known.
Pieces of undressed stone, waste fragments of stone or fragments of slate.
Waste resulting from the processes associated with the making of shoes.
waste resulting from the working of wood or associated with a carpenter's workshop.
An unhewn piece of felled tree, or similar rough mass of wood.
A drinking vessel, made of glass, designed expressly to be used for the consumption of wine.
A ring, flange or short piece of pipe, made of iron, clay or other materials, used to join and seal two sections of water pipe.
The remains of a shell of a mussel.
Use for ticks and true mites. Related to spiders, mites are widely present in archaeological deposits but are rarely studies in detail as they can prove difficult to identify.

Use for the remains of internal parasites of vertebrates, including humans, such as flukes, tapeworm, including their calcified cysts, etc. Eggs of the nematodes Ascaris sp. (maw-worm) and Trichuris sp. (whipworm) are commonly reported.
Group of fresh water crustaceans which include the water fleas (Daphnia ssp.) the egg cases (ephippia) of which are found in archaeological deposits.
Small crustaceans ranging in size from 0.2mm to 30mm and possessing a bivalve carapace or 'shell'.
Molluscs found in salt or brackish water. Use more specific term where known.
Molluscs found in fresh water or terrestrial habitats. Use more specific term where known.
Mark 8 or the eighth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Use for Insectivores (hedgehogs, shrews, moles), Chiroptera (bats) and rodents (squirrels, rats, voles, mice, dormice).
Microscopic living things, usually unicellular, occasionally multi-cellular. They lack cell nuclei.
Algae usually found as a silica skeleton. They obtain their food by photosynthesis and are used in ecological reconstruction.

Simple organisms, mostly single celled, that move by means of two flagella (complex cellular projections). Most live as marine plankton, but some occur in fresh water. Members of the Kingdom Protista.

Single celled marine organisms. Some form calcareous tests (shells). They are used archaeologically to study the nature of marine environments or establish the presence of marine conditions or products (e.g. imported seaweed).
Kingdom of living things, lacking chlorophyll, that obtain their food from organic matter, usually by absorption. They include mushrooms, moulds and yeasts.
A metal, shankless bit, with a ring on either side used to control an animal (usually a horse) by exerting direct pressure on the  tongue, lips and the side of the mouth.
20th century plant for separating minerals using variations in water-repellent properties under controlled chemical conditions. Survives as ruins of buildings or tanks.
18th-19th century stone-lined pit which held the balance bob for a pump-rod or flat-rod system. It includes examples where the surviving feature is a pillar for the bearing, rather than the pit.
Residues from ore-processing operations; intact tips and deposits may preserve considerable evidence on the processes used. A high rpoportion have been destroyed by reprocessing.
A piece of openwork fabric made from twine or cord, either natural fibre or artificial, forming a mesh used for catching birds, animals or fish or for holding other inanimate objects.
A linear open working along a lode vein, worked directy from the surface. Survives as a gully or ravine, normally with closed ends.
Factory producing asbestos sheeting and or asbestos fibre.
A covered passageway projecting into or across a ditch of a fortified place to provide flanking fire to the ditch in which it stands or for the purpose of sheltering communication with outworks.

A signalling structure used on WWII airfields, comprising a concrete square base with a kerbed border into which concrete signal symbols could be placed to advise pilots in the air of current airfield state e.g. directions of landing and airfield circuit.
Large concrete letters representing the ground-to-air airfield code. It has been used to show pilots in WWII the name of the airfield they were above e.g. DW for Dunkeswell.

An airfield building housing a turret gunnery trainer used to teach air gunners how to report the correct position of enemy aircraft by practising shooting against projected moving images of enemy aircraft displayed on a target screen (WWII).
Building or buildings housing  equipment for generating heat for a building complex.
An aircraft maintenance workshop deriving from the use of  weather proofing varnish to aircraft canvas called "dope" in order to keep the canvas taut and airtight. From 1912 onwards.
North Yorkshire
South Yorkshire
England

A large circular defence work surrounded by a brick revetted ditch and sunken below a glacis. Usually built out of brick with the embrasures lined with granite blocks. Armed with ten or elven guns. Early 19th century as part of coastline defence.
A housing estate comprised of housing stock owned and let by a local authority.
A room, usually at ground level or below, housing the tank in which water is heated as part of a building's heating system.
A building housing machinery for crushing chalk for whiting. Whiting was used in toothpaste, paint, tablets, putty and other products.
A ground used for the performance testing of motor vehicles, for example prototype vehicles.
A defence work, either a detached fieldwork or an outwork built as part of a fortification as a last defensive position.
A room within a building, such as a shop or leisure complex,sometimes equipped with cubicles or screens to allow a degree of privacy, where clothing can be tried on or changed.

In fortification, a detached triangular outwork consisting of two battered faces forming a salient angle. Usually positioned in the ditch in front of a rampart and between two bastions. Term mainly for military architecture from 15th century and later.
Use for the remains of a cargo which have been accidentally lost at sea, or purposefully dumped, and which consist the only physical evidence of a vessel.
An open grating of wrought iron, bronze, wood etc., forming a screen to a door, window or other opening, or used as a divider.
West Yorkshire
A building housing washing facilities and toilets. The term occurs mainly in a military context.

Buildings used for the accommodation, welfare and recreation of servicemen, especially those serving in the Royal Air Force. Use only for buildings associated with military installations. For non-military, use DOMESTIC class and its narrower terms.
Kent
Kent

A land based installation armed with wire -guided and powered  "Brennan torpedoes" which were in operation beween 1890 and 1906. These torpedoes were invented by Louis Philip Brennan. The stations were used to defend the coast from enemy shipping.
A building housing material used to explain the significance of a site or landscape to the public e. g. an archaeological site or nature reserve.
A type of 1930s civillian aircraft hangar comprising a large gabled building  with a mild steel structure and asbestos cladding.
A recess, usually situated in the north wall of a chancel,  often canopied, containing a decorated tomb chest representing the burial and resurrection of Christ.
West Yorkshire
A defensive construction situated in the sea, designed to protect the land from seabourne attack. The term applies mainly to those monuments built from around 1860 onwards.

A building or part of a building, sometimes attached to a religious community, where religious activities such as worshipping, meetings, teaching about the faith and conferences take place. It can also provide accommodation.
A Saxon quoin consisting of alternating horizontally and vertically laid stones.
A component of a salt works housing iron pans where the brine was evaporated above a furnace and flue. Such houses were lightly built in order to allow the heat and steam to escape.
An open roofed structure on which climbing plants are grown in order to provide a shaded walkway or seating area.

Satellite craft belonging to a larger vessel, usually a rowing vessel; used to pick up or set down passengers or crew when lying offshore, or stowed on board as the "long boat" or "jolly boat" for lifesaving purposes.
A room or rooms containing fitness equipment such as running machines and weights.
Manmade structure that contains water that is heated to a high temperature and sometimes has bubbling air jets. Meant to be used for therapeudic purposes.
A room, usually lined with wood panels, that is heated to a hot and steamy temperature using a small stove and intended to be used for relaxation and therapeutic purposes.
Obstacles, including scaffolding and anti tank blocks designed to impede an enemy's attempts to land forces onto open beaches.
A structure used for the secure storage of bicycles.
Metal knives, forks and spoons, carried either as an export cargo or for crew and/or passengers.
Tableware manufactured from any kind of ceramic and either carried as an export cargo or for the benefit of crew and/or passengers on board ship.
French warship broadly equivalent to the English 4th to 6th Rates, with as few as 4 to as many as 50 guns.
Preparations for beautifying or enhancing the body, face, hair or skin, e.g. creams, and coloured "make-up" items, e.g. rouge, lipstick, etc.

Transport vessel used for the repatriation of wounded troops, particularly during the First World War. Loosely described as "hospital ships", these ships were distinct from hospital ships proper by being defensively armed.

A loom developed by Joseph Jacquard in 1801 which used a series of punched cards to control the movement of the warp threads thereby allowing complex patterns to be created without the intervention of the weaver
A place where a group of people live together sharing accomodation and goods, forming their own community based upon common ideals.
A building where people congregate to undertake sustained mental contemplation or religious or spiritual reflection.
An ornamental panel or decorative structure situated above a mantelpiece
Outer cases for ammunition shells, e.g. Howitzer shells; not "live" ammunition, i.e. either at the first stage of manufacture, or having been expended.

Manmade structure for bathing or swimming that is located on the beachfront and filled by tidal waters. Similar to a LIDO, with the main difference being the extent of the built up complex around the pool.
A Roman market hall principally selling meat and poultry but also other provisions.
Goods, usually foodstuffs, preserved in glass bottles, jars, etc. Examples are bottled fruit, pickled onions, jam, honey.
Paper currency. Bank notes may be of any denomination or value and of any nationality.
A machine used for the purification of water, usually for drinking purposes.
Paper products intended for note-taking or correspondence, e.g. blank notebooks, diaries, writing paper, postcards
Previously known as Madras.
A simple type of plant. For most of their lifecycle they exist as haploids (i.e. only one set of genes as opposed to two). Most have clearly differentiated stems and leaves.
Material of unknown origin observed adhering to, or found within, an object of another material.
Traces of food observed adhering to, or found within, an object or another material.
Material derived from living things. Use more specific term where known.

Amoebae which are partially enclosed in external shells, or tests. Found in wet soils, freshwater, decaying organic matter and on vegetation such as mosses. Used to examine environmental factors such as water acidity and moisture content.

Use for any soil or sediment. Sediments consist of mineral and/or organic material deposited by any process involving natural or human agencies. Soils are discrete bodies of altered mineral material (either sediment or in situ rock remains).
A wind-blown deposit.
Wind-blown sand.
Wind-blown silt.
Deposits laid down as the result of river action.
Deposits formed as the result of the action of ice masses during glacial periods.
Unsorted sediment (i.e. containing everything from clay to boulders) laid down directly by a glacier.
Deposits formed by the mass downward movement of surface deposits over underlying frozen ground under periglacial conditions.
Deposits that accumulate at the bottom of a slope, at a break in a slope, or where a barrier is encountered.
A soil, which may be buried or exposed, that has developed in a past landscape.
Material consisting of at least 90% organic matter by dry weight. Formed from plant material under damp, wet or acid conditions where the rate of accumulation is greater than the rate of decay.
A rock-like deposit consisting largely of calcium carbonate, formed by the precipitation of calcium carbonate out of calcium-rich water bodies such as springs.
A residue left as the result of the burning of material.
Volcanic ash.
Use for deposits formed in estuaries.
Use for deposits formed in lakes or ponds.
Fine-grained, non-humified, organic mud formed under water. Principally composed of plant material, typically of faecal origin.
Use for deposits formed by the action of the sea or under marine conditions.
Use for deposits formed in caves.
Use for deposits formed as a result of the modification of soils by humans for agricultural purposes.
Use for deposits formed as a result of construction activities undertaken by humans or animals.
Use for deposits representing material discarded or remaining as a result of a process or processes.
Deposits formed under conditions present adjacent to ice masses during glacial periods.

Originally denoting a Byzantine vessel, powered by oars, from the 6th century onwards, this developed into a large Mediterranean ship with oars and a single mast, used for trade or for war transport, (e.g. during the Crusades) until the 15th century.
A well concealed structure, usually constructed underground, intended for use by members of the British Resistance Organization in the event of invasion.
An anti-personnel device consisting of a 40 gallon fuel drum placed on top of an explosive charge and detonator. When detonated the barrel would explode sending burning fuel over the intended target.

Name given to a workhouse after 1929. The Local Government Act of 1929 abolished Poor Law Unions and Guardians, and control passed to public assistance authorities run by county boroughs and county councils. Lasted until 1948 when poor laws were repealed.
A decoy site designed to simulate a burning urban area during a bombing raid in order to lure enemy bombers away from legitimate targets.
A deposit that has been burnt and not subsequently disturbed. Refer to Archaeological Science thesaurus for terminology relating to those redeposited from their original location.
A construction trench dug to receive a line of posts for a wall, with associated packing.
A tunnel with strengthened construction, used as an emergency exit from a civil defence building.
A hearth constructed specifically for the manufacture of pitch.
A former ground surface buried beneath an earthwork or other sequence of deposits. (includes palaeosoils, turf lines)
Debris consisting of excess construction material used in the building of a nearby site or structure. If unsure of whether debris is from construction or demolition, index with both terms.
A building housing a fan used for the ventilation of mines

A small dispersal WWII military aircraft hangar featuring an "A" shaped steel frame clad with corrugated iron; end doors were supported by outriggers when open.Typically used on aircraft storage units or satellite landing grounds. Variations in size.

A structure consisting of different cells equipped with instrument posts which supported finders. These provided range and bearing of the projected position of the target to guns emplaced in a nearby battery. Errected along the coast in the late 1870s.
Sites, buildings or stuctures associated with the entire process of salt production.

A large shallow pan, usually metal, in which seawater or brine is evaporated for the extraction of salt. The name is also often applied to the exterior pits or ponds used for the same purpose (see Thesaurus of Monument Types).
A tank within a salt works used for storing brine after is has been pumped from underground. The brine is then fed by gravity into the evaporating pans in the Pan House.
A component of salt works containing flues and drying areas where salt blocks are dried before being crushed and bagged.

A type of large permanent military aircraft hangar with a curved steel frame and storage annexes on its side used in World War II. It was intended for storage purposes on Aircraft Storage Unit stations.

An artificially constructed wall with recessed and projecting grips for hands and feet and places to attach ropes. Used for practising rock climbing. If the wall is situated within a sports centre use term from Components thesaurus.

An artifically constructed wall with recessed and projecting grips for hands and feet and places to attach ropes. Used for practising rock climbing. If the wall is a free-standing external structure use term for the Thesaurus of Monument Types.

A sunken, circular, concrete pillbox used on airfields. They remained flush with the surface to permit the free movement of aircraft but, if attack threatened, could be raised hydraulically or by a counterbalance, and manned to give covering fire.

A type of military aircraft hangar of the Cold War, hardened and therefore protected against the effects of nuclear weapons. It comprises a semi-circular structure built of corrugated-steel supporting a reinforced-concrete skin. Three NATO designs.
Buildings and structures associated with a private aviation club undertaken as a leisure pursuit. Usually situated on or near an airfield.
Senegal
A military side-opening aircraft hangar originally designed for seaplanes and used RNAS bases from 1916. Steel framed with asbestos or corrugated iron cladding.
A building or site where aircraft can be stored and maintained.
Hampshire
Victoria, Australia
South Yorkshire

Headquarters buildings on military airfields for administrative purposes housing offices, lecture rooms and in some cases a library and a meteorological office. On smaller airfields it is called Station Offices. Abbreviation SQH.
A military storage aircraft hangar built  in the late 1930s. It comprises a semicircular concrete structure with reinforced concrete columns, featuring a curved roof and straight walls.
A military storage aircraft hangar designed in 1937. It has a curved profile and is constructed from steel ribs supporting a concrete skin. The roof is covered with earth and turf.
A monument whose presence is inferred from verbally delivered information drawn from the speaker's personal knowledge.
A special school to train personnel for employment in Air Traffic Control and operation duties.
An upper story in a chapel, church or cathedral, situated above the aisle and below the clerestory, often arcaded and sometime called a Tribune.
A mechanical component or device that can change the direction of motion of a pump rod from the vertical to the horizontal plane and vice versa.
A counter balance designed to support the excess weight of a mineshaft's wooden beams.
A device used in the production of hard cheeses that exerts pressure upon fresh curds in order to remove and drain away excess whey.
A large room with fixed seating, often including audio-visual facilites, in which lectures are given.
Previously known as Bombay.
A temporary settlement or shanty-town erected by railway construction workers or "navvys".
A type of fairground or seaside amusement, often a permanent structure, where carriages travel at high speeds on an undulating track raised some distance from the ground.
Personal apparatus for telling the time, worn either as jewellery or purely functional in nature, usually on the wrist or as a suspended fob.
A quadrangle or courtyard, often grassed or planted, surrounded by cloisters
A depot for the depositing, storage and dispatch of plant or other resources associated with the delivery of local government public services.
A plant used to sterilize water for use in public bathing establishments, not to be confused with desaliation or  purification units for drinking water.

A building which has been moved from its original site either through active human intervention or natural processes such as erosion. For structures or objects such as gravestones use MOVED STRUCTURE.

A man-made construction or object (such as a gravestone) which has been moved from its original site either through active human intervention or natural processes such as erosion. For buildings which have been moved use MOVED BUILDING.
A room set aside for the initial treatment of injuries sustained for example in public amenities such as lidos.
Seaside structure, usually consisting of a manmade retaining wall that keeps a relatively large area of the tidal water partitioned off for controlled boating or swimming.
A knife prior to undergoing the processes of sharpening or finishing, consisting of a single piece of metal from which the blade and tang have been shaped.

A pit in which lye is used to clean hides/bones/etc. generally as part of the tanning process to remove excess fat, flesh, hair, etc. from the raw hide.  The residue from these pits formed a crude soap which could be used for various cleaning purposes.
Cut or uncut stones, usually intended to be set into jewellery, and including precious gems, e.g. diamonds, sapphires, or semi-precious materials, e.g. quartz, agate, amber.

A concrete structure, based on drawing number (11008/41), intended to be the headquarters for the coordination of an airfield's defences. Constructed partially underground it was considered less vulnerable than the (3329/41).
A structure, often concrete or brick, used as a shelter by members of the British citizen army during watch or patrol duties, or air raids, in wartime.
Obstacles, often semi permanent, which are placed on railway lines to prevent the enemy from using them. Set up during the defence of Britain.
Stop-line against invading tanks in form of a ditch during the defence of Britain.
Place for the Home Guard to store equipment and amunition, either structural or subterranean during the defence of Britain.
General term describing any defence work where no more specific term is applicable.
A bridge which has had mines placed within its structure to enable it to be destroyed in the event of an invasion.
Chamber built into underside of a structure to exercise demolition.
Fixed or hardened installation for machine guns. Temporary soft installations are possible as well.
Obstacles like concrete cubes, cylinders or pimples erected in the defence of Britain.
Block, often made of concrete, to secure smaller maritime craft. Many were made during the Second Wold War to secure craft which were to be used in the D-Day landings.

Baggage, plate, money, clothes and other personal belongings of all kinds. Use only where the vessel is a cargo vessel conveying the goods of a person of consequence, e.g. a noble or diplomat, rather than for a general passenger vessel.
A site, usually including fuel tanks, pipe works and control buildings, where flaming petroleum was intended to be used as a weapon against a hostile invasion.
Edible fruit of the vine, which may be either red or white.
Cargoes transported in sacks or bags, usually wheat, corn, flour, fruit, or coal. To be used only where the cargo is said to be "sacks" or "bags" of goods. Use specific term where known.
World War II naval support vessel usually converted from a mercantile or other warship type and used for the distillation of water by both the Royal Navy and the American Navy.
A rectilinear ritual enclosure of Iron Age date
A factory used for the production of acetate.
Debris derived from the demolition of buildings or other structures. If unsure of whether debris is resulting from construction or demolition, index with both terms.
A deposit that forms the ground surface (when the evidence is collected), particularly a hard surface such as a floor or road.
One of several stones used to raise a farm building, such as a granary, above the ground surface.
An alluvial deposit laid down in an estuary.
A deposit that has been burnt and has since been removed from its original location. Use BURNT and appropriate object or material type.
A naturally occuring deposit of calcareous tufa ('shell marl') sometimes found in alluvial deposits.
A naturally occurring deposit formed by the decomposition and partial carbonisation of vegetable matter in waterlogged conditions.
A deposit formed by wave and tidal action on an estuarine or marine beach.
The fruit or seed of a cereal plant such as wheat, corn etc.

The fertilized ovules of a plant, often occurring in an archaeological context, in the form of small roundish bodies or grains. Seeds are dispersed naturally or collected for sowing to produce a new generation of plants.
Man-made, roofless edifice or construction visible as substantial above-ground remains retaining evidence of architecture and materials, but which has been substantially destroyed.
Man-made roofless edifice or construction which is intact or substantially intant, with significant survival of original features, even if no longer serving original intended funtion.

A monument consisting of a built structure, but which has been demolished so that only a ground plan and foundations, or similar, are thought to remain. Where all below ground traces have also been removed use DESTROYED MONUMENT.
An unconsolidated geological deposit sometimes iused as a bonding material in stone walls.
A privately-funded home for the care of the elderly.
Mark, usually consisting of a horizontal line above an arrow, cut by the Ordnance Survey as part of the survey of Britain and referenced to a known height above mean sea level.
A stone, of unidentified function, showing evidence of great heating at some point in the past, leading to vitrification.
A concrete marker placed to indicate the direction of a target on a bombing range to aircraft.
An enclosed observation tower, usually made of brick or concrete and raised on four legs, associated with WW2 bombing ranges.
A store for hay, at a remove from the farm (Scots)
Residence of a leading land-holding family within the district.
Cluster of dwellings of medieval or later date (Scots)
A pit used to trap game. Often originally covered and consealed, and sometimes with sharpened stakes in the base.
Temporary accommodation for war evacuees.
A building or settlement enclosure with a thick drystone wall, generally circular or oval in plan, usually sited in an elevated position.
A civil and administrative area incorporating a town of medieval origin.

An Iron Age round defended house, found mainly in the north and west of Scotland. Brochs have a tapering profile and thick, usually hollow dry stone walls which contain galleries, cells and a stairway, with guard cells at the entrance.
A paddle blade, typically of wood, from a horizontal or vertical mill wheel.
A cargo vessel designed to carry goods packed in large containers that can be loaded directly onto trains or lorries.
A small cargo vessel used on the West coast of Scotland.
A factory where security safes are manufactured.
A factory for the manufacture of military tanks.
Factory or workshop making bits, spurs and other small metal objects associated with horse harness.
Feature visible following archaeological excavation

A purpose-built facility providing an area for wheeled sports, such as skateboarding, skating and BMX cycling, equipped with ramps and other structures and obstacles for the performance of tricks and manoeuvres.
A mill for producing abravive papers and cloths such as glass paper or emery cloth.
A mill for grinding ochre for the paint making process.

A sailmaker's thimble used in the sewing of canvas, consisting of a flat thimble in a canvas or leather strip with a thumb hole. The whole is worn across the palm of the hand, which gives it its name.

An astonomical instrument, and navigational aid, in the form of one eighth of a circle and used to measure the angular altitude of heavenly bodies. Invented in 1731 and used into the 19th Century, it was superceded by the sextant.
A clock with special mechanisms and dials to display astonomical information.
An iron bar or rod running through the core of a windmill's windshaft that causes the opening and shutting of the vanes on patent sails.

A device, usually cast iron and often decorative in design, placed upon, embedded in or built into a doostep facilitating the removal of mud, dirt, manure etc. from footwear before entering a building.
A stone, usually inscribed, laid during a ceremony to commemorate the founding of a new building
A single-engine, two-crew biplane day bomber and general purpose aircraft, developed from the IIIF (some of which were converted into Gordons) and first flown in 1931.
Fife, Scotland
Single-seat, single-engine fighter biplane renowned for its high performance and manoeuvrability. Entered service in 1917.
Norfolk

Twin-engine, three-crew, long-range heavy bomber biplane. Entered service in 1917. Of wooden construction with a fabric covering, the Vimy was fitted with a skid under the nose of its fuselage to prevent tipping forward upon landing.
Four-engined, five to seven crew, heavy bomber biplane. Entered service in 1918.
North Yorkshire
Niche intended for pigeons or other birds to nest in, allowing the squabs and eggs to be harvested. Found inside specially built dovecotes and in the walls of other buildings.

A supermarket for American military personnel, the National Guard and the Reserves and their immediate family, usually sited on a military installation throughout the world. Use term only in conjunction with an American military base.
A prepared area used for the game of baseball.
A roofed structure, open on one side, usually attached to a building, providing a seating area and its occupants with an uninterrupted exterior view.

A steel aircraft hangar evolved from the German "Lamellendach", a segmental roof design of the 1920s using a diamond shaped web of pressed steel producing a hangar with a shallow curving profile. Used for both military and civil purposes.

A short-term storage centre of goods or special parts to facilitate the rapid processing of orders and supply of goods to customers; unlike a warehouse, the emphasis is on the moving of goods rather than on a long-term storage.
A mutiple role hangar for aircraft and general storage, manufactured in the USA as a kit for on-site assembly  during WWII and post-war. It comprises a steel box frame and a canvas covering.
A room in which public or private auctions are held.
Writing implements; formerly quill pens made of bird feathers, and in more modern times fountain pens made of various materials with metal nibs, both used with ink to write.
Instruments for measuring and displaying time. Often manufactured as a piece of furniture e.g.a grandfather clock.
A steel framed seaplane hangar designed for Royal Navy Air Stations by the admiralty in 1917-1918.
Single engine, two-crew shipboard reconnaissance and patrol seaplane. Entered service in 1939, this was the last combat floatplane built in Europe.
An area on post-war military airfields for parking aircraft on quick reaction alert to allow immediate access to the runway. Abbreviation ORP.
Arado Flugzeugwerke. Formed in 1931 in Germany when the aircraft manufacturer Albatros Flugzeugwerke was declared bankrupt and part of it merged with Arado Handells-Gessellschaft.

Series of rooms in a workhouse, prison or hospital, often including porter's lodge, baths, clothes store, washrooms, casual cells, rooms etc, for receiving inmates/patients. Use term in Monument Type Thesaurus if it is a freestanding building.
Series of rooms in a workhouse complex where children were housed and looked after.
Series of rooms within a workhouse where elderly men were housed.

A large rectangle roof tile with an upstand on one side, a roll in the centre and another roll on the other side, which fits over the upstand of the adjacent tile. The name does not denote a relationship with the Roman period.

Extremely thin foil made out of ethyltetraflouroethylene, a modified copolymer which is extruded into a thin film and which is related to Teflon. It has a very high level of light transmission in visible and ultra violet range. Used instead of glass.
A tall pole topped with a bell used to summon the workforce to their place of work.
A building housing the brakes for an incline railway or tramway.
