A pump used for moving brine (salt water).
Use both terms
A mill used for the preparation and production of Calamine.
A site associated with the large scale construction of buildings or items manufactured by the building industry.
A building or site where lead is obtained from ore.
A stone or timber lined channel for conveying ore out of a working.
Term applied to a pit trap itself and also a walled enclosure containing one or more pit traps.
A grave which has been formed by cutting into the bedrock of a site.
A chute for conveying salt.
A group of, usually three, standing stones forming a square with an open side and often found with a stone circle.
A site where tanks and armoured fighting vehicles can be stored.
A building or site used for the manufacture of whiting either from crushed chalk, limestone, marble or through chemical preparation.
A small island, especially within a river.

An establishment originally providing terminals to allow the public to access the internet, usually for a fee. They originally provided snacks and drinks to customers although now this is not always the case.
Refers to art, whether carving or painting, applied to free -standing stones or cave walls.
Art applied in pigment to rock wether in the form of a free-standing stone or the walls of a cave.
A searchlight battery used to light a beach.
A slight structure built on an allotment for shelter or storage, or for use as a workshop, by the allotment holder.

Purpose-built structure, other than a bollard, to prevent vehicle or pedestrian access to a road or site, for example concrete blocks to obstruct vehicles accessing beaches on the north-east coast for illegal sea-coaling.
Fast arterial road with separate carriageways limited to motor vehicles
A circular construction at the intersection of two or more roads to aid the passage of vehicles from one road to another.
The blue dyestuff prepared from the leaves of the plant Isatis tinctoria, and sometimes used to discribe the plant itself.  Later superseded by indigo.
A cover consisting of a plate for covering over or closing in a chamber or receptacle.
An iron cover for a manhole
A building or site used for the production of naphtha, a volatile petroleum-derived product used in the manufacture of solvents, cleaning fluids etc.
A tower with one or more horizontal platforms extending out over deep water for use in diving competitions.
Late nineteenth and early twentieth century warship armed with guns and torpedoes.
The site of the formal burial of cremated bone, sometimes 'urned' in a vessel or casket of glass, wood or, more commonly, ceramic.
An intrusive feature cut for the purpose of containing a cremation burial within it.
A hollow case containg explosive, incendiary, smoke-producing, poisonous or other offensive material, designed to be deposited, dropped, thrown or shot froma mortar.

A cylindrical bomb, designed by Barnes Wallis in 1941, containing hydrostatic pistols measuring water pressure for detonation at a depth of 30 feet.  Dropped whilst fast revolving at a height of 60 feet at 240-250 mph to maximise the bouncing effect.

An ornamental (carved and/or painted) frieze carved into, or attached to, the planking either side of a vessel's bow carrying the vessel's name and often illustrating some aspect of the name, port/country of origin etc.

A hinged plate of brass, iron or wood inboard of a ship's scuttle or porthole which can be lowered and secured with a butterfly nut to prevent damage to glass in heavy weather or mask internal light from enemy vessels.
A water-tight cover that closes and opening in a vessel's deck used for the ingress and egress of persons and cargo.
A hole or opening in a ship's hull to allow light and air to enter the vessel, or to aim a weapon through.
A flexible pipe, usually fixed to a pump or tap, for the conveying of water.

A covering of thin copper plates secured, on top of a layer of tar and horsehair, to the bottom of wooden ships to protect the hull against weeds, barnacles and especially Teredo navalis, a wood-boring worm prevalent in tropical seas.

A vault composed of concave cones, inverted and overlaid with ribs that rise from the springing of the vault and diverge equally in different directions, producing an effect like the ribs of an opened fan.
A semi-circular window, often decorated and with its glazing bars radiating like the ribs of an opened fan, set above a door.
The heat-resistant wall, or sometimes decorative cast iron panel, at the back of a fireplace.
A convex, finger-like moulding, usually applied in a series to form a pattern of ridges.
An architrave surrounding a door, window or niche interrupted by large blocks of stone, and often by a massive keystone set under a pediment. Named after the architect James Gibbs (1682-1754).
The ridge formed at the intersection of two vaulted surfaces.
The band or block from which the springing of an arch occurs.
A short principal rafter that that rises from a tiebeam to a collar.
A rectangular dripstone.
A termination, either in the form of a decorative feature or a right-angle applied to the end of the moulding, of a label, dripstone or string course.
A projecting structure in the roof of a mill containing a winch, allowing loads to be lifted clear of the building's wall and protecting the winch from the weather.
An upright framing member, or mullion, that separates two panels, such as in a panelled door or a window.
A section of stone or brickwork employed in a timber-framed building to fill the spaces between uprights or studs.
A colonnette set in a corner or angle, such as the meeting of two walls or the place at which a doorframe meets the wall it is set in.
A pediment with a gap at its apex, sometimes filled with an urn or other decorative feature.
A decorative motif representing a palm leaf. Often painted, incised or applied in relief, can occur singly or as a repeating pattern.
A gutter running behind a parapet wall, the water channelled by it being discharged from holes in the wall.
A screen that separates a tomb or a chapel from the main body of a church.
A metal or stone plate or tablet, usually inscribed, set into a wall, pedestal, floor etc., often serving as a memorial.

A large, movable barrier, usually an iron or wooden grating with pointed bars along its bottom edge, with its sides set in vertical grooves above a castle's gateway enabling it to be dropped to bar entry.
A stone screen, usually found in a monastic or collegiate church, that separates the choir from the nave.
A small square or lozenge-shaped pane of glass as used in a leaded light.
A horizontal iron bar set in a window opening to which a leaded light is fixed.
A half or whole baluster applied to a wall or pedestal, thus described as engaged.
A vertical iron bar fixed within a window opening to support a leaded light.
A capital featuring stylised, often projecting, three-lobed leaves.
One of a building's horizontal divisions, being the space between two floors, or a floor and the roof structure.
A short timber connecting a cruck blade to a wall above the point at which the blade diverges from it.
An iron plate connecting two or more timbers together.
Any member that connects two bodies, such as the sloping sides of a roof, to prevent them pulling apart.
A baluster, circular in plan, turned and cut on a lathe.
A spirally turned baluster.
An arch formed around two arcs whose radii are each equal to the span of the arch.
A window with three openings, the central light being arched and wider than those flanking it.
Wooden panelling, especially interior wall panelling that rises only to dado height.
An arched half-rib applied to the lateral wall surface in a vaulted bay, its function, rather than structural, being to complete the pattern of the vault's main ribs.
A room or cupboard usually used for the storage of garments.
A late 12th Century capital featuring large, unribbed leaves growing outwards from each angle before curving up towards the abacus and turning inwards at the top.
An inclined course on top of a projecting sill, cornice etc., designed to throw off rainwater.
A small tank or cistern, often lead or cast-iron and sometimes ornamented, that collects rainwater from a gutter or channel prior to it being discharged.
A latrine, or privy, situated at the rear of a monastery dormitory.
A half-pier, corbel or other architectural element, usually situated at the end of an arcade, attached to a wall to support an arch.
The vertical face of a step.
An arch with jambs that do not stand at an angle of ninety degrees to its face.
A longitudinal member in a roof, running beneath the collar beams and intended to give stability to the roof.
An aisle divided into chapels. This term is sometimes applied to the screens dividing the aisle, or the chapels themselves.
A small convex moulding, often decorated with beads and reels.
Ground-covering herbage, some varieties of which can be used, especially when dried and in large quantities, as a construction material.
A fitting specifically functioning as the strengthener and support for the end of a strap of leather or fabric.
A device on an airfield for securing aircrafts when parked outside in order to prevent major movement due to the weather or other conditions.
Wooden boxes or cases for carrying fruit and other similar goods.
Colour or dye, often in powder form, from natural mineral or vegetable sources (e.g. ochre) or created through chemical process (e.g. lamp black).
A sitting room fitted with large windows for the purpose of admitting the maximum amount of sunlight.
Ceramic vessels made from potash, sand, feldspar and clay which is biscuit fired at a temperature of around 1000 degree Celsius. Usually glazed in order to become watertight.
Three-masted fishing lugger built in and operating out of Yorkshire on the North Sea fisheries; so named as it was crewed by five joint owners, plus two or three paid hands.
An aircraft hangar designed to be moved from site to site as necessary.
A temporary, steel-framed transportable hangar developed by Teesside Bridge and Engineering Company to replace the obsolete Bellman hangars.

A transportable hangar designed by Callender Cable and Construction to Air Ministry drawing number 6633/37. A steel box-girder framework with corrugated iron cladding and canvas doors it had a clear door height of 25ft.
A small arched hangar built by the Canadian company Fromson of Byfleet to drawing number 3971/43. Used only as storage sheds on RNASs.
A transportable hangar designed by A & J Main of Glasgow.
An all-steel end-opening, hangar with canted sides designed for folded-wing aircraft.
An aircraft hangar built to Air Ministry design. Mainly constructed on aircraft factory aerodromes.
An aircraft hangar built to Air Ministry design number 454/43. Mainly constructed on aircraft factory aerodromes
Aircraft hangars designed by T. Bedford Consulting Engineers to meet the requirement to repair damaged heavy bombers in situ on their airfields.
An aircraft hangar designed by T. Bedford Consulting Engineers usually erected on aircraft factory sites rather than operational airfields.
A single-span aircraft hangar designed by Boulton & Paul of London and Norwich (drawing number 4178/44). Mainly used on aircraft factory sites and at Armament Training Schools.
A double-span aircraft hangar designed by Boulton & Paul of London and Norwich. Mainly used on aircraft factory sites and at Armament Training Schools.
A semi-permanent ahed designed to Air Ministry specification 1136/27 as a quick and cheap hangar for stations overseas
An aircraft hangar designed to Air Ministry specification (drawing number 6910/43). Similar in design to the ROBINS AIRCRAFT HANGAR but larger.
An aircraft hangar designed to Air Ministry specifications (drawing number 2243/41). Constructed from prefabricated A-frames and clad in corrugated iron.
An aircraft hangar designed to house seaplanes.
A side-opening steel framed shed. A smaller version of the SEAPLANE SHED (TYPE F) they were built from 1916 on RNAS seaplane bases
A watch office designed for bomber satellite station comprising a long, temporary brick hut with a watch office, operations room and crew briefing room.

A detached building without an operations block and crew briefing room designed on modern lines similar to, but smaller than WATCH OFFICE (12779/41). Began appearing on new stations from September 1941.

A central tower with a single-storey wing either side. The tower contained the watch office on the ground floor, observation room on the second with each wing containing an office for the Chief Flying Instructor or the officer commanding and their aides.
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the Air Ministry. Usually found on or near airfields.
A site or building associated with active or passive defence of the landing ground and buildings of an airfield.
A pillbox constructed for use in training exercises forming part of a simulated defensive position
A pillbox in which the roof is detached from the walls and supported by a central pillar, thus leaving an embrasure allowing a 360 degree field of fire.
A pillbox which has been modified from a standard Directorate of Fortifications and Works design. Double index with specific type where known.
A construction designed to look like a pillbox in order to deceive or confuse the enemy.
A pillbox constructed of prefabricated concrete panels. Double index with specific type where known.
A pillbox with walls that have been thickened to protect against shells. Double index with specific type where known.
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the chief engineer of GHQ home forces.
A kitchen set up, specifically during World War Two, to serve food to members of the public, especially families whose homes had succumbed to enemy bombing.
An area of privately owned land attached to, and incorporating, a country house and associated buildings.
A structure providing protection from the elements to passengers waiting to board a ferry service at a dock, riverside, harbour or quay.
A linear groove worn into the surface of a road or thoroughfare by the continuous passage of wheeled vehicles. Usually expected to occur in pairs.
A tank found on hop farms in which creosote was held, heated from below by a fire with a chimney. The ends of hop poles were dipped in the tar to prevent rotting in soil.
A hut provided as accommodation for hop pickers and may also be know as a Hop Pickers' Hut
A container packed with explosives, with a detonator triggered by contact or a timer,  for the purpose of destroying enemy craft, personnel etc.
A mine designed specifically to be dropped from an aircraft, often into the sea.
A machine consisting of a number of moving parts designed to produce a specific physical effect, such as the powering of a craft or other device.
The engine housed within the fuselage of an aircraft that powers its flight.
For funerary monuments use CATACOMB (FUNERARY), for wine use WINE CELLAR
A building used as the headquarters for the Home Guard during the Second World War.
Line, cord or thread, especially that used for tying up parcels, etc. Also use for "twine", i.e. twisted thread, for the same purpose, and medieval equivalents, e.g. "packthread".
Fish of the Salmonidae family, caught for food.
A workshop or factory unit where small or light goods are manufacture without the need for large-scale industrial machinery.
Modified or damaged by an animal.
The measurement of chemical alterations in the amino acids in protein molecules from bones, shells and teeth. Date range can be between 1,000 and several million years.
Characterisation of organic molecules extracted from fossil or sub-fossil materials, including lipids, DNA etc.
Material preserved by the exclusion of oxygen usually due to saturation with water which inhibits decay by micro-organisms.
Outgrowths of bone borne by most members of the deer family (Cervidae). They are shed and re-grow each year.

Measures the remanent magnetisation direction of magnetic minerals. Useful for dating fired structures, in-situ since their last firing, and for sediments settling from non turbulent water bodies. In the UK, calibration data extends back to 1000BC.
The analysis of the amount of phosphorus (P) (liable fraction) available to plants.
A technique in which the date is deduced from the presence of fauna and/or flora considered to be characteristic of a given peirod of time or that gives and indication of a probable date.
The removal of fragile or complex remains from an investigation as a block of earth for excavation under laboratory conditions. Typical examples are grave goods and cremation burials.
Any of the pieces of hard tissue consisting largely of calcium phosphate that make up the skeleton of a vertebrate animal.
Use for material that has been burnt.
Material burnt at high temperature (above 700 degrees Celsius) leaving only the mineral component.
Wood that has been burnt and largely reduced to carbon as a result of burning in a reducing atmosphere below 500 degress C (Celsius).
Material that has been burnt and at least in part reduced to carbon as a result of burning in a reducing atmosphere below 500 degrees Celsius.
Examination of a material using chemical means.
Material that has been altered as a result of chemical action.
The identification and grouping of stone types in stratigraphy.
The method of retrieving animal remains, artefacts and other remains by dry or wet-sieving whole earth samples, typically over 100 litres, sieved through a 2mm or larger mesh.
Material with evidence of the application of a pigment or dye.
Use for a combination (alloy) of two or more different metals where copper (Cu) is the principal component.

Waste material from the digestive tract of animals. The term coprolite comes from the Greek 'kopros' meaning dung and 'lithos' meaning stone, and is used for faecal matter that has been preserved by mineral replacement or dessication.
Techniques applied to a material in order to date it or material associated with it. Use more specific terms.
Use where decoration is present.

The measuring of annual tree-ring growth shown by most tree species in temperated regions. Regional chronoliges are required to date any particular piece of wood, the longest of which, for Germany, works for the present to approximately 14,000 yrs ago.
A camping place set aside for the use of caravans.
A purpose built indoor cricket facility for training and playing matches
Submerged obstacles to stop the landing of Seaplanes
An outdoor trail that has keep fit equipment with supporting information plaques intermittently positioned along its route
A prepared piece of ground on which the game of Petanque is played.
Sedimentary clay with smectite mineral properties, originally used for the cleansing ["fulling"] of cloth; in the 20th century it was used for a wider range of industrial applications.
A site used for the butchery of animals.
A loft, balcony or gallery, in a hall or church, for the use of musicians.
Terms covering features of a monument or building which imply the previous presence of a component or structure. Use for negative evidence of a component or structure.

A hole in a wall in which cross timbers, known as putlogs, were placed to allow scaffolding to be erected. Putlog holes are often left unfilled and are often the only evidence for the use of scaffolding.
A slot, usually in a wall, into which a beam was placed.
An ornamental moulding consisting of a series of small, regularly placed squared or rounded blocks.
The vertical lining of a doorway, window or other opening.
An internal door flush with, and decorated to match, the wall it is set in for the purpose of concealment.
Alternative name for the Tuscan Order according to Vincenzo Scamozzi. Not to be confused with COLOSSAL ORDER.
The area directly in front of a fireplace or the floor of a firecplace itself.
A wooden panel, mounted on the wall of a church, bearing the Achievement of Arms of an individual whose funeral has taken place there.
The end of a timber post made wider than the rest of its length on one face to accomodate tiebeams, wall-plates etc..
A sculptural or decorative representation of a human figure. Includes mythical and fantastical figures such as Cupid, Atlas etc.
A sculptural or decorative representation of an animal. Includes mythical and fantastical animals such as dragons, centaurs etc.
A carved stone female figure often found on castles and churches.
A rafter set diagonally where two sloping rooves meet.
A heated room within a monastery where monks could warm themselves.
A stage in a church tower where bell ringers stand.
A wooden bench with a back and ends, usually fixed and found in churches. The bench ends are often decorated.
A wooden, metal or stone strip attached to the floor between the door posts in a doorway covering the joint between two floor surfaces.
A secondary rib usually springing from the junction of two other ribs, or one that rises between a main diagonal and transverse rib, from the springing to the ridge rib.
A horizontal member dividing a window into two or more lights.
The horizontal surface of a step or stair.
A vertical stone mullion or shaft situated in the centre of a wide doorway to support its lintel or tympanum.
A horizontal, supporting beam set above an opening in an external wall, a fireplace opening or in timber framed construction set forward from the lower part of a building to support a jettied wall.
A beam often situated above, and spanning the width of, the west end of a chancel and supporting a cross or crucifix.
A vault whose bay is divided by diagonal and transverse ribs into six compartments or cells.
A thin wooden slab or tile used in quantity as a roof or wall covering.
A thin masonry facing or cladding employed to conceal the surface or structure behind it.
An open balcony or gallery extending along the outside of a building, providing principal rooms with shade by means of a roof or canopy supported by posts or light columns.
The area between the base and the cornice of a plinth.
The lower area of a interior wall between the skirting board and the dado rail
A covered walkway attached to a building.
An apartment or suite of rooms usually occupying the top floor of a building.
A structure used to test the aerodynamics of aircraft or vehicles.
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the chief engineer of South-Eastern Command.
A pillbox built to a design drawn up the chief engineer of Scottish Command
A pillbox built to a design drawn up the chief engineer of Scottish Command
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the chief engineer of GHQ home forces.

A circular pillbox, usually consisting of a concrete pipe with a timber and corrugated iron roof, surrounded and covered by earth and sandbags. Built to a design by Norcon Ltd, a company dealing in concrete pipes.
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the commander of the Royal Engineers in Southern Area (Taunton Line).
A pillbox built to a design drawn up by the commander of the Royal Engineers for the Colchester Garrison.
A pillbox built to a design by the commander of the Royal Engineers for the Colchester Garrison.

A hexagonal pillbox, with an internal anti-ricochet wall and loopholes for fives light machine guns and one rifle. Originally designed to have 15in bulletproof walls many were built with 42in thick shellproof walls. Designed by DFW branch 3.
A rectangular pillbox with an enclosed square plan section for three light machine guns and an adjacent open area housing a mounting for a light anti-aircraft weapon. Designed by DFW branch 3.
An anti aircraft battery usually mounting smaller, faster weapons such as Bofors guns or a single anti-aircraft machine gun, intended to engage fast low flying aircraft.

A hexagonal pillbox with an interanl anti-ricochet wall. The rear wall was lengthened to take two rifle loopholes in addition to the five light machine gun. Both 15in and 42in thick walls are common. Designed by DFW branch 3.

A circular pillbox designed by the Engineering and Metals Company using 'Armco' corrugated iron sheets as the inner and outer skins into which concrete was poured, giving a 12in wall thickness. The design was taken up by DFW and assigned a drawing number.

A square pillbox with loopholes for four light machine guns with 18 in thick walls. Probably designed by DFW branch 3 although it may have been adapted from an external source as Southern Command correspondence refers to the type as 'Stento'.

A large octagonal pillbox, with a projecting entrance, equipped with loopholes for eight light machine guns and a light anti-aircraft mounting sited in a central well which was accessed from inside the pillbox. Designed by DFW branch 3.

A square pillbox with walls up to 48in thick, designed to emplace a 2 pounder anti-tank gun. A large opening in the back allowed the gun to be wheeled into position at the large embrasure in the front wall. Designed by DFW branch 3.
A defensive structure or site where an anti-tank gun is emplaced.
A large, rectangular pillbox based on the FW3/28 with the addition of a small infantry chamber to one side of the main gun chamber.

A pillbox design, assigned a drawing number by DFW branch 3. Although originally believed to be a distinct type, FW3/45 has recently been found to be a design for modifications to existing types. Double index with specific type where known.

A pillbox design, assigned a drawing number by DFW branch 3. Although originally believed to be a distinct type, FW3/45 has recently been found to be a design for modifications to existing types. Double index with specific type where known.
A pillbox which varies from standard designs.
A machine gun post designed by James Ruck constructed from hollow blocks and prefabricated concrete sheeting with loopholes allowing for a garrison of eight.
A rotating, domed, steel turret set over a circular pit used as a gun emplacement.
A flatbed lorry with a concrete defensive position fitted on the back enabling the "pillbox" to be driven to where it was most needed in the event of an airborne force landing on the airfield.
The first standardized design for a building for the duty pilot. It took the form of a small bungalow with a bay window on the front elevation.
A small single storey structure with just one room containing a pyrotechnic cupboard and built of rendered brick with a flat reinforced concrete roof
A fighter satellite station watch office built to Air Ministry design drawing number 14383/40.
A fighter satellite station watch office built to Air Ministry design drawing number 17658/40.
A fighter satellite station watch office built to Air Ministry design drawing number 18441/40.
A fighter satellite station watch office built to Air Ministry design drawing number 3156/41.
A two storey building with a watch office on the ground floor and a control room above. Originally based on drawing number 12096/4.
A night fighter station watch office based on the standard design dor Bomber Satellite Station watch offices
Material preserved due to very low humidity which inhibits decay by micro-organisms.
Use for the remains of an egg whether from a bird, reptile or amphibian.
The measurement of trapped electrons by exposure to high-frequency electromagnetic radiation. A useful technique for dating tooth enamel, shells, coral and calcite form 5,000-1,000,000 years old.
Use for feathers, an epidermal growth found in birds consisting of a quill, shaft and two vanes of barbs.
Any metal prinicipally composed of the chemical element Iron (Fe).
Use for any thread-like material.
A technique for the dating of damage tracks in volcanic materials caused by the fissioning of decaying radioactive uranium (U) isotopes. Useful in samples more than 50,000 years old.
Method used for the recovering of material by floating large whole earth samples, usually between 40-60 litres per context (or 100% if context contains less than this).

A relative dating technique for assessing bones from the same deposit. Often used to check for contemporaneity of bones selected for radiocarbon dating or to check for hoaxes such as the Piltdown Man.
Material that has been damaged by fungal growth or secretions.
A precious metal characterised by its yellow colour and resistance to tarnishing.
Use for hair, fur etc: filaments growing out of the outermost layer of mammalian skin.
The retrieval of material from deposits by hand, normally large objects visible with the naked eye, eg. Mammal remains and marine molluscs.
Aspects of a material which result from the modification or use of the material by humans.
The chemical breakdown of a material by water.
The negative trace left by an object type or material (eg. animal, plant or textile) on another object type or material, often on ceramics or metal corrosion products.

The light emitted from sedimentary minerals or mineral inclusions in bricks when stimulated in the laboratory by infrared light. Used to date samples up to 250,000 years old; especially appropriate for geological sediments containing feldspars
The analysis of inorganic phosphorus (P).
Use for a tusk or tooth of a mammal large enough to be carved or used to make objects such as those of mammoths, elephants, walruses and whales.
A technique which uses the measurement of decay in radioactive lead (Pb) isotopes to determine a date. Useful for sediments and lead-based paints between 1 and 400 years old.
Animal skin that has been tanned or tawed.
The weight loss from low-temperature burning of material. It correlates well with organic matter (material derived from living things) content.
The degree to which a material will become magnetised when placed in a magnetic field.
Use where the material presents debris or waste from manufacturing.

Class of elements and alloys that are characteristically lustrous, ductile, fusible and malleable. These are extracted from ore minerals originally existing in nature and processed before becoming a recognisable metal.
The microscopic analysis of thin sections of resin impregnated stratigraphy.
The use of magnifying equipment to examine materials not visible to the naked eye.
Preservation of material by toxic effect of corrosion products in the immediate vicinity, or within, the material.
Replacement of organic material by minerals, including calcium carbonate and calcium phosphate.
The study of minerals.

A dating technique for the founding of individual populations based on the assumption of steady rates of mutation in mitochondrial DNA. Sometimes used to produce dates for stratigraphic layers containing fossil specimens of populations.
Techniques investigating more than one element at a time.
Aspects associated with the genetic make up and/or factors that affected the organism from which the material is derived during its life
Any metal that does not contain the chemical element Iron (Fe) as a principal component.
Use for congenital (present at birth) abnormalities (absent/extra or morphologically unusual features) present in an individual or population.
A technique used to date obsidian (volcanic glass) of all ages and is thus not commonly used in the UK.

The light emitted from sedimentary minerals or mineral inclusions in bricks when stimulated in the laboratory by light of a different wavelength. Used to date samples up to 250,000 years old; especially appropriate for geological sediments.
The use of oxygen (O) isotope ratios in ice or ocean sediment cores to date global environmental change.
The analysis of the distribution and proportion of sand, silt and clay in a deposit.
Use for bone remodelling, new growth, loss or destruction caused by age, activity, disease or trauma during life.
The degree of acidity or alkalinity of a material.
An alignment of posts or postholes of unknown function
An alignment of stakes or stakeholes of unknown function
An alignment of trees planted as part of a designed landscape. For a belt lining a road use TREE AVENUE.
A group of trees planted as part of a designed landscape.
A building or site used for the production of anchors.
A building or site used in the production of enamelled goods.
A building or site used in the production of japanned goods. Japanning was the process of covering a material with a hard, black lacquer in imitation of Japanese lacquer work.
A building or site for the industrial manufacture of locks.
A kiln used for extracting salt through the evaporation of salt water.
The lowest part, usually projecting, of a pedestal or the base of a column.
A site used for the extraction of peat.
An aircraft used for towing gliders aloft.
An aircraft used for towing another aircraft or object, such as a glider or target.
Garden area next to public house used for the comsumption of alcoholic beverages.
An area speciallly developed to accommodate commercial buildings.

A coin struck, cast or stamped imitating an official coinage issue of contemporary or slightly later time period. The piece may consist of a similar alloy or a base core with plating of varying thickness.
A modern piece imitating an ancient coin, such as a replica sold in a museum.
A modern piece imitating an ancient coin in an attempt to deceive, usually for financial gain.
A boat roofed over and fitted up as a home for living in permanently or temporarily.

A stone faced earth bank, usually with a concave batter, and with the base the same width as its height and the top half the width of the base.  Vegetation usually grows out of the top.  Found mainly in Cornwall, but also elsewhere in the Atlantic Arc.
A shell-shaped moulded hood over an exterior opening, such as a doorway.
Permanently moored historic maritime craft preserved and converted into a museum and open to the public.
A room set aside within a club, hotel, large residence etc. for the benefit of guests or individuals who wish to smoke.
A room intended for the placement and use of a billiard table.
The fragmentary or substantial remains of a vehicle or aircraft. Where recovered from excavation double index with SUB SURFACE DEPOSIT.
A large communal room within a college complex used for functions, assemblies, examinations etc.

Area in a deer park where a single deer was chased by dogs over a set distance, with bets made on the outcome. It usually includes a stand (for viewing) and can also include  three distance markers, a finishing post and a ditch behind the last post.
A room in which music is performed.
A branched, hanging light fitting, often ornate in design, provifding illumination from a number of candles or lightbulbs.

TERM: ROYAL NAVAL AIR STATION CONTROL TOWER
SCOPE_NOTE: A control tower constructed on RNAS stations by the Royal Marine Engineers. Built to a common ground floor plan they could be built with one, two or three storeys above this depending on the requirements of the station.
A three storey RNAS control tower, incorporating meteorological office on the ground floor and an air watch office on the second floor.

A four-storey RNAS control tower. The first floor contained offices for the commander flying and meteorological offices and the upper two floors, in the form of a central tower, provided offices for air traffic control.
Based on a typical 18ft span, 40ft long temporary brick hut but with two bay windows in the front elevation, one for the watch office and one for the chief instructor.
Stone used for grinding or polishing during the manufacture of lithic implements
A small, single storey building used as the Pilots' room on fighter stations and as the watch office on bomber stations.

A two-storey, structure with a brick ground floor and a reinforced concrete upper floor with balcony and large windows to the watch office and control room. This became the most common building design for air traffic control in the Second World War.
A small building housing pilot's and locker rooms with flight offices and a watch office. The only known example was built at Tangmere.
A two-storey watch office, built to Air Ministry drawing number 1959/34. It became the standard design for watch offices with a large, almost square, ground plan with a central observation tower.
A temporary settlement established as a public protest against an aspect of government policy or more specifically the development of a site.
An informal encampment, usually near a military establishment, set up as a public protest against that establishment or against some aspect of military policy.
Small, heavily built coble, usually fitted with lugsail and oars, used on the north-east coast of England to assist, tow, pilot, provision or otherwise attend ships.
A float or pontoon supporting a flexible steel roadway as part of a Mulberry Harbour.
A building where advice and aid appertaining to physical and economic wellbeing of disadvantaged members of a community are made available.
An establishment from which food is distributed to the public during wartime or similar states of emergency.
The examination of material by physical means, including detailed observation.
Microscopic mineral body (usually silica) found in many plants.
Material that has been penetrated or disrupted by the roots or rhizomes of plants.
Light microscopy in which vibration directions of the light are constrained into single planes.

Use for pollen and diaspores. Pollen consists of pollen grains which are the male gametes of flowering plants. Diaspores are the dispersive units of mosses, ferns, fern allies and some plants. To describe the actual object use PLANT REMAINS.
The measurement of the ratio of a radioactive potassium (K) isotope and the argon (Ar) gas produced as a by-product of its decay. Useful for dating volcanic material older than 1,000 years.

The measurement of the ratio of the radioactive Carbon 14 (C-14) isotope and non-radioactive carbon isotopes. Useful for dating organic materials such as wood and bone between 500 and 45,000 years old.
Material comprising entrie or partial transverse sections of stems. Bark may be present or not. Can include complete sections of tree trunk but generally comprises smaller (<20cm diameter) material.
A process using an electron microscope in which the surface of the specimen is scanned by a beam of electrons which are reflected to form an image. Very high magnification is possible.
Use for any shell of an animal, principally, molluscs, crabs etc.
Use for material that has been burnt at high temperature in a good air supply such that only the silica component remains.
A precious metal of lustrous, white colour with great malleability and ductility.
Use for the remains of epidermis or outermost layer. Relates to both animals and plants. If describing the actual object use PLANT REMAINS, ANIMAL REMAINS or HUMAN REMAINS.
The analysis of the amount of phosphorus (P) present in a soil.

The recovery of material from samples collected during field investigations, usually taken by specialists with a particular area of expertise. Normally processed in the laboratory. Also use for the processing of samples subsequent to investigation.
The application of a chemical test to a material, usually as a rapid approximation.
Comparison of different proportions of natural occurring isotopes of lead (Pb), strontium (Sr), oxygen (O), carbon (C) and nitrogen (N).
The careful observation and written description of the physical characteristics of stratigraphy. It will normally include information on texture, colour and the nature of the different components.
The use of ash and tephra deposits characteristic of single known-date volcanic eruptions to date stratigraphic sequences.

The measurement of the light emitted from sedimentary minerals, mineral inclusions in bricks, burnt flint or unburnt calcite when they are heated. The signal relates to their prior exposure to radioactivity. Used to date samples up to 500,000 years old.
Use where evidence of tool marks is present
Use for teeth, hard structures found in the jaws of vertebrates used principally for chewing and eating.
The analysis of organic plus inorganic phosphorus (P).
The use of annual incremental growth in temperate trees to investigate environmental, especially local, parameters and the history of individual trees.
Small (<2cm diameter) roundwood often complete with buds or leaf scars.
The measurement of the decay of radioactive uranium (U) isotopes. Particularly useful for dating calcite and sometimes bone, tooth and shell up to 70,000 years old.
Hard, compact, unprocessed, fibrous cellulose substance. The roots, trunks and branches of trees and shrubs consist of this tissue.
Use for any material that shows evidence of modification by humans.
The production of an image on a photographic plate as a result of X-rays (very short wavelength electromagnetic radiation) being passed through an object.

A surface technique that uses the diffraction of X-rays to examine the mineral composition of a sample. Useful for identifying corrosion products, pigments etc. but of little use with organic compounds which consist largely of carbon, oxygen and hydrogen.

A surface technique of spectroscopic analysis which relies on the interaction of primary X-rays with the sample to generate a range of secondary X-rays. These have energies characteristic of the elements present in the sample.
Fairground attraction designed to create optical illusions to give a sense of unbalance and unease.
Fairground attraction containing a number of ghoulish displays designed to scare visitors.
A building containing soft play equipment for children.
A room, usually in a hospital, in which a number of beds are located.
A sitting room or lounge in a house intended mainly for use during the morning.
A room set aside for the purpose of reading, such as in a library or a club.
A room in a house, hotel, business premises etc. where guests or visitors are received.
A roof featuring a covering of straw, reeds, rushes etc. used extensively during the medieval period but also popular in rural or rustic architecture.
A group of electricity-producing windmills or wind turbines.
An apparatus designed with a large vaned wheel rotated by the wind in order to generate electricity.
A building or compound housing a permanent establishment of members of a religious organization to do missionary work.
An opening or cavity through which a stream or natural watercourse disappears underground.
A board, wall painting or other structure displaying advice, giving information or directions
A sundial capable of giving an accurate reading of standard time to the minute.
A tunnel built to allow internees (in a camp, prison etc.) to escape.
Area of land set aside and managed for the preservation of flora, fauna, their natural habitats and physical features.
Set of three seats for the clergy found in the chancel
Fossilized animal dung, often ground into powder and used as fertilizer.

A small clinker-built craft, dating primarily from the 19th and early 20th centuries, fitted with oars and often a sail, usually found on the north-east coast of England and used for fishing or pilotage.
Garden or open-air enclosure, usually connected to commercial premises, where tea and other refreshments are served to the public.
House, where destitute Jews converted to Christianity after the expulsion. Latin for "House of Converts".

A decorative emblem stating the name of a village or town and depicting aspects of the place's history of culture. Most signs are mounted on a post and usually errected in a central position near the church or village green.
A recess or cupboard within a church, usually positioned near the altar, used for the storage of sacred vessels.
Shelter on military airfield to provide night time accommodation for airmen during WWII.

A facility where natural gas is made smaller in volume, to facilitate its distribution through the National Transmission System. Term can also be used for a station, which recompresses the gas to the required pressure.

A room provided for the use of people waiting for a service, such as a train or bus service, or to see an individual such as a doctor or a dentist. When a dedicated structure, see Thesaurus of Monument Types.
A building or other establishment used for the retail, making and repairing of jewellery.
A large Mediterranean cargo or transport vessel of the 15th to 17th century, usually less than 400 tons.
British, single-engined, light day bomber biplane. Built in 1923, this was the RAF's first interbellum designed day bomber.
A stand, either fixed or free-standing, usually with a sloping surface from which a bible, book or notes can be read, found in a church or lecture theatre.
A room containing one or more thrones.
A room within a school, private house or institution used for lessons.
A room equipped for the care of babies and young children.
Originally a room in a house where a family would gather, usually in the evening, to sit and read, write, sew, play music etc. This term has become commonly used as an alternative to living room.
A government employment agency for those out of work offering advice on jobs, training and retraining.
A room within a house or building used to exhibit artworks, often decorated and lit accordingly.
A room where organizations and associations meet for the undertaking of presentations and consultation.
A room intended for the purpose of teaching a group or class of students simultaneously.
A room in a public house, hotel, club etc. containing a bar from which alcoholic drinks are served.
A decorative structure of wood stone or metal, incorporating a shelf, surrounding the opening of a fireplace.
In Roman architecture either 1. A block of buildings enclosed by four streets or 2. A large tenement house or apartment block.
A meeting room intended specifically for the use of a board of directors or governors of an organization or company..
A room equipped with apparatus to facilitate physical exercise, gymnastics or indoor sports.
A large room within a school or college used and appropriately furnished for the sitting of examinations by students..
The area or platform at the top of a staircase.
A channel that returns water that has been used to turn a waterwheel back to the river or source from which it came.

An apparatus, featuring an ascending and descending platform or compartment, for carrying people or objects from one level or floor to another. This term can include the shaft or well in which such an apparatus operates.
Starshaped cairn with three radial arms of equal length, a monument unique to upland Northumberland. (Late Neolithic or early Bronze Age).
An area or series of tiles applied, usually to an interior floor or wall's surface, for practical or decorative effect.
A telephone exchange housing one end of an underwater cable and used to send messages overseas.
A ditch constructed to surround a town for defensive purposes.
Redcar and Cleveland
A box or cupboard enclosing the fuses for the electrical circuits within a building.

A pass, vulnerable to attack from the enemy but essential for the movement of troops and which, if captured, could divide a defending force. As a result such passes are defended with anti invasion defences such as pillboxes.
An area, often a village, with fixed defences such as pillboxes, anti tank ditches and gun emplacements, designed to stop the advance of an enemy force and to hold out for an agreed period of time.

A piece of metal or wood, or other material used in the manufacture of an item, intended for further fabrication and therefore representing an unfinished object. Usually relates to objects manufactured in quantity such as coins, knives etc.
A flat, circular plate, usually made of iron, on which food items are baked.

A piece of wire or similarly flexible material shaped to form a clip for fastening papers together; invented by the Norwegian Johann Vaaler in 1899.  The familiar double-oval 'Gem' clip was developed by Gem Manufacturing Ltd. in England the same year.
Purpose built or modified structure used for scenery in a film.
A suburb of a town, especially Roman or Medieval, situtated or extending beyond its formal limits, usually demarked by defences.
Purposely built camp with recreational facilities and individual chalets for accommodation.
Lead which has been rolled into a sheet and often used as a roof covering.
A concave glass dish used to hold material for observation or experimentation; so named for its resemblance to the disc covering the face of a watch.
An object marked or shaped by the pressure of another object upon its surface, whether by deliberate process or unintentionally.
A device, often consisting of a cyclinder containing a piston or plunger, used to raise or move liquids or gasses by means of compression, lifting or suction.
A tube, cyclinder or similar casing enclosing the mechanism of a pump.
Three-dimensional artwork usually created out of stone, e.g. marble; metal, e.g. bronze; ceramics, e.g. terracotta, or other suitable materials.
A tool, featuring a straight, horizontal handle from which extends a metal hook halfway along its length, used by a shearman (one who shears sheep) in the handling of wool.
The metal ornamental bedding and surround in which a gem or stone is mounted.
A piece of material that has been inlaid, or prepared and shaped for inlaying, in an object, decorative feature or other setting.
A carved or moulded decorative projection adorning an object or, in the case of architectural features, the termination of a moulding or the intersection of ribs or beams.
A straight rod, made of glass, plastic or other materials, used  to agitate or mix chemicals, pigments, beverages or other fluids or substances.
Machinery, e.g. drive wheels, used in powering and excavating mines, i.e. mines for the extraction of minerals such as coal, lead or tin.

Rocket projector site with a circular or octagonal concrete holdfast, 1.5m across, surrounded by a 4.6m radius octagonal concrete surround. Six such rocket projectors were arranged in a 3 x 2 grid. Personnel shelters placed midway between each site.
64 Type DFW55373 projector sites arranged in and 8x8 grid or in 4 groups of 16. 30m between each projector, with hardened personnel and ammunition shelters located midway between each
6 DFW55373 projector emplacements spaced in a 3x2 rectangular gid, but each spaced 35m apart. No blast protection was provided at the shelters, which were placed between the projector emplacements.
An exterior, vertical pipe that carries rainwater from a roof's guttering, usually to a drain.

A shelter for doves or pigeons, often containing nesting boxes, either free-standing or built into other structures (barns, towers etc.). If a dedicated,  free-standing structure, index with MONUMENT TYPE: DOVECOTE.
A structure, part of a structure or area constructed from plain bricks.
A trough or watercourse constructed to collect rainwater from a roof and channel it towards a drain or pipe.
Small ornamental pyramid or cone, often decorated, crowning a spire, turret, buttress etc.
An area of plasterwork modelled or incised with ornamental designs or motifs.
A raised platform, especially in a theatre or auditorium, for the use of performers or speakers etc.
An inclined wooden trough which channels grain evenly from the feed hopper into the eye of the stones in a corn mill.
A mechanism, either automated or consisting of winches and pulleys, that raises sacks of grain on ropes or chains from one floor of a mill to another, usually through one or a series of trap doors.
A casement, usually wooden, in a mill enclosing the grindstones and preventing the loss of ground material before it is channelled into sacks.
A funnel-like container from which grain or other material is fed to a grinding mechanism below.
The primary mechanism within an engine or device that transmits motion, especially rotary motion, to  wheels, cogs, turntables etc.
The main gearwheel in a water mill, sharing the same shaft as the exterior waterwheel but placed within the mill.
The first driven gearwheel on the vertical shaft within a corn mill which meshes with the brake wheel in a  windmill, or the pit wheel in a watermill.
The gearwheel on the upright shaft within a windmill from which secondary drives operating other parts of the machinery are powered. are taken
A large gearwheel which, together with a smaller gear called a pinion, connects two parrallel shafts and, in a corn mill, drives the stone nuts.
A flat, circular stone, usually made of sandstone, used in pairs for grinding corn and other meal.
Pinion which engages with the spur wheel and drives the millstones in a corn mill.
A funnel, connected to an opening in the floor of the tun encasing the grindstones in a corn mill, that carries ground meal away to a bin or sack.
A channel or pipeline that feeds water to a waterwheel.
A gate or valve that controls the flow of water from a reservoir, harbour, etc..
A mechanical device, used in a corn mill, that separates bran from meal to produce a whiter flour.
A device which automatically controls a particular funtion within a machine or mechanism, such as regulating the gap between millstones in a windmill.
The large main axle on which a waterwheel, which turns the shaft, and a pitwheel are mounted.
A mechanical device, used in a corn mill, that sieves and grades flour or meal and separates oversized particles.
The main vertical axle running through the centre of a mill.
The main axle projecting through the front of a windmill on which the sails are mounted.

A small three-masted lateen-rigged vessel used exclusively in the Mediterranean from the 16th to the 19th century. Its hull was similar in form to that of a polacre but with an extended bow and stern.
The residence or official premises of a consul, the official appointed by a state to protect its citizens and commercial interests in a foreign state.
A channel, usually placed upstream of a mill, that carries water from a river or other water source to a waterwheel.

Privateer operating under government licence to act against enemy merchant shipping. The term is closely associated with North African privateers which operated off the Barbary coast prior to the mid-1800's.
The main vertical beam standing at the centre of a post mill carrying the bearing upon which the body of the mill rotates.
The rotating top section of a tower or smock mill.
A small brewery, often situated in a public house, producing limited quantities of beer, for consumption locally and/or on the premises.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany
Scotland
East Lothian, Scotland
Stadium housing a track and associated buildings and structures for the public racing of greyhounds.
Lancashire
Scotland
Angus, Scotland

A wall within a lead mine surrounding a dressing floor, where waste from mining and smelting is deposited, to protect livestock from entering and consuming contaminated material and becoming poisoned, or 'bellanded'.
A building with a range of educational and recreational facilities for the exclusive use of its all-female membership.
A cleansing house associated with Jewish burial ceremonies
An enclosed encampment, often featuring temporary or semi-permanent structures, used for the detention of prisoners of war, refugees or other civilians detained on political or social grounds.
A flat, horizontal piece of  timber or masonry projecting  from or recessed into a wall to hold objects.
Used to identify the variations of an aircraft. Index with Manufacturer, Form and Function.
Mark 1 or the first production variation of an aircraft.
A channel or casing containing and protecting wiring, piping etc.

Unspecified Second World War anti-aircraft battery. There were three types of battery. The U2P and U20P had different arrangements of DFW55373 projector sites for the 20-barrelled 3" projectors. The U9P mounted 12-barrelled projectors.
This is the top term for the class. This class includes terms with very broad definitions which could be assigned to three or more classes. See UNASSIGNED Class List for narrow terms.
A plinth or pedestal, usually of concrete, to which an anti aircraft or coastal battery gun was fitted. Holdfasts are often the only evidence for a weapon which survive.
A centre in which the public donate blood that will be used for the care of patients in hospitals.
A site in which one or more searchlights and their accompanying structures were positioned to locate enemy aircraft or surface vessels for the benefit of batteries and night fighter aircraft.
Gun emplacement for static or mobile light anti aircraft artillery.
Unable to identify actual place from documentary sources alone.
64 Type DFW55373 single projector sites arranged in an 8x8 grid or in 4 groups of 16. 30m between each projector, with hardened personnel and ammunition shelters located midway between each
Mistranscription from original source
Unable to identify actual place from documentary sources alone.
Range used by the Navy with reinforced observation huts which housed quadrant equipment to record accuracy and damage.
Unable to identify actual place from documentary sources alone.
A roof consisting of trusses that have a pair of brackets supporting the hammer posts that in turn support the rafters.
The main gear wheel, which is engaged by a brake to halt or slow the machinery, mounted on the windshaft of a windmill.
The area at the end of an axle or shaft around which a wheel, bearing etc. pivots or rotates.
An adjustable, horizontal beam, supporting the vertical stone spindle in a water or windmill, which allows the gap between the grinding stones to be varied.
A large tank or cask for storing or holding goods, whether liquid, such as chemicals or fermenting beer, or dry, often during a production process.
A building or buildings used for the production of pens.
The large wooden framework that supports the grinding wheels in a corn mill.
An undershot waterwheel, developed by General Jean Victor Poncelet (1788-1867) in France, which improved efficiency through the replacement of flat, wooden paddles with curved, metal vanes.

An enclosed structure, usually glass fronted, designed to contain, and facilitate the viewing of, objects or notices. May be built into the fabric of a room, affixed to an exterior or exterior wall or free standing.
Fine art depiction in oil, watercolour or other media on wood panels, canvas or paper
A room in which disused items, such as furniture, are stored.
A building or buildings used for the production of whistles.

An enclosed structure of brick, stone or metal in which material is heated or burned, or, in a domestic context, food is cooked, through the continuous radiation of heat from its floor, walls or ceiling.
A counter from which beverages are served in a bar room.
A workroom or apartment, often with a north-light, used for the creation of artwork by painters, sculptors etc.
A communal wash area, sometimes a dedicated outbuilding, or facility, such as a basin or trough, used by monks.
A panel, usually wooden or stone, painted or engraved with an illustration or inscription.
An interior wall, usually not load bearing, that divides a space.
A device, monogram or symbol incised in stonework by a mason as a means of identifying his work. Particularly common in Romanesque and Gothic buildings.
A place where telephones and their components are manufactured
An establishment where beauty treatments and associated therapies are provided by professional practitioners.

A horizontal surface separating the base of a rampart or earthwork from an associated ditch or moat. Can also refer to a continuously sloping bank of earth against a wall, as in a fortified city wall.
A section of roadway attached at one end to a harbour or dockside and ending at a landing stage, rising and falling with the tide, for the loading and unloading of vehicles and pedestrians.
A large area, usually open-air, used for permanent, seasonal or regular shows, events or exhibitions.
Former name of Vaasa when part of Grand Duchy of Finland.
An establishment for the preparation and selling of food to be consumed off the premises.
A tool with an edged head and a wooden shaft, used for a variety of purposes.
A weapon featuring a single or double edged head attached to a wooden shaft.
One of a number of tiles cemented together to form pillars supporting the floor above a hypocaust.
One of the component tiles used in the construction of a tile hearth, being the floor of, or area in front of, a fireplace.
A three-cornered arrowhead.
An arrowhead with its base hollowed to allow it to fit onto the shaft of an arrow rather than having a tang that fits into the shaft.
Animal remains bearing evidence, such as knife marks on bones, that they were slaughtered and used for food.
Debris resulting from the manufacture of tools and other artifacts from bone.
Rendering material containing lime and sand spread on walls as a pliable mixture before drying to a hard surface.
A construction material made by the firing or baking of clay.
A hard, unglazed earthenware, characteristically reddish-brown in colour, used in decoration and construction.
A collection of associated artefacts recovered from a single site.
An object decorated or otherwise marked by the use of a stamp; for example, a maker's stamp.
Remains of any of the groups of animals characterized by having a bony or cartilaginous spinal column (backbone) and a well developed brain.
Remains of one of the groups of animals characterized as lacking any form of backbone or spinal column.
Mark 2 or the second variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Remains of Bryozoa, which are small animals, usually marine, that form colonies producing coral-like skeletons or jelly-like masses.

Remains of animals characterized as having bodies made up of annular segments, such as worms and leeches. Earthworm eggs and granule comonly occur. Bristle worms are found associated with marine molluscs.
Remains of the animal group characterized by having jointed limbs and segmented bodies, including woodlice, spiders, insects etc. Note, crustaceans have been included in this category.
Remains of the animal group Crustacea: hard-shelled arthropods which are largely aquatic. Use for the remains of shrimps, prawns, crabs and lobsters, and also woodlice.
Remains of arthropods characterized as having a body divided into two segements and four pairs of legs, such as spiders, scorpions, ticks and mites.
Remains of the group of animals characterized as being radially symmetrical in form, such as sea urchins, sea cucumbers and starfish.
Remains of parasitic or free-living worms of the phylum Nematoda, characterized as having slender, cylindrical unsegmented bodies. Cysts of Heterodera commonly occur archaeologically
A Mark 1B aircraft which has undergone further modification to enhance performance or armament.
A WWII British biplane produced by Hawker Aircraft, used for army cooperation duties.
Mark 5 or the fifth variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
A Mark 2B aircraft with which has undergone further modifications to enhance performance or armament.
A US aircraft manufacturer. The Cessna Aircraft Co Inc was established in 1927
A twin engined advanced trainer aircraft developed for the military by the US firm of Cessna
Beech Aircraft Corporation, also known as Beechcraft, established 1932
A twin engine advanced trainer developed by Beech/ Beechcraft , a US firm, used in WWII
A Mark 5A aircraft which has undergone further modifications to enhance performance or armament.
Mark 3 or the third variant of an aircraft with its associated modifications.
Former name of Kolobrzeg
Fish eggs, e.g. from cod or, for example, caviar.
Oared sailing vessel developed in the 15th century, the larger English version with secondary oars coming into use in the 16th century. Not to be confused with GALEAS.
An inclined ramp of earth, stone or brick used to deliver fuel to the firing hole of a kiln. Mediaeval and later.
Series of machines for mechanically slaking lime. 20th century.
A quarry for the extraction of Soapstone (also known as steatite or soaprock), a metamorphic rock largely composed of the mineral talc and rich in magnesium.
A quarry for the extraction of Serpentine, a major metamorphic mineral which is easily polished and easily carved. A major variety, lizardite, is found in Cornwall.
A range of techniques that use the build up of charge stored within a crystalline material to estimate its age
A technique that uses the emission of gamma rays of specific energies to identify the presence and concentration of certain radioactive isotopes in a sample
A technique that uses the emission of alpha particles of specific energies to identify the presence and concentration of certain radioactive isotopes in a sample
Material used for construction, commonly fired in its manufacture.
Object produced commonly by firing clay, but can include coarser material to temper it.
A form of silica, similar to quartz. Commonly black or white in colour and used for tool manufacture. Flints heated in antiquity may be dated using thermoluminescence.
A material composed of mineral grains derived from the breakdown of rocks by environmental processes.
Any carbonate material produced by biological activity, for instance operculae of snails.
A mineral composed of SiO2. Commonly clear or milky in appearance. A common constituent of rocks and sediments.
A group of aluminosilicate minerals with varying compositions. The most common mineral in igneous rocks, and common in other rocks and sediments.
A mineral of the composition Zr[SiO4]. Commonly brown or yellow in colour. May contain high levels of uranium and thorium. Can be used for dating using luminescence or fission track methods.
A general term to describe a sediment or sample that contains a variety of different minerals.

Area or zone of sea where a battle, skirmish or action was fought between naval ships or warships and privateers. Not to be used for enemy action upon mercantile ships or a sudden strike by mine/torpedo against an enemy warship.
A settlement used for trading.
1st World War end-opening aeroplane hangar.
1st World War end-opening aeroplane hangar.
1st World War end-opening aeroplane hangar.
Moorings for a seaplane not part of a seaplane base.
1st World War end-opening aeroplane hangar.
An arcade providing shelter for perishable market goods which also provides protection from the elements for the occupants of the adjoining properties.
Vertical screens made of wood or steel framing mounted on concrete blocks were built to protect airships from cross winds when entering or leaving the airship sheds.

Underwater investigation of the seabed, using side-looking sonar device that emits fan shaped acoustic pulses down toward the seafloor. The intensity of the acoustic reflections from the sea floor are recorded as an image of the seabed.

An acoustic method which involves the creation of a shock wave through the ground. By recording the time interval between the initial shock and the reflected or refracted shock waves it is possible to define subsurface deposits.
A sensing technique that consists of measuring minute variations in the gravitational pull of the Earth in order to detect gravity anomalies arising from voids and cavities within the earth.

Observations made by antiquarians (Those who studied sites and landscapes prior to archaeology and architectural history becoming established disciplines in the 19th century) and reported through publication or from unpublished manuscripts.
Field survey undertaken to investigate land formation processes often carried out in association with, or in the vicinity of, an archaeological site, or as part of a wider landscape project.
The recording of a surface, or surfaces, using scanning technologies, to create a 3D model of the target structure/object.

The unplanned observation of archaeological features or the recovery of artefacts of interest, for example either random finds by members of the public or the unplanned observation of archaeological features during the course of unmonitored developments.
The taking of photographs during informal site visits, which may be undertaken by amateur archaeologists or architectural students. More formal, detailed surveys should be termed Photographic Survey.
An end scraper that has a retouched end which is convex in form. (Source: SARC)
An end scraper made on a flake that is wider than it is long. (Source: SARC)

An end scraper which has a retouched end that is straight in form. If the tool blank is a blade or flake, and the retouch is abrupt retouch rather than scraper retouch then use either Truncated blade or Truncated flake. (Source: SARC)
An end scraper which has a retouched end that is concave in form. (Source: SARC)
A side scraper with a short concavity retouched into an edge. This may be achieved by a single blow. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a half moon or crescent shape. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a point, usually with oblique retouch. They are synonymous with 'obliquely blunted points' of the English Mesolithic. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a triangular shape. They can be sub-divided into scalene and isosceles triangles. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a trapezium shape. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a rectangular shape. (Source: SARC)
A microlith retouched to a thomboid shape. (Source: SARC)

A stone axe in which the surface is fully covered by negative removals. Core axes may be made on flakes and have part of the flake's original surface but this cannot be part of the edge otherwise use FLAKED AXE. (Source: SARC)

A stone core with a conical form and a core platform which may or may not be prepared. Blades are removed around the circumference of the platform. The end of the core opposite the platform usually tapers to a point. (Source: SARC)

A small stone core with a conical form and a single core platform which may or may not be prepared. Microblades are removed form the circumference of the platform. The end opposite the platform usually tapers to a point. (Source: SARC)

A stone core made on a large thick flake and characterized by a distinctive, unworked or slightly-shaped handle section. The platform is plain and microblades are detached mainly form the front section of the core. (Source: SARC)

A core which has two opposing platforms. One end serving as the main platform for the removal of blades - the other being used to straighten the face of the core and correct knapping errors. Removals are taken from the full circumference. (Source: SARC)

A core used to produce flakes from a single plain platform. The base of the core, or 'keel', is often formed by alternate removal from a process resembling cresting. Often one end has a relatively unmodified section. (Source: SARC)
A channel carrying overflow water past a dam. Early 19th century onwards.
A bridge used for carrying liquids, usually water, although sometimes oil, in a pipeline over a river. Mid 19th century onwards.
A pond used for dissipating heat by evaporation from steam engine condensate. Mid 19th century to mid 20th century.
A site, building or factory where seawater is used in the production of salt.
A multi-level structure designed to simulate tall buildings to allow firefighters to practice firefighting and rescue techniques
An impulse water turbine comprising a wheel with hemispherical cups arranged around the circumference using high water pressure to revolve the wheel.
A pier used to raise a structure or building above ground floor level so that there is open space beneath the structure
A pit used to bury a large number of people who have died, or been killed, either as a result of warfare, epidemics or natural disasters.

Any one of the cargo vessels of that name belonging to the different Baltic nations, in use from the mid 18th to the early 20th century. Usually ketch-rigged. Not to be confused with the oared GALEASS.
Observations made by an archaeologist or architectural historian as the result of a field visit to a site or monument.
A geophysical technique for imaging subsurface structures in cross section from electrical measurements made at the surface, or by electrodes in one or more boreholes.
A coupled timber built end-opening First World War aircraft hangar.
A landing circle marked out in white used as the airfield symbol.

Test pits dug by geotechnical engineers or engineering geologists to obtain information on the physical properties of soil, sediments and bedrock around a site to design earthworks and foundations for proposed structures.
A Very High Frequency device to allow aircraft to pinpoint their position as an aid to naviagation. Built as part of the Rotor programme.

An emplacement housing mobile sound locating acoustic dishes/horns for the detection of incoming enemy aircraft and the triangulation of their positions so that they could be targeted by Anti aircraft guns.
A building which has been fortified, often as a temporary measure rather than as part of the original design
An holistic approach to landscape, using GIS, which maps diversity of landscape character as a means to managing future change in ways that are appropriate and sustainable.

A map-based understanding of coastal and marine historic character; its GIS and linked texts extend Historic Landscape Characterisation principles to give a common framework of baseline information for the sustainable management of change from land to sea
The accurate survey and analytical depiction of earthworks and their relative chronological relationships by means of hachures and related symbols.
A rectangular multi-storey block of flats, greater in width than height.
A tall multi-storey block of flats, slender with a square plan.
Block of flats incorporating broad, street-width balconies to give access to dwellings and connect to other blocks.
Block of flats within which the individual dwellings are accessed by narrow external balconies.
A clip for marking or holding down pages in a book.

A specific type of hook used in textile production, also known as a sheer board hook. Harbicks were used in pairs to secure a cloth to a cropping board so that the nap (of the cloth) could be sheared.
A core with more than two distinct platforms usually including one or two striking surfaces and the the traces of former platforms. Usually restricted to flake production. (Source: SARC)

A stone core which is irregular in shape. It can have numerous usuable or abandoned striking platforms. It is the most common core type and it is often the last attempt of a knapper to extract the final usable flakes form the core. (Source: SARC)
A matzevah from the Ashkenazi group of Jews descended from medieval Jewish communities of the Rhineland and Eastern Europe.  Characterised by upright headstones with Hebrew Inscriptions

A jar-shaped vessel with pierced apertures or cut-out on an open or closed pedestal base. Herbs, spices or scented woods would be placed in the pot and a burning coal placed underneath to warm the herbs so they would release their scent.
Canal docks where the freeboard of a boat was marked. By placing increasing ton weights at 4 points around the boat, its displacement could be marked for toll purposes.
A heating apparatus in which coals or embers are placed in the pedestal or base below a container in which food or liquid could be held and kept warm.
A small, handled, open vessel, generally with a steep profile, designed to sit partially within a larger vessel and used to warm drinks. (Source: MPRG)
A matzevah from the Sephardi group of Jews descended from medieval Jewish communities of the Iberian Peninsular and Northern Africa.  Characterised by flat slabs with Hebrew Inscriptions

A vessel used as the lower part of a distillation unit consisting of a round-bottomed vessel with walls sloping inwards towards the rim. Some examples may have an external flange to support the upper unit (ALEMBIC). (Source: MPRG)
A deep, rectangular or oval, straight-sided vessel with an everted, crenellated rim, used to hold either wax for dipping candles or molten sulphur for dipping matches. (Source: MPRG)
A costrel with a barrel-shaped body and a centrally placed neck. One end is usually flat and the other domed. Two opposed strap handles or lugs join the rim or neck and shoulder. (Source: MPRG)
A costrel with a cylindrical body and a centrally placed neck. One end is usually domed and the other flat. Two opposed strap handles or lugs may join the rim or neck and shoulder. (Source: MPRG)

A costrel with a flattened spherical form: the back is flat and the front domed or mammiform. The base may be slightly flattened or rounded. Two opposed strap handles or lugs join the rim or neck and shoulder. (Source: MPRG)
A costrel with a narrow-mouth and two opposed handles or lugs on the shoulder.
A complex of buildings where barytes is processed for industrial use.
A mechanically operated display board used in greyhound racing, which showed the state of the Tote, or cumulative betting on individual greyhounds.
A site including a pitch, stands and other ancillary buildings associated with the game of rugby.
A building or room used for the repair and maintenance of machinery in a large complex, such as a hospital, school or factory.

Any object, often made of ceramic or 'porcelain' used for the purposes of personal cleansing, especially fittings such as toilets, baths and basins. May survive as fragments in the archaeological record. Use more specific term where known.
Loose fibres obtained by unpicking old ropes. Mainly used to caulk seams in wooden vessels.
A conical container, usually made of earthenware, into which boiling sugar was poured and allowed to crystallize.
A metal safe built in to wall
A building or group of buildings used for the raising of mink, a semi-aquatic mammal which is farmed for its fur.
A place of worship for the followers of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints
A fertilizer derived from nitrogen; also known as nitrate of ammonia.
A building housing one end of an underwater telegraph cable.
A 19th century ore processing works which processed the waste material from a mine.
Mediaeval-17th century mining method which involved exploiting an exposed surface vein. Rarely associated with waste.
Hydrocarbon secretion of a tree or bush, either naturally exuded or deliberately tapped from the tree, valued for its varied uses in chemicals and perfumery.
An extractive pit or pits, usually 2.5m square by 2m deep dug to extract tin ore in areas where streamworking is not possible. Usually dug along a vein rather than across it.
Large granite stone used as the base stone of a stamping mill against which ore was crushed. Contains distinctive striations from the crushing process.
A stone with a rectangular depression into which molten metal, usually tin, was poured to create ingots.
A cylindrical device using ceramic or metallic balls to grind materials like ores, chemicals, ceramic raw materials and paints
A supported, roof structure covering all, or part, of a railway platform.
A site used for the functional testing of aircraft and their components.
A building containing machinery for operating sluices.
A building in which purified charcoal was produced by distillation of wood in sealed cast-iron retorts heated in fire-boxes. Tarry by-products were sometimes recovered by condensation flues.

An area of managed countryside designated for visitors to enjoy recreations, such as walking specified parks and trails, in a rural environment. Often provides public facilities such as parking, toilets, cafes and visitor information.
A building or site incorporating sonar equipment used for detecting the presence of enemy ships or submarines.
