A short squat gun or cannon used to test the strength of coarser blasting powders. Mainly 18th-19th centuries.

Heavy anti aircraft battery used from June 1944-May 1945 to combat the V-bomb threat. They are distinct from normal HAA batteries, being laid out in a V-shape, and early on were mainly for mobile 3.7-inch guns.
WW2 LAA battery consisting of two or four 40m guns or Bofors guns. Associated structures included tented accommodation, ammunition shelters, a 100 gallon water tank, latrines, wash-house and kitchen.
40mm gun emplacement created between 24th-26th June 1944 as part of the fourth deployment of Diver LAA guns to the Kentish Gun Belt. Each site had an extant searchlight battery.
A rigid frame type of airship pioneered by Count Zeppelin and used by the Germans in WWI for military purposes: do not use asa generic name for airships
Place where ships and boats are dismantled.
Any subsurface investigation conducted to assist with the technical rather than archaeological aspects of a proposed development or extraction scheme.

Active sonar systems are based on the behaviour of sound waves in water; acoustic energy is transmitted and the time for the returning echo is measured to allow submerged seabed features to be mapped. Use specific type where known.
An underwater technique that records bathymetric (depth) data by generating point depths in a line directly beneath the transducer mounted on a vessel as it progresses along the acquisition line.

A place of worship for the sect known as 'Cokelers', formed circa 1850 by John Sirgood. Most aspects of Dependent belief are fairly orthodox within the Arminian traditions of Protestant dissent. Chapels can be found in Sussex, Surrey, London and Kent.

A maritime investigation that records depth data which can be used to map submerged topography utilising echo sounders which emit a short acoustic pulse. Depth is calculated by measuring the time taken for the pulse to be reflected back to the transducer.
An establishment where deaf people receive education, training and social support.
A residential home for adults with learning difficulties and/or physical disabilities.

TERM: HOSPITAL FOR PEOPLE WITH LEARNING DIFFICULTIES
SCOPE_NOTE: A hospital where people with learning difficulties receive medical treatment.
A residential home for children with physical or learning disabilities, sensory impairment and/or mental health issues but who do not necessarily need medical attention.
A residential home for children with physical and/or learning disabilities, sensory impairment and/or mental health issues who need medical intervention and/or care provided by registered nurses.
A grouping of retail warehouses and supermarkets with associated car parking.
Microscopic charcoal fragments that are concentrated and counted as part of standard pollen preparation techniques.
A measure of the proportion of water within a sample.
A method of determining peat degradation; quantified as the percentage light transmission value of the extracted humic acids, measured at a specific wavelength.
Roughly spherical, > 5 m, soot particles produced from the incomplete combustion of fossil fuels. Used as an indicator of industrialisation, and can also be used as a dating tool.
Prefabricated small building that is designed and built to be movable rather than permanently located.
Prayer hall at burial ground, especially a small walk-in memorial devoted to a deceased Hasidic rabbi.
Programmes of research that seek to identify the archaeological and/or architectural significance of a site or landscape.

Controlled investigation, recording and removal of archaeological deposits in targeted areas in order to answer specific questions relating to a particular archaeological site or landscape. Usually undertaken by university departments or amateur groups.

The assessment of the age of a hedge based on its nature, condition and the number and type of woody plant species present. Most surveys make use of Hooper's hypothesis which states that for every 27m a new woody species invades a hedge every 100 years.
An engine in which the power is provided by electricity either in the form of batteries or direct from the mains supply.

A maritime technique which involves the simple process of bringing up surface sediments from the seafloor for analysis usually using mechanical apparatus. As the process recovers a mixture of sediments it cannot be used to characterise stratigraphy.

A technique utilised in maritime recording; a remote operated vehicle (ROV) is a tethered underwater robot. ROVs have been used to locate and inspect a number of historic shipwrecks in depths beyond the reach of human divers.

A maritime coring technique which penetrates the ground due to the force of gravity. Since the speed of penetration is the same as the sampling speed, it barely disrupts the sedimentary layers. A cable attached to the ship is used to recover the core.

A maritime coring technique which uses vibration to facilitate ground penetration. With the force of gravity, and sometimes a piston, it can penetrate much deeper layers although the vibration provokes a slight mixing of the sediments.
A school in which students are taught according to the beliefs of the muslim faith.
"Looking glasses", up to and including the medieval period made of polished steel or other reflective metals; later a piece of glass with a reflective coating, e.g. silver or aluminium.
Cargo vessel or warship captured by a warship or privateer of a hostile nation in time of war, usually taken into that nations mercantile, privateering or naval service.
A factory in which varnish is manufactured.
Factory for the production of safety fuses used in the ignition of gunpowder for blasting.
A building or part of a building used for the storage of furniture or furniture related materials.
A room specifically used for the display of furniture and other related materials
An instrument for measuring magnetic forces, especially the strength of terrestrial magnetism.
Metal cylinder for producing charcoal using the retort method
Conventual order of nuns founded in 1253, inspired by the life of St Francis of Assisi
An area used for the training of personnel in civil defence procedures.
A site visit to ascertain the nature and extent of the site and its surrounding environs by means of a visual inspection from which a written and/or photographic record is made.

An underwater technique used to create 3D terrain models and to record objects on the seabed through the comparative analysis of reflections from high frequency sound waves emitted in multiple beams allowing large swathes of the seabed to be surveyed.

An extra processing unit which can be used in conjunction with single beam echo sounders to determine the roughness and hardness of the seafloor. Mainly used for marine biology, but has been used in archaeology.
A planned programme of investigation conducted within a defined area aimed at identifying and surveying previously unrecorded sites and checking the condition of known sites.
Technique using electromagnetic fields to map subsurface electrical conductivity anomalies. Can be used as a high-sensitivity metal detector.

A maritime technique similar in theory to sub bottom profilers, however for 3D seismic surveys the receiver array is more complex involving multiple receivers so that a volume of sediment is studied rather than a single 2D line.

An overview of the historical and architectural development, character and heritage assets of a settlement or area.  An HAA may result in the creation, at varying levels of intensity, of individual site-based records informed by area context.

The investigation of heritage assets along thematic lines, usually to inform the production of a thematic study. Such studies bring specialist insights to bear on the particular area of study, but may not address other aspects of the site's significance.
Transport vessel hired for the enforced removal of convicts to penal colonies abroad(e.g. Virginia, Australia), or for their return to Britain.
Transport vessel, usually a hired vessel of mercantile origin, used for the exchange of prisoners-of-war; sometimes, specifically a hospital ship with such prisoners.
A small narrow rectilinear enclosure with high hedges boundaries for the cultivation and shelter of flowers, particularly Daffodils and Narcissi.
Building used for the display of inscription panels and memorials to those buried in the underlying catacomb.
A house used to accommodate Llamas at a zoo or wildlife park.

A distinctive form of terrace found in the northeast consisting of a long, two storey terrace indistinguishable from a conventional house externally, save that each unit has two front doors, one leading to a separate dwelling or dwellings upstairs.
An enclosure, usually within a zoo, designed to represent the natural environment for Lemurs, including shelter.
A dark outbuilding or cellar with internal recesses for overwintering skeps of bees.
Small vernacular building used by fishermen for the preparing of nets and storage of equipment.

A German aircraft manufacturer of the 1930s and 1940s, pre-war the company were noted for making sailplanes and sports planes; during the Second World War they made military aircraft including flying bombs.

The Fi 103 is the more technical nomenclature for the Second World War German V1 flying bomb, produced by Fieseler. Multiple index together with Fieseler and flying bomb for maximum chance of retrieval for users.

A site where a cable was fired into the air, with parachutes attached to either end, to present an aerial obstruction to bring down, through contact, fouling and general drag, or obstruct the passage of an aircraft. Usually found as one of a group.

A garden or park, with ancilliary buildings, in which young and domesticated animals are kept for public exhibition, especially for children. Children are given the opportunity to come into close contact and handle animals.
An area of either natural or artificial stone arranged to resemble a rocky outcrop or cliff face within animal cages/enclosures of a Zoo.
Mascarene Islands, Africa; dependent territory as a departement of France.
Flat-bottomed barge with shallow draft adapted for carrying bulk cargoes among the shoals of the Thames Estuary; usually spritsail-rigged, though other rigs were permissible.
An area of the sea or coastline where vessels have been abandoned.
A building or group of buildings in which communications signals, usually intercepted fro military purposes, are analysed.
French Banker, fishing vessel for the Grand Banks of Newfoundland, generally three-masted or of brig type, from the late 19th and 20th centuries.
An indoor or outdoor market where hay and straw is sold.
A purpose built theatre with a central open yard, dating to the Elizabethan period. Famous examples include The Globe and the Swan.
An inn temporarily used for the performance of plays and other public entertainment.
Pairs of canal gates (also called Brindley gates) designed to rapidly shut off  a section of a canal to prevent flooding
A building or structure where electricity is generated.
The highest judicial court where appeals can be heard and whose rulings are not subject to further review by another court.

The interpretation of information on aerial photographs usually resulting in the production of maps and records of archaeological sites and landscapes. Many aerial photographs may be consulted for a single analytical survey.
A burial ground for followers of the Islamic faith.

Any animal other than livestock (animals carried as food); animals used for transport (horses; mules); and domestic pets. Such animals may be exported as specimens, for zoos, menageries, and circuses, or as unusual pets (e.g. elephants, monkeys).
A roof with a slope of less than ten degrees to the horizontal.
A church, the plan of which is based on that of a Roman basilica.
Platform, usually stone-built, which holds the winding gear of a mine shaft.
A mechanism used to transport minerals or granulated materials.
An oven used in the coal industry for the recovery of gas, tar and other by-products of the coking process. Late 19th century-20th century.
A factory where general hardware, fittings, items of ironmongery are produced.
A building or part of a building used specifically to store items of hardware and ironmongery.
A room to display various items of hardware and ironmongery.

A prefabricated structure of a steel frame clad in corrugated iron. Semi-circular in section they were used for storage and as workshops, cinemas etc during WWII. Designed at Romney House, London by the Directorate of Fortifications & Works.
A lightweight prefabricated structure of corrugated galvanized steel having a semicircular cross section. The design was based on the Nissen hut developed by the British during the First World War.
A central point for the deposit, collection and recycling of waste materials.
Items worn or carried as an adjunct to clothing, for example, headdresses, sashes, fans, masks etc.
A sweet fluid substance, the nectar of flowers, gathered and worked up for food by insects such as bees.
A key for winding a clockwork mechanism.
Large semi-subterranean feature often packed with straw for the storage of potatoes and other root crops.
A workshop for the manufacturing of furniture.

An establishment where alcoholic and non alcoholic drinks are served, food may also be served. May be a an individual room within a larger multi purpose building such as a sports pavilion or a theatre.
A building housing a double inlet fan that was used for the ventillation of mine shafts
Buildings associated with the extaction of uranium from its pitchblende or copper ores.
Plant for the processing of uranium ores, such as pitchblende. Uranium is the principal extract, but radium may also be recovered as a by-product
Mine for the extraction of bismuth, which usually occurs in small quantities in the ores of other metal ores, particularly lead, and some copper ores.
A building or part of a building used for the storage of shoes or boots.

A type of clinker built wooden boat or ship held together with tendons of flexible wood such as roots and willow branches. Sewn boat construction techniques were used in many parts of the world prior to the development of metal fasteners.
An building, often including recreational facilities, provided for the relaxation of serving Royal Air Force Personnel.
A building or part of a building used for the storage of stationery materials.
A commercial building, or buildings, used for the production of soft drinks.
A large warehouse or store for upholstery.
A building or room used for the exhibition of upholstery for sale.
A ditch which is not continuous but instead is made up of segments which may vary in length and width.
A layer underneath the topsoil containing rubble or fragments of building material, e.g. mortar, tile, flint.
A layer of remains left by a single culture, from which the culture can be dated or identified.
From 1822, any vessel in the service of HM Coastguard, principally deployed on Customs and Revenue duties, i.e. anti-smuggling operations. Superseded the Preventive Service Vessel.

Any vessel in the service of one of the historical or modern agencies concerned with the prevention of inbound or outbound smuggling: namely the Preventive Service, the Coastguard, or the Customs and Excise. Use more specific term.
The taking of photographs from above using photographic equipment mounted on, or used from an aircraft or other airborne vehicle.
Airborne survey to discover, record and monitor archaeological sites and other heritage assets. Sites will usually be recorded by aerial photography.

Any activity, undertaken by professional archaeologists or experienced amateurs, that has a physical impact, actual or potential, upon the archaeological resource, substituting the physical resource with recorded information.
An offshoot of the Wesleyan movement founded in 1838 by John Banyard at Rochford, Essex. In 1956 it changed name to the Union of Evangelical Churches. There are 17 chapels in Essex and London.
A building or area where stone is stored for industrial or agricultural use.
A place of worship and dwelling for members of the Buchanites, a sect that originated from Irvine, North Ayrshire, in the late 18th century.
An object in the sea bed recorded on the Hydrographic Office plot of objects snagged by nets during trawling.
Concrete or steel pontoons that supported the Whale piers. They were moored in position using wires attsched to Kite anchors.
A purpose built tower used for the testing of helicopter rotor blades.
A purpose built apparatus for the testing of helicopters.
The area of a town or city, such as a harbour or dockyard, alongside a body of water.
A site on which rigs, towers and other associated structures and buildings used for the testing of helicopters and helicopter parts are located.
A commercial premises offering advice on destinations and other travel arrangements, and where travellers may purchase flights,make hotel reservations or book package holidays and tours.

TERM: City Of London Coal Duties Boundary Marker

SCOPE_NOTE: A boundary marker for the payment of tax or duty.
A building or subterranean structure used for the storage of beer.
A building or subterranean structure used for the storage of meat.
A space used for the storage of chemicals.
A room containing a boiler, used to provide heating.
An artificial mound created by the disposal of aggregate originally used as ballast in ships.
A mill used for the preparation of Barilla, an ash of burnt seaweed that was used for the production of soda.

A term for any vessel powered principally by sail and oars, or oars alone, used especially for war. As a broad term it may refer to Roman galleys, or more specifically to an Anglo-Saxon or Norse warship of the Viking Age.
Accommodation for the warrener(s) usually located within the boundary of the Rabbit Warren. They also provided a place to store nets, traps and other necessary equipment.
A room or building for hand knitting garments on simple hand frames.
A training ground and fighting arena for knightly sports.
A small opening built into a wall to allow small animals through.
Any building, group of buildings, or site at which tungsten ores have been converted to sodium tungstate by means of the Oxland Process. This was first used at Drakewalls Mine, Cornwall, in 1850.
Any building, group of buildings, or site in which antimony was smelted. Mainly 18th century.

Recording and analysis of built structures utilising close observation as well as manual or electronic survey equipment such as GPS and REDM (Reflectorless Electromagnetic Distance Measurement). Includes research, fieldwork and a report.
Transect or area-based arrangements of drilled auger-holes used to describe deposits and collect samples.
Type of survey involving the drilling of deep and narrow shafts in the ground used to describe deposits, understand stratigraphy and collect cores amples.
A subsurface detection method performed by striking the ground with a heavy wooden mallet or a lead-filled container on a long handle.

A system of excavation, developed by Mortimer Wheeler, whereby a site was uncovered by means of a grid of square trenches with baulks between them to aid the recording of the stratification of all four sides of each trench.

A descriptive survey involving the systematic measurement and recording of the dimensions or features of a building. Where the survey is accompanied by systematic investigation and analysis, use Architectural Survey.

Capturing visible spectrum photographs or images of monument features or character using still or motion cameras from an aircraft or other airborne vehicle or apparatus. Covers both digital and film-based cameras.
The retrieval of samples for laboratory analysis from buried features that have been sampled using boring equipment.

The extraction of wood samples for dating analysis. Tree ring dating is the science of dating cultural and environmental events in the past by comparative study of the growth rings in trees and aged wood.

A programme of assessment of the known or potential archaeological resource within a specified area or site on land, inter-tidal zone or underwater by the consultation and collation of existing written, graphic, photographic and electronic data.

The supposed detection of subsurface features by employing a twig, copper rod, pendulum, or other instrument. Discontinuous movements in these instruments are believed by some to record the existence of buried features.

An information gathering exercise to facilitate an understanding of the potential environmental impact of a development proposal; includes the collation of specialist reports from a variety of disciplines.
Intervention into the archaeological resource intended to gather information about past ecologies and economies, formation processes, and to retrieve material for scientific dating purposes.

Removal of samples from deposits, including archaeological contexts to recover information about past environments and economies, retrieve material for scientific dating and for the investigation of the deposits themselves e.g. formation processes.

A limited programme of intrusive fieldwork which determines the presence or absence of archaeological features, structures, deposits, artefacts or ecofacts within a specified area or site on land or within the inter-tidal zone.

Controlled intrusive fieldwork which examines, records and interprets archaeological deposits, features and structures and, as appropriate, retrieves artefacts and ecofact remains within a specified area or site on land or within the inter-tidal zone.

Periodic visits being made to a site by an archaeologist to record archaeological deposits and recover finds that have come to light since the previous visit. An archaeological presence is not maintained during groundwork as it is with a watching brief.

The non intrusive processes by which information is collected about the location, distribution and organisation of past human activities. The approaches can be either extensive or intensive depending the objectivies that need to be addressed.

The systematic study of ground surfaces and collection of visible archaeological material. Fieldwalking can be carried out as line-walking, grid collection and transect or quadrant sampling. Any material recovered is logged and stored by sample unit.
The taking of samples at regular intervals from the surface of a study area in order to retrieve information on the different chemical elements present.

Ground-based or marine subsurface mapping of archaeological features using different sensing technologies. Most commonly applied are magnetometers, electrical resistance meters, ground penetrating radar, side scan sonar, and electromagnetic conductivity.

A technique that measures the amount of time it takes pulses of  electromagnetic energy sent into the ground, from a transmitter, to reflect back from the interfaces between layers and other subsurface features in order to produce a subsurface profile.

TERM: Infra Red Line Scan Aerial Photography

SCOPE_NOTE: Aerial photography using infrared sensitive film or sensors to reveal soil and vegetation characteristics not apparent in photographs derived from conventional aerial photography.
A specific type of Infrared photography that uses an airborne scanning infrared sensor to record differential spectrums of features both extant and buried.
Use both terms.
A bowl-shaped cavity or depression created in the subsoil by the long term presence and growth of tree roots or when a large tree is blown over or has its stump pulled out.
A shaft cut to facilitate the extraction of salt from halite deposits by pumping water into the deposit and pumping out brine from which the salt is later extracted.
A structure for the storage of brine prior to processing, by evaporation, to extract salt.
A civilian settlement outside a Roman fort.
A large trough or vessel commonly created from a hollowed out tree trunk for the storage of brine prior to processing for salt.
The limit line of a township.
A building housing an electric powered ventilation fan for use in deep mine shafts

An investigative method using an infrared camera to detect temperature differences in the ground. The thermal camera does not record the actual temperature of the object in question. Instead the camera records the infrared radiation emitted by the object.

Light detection and ranging is a type of aircraft based remote sensing which records reflected laser pulses. The data can be used to produce very accurate digital elevation models. For ground-based work use LASER SCANNING SURVEY.

The extraction of samples from selected features on a site to identify a characteristic magnetic response from sediments derived from the features in order to predict the response that similar features would produce. Also used to prospect for sites.

Survey using a magnetometer, a device capable of detecting variations in magnetic susceptibility between topsoils, subsoils and rocks, can also be used in a maritime context to detect variations in the magnetic field of seabed sediments.
A field and desk based assessment of heritage asset condition and vulnerability so that informed decisions can be made regarding how best to manage the resource.
A dimensional check on a building or site giving detailed measurements.

Structured and carefully executed scanning of the ground surface with a metal detecting device in order to recover surface scatters of metal objects and plot them spatially within the study area; a technique useful in battlefield archaeology.

The hobby of using a metal detector to hunt for buried coins or artefacts; alternatively the use of a metal detector to locate metal artefacts on an archaeological excavation that otherwise would go unnoticed.

Recording using specialist equipment that allows discrete wavelengths in the visible spectrum and beyond to be recorded. The combination of different spectral bands allows features to be identified that would not be visible to the naked eye.
Any activities, that have a physical impact upon the archaeological resource where the purpose is not primarily archaeological research.

Controlled investigation, recording and removal of archaeological deposits according to the principles of strategraphic excavation. The size of an open area can range from holes to examine pile foundations to extensive trenches of 100 square meters.
The systematic collection of samples from a defined study area analysed for phosphate content. Elevated concentrations of phosphate are a generalised signature of human activity.

The measurement of a surface, either in elevation or plan, determined from measurements derived from two or more photographic images taken from different positions; this allows three dimensional viewing of the surface to be mapped.

Detailed survey using photographic images to record archaeological and architectural sites or features of interest. Record photography is an important aspect of recording such features before they are destroyed.

Systematic recording of building facades that produces a seamless mosaic of digital images by identifying control points and defining limits to each image. The rectified mosaic can then be introduced into a CAD environment.
Survey using photographic or other recording equipment mounted on or used from either an aircraft or other airborne vehicle or a maritime vessel/submersible craft.
Controlled investigation, recording and removal of archaeological deposits under threat of destruction from building development. A pre PPG 16 activity, usually under strict time constraints.
Examination, recording and plotting of variations in the electrical resistivity of soils in order to locate and define buried features.

The monitoring of the excavation of a hole made by a non-archaeologically trained person. Any archaeological evidence that comes to light is recorded by the archaeologist during the course of the work although he/she cannot suspend the groundwork.

The capture of imagery using an orbiting satellite. The type of imagery is very varied including visible light photography, infrared and multi spectral photography as well as imagery derived from radar and lidar data.
Removal of a sample from a vertical section generally using a U sectioned tin to extract an intact column of the observed stratigraphy. Used in the study of pollen, diatoms etc.

An excavation technique that involves the machine stripping the topsoil/subsoil from the area to be excavated, plotting observed features onto a site plan and then partially or fully excavating those features.

Used to identify and measure various sediment layers that exist below the seabed. A sound source emits a signal vertically downwards and a receiver monitors the return signal that has been reflected off the seafloor and sub seabed sediment layers.
Systematically positioned hole, or holes, utilised in all studies that aim to sample the nature of the topsoil and subsurface deposits.
The extraction of a limited quantity of wood for scientific analysis.

The controlled measurement of natural and artificial landscape features to produce a measured plan or a 3D data set reading as a plan. Features are depicted by either hachures, symbols or contour lines.
An object which has been carved. Use more specific term where known.
A jug with a sinuous profile where the rim, girth and base are of roughly equal diameter, and the neck and lower body are narrower.(Source: MPRG)
A jug with little or no discernible neck and an even, convex profile form rim to base, which are roughly equal in diameter. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with a body profile resembling two cones joined together at their widest points, producing a distinct carination. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with more or less straight sides that flare out from a narrow rim or neck to a wider base. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with straight vertical sides and roughly equal rim and base diameters. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with a rounded profile and a rounded base, i.e. with no discernible basal angle. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with a maximum diameter in the lower half of the vessel and with no discernible shoulder. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with an evenly rounded profile and a discernible basal angle; the maximum diameter is near the mid point and in the upper half of the vessel. (Source: MPRG)

A specific form of rounded jug with a wide mouth, a large parrot-beak spout and three handles in the form of wide straps that spring from the rim to the girth.The spout may have a lug applied to the outside. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with a roughly cylindrical or slightly flaring lower body, a pronounced inward-sloping shoulder and a marked neck/body angle. (Source: MPRG)
A jug with a constriction between the upper and lower body sections. (Source: MPRG)
Any type of jug with decoration representing the form of a human face or figure. The shape of the vessel often forms the outline of the human face or figure. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A type of jug decorated with applied figures in the form of knights in armour. (Source: MPRG)

A jug that incorporates a practical joke or conundrum into its construction. A combination of cut-outs in the body and hollow handles and tubes render conventional use impossible. The puzzle being to work out how to empty it. (Source: MPRG)
A jug form characterized by the addition of three applied feet. The feet are usually short and stubby. Double index with the appropriate profile type. (Source: MPRG)

A jug form which usually has a short, narrow neck and rim and an applied spout. The spout is usually tubular and free standing, or attached to the rim/neck, rising from just above the high shoulder or girth. (Source: MPRG)

A jug with a pierced bunghole just above the base. the bunghole can be made through an applied knob or disc of clay, or simply a hole in the vessel wall. In use, the hole would probably have had a tap or spigot attached. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A circular flask with one or two flattened faces. (Source: MPRG)
A flask with a rounded, almost spherical shape. (Source: MPRG)
A flask with a hollow ring-shaped form. (Source: MPRG)
A jar whose profile resembles two truncated cones joined together at the widest point, forming a carination at the centre of the vessel. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with vertical concave body walls. (Source: MPRG)
A concave sided jar made in tin-glazed earthenware. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with roughly vertical body walls which in some cases may be slightly convex. (Source: MPRG)

A jar with a profile that flares outwards from base to rim, but usually with a constriction at the neck. Squat examples, with a height less than the minimum diameter, could be classified as bowls. (Source: MPRG)
Material, especially rock, worn smooth by the passage of water.
A jar with a rounded profile merging into a rounded base with no discernible basal angle. (Source: MPRG)
A specific form of globular jar with a rounded or very sagging base and an inturned, generally simple, rim. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with a profile that slopes inwards from base to rim. Particularly shallow examples have been term Peat Pots; this is a term with a restricted distribution in northern England. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with an evenly rounded profile. (Source: MPRG)
A specific type of small rounded jar. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with a roughly cylindrical or slightly flaring lower body and a rounded, inward sloping shoulder. (Source: MPRG)
A jar adapted by the addition of a single handle. Profiles vary and should be double indexed with the appropriate JAR type. (Source: MPRG)

A jar with a single handle attached to the rim edge and looped over the top of the vessel. There may be a lip. Profiles can vary and should be double indexed with the appropriate JAR type. (Source: MPRG)

A jar adapted by the addition of two handles. Handles may be horizontal or vertical loops or horizontal or curved lugs. Handles are nearly always opposed. Profiles vary and should be double indexed with the appropriate JAR type. (Source: MPRG)
A factory used for the industrial manufacture of chlorophyll for medical purposes.
A factory used for the industrial manufacture of firelighters.
A site, building or factory where geologically-derived brine is used for the production of salt.
A coastal site producing salt by boiling of unconcentrated seawater in a PANHOUSE, normally using coal fuel.  Foreshore BRINE TANKS may also be present
A coastal site producing salt by solar evaporation of seawater in a series of PONDS, followed by boiling of the concentrated brine in a PANHOUSE
A coastal site producing salt by scraping up salt-impregnated sand and silt, leeching out the salt to produce a concentrated brine, then boiling in 'saltcotes' (small huts containing lead pans)
A coastal site producing salt by solar evaporation of seawater in a series of PONDS, without any boiling stage
A shallow pond containing salt water and used for the manufacture of salt through the evaporation process. For metal vessels associated with the DIRECT BOILING and SLEECHING SALT WORKS use SALT PAN.
A coastal site producing salt by dissolving rocksalt or other impure salt in seawater, then boiling the concentrated brine in a PANHOUSE
A building containing pans in which salt water or brine was boiled to produce salt.
Spice from the bark of an East Indian tree
A hard aromatic seed, obtained from the fruit of an East Indian evergreen tree and used as a spice.
Dried flower buds, used as a pungent aromatic spice.
A handheld lamp used to send morse code messages ship-to-ship or ship-to-shore.The lamp and its reflector can be covered/uncovered by a trigger operated shutter.

TERM: Royal Flying Corps Side Opening Aircraft Hangar

SCOPE_NOTE: Use only for the historic region of North America. For modern places use NORTH CAROLINA or SOUTH CAROLINA.

Archaeologically excavated trench, either hand of machine dug, as part of a sampling programme to evaluate the presence/absence, nature, preservation, age and extent of any buried archaeological features.
The unsystematic study of ground surfaces and collection of visible archaeological material.

A formal programme of observation and investigation conducted during any operation carried out for non-archaeological reasons that may damage archaeological deposits. This will be within a specified area or site on land, inter-tidal zone or underwater.
A flat slab on the top of a capital
Masonry placed to sounteract the thrust of a vault or arch
A recess or niche in a wall.
Two buttresses which meet at a right angle at the corner of the structure they are supporting.
The top stone of a gable end
A moulding in the form of an outward curve.
A curved construction, spanning an opening, formed from wedge-shaped blocks supported by mutual pressure.
Elements which relate to the composition of an arch.
A moulding which is small, convex and circular.
A projecting string course.
A development of plate tracery, from the mid-13th century, using slender shafts and shaped members braching out from the mullions to form a decorative pattern in the window-head.
The inclined face of a wall.
A vertical division, internal or external, not necessarily marked by walls.
Small roll moulding of continuous section, typically less than one inch (25 mm) in diameter.
A chamfer moulding with a small roll moulding of continous section.
An ornamental moulding consisting of a series of small, regularly placed squared or rounded blocks.
Tracery which is applied to the surface of a wall.
Elements applied to a wall without an opening.
An ornamental projection at the intersection of ribs.
A roll moulding in the form of a 3/4 circle projecting from the face of a chamfer.
A projecting stone to carry weight
A structure, part of a structure or area constructed from plain bricks.
An oval window placed with its long axis horizontal.
A mass of masonry or brickwork projectign from or built into a wall to give strength.
A moulding carved to represent a length of rope or cable.
The top part of a column
A vertically hung sash opening in or out.
The notional middle of the circle form all or part of an arch.
A moulding formed when the right-angled edge of a piece of wood or stone is cut away
The stone or brick projection containing the flue.
A masonry or brickwork structure projecting above a roof and containing several flues.
An external covering to a wall for aesthetic or protective purposes.
A buttress which encases the corner between two walls.
A walling material made of clay, gravel, straw and sand (or a combination).
A free-standing upright, circular in section.
A pier with several shafts.
A moulding taking the form of a semi-circle cut into the stone or wood.
A moulding in the form of a semi circle project from the face fo the stone or wood.
The capping or covering of a wall, either plat or moulded, to throw water off.
A projecting block, usually stone, supporting beam or other member.
An arch built by corbelling or cantilevering in from both sides with horizontal joints. Also known as a false arch.
Brick or masonry with courses built out beyond the one below.
A projecting ornamental moulding at the top of a building.
A single horizontal row of bricks or stone in a wall.
The highest point of an arch or vault.
The outer wall of a castle, usually with towers.
A fourteenth century form of bar tracery consisting of complex, sinuous lines. Also known as Flowing Tracery
A raised platform at the end of a medieval hall for the head of the household.
A buttress placed at the exterior corner of a building, forming a 135 degree angle with the walls it supports.
One of a pair of arched ribs thrown diagonally across a square or rectangular bay, form springer to springer, to support a vault.
The entrance to a building, apartment or any enclosure consisting of a movable barrier, usually lockable, of wood or other materials.
A window opening on a sloping roof.
A projection above an opening to divert water
An arch whose span is greater than its radii.
A recess for a window or door opening.
An arch whose height is equal to its span.
The outer curve of an arch.
The finishing applied to the outer surface of a building.
A flat dividing two mouldings

A distinctive form of jar being a flat-based, straight-sided or slightly rounded jar with two opposed, upright, rounded, tongue-shaped lugs raised from above the rim and bridged by added, internal struts used to suspend the pot over a fire. (Source: MPRG)
A jar with one or more lips added on the outside of the vessel wall over a hole pierced through the wall. The lips do not usually rise above rim level. (Source: MPRG)

A jar adapted by the addition of three or more vertical loop handles. They may be equally spaced, or confined to one section of the circumference. Profile vary and should be double indexed with the appropriate JAR type. (Source: MPRG)
A jar adapted by the addition of a straight handle and three feet. Profiles vary and should be double indexed with the appropriate JAR type. (Source: MPRG)
A specific form of cauldron, generally of rounded profile made in the Low Countries. (Source: MPRG)

A jar adapted by the addition of a pierced bunghole just above the base. The hole can be simply a hole in the wall of the vessel or made through a circular knob or disc of clay. There may be one or two vertical loop handles. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl whose form resembles two cones joined together at their widest points, forming a carination.
A bowl with a sharp change of angle in the vessel wall, generally at the point of maximum diameter. the carination may be in the upper or lower half of the vessel. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with concave body walls. Wide-mouthed, narrow-based examples, particularly those in larger sizes, have been termed Pans or Pancheons. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with straight sides which turn outwards, forming an obtuse angle with the base, i.e. and inverted, truncated, conical shape. (Source: MPRG)
A flared bowl of medium to deep depth, with wide horizontal everted rim. These vessels may have a single handle. (Source: MPRG)
A wide-mouthed, narrow based flared bowl associated with dairying activities. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with no noticeable base angle, so that the walls and base form a continuous rounded curve (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with convex body walls. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with straight sides which are at an approximate right angle to the base, i.e. a roughly cylindrical shape. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl adapted by the addition of a short tubular spout applied just below the rim.
A bowl adapted by having a pedestal base. (Source: MPRG)
An Early Saxon name for a pedestal bowl. (Source: MPRG)
An Early Saxon name for a Biconical Bowl. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl comprising three or more equally spaced lobes. There may be one or more moulded animals or other figures inside the base and two or more handles. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl divided into two or more compartments by vertical slab partitions. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A vessel comprising of two or more bowls, generally of small size, joined together. There may be one or more handles of varying forms. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl adapted by the addition of one or more handles. The handles may be vertical or horizontal loops, or straight, or may comprise vertical or horizontal lugs. (Source: MPRG)
A jar adapted by the addition of one or more handles. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl adapted by the addition of a single handle

A bowl with a straight handle projecting horizontally or diagonally upwards from the rim, particularly or completely hollow, but not opening into the vessel. A jar adapted by the addition of one or more handles. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl with a single loop handle crossing over the top of the vessel from one side of the rim to the other. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl adapted by the addition of two handles, generally opposed. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A small, double-handled bowl with horizontal loop handles decorated with a cockerel motif. (Source: MPRG)
A bowl adapted by the addition of three or more handles. (Source: MPRG)
A dish with straight or convex sides that turn inwards, forming an acute basal angle. (Source: MPRG)
A dish adapted by the addition of a pedestal base. (Source: MPRG)
A dish comprising three or more lobes, usually equally spaced. There may be one or more animal or other figures inside the base and two or more handles. (Source: MPRG)
A round, oval or rectangular straight-sided dish, divided into two or more units or compartments of varying sizes by vertical slab partitions. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A vessel comprising two or more dishes, generally of small size, joined together. There may be one or more handles of varying forms. (Source: MPRG)

A type of dish specifically designed to catch the juices from roasting meat. The dish may be oval, semi-circular, rectangular or wedge-shaped. Usually has one or two handles located on one long side and a lip at one or both short sides. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A shallow tray or dish used for baking food.
(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
An axe with a cutting edge and a hammer head.
An mill in which manganese was ground to a powder between two horizontal millstones.
An ore works at which gold was separated from the ore by the addition of mercury.
A long building with a louvred roof in which silver is refined using the Pattinson Process, which had been developed in the 1830s.

Any building or site in which silver was refined and/or extracted by smelting, cupellation, liquation or by the Parkes Process. IA-C20. Don't use for lead or copper smelters at which silver has been extracted unless silver-related features survive.
Works for the extrusion of aluminium and for creating aluminium products.
A building housing a steam driven ventilation fan used in mines
A zinc smelting furnace patented by William Champion of Bristol in 1738 for the reduction of zinc from zinc oxide by means of condensing.
A moulding in which the bead moulding is recessed so that the outer curve is level with the face of the stone or wood.
A buttress set away from the structure it supports, joined to it by an arch.

A pointed arch which, on a plan, is shown to be constructed around four arcs: two centred below and two centred upon the springing line, which is the level at which the vertical sides of the arch begin to curve.
The triangular upper portion of a wall at the the end of a pitched roof.
A medieval lavatory.
A form of bar tracery consisting of simple symmetrical shapes such as circles, trefoils, etc. Use in the second half of the 13th century.
The part of an arch between the crown and the springing.
Stone, brick or tile laid diagonally, with courses alternating in direction.
An external angle formed by the meeting of two sloping roof surfaces.
A concave moulding where the profile is a quarter of a circle. Also known as Cavetto.
A projecting bracket-like moulding on which the end of an arch appears to rest.
A development and amplification of Y-tracery in which each mullion branches into two curved bars intersecting the adjacent bars; thus each group of 2 or more lights forms an arch within an arch.
The inner curve or underside of an arch.
The vertical face of an archway, doorway or window - the part of the jamb that lies between the glass or door and the outer wall surface is called the reveal.
A notch or tooth in the joining surface of any piece of building material to prevent slipping.
A roll moulding with an arris resembling the keeled hull of a ship in section.
The central stone of an arch or vault.
A layer of stones or brick binding the face of a wall with the core.
A pointed, two-centred, arch whose height is much greater than its span.
A tertiary rib that originates neither from the main supports nor the central boss and is used as a decorative link between the main ribs and the tiercerons.
A horizontal beam or stone bridging an opening
A gallery or room open on one or more sides.
A Saxon quoin consisting of alternating horizontally and vertically laid stones.
A secondary decorative or structural rib placed along the longitudinal axis of a bay.
A parapet projecting on brackets on the outside of a wall with openings in the floor for weapons/oil etc.
A piece of wood, brickwork or stone surrounding a fire.
Used for recording structural elements encountered during excavation
Tiles applied to timber-framed walls to make them appear brick built.
A lime-based material used for bonding building fabric.
The carved contours given to elements of a building structure (eg door arch)
The vertical element of a window.
A moulding in the form of small pyramids in a continuous line.
The brickwork infilling of a timber frame.
A pointed arch in which the arcs comprising it are centred on points both outside and inside the arch so that the point takes the form of a double S, or ogee.
A moulding with an S-shaped profile.
A stone block used variously as the base for a post, as the springing point of an arch, or as a supporting block within a wall for a timber member.
A flat surface, sunk or raised within a framework.
Tracery in which the mullions pass uninterrupted to the head of the arch.Introduced in the fourteenth century.
A low wall, sometimes battlemented, placed to protect any spot where there's a drop.
A solid masonry support, distinct from a column.
A shallow pier projecting only slightly from the wall face.
A free-standing upright member - doesn't have to be cylindrical.
The earliest and most elementary form of tracery, having the effect of simple openings cut out of a stone infilling or plate.
The projecting base of a wall or column.
Dressed stones at the corners of a building, laid so their faces alternate long and short.
An arch built into a wall above another arch or lintel to relieve it of some of the weight of the structure above.
Plastering of an outer wall
A form of bar tracery consisting of circles drawn at the top and bottom into ogee shapes
A moulding with a reversed-S shaped profile.
A projecting band on a ceiling or vault.
Large convex moulding, usually semicircular or three-quarters of a circle in section.
A deeply concaved moulding, with a projecting lower edge, that sits at the base of a column between two torus mouldings.
A moulding resembling in outline the end of a rolled scroll of paper; the overlapping edge may be either angular or curved.
An arch made up of part of a circle, the centre of which is below its springing line.
The trunk of a column b etween the base and the capital.
A beaker adapted by having a pedestal base. The upper part of the pedestal is solid and may be thrown as an integral part of the vessel, or added as a separate element.(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A beaker with convex body walls. (Source: MPRG)
A beaker with a construction above the base to form a waisted profile. (Source: MPRG)
A cup with a marked change of angle in the body wall, generally at the point of maximum girth. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A cup with sides falring outwards from the base towards the rim, usually with a single handle.
A cup with a rounded body beneath a deep neck. There may be a marked junction between neck and body and the angle of the neck may be inward-sloping, upright or everted. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A cup with convex body walls. (Source: MPRG)
A cup adapted by the addition of a pedestal base. (Source: MPRG)

A vessel composed of three or more equally spaced lobes and usually, a waisted or pedestal base. The handles are vertical loops, generally of strap form. There may be two opposed handles, or one per lobe junction. (Source: MPRG)
A vessel composed of three or more separate compartments, joined together and pierced to allow liquid to flow from one to another. There may be one or more handles. (Source: MPRG)

A form of cup which incorporates a joke or conundrum, where cut-outs or holes in the body make conventional use impossible. The puzzle is how to drink from it without getting wet; usually achieved by sucking through a hollow rim or handle. (Source: MPRG)
A mug with little or no discernible neck and an even, convex profile from rim to base, which have roughly equal diameters. (Source: MPRG)
A mug with more-or-less straight side which flare out from the rim to the wider base. (Source: MPRG)
A German stoneware form of conical mug. (Source: MPRG)
A mug with roughly vertical body walls. (Source: MPRG)
A mug with straight sides flaring outwards from the base towards the rim. (Source: MPRG)
A mug with a rounded body profile below a deep neck. There may be a marked junction between the neck and the body. The neck may be inward-sloping, upright or everted. (Source: MPRG)
A specific German Stoneware form of rounded mug. (Source: MPRG)
A lid with a carinated conical profile and straight vertical sides, surmounted by a conical top with and integral knob. (Source: MPRG)
A lid with a shallow conical profile and an integral knob. (Source: MPRG)
A simple flat-topped lid resembling an inverted dish but with no central knob or handle. (Source: MPRG)
A lid with a shallow domed profile and a central knob. (Source: MPRG)
A simple, flat or nearly flat lid. In ceramic forms, often made by rolling out clay rather than by throwing on a wheel. (Source: MPRG)
A lid resembling an inverted dish with a flat top and an integral or added knob or loop handle. (Source: MPRG)
A lid comprising a shallow flared dish with an integral knob rising from the centre. (Source: MPRG)

A lid with a distinct flange, projecting upwards, horizontally or downwards, and an integral knob. Complex examples can include a simple locking device: lugs on the lower flange can be twisted into matching cut-outs in the rim to lock it. (Source: MPRG)

A type of flanged lid where the lower flange is partly cut away to leave two projections or lugs, which can be fitted into corresponding cut-outs in the rim of the vessel beneath and secure the lid when it is rotated. (Source: MPRG)
A complex or ornate lid which cannot be easily classified according to the main forms of lid. (Source: MPRG)
A candlestick in which a simple socket is set in the centre of a drip tray or saucer. There may be a vertical loop handle linking the socket to the rim of the saucer. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)

A candlestick in which the socket is above a drip tray or grease tray, placed on a pedestal base which is generally hollow. There may be a vertical loop handle and one or more secondary drip trays. (Source: MPRG)
A deep, square or rectangular, flat slab of clay, the upper surface of which has two or more cup-shaped holders cut into it. (Source: MPRG)

A pedestal lamp with a drip-tray below the bowl. There may be a vertical loop handle linking bowl and drip-tray. Some variants have a more enclosed bowl form with a small tubular spout projecting from the bowl. (Source: MPRG)
A small hemispherical bowl with a pinched or pulled wick lip. (Source: MPRG)
A small bowl on a pedestal base, which may be solid or at least partly hollow. It may have a wick lip at the rim or a lug handle. (Source: MPRG)

A small bowl on a pedestal base above a drip-tray or saucer. It may have a wick lip at the rim. May have pierced lugs projecting form the rim for suspension of a handle, spout or vertical loop handle linking bowl and saucer. (Source: MPRG)
A small hemispherical or flared bowl with a solid pointed base or spike. May include a wick lip at the rim and one or two pierced lugs for suspension. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
Use only for historic state of Czechoslovakia, where new state is known index with CZECH REPUBLIC or SLOVAKIA.
A flat arch or lintel with quadrants on the corbels rising from the jambs.
The horizontal member at the base of a timber-framed wall or the base of a door or window frame.
The edging attached to the base of an internal wall.
The horizontal distance between two supporting members, such as the abutments of an arch, the walls carrying a roof, etc.
The triangular space to the outside of the haunch of an arch.
The sloping chamfer cut into walls, eg. for a window opening.
The point at which an arch or vault rises from its support.
An arch whose purpose is to arrest or prevent structural movement in a building.
A horizontal band set into and projecting from the surface of an external wall, usually moulded.
A chamfer moulding with a shallow flat recess and raised edges.
A depressed arch formed around three arcs: two struck from the springing line with one centrally placed arc struck from below it.
A secondary rib issuing from the main supports and inserted between the transverse ribs or wall ribs and diagonal ribs.
Ornamental work at the head of a window.
Decorative forms of window openings.
A horizontal bar in a window.
The rib running at right angles to the wall across the width of the space that is vaulted. It supports the vault and defines a bay.
A secondary decorative or structural rib placed along the transverse axis of a bay.
A flattened pointed arch, with a low elliptical shape, usually drawn from four centres.
Stones left projecting from a wall for subsequent bonding into another wall.
A vaulted room beneath an upper room.
An arched ceiling or roof, the depth of which exceeds its span.
The parts which go to make up a vault. Use specific terms.
One of a series of radiating wedge-shaped stones or bricks used to form an arch.
A structure, usually of brick, stone or timber, that encloses or defines a space or room.

Material used to form a structurally sound base for the construction of the wall above. The depth and width of the footings and material used varies greatly and depends on the nature of the site and on the available building material.
An undulating moulding, consisting of shallow concave/convex/concave curves.
A compartment of a vault.
An opening in a wall, roof, door, etc to allow light to enter. Usually used to include all component parts.
The components which form a window.

The lowest of the three main parts of an entablature. Also the lintels, jambs and mouldings surrounding a door, window, panels or niche; or the ornamental mouldings around the exterior curve of an arch.
A horizontal timber member.
A defined portion of a door, usually rectangular, which may be recessed, level with or proud of its surrounding surface and may be framed by mouldings or channels.
The horizontal member in a panelled door.
A diagonal timber used to strengthen a timber frame.
A purlin that is joined to a principal rafter by a tenon joint.
Walls that are constructed of timber posts set very close together, the spaces infilled with plastered panels.
Beam tying together a pair of rafters, distinct from a tie beam
A longitudinal member in a roof, running beneath the collar beams and intended to give stability to the roof.
Rafters that infill between the principal rafters.
A horizontal timber member of a timber framed wall.
An upright timber standing on a tiebeam to support a collar or purlin. Once used as an alternative to king post, this term is now restricted to the shorter post ending at collar level.
A roof with a post placed centrally on a tie beam to support a collar purlin.
A truss formed from pairs of curved timbers, known as blades, the pair frequenty derived from the same tree.
The entrance to a building, apartment or any enclosure consisting of a movable barrier, usually lockable, of wood or other materials.
A horizontal member in a panelled door, usually below the Top Rail and above the Lock Rail.
A vertical timber resting on a hammer beam and forming a triangle between it and a principal.
A short projecting beam that does not meet its opposite and corresponding member which recieves a Hammerpost and an arched brace.
A roof consisting of trusses that have a pair of brackets (the hammerbeams, like a tie beamwith the central section missing), supporting the hammer posts that in turn support the rafters.
An upright member on the side of a door into which the hinges are fixed.
A roof with sloped instead of vertical gable ends.
The projection of an upper storey beyond the one below, created by beams and joists of the lower storey projecting beyond the external elevation.
Horizontally laid timbers between the walls and beams of a building to carry the floorboards.
A vertical member placed on the centre of a tie beam to support a ridge or ridge beam.
A curfew with straight sides flaring outwards from the top. (Source: MPRG)
A curfew with a rounded profile merging into a rounded top, with no discernible angle. (Source: MPRG)
(Source: MPRG)
A curfew consisting of a half section of an inverted bowl. The form has been adapted for use against a wall. (Source: MPRG)

A curfew consisting of a half-bell shape with a raised flange around the cut-away side. A vertical loop handle joins the flange and body. The form is adapted for use against a wall and some are highly decorated. (Source: MPRG)
The material which floats during the floatation of samples as a means of recovering charred plant remains from an archaeological context.

The material that does not float during the floatation of samples as a means of recovering charred plant remains from an archaeological context. Also, the material remaining following wet or dry sieving of course sieved samples.
A Jewish graveyard headstone.
A cast iron post similar to a lamp post, with revolving top to carry either coloured plates, or an oil lamp with coloured glass at night. Associated with canal or river navigation locks.
A ventilating fan house with an expanding chimney.
An electric fan used for the ventilation of mines.
A building housing an electric powered mine ventilation fan.
A roof consisting of trusses with a single timber from the tie beam to the apex of the roof, supporting the ridge purlin.
Strips of wood (laths) nailed to other timbers that are coated in plaster to form a wall finish.
A roof with one slope only and built against a vertical wall.
A horizontal member in a panelled door adjacent to the handle and/or locking mechanism.
A lantern-like structure in a roof with an opening in the sides for the venting of smoke.
A roof with two pitch angles, the lower being lower and steeper than the upper.
A defined portion of a door, usually rectangular, which may be recessed, level with or proud of its surrounding surface and may be framed by mouldings or channels.
An upright framing member, or mullion, that separates two panels, such as in a panelled door or a window.
Exterior plastering of a timber framed building, usually decorated into naturalistic patterns, eg foliage, figures.
A roof with gables at both ends.
A wide piece of sawn timber, usually one and a half to four and a half inches thick and six inches or more wide.
In wall frames, vertical timbers that are the full height of the frame (shorter uprights are studs). In roofs posts are the vertical timbers that carry longitudinal ones.
Rafters that are the main structural inclined timbers in the roof trusses.
A horizontal timber set in the plane of a roof's slope and supporting common rafters.
Two vertical timbers sat symmetrically on the tie beam, restrained by a collar beam that supports the side purlins.
A roof consisting of trusses with a pair of vertical timbers sat on the tie beam supporting the side purlins.
Inclined timbers sloping from the wall top to the apex and supporting the roof covering.
A short horizontal timber in a timber framed wall.
The horizontal timber at the apex of the roof supporting the top ends of the rafters.
A longitudinal member that recieves the ends of common rafters at the apex of a roof.
The exterior upper covering, and its supporting structure, of a building.
An upright member on the side of a door that houses the shutting/locking mechanism.
A longitudinal member set in the plane of a roof's slope and supporting common rafters.
The lowest member of a wall frame into which the posts and studs of the frame are tenoned (also known as a Sole Plate).
Sloping supporting timbers in a frame.
Intermediate posts between the main posts in a timber frame.
A projection from the end of a timber to sit in a mortice.
A beam tying together the feet of principal rafters preventing their spread and forming the roof truss
A method of constructionwhere walls are built of jointed interlocking timbers.
A defined portion of a door, usually rectangular, which may be recessed, level with or proud of its surrounding surface and may be framed by mouldings or channels.
The horizontal member in a panelled door.
A purlin that sits in a trench cut in the back of a principal rafter.
A triangular framework within the roof, self-supporting and dividing the building into bays.
A horizontal timber along the top of a wall to recieve the rafters of a roof.

A system used to infill panels in timber-framed structures, comprising of vertical staves of oak, interwoven with fine flexible branches or twigs, usually of hazel and daubed with a mixture of mud, dung and chopped straw.
A form of wall cladding composed of overlapping horizontal boards on a timber framework.
A brace running from principal rafter to purlin to strengthen the frame.
The lowest horizontal member of a window frame.
A large cauldron used in the making of a preservative from the bark of spruce, fir or other conifers. The preservative was used to treat nets, sails and other fishing gear.
The warm room in a Roman baths.
A small cold water bath, often known as a natatio when part of a Roman bath complex.
An impression made in soft ground by a passing animal or human. The soft ground may have subsequently hardened.
The exercise hall of a Roman baths complex.
A core part of a town or city that has or had a particular set of characteristics; for example an area of high status residences or an area where a particular industry/trade was centred.
The piece of stone or flint remaining after blades have been produced.
A two dimensional image using paint applied to the surface of a ceiling.
A two dimensional image using paint applied to the surface of a ceiling.

High speed craft developed in the 20th Century which employ a wing-like structure mounted on struts below the hull which lift the vessel above the water line during forward motion, reducing drag and increasing speed.
A multihulled craft consisting of two hulls, or vakas, which are usually joined together by a frame or other structure, formed of akas. Catamarans can be sail or engine powered.
A pond with protection for nesting ducks and other wild fowl
A working tunnel or gallery in a mine used for the extraction of ironstone.
Former terrestrial landscape of any kind now submerged through erosion, as at Dunwich, or historical inundation processes, eg. post-glacial submersion of the North Sea landscape ("Doggerland").

A type of motorboat that provides accommodation for crew and passengers within the crafts cabin. Cabin Cruisers are usually between 25 feet and 45 feet long in length and are not to be confused with cruise ships which are substantially larger.
A small ferry powered by steam or diesel engine, which pull vessel from one side of a river crossing along submerged chains.
An enclosure used for baiting bulls.

A residence of two or three monks of the Savigniac order dependent on a foreign mother house. The order was originally founded by monks in Savigny, Normandy, in 1105 and first established in Britain in 1123 at Tulket, Preston.
A rural cross erected to show the way.
A room in a monastery used by monks or nuns as a day room.
A room in a monastery used by monks or nuns as a day room.
A well with an unusually high mineral content that combined with extensive periods of evaporation may give objects a stony exterior. Once believed to have been caused by magic or witchcraft.
A circle of wooden stakes or stake holes in the ground.
A burial ground for victims of cholera.
A depression in the ground caused by the explosion of a mortar shell.
A natural or man-made gap in vegetation or other combustible material that acts as a barrier to slow or stop the progress of a fire.
A system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used to simulate an airfield and thus confuse enemy aircraft into bombing these counterfeit targets.
A system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used to simulate a dockyard and thus confuse enemy aircraft into bombing these counterfeit targets.
A pit dug into the ground or a simple construction made of stone, brick or metal. Designed to contain a fire and prevent it from spreading, but can also be used to heat stone for breaking.
A place where silica or silicate, the most common mineral component of rock, is extracted from the ground.
A defensive embankment with three or more ditches.

The second phase of the Neolithic associated with the construction of passage graves aligned with the sun and the transition from causewayed enclosure to henge monuments. In the UK c. 3300 BC to 2900 BC.
An area of several rooms in a medieval house or building. Probably for domestic use.
A device inserted in the ear canal to protect the wearer from loud noises or the intrusion of water, foreign bodies, dust or excessive wind.
A type of cast chisel with a sharp, concave edge for shaping wood, stone or metal. A particular type of British Bronze Age tool.
A type of mace with bolster shaped stone or metal head on a wooden or metal shaft. Where the use is thought to be ceremonial, double index with ceremonial object.
A Mesolithic type of mace head made of stone.
A mill used to dress ore by means of a jigging machine.
A mound kerbed with wooden stakes or boulders.
A nail used for roofing.
Metal shaped blade that flares out to a curved cutting edge, with a side loop to further assist hafting.
A tool used to notch, line cut or scratch into a surface.
A shed for storing fishing bait.

Type of leaf-shaped socketed spearhead with two small holes or loops on either side at the base of the blade. Possibly meant to assist in securing the metal spearhead to the wooden shaft, or to tie streamers of some kind to the top of the spear.

A spearhead with an elongated hollow cast into the base of the blade to receive the end of the wooden spear shaft. The spearhead was secured to the shaft by pegs set at right angles or by lashings fixed to loops cast at the base of the spearhead.
A type of spearhead with a triangular blade bevelled at the edges and with a groove(s) following the outline.
A device for catching eagles, falcons and hawks.

Style of early Bronze Age pot found widely in north-western Europe with a deep, largely plain, outwardly flared body above which is sharp carination, usually decorated and sometimes with an applied cordon, and an inwardly angled neck.
A collared urn with a heavy rim or collar on top of a straight-sided or slightly bowed body narrowing to a small flat base. Decoration may extend for a short way below the collar, but this is rare.
A large vessel with raised or applied cordons running horizontally on the body of the vessel.

A collared urn with a heavy rim or collar on top of a concave neck or cavetto zone, which may or may not be decorated, and this in turn leads down to a straight-sided but narrowing body. Decoration may extend below this cavetto zone, but this is rare.
Urn with a heavy rim or collar which may be vertical or slightly inverted. This may carry incised or impressed decoration, particularly herring-bone, encircling lines, hurdling or chevron decoration.
The impost, or point at which a vault rests upon its support, and from which it seems to spring. Hence the term describes the bottom stone of a vault, which lies on the impost.
The impost, or point at which a vault rests upon its support, and from which it seems to spring. Hence the term describes the bottom stone of a vault, which lies on the impost.
Muslim funeral mosque.
An open area within an exchange building (e.g. cotton exchange, corn exchange, stock exchange) where goods are traded.
A bungalow joined to another to form one building.

A prefabricated cargo vessel produced in large numbers by North American shipyards during World War II to replace shipping losses caused by German submarines and replacing the earlier 'LIBERTY' ships.
One of the allotropes of carbon, commonly used in pencils.
A C20th military building used to test the efficiency of gas protection equipment provided for drivers of all forms of vehicles.
Vertical or horizontal levels driven into a hill slope to assess the viability of mineral resources but never fully exploited.
Wool, textile, or synthetic floor covering material.
Mineral ore comprising mainly aluminium ore and mined for aluminium extraction.
A frame containing glass tiles or bricks set into a pavement to allow the lighting of basement areas.
Vessel fitted with broadcasting equipment and used for off-shore radio programme transmission.
Small port on River Trent, North Lincs.
A trench in the form of a flattened 'W' with a flat concrete roof covered in turf, supported on concrete pillars. The name derives from the resemblance to a child's drawing of a seagull in flight.
McDonnell Douglas was a major American aerospace manufacturer and defense contractor, producing a number of famous commercial and military aircraft.

A tandem two-seat, twin-engined, all-weather, long-range supersonic jet interceptor fighter/fighter-bomber originally developed for the United States Navy by McDonnell Aircraft.It first entered service in 1960 with the U.S. Navy.
Specially designed/fitted carriers of crew and/or supplies to offshore oil platforms.

Generic name for a vessel used for work rather than for recreation, transportation, or military purposes. The vessels include tugs, barges, landing craft, dredgers and standby safety vessels. Use only were the exact type of vessel is unknown.
A type of ferry that is designed to carry wheeled vehicles that can be driven on to and off the vessel.
A fishing vessel that catches fish by using a Seining net, that is a large net that is made to hang in the water by attaching weights along the bottom edge and counteracting floats along the top.
German port of the western bank of the mouth of the River Weser.
German port on the River Ems.
Port in Somalia, one of largest in East Africa
A natural compound used as in the building and medical industies.
A heavy chain, usually of gold, worn as insignia of office or a mark of fealty or other association from the Middle Ages onwards.
A long-handled implement designed to allow the user to scratch their own back.
A case designed to hold a fan.

The Inquisition was an institution of the medieval church designed to combat heresy. It lapsed during the 14th and 15th centuries but was revived in Spain in 1478 against apostate Jews and Muslims and later Protestants in Spain and the Netherlands.
A piece of plate armour designed to protect the shoulder.
A portable writing-case or surface, especially one for use on the lap. May contain compartments for storing writing materials and paper.
Site for the disposal of unexploded ordnance, possibly attached to a bombing range.
An establishment in which prostitution is practiced.

An earthwork feature used by hunters to trap deer comprising a steep ditch into which the deer are chased with an enclosure to hold them at one end, known from the Isle of Rum and a debateable example in Cumbria.
A reinforced and padded item of clothing designed to protect the upper body in sports associated with physical contact or possible injury from sporting equipment. For military uses use BREASPLATE.
Clothing designed to protect the wearer from physical hazards.
A flag or object depicting a symbolic representation carried as part of a religious ceremony.
Arlingham civil parish, River Severn, Gloucestershire
Aland Islands, Finland

A Dutch barge-like sailing vessel whose shallow draught enables it to navigate in shallow water not accessible by other vessels. Used for fishing or carriage of cargo in the 19th century this type of vessel was adapted for use as a type of leisure craft.
A mine used for the extraction of any hard dark-coloured rock.
Material, stone or wood, lining the inside of a grave.
Factory for the production of Pet Food.
An area of shallow linear cuts made by the removal of turf for fuel or building material.
A temporary settlement or encampment erected by construction workers (eg for reservoir construction).
Buildings used in the production of animal food.
A ticket booth in a theatre or cinema.
Mud walled building found on the Solway Plain.
A monocular optical instrument possessing magnification for observing distant objects, especially in astronomy.
A device used to gauge the speed of a vessel at sea.
A building or site used for naval communications.
A car park on the roof of a building.
A system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used to simulate a domestic site such as a city and thus confuse enemy aircraft into bombing counterfeit targets.
Tracked, armoured fighting vehicles designed for front-line combat.
Machinery and parts for the manufacture or assembly of military tanks, i.e. armoured vehicles.

Aircraft as cargo carried whole or crated ready for assembly on arrival at the destination port. Do not use where the vessel is an aircraft carrier and the aircraft is carried as part of the vessel's armament.
A housing for racing pigeons usually situated in allotments of back yards.
A burial ground for Nonconformists. Use more specific term where known.
King of Bernicia (592-616). Took control of Deira on the death of thelric and banished his son Edwin. Killed by Rdwald at the battle of the river Idle.

King of Deira and Bernicia (616-633). Took control of Bernicia on the death of thelfrith having spent his time in exile at the court of Rdwald. Killed by Cadwallon and Penda at the battle of Hatfield.
King of Deira (633-634). Reverted to paganism and killed at York by Cadwallon, king of the Britons.
King of Bernicia (633/4-634). Reverted to paganism and killed by Cadwallon, king of the Britons.
King of Northumbria (634-642). Defeated Cadwallon at the battle of Heavenfield. Killed by Penda at the battle of Maserfelth.
King of Deira (642-651). Betrayed and killed at Gilling on the orders of King Oswiu of Bernicia.
King of Bernicia (642-670), became King of Northumbria after the death of Oswine (651-670). Defeated Penda at the battle of the Winwd in 655 and ruled the kingdom of the Mercians (655-8).
Sub-king of Deira (c.651-655). Fought with Penda at the battle of Winwd.
Sub-king of Deira (c.655-664).
Sub-king in Deira (c.664-670), King of the Northumbrians (670-685). Killed in battle against the Picts at Nechtansmere.
Sub-king of Deira (c.670-679).
King of Northumbria (686-705)
King of Northumbria briefly for 2 months (705-706).
King of Northumbria (706-716).
King of Northumbria (716-718).
King of Northumbria (718-729). Appointed Coelwulf as his successor.
King of Northumbria (729-737). Deposed and restored 731, resigned in 737 in favour of Eadberht.
King of Northumbria (737-758). Resigned in favour of his son Oswulf and 'recieved the tonsure of Saint Peter'. Died in York in 768.
King of Northumbria (758-759). Treacherously killed by his thanes.
King of Northumbria (759-765). Driven out by his people at Pincanheale in 765.
King of Northumbria (765-774). Exiled in 774, first to Bamborough, then to the king of the Picts.
King of Northumbria (774-778/9). Expelled and driven into exile.
King of Northumbria (778 or 779-788). killed by the treachery of Sicga.
King of Northumbria (788-790). Expelled in 790, tonsured at York and then driven into exile where he died in 792.
King of Northumbria for 27 days in 796. Fled to Lindisfarne and thence to the King of the Picts. Died in 799.
