King of Northumbria (796-806) and again in (808-810). Expelled in 806 and restored in 808 with the help of Charlemagne and Pope Leo III.
King of Northumbria (806-808).
King of Northumbria (810-840 or 841).
King of Northumbria (840 or 841-844) and again (844-848). Expelled in 844 and then restored.
King of Northumbria (844).
King of Northumbria (848 or 849-862 or 863) and again (867). Expelled in either 862 or 863 and replaced by lle (not of the royal line). Killed at York.
The cold room in a Roman baths.
The deliberate deposit of a body in the ground, usually located in a special area set aside for the purpose of burial, such as a graveyard or cemetery.

A landscape which has been specifically designed or modified. Often indicated by proven below ground stratigraphy, revealed by deliberate investigation including geophysical survey, or other surface monuments or structures.

Usually dating from the early 20th century these cabinets, sited alongside public highways, were used for the distribution of electricity for street lighting control and later for domestic use. In Wolverhampton these boxes also serviced the tram system.
A shop selling household furniture.
A shop that sells men's clothes, either off the peg, bespoke or both.

A single engine, jet propelled twin boom aircraft which came into service in 1945 in a variety of roles including night fighter, trainer, the carrier-borne Sea Vampire, and the MK5 version, a fighter bomber.  Produced by De Havilland.
Sacred Jewish texts and appurtenances buried within a Jewish cemetery.
A garden associated with a crematorium where the ashes of deceased infants are scattered or buried.
A room, within a building or institution, equipped for conducting scientific experiments or research.
King of Kent (c.455-c.488).
King of Kent (488-c.512).
King of Kent (c.512-c.560.

King of Kent (560 or c.585-616). Described by Bede as reigning for 56 years (he died on 24 Feb 616) but another source describes him as the son of a king of Kent when he married Bertha, daughter of Charibert in c.580.
King of Kent (616-640).
King of Kent (640-664).
King of Kent (664-673).
King of Kent (673-685). Died 6th February 685 from wounds recieved in battle against Eadric and the South Saxons.
King of Kent (685-686). Following his death in 686 various usurper or foreign kings plundered the kingdom until Wihtred 'freed the people from invasion'.
King of Kent jointly with Swfheard (of Essex) between 690 and 692. Sole king of Kent (692-725).
Joint king of Kent with Withred (690-692). One of the 'usurper or foreign kings' mentioned by Bede as plundering Kent following the death of Eadric.
King of West Kent (725-748).
Following the death of Wihtred in 725, the kingdom of Kent was divided into its two component parts with Withred's sons becoming kings.
Following the death of Wihtred in 725, the kingdom of Kent was divided into its two component parts with Withred's sons becoming kings.
King of West Kent (748-762).
King of West Kent (762-c.764).
King of West Kent (764-c.775). King of all Kent (c.775-779).
King of East Kent (735-762).
King of East Kent (762-764).
King of East Kent (c.764-?).
King of East Kent (c.765-?).
King of Kent (784).
King of Kent (796-798). Captured in 798 by Coenwulf, king of the Mercians who installed his brother Cuthred as king of Kent.
King of Kent (798-807).
King of Kent (821-825). Driven from Kent by Ecgberht, king of the West Saxons and from c.825 onwards Kent was ruled by the West Saxon kings.
King of Deira (560-588 or 590).
King of Deira (588-593).
King of Bernicia (547-559 or 560).
King of Bernicia (559-560).
King of Bernicia (560-568).
King of Bernicia (568-572).
King of Bernicia (572-579).
King of Bernicia (579-585).
King of Bernicia (585-592).
An interment of a human body that displays unusual burial practice such as positioning of the body, decapitation, dismemberment or over-secure burial.
A classroom constructed from prefabricated sections.
A building, often converted from its original use, for use as a temporary accommodation by members of the Women's Land Army during the First and Second World Wars.
An ornamental garden feature, sometimes with an associated bath house.
A bridge that crosses over a railway.
A bridge crossing under railway property.

A flour mill which uses one or more pairs of horizontal millstones to grind wheat into flour which millers call a sudden death process; within not more than 90 seconds complete wheat grain becomes wholemeal flour.
A flour mill using both stones and rollers to produce flour and, perhaps mainly from the stones, animal feed from grains other than wheat.
A machine, usually contained in a building called a flour mill which reduces grain into constituent parts or streams  which include flour. For a Flour Mill buliding use FLOUR MILL in Monument Type.

A flour milling machine which uses one or more pairs of horizontal millstones to grind wheat into flour which millers call a sudden death process; within not more than 90 seconds complete wheat grain becomes wholemeal flour.

A flour milling machine which uses horizontal steel rollers and dressing machines  seives and purifiers  to gradually reduce wheat grains into constituent parts or streams which millers call a gradual reduction process.
A flour milling machine using both stones and rollers to produce flour and, perhaps mainly from the stones, animal feed from grains other than wheat.
An air-cushioned vehicle capable of travelling over land or water.
An industrial facility concerned with the manufacture of magnesium from magnesium hydroxide derived from sea water. Magnesium was used in the manufacture of aircraft.
A mechanism used to turn a tram around.
East Friesland, Lower Saxony, Germany

Plain clay tile suspended, loose, from the top edge of a tiling lath or batten so as to overlap two courses below. It is held in place by a small wooden peg wedged into, or passed through, one (or sometimes both) of two holes in the head of the tile.
A lime kiln where the fuel is not mixed with the limestone but burnt below it.
A small area of managed woodland, created to provide cover for foxes.
A small area of managed woodland, created to provide cover for deer and other game.
An earthwork or structure on a rifle range used to mark a set distance from the rifle butts (usually at 50 or 100 yard intervals).
An obstacle on a golf course constituting a hazard. Usually taking the form of a sand trap or dirt mound.
Cubicles for housing rams, resembling pigsties with their own yard but slightly larger.
A German coastal minelaying submarine in use during the First World War. The U Boat carried 12 mines but was otherwise unarmed with no deck gun or torpedo tubes.
A German coastal attack submarine in use during the First World War. The U Boat had 5 torpedo tubes (4 bow/1 stern) and carried 10 torpedoes as well as an 88mm (or in some cases 105mm) deck gun.

A German coastal minelaying submarine in use during the First World War. In addition to 18 mines, the U BOAT also carried 7 torpedoes in 3 tubes (2 bow/1 stern) and and 88mm or 105mm deck gun. A very successful design, UCIIs sank more than 1800 vessels.
The main hall of worship within a Sikh Temple.
A building used to store fodder for deer.
A large, deep, manmade pool, usually with accompanying diving boards/platforms and forming part of a swimming pool complex.
Moored barge providing a refuge for shipwrecked sailors or downed airmen, for example the air-sea rescue Cuckoo barges of WWII.

A type of stoneware jug dating to the 16th and 17th centuries, popularly known as a Bellarmine jug, shaped in the figure of a bearded man. They were produced in the Cologne region, particularly Frechen.
A muzzle loaded explosive projectile fired from a mortar. Typically they are short range and low velocity with a high arcing trajectory.
Outer casing of an explosive cartridge fired from a cannon or mortar.
A workshop used in the manufacture and preparation of cotton
Citrus fruit, usually green.
A channel for conveying vegetables.
A bank which specializes in accepting savings deposits. Originally established to help the poor.

Used by Ordnance Survey to record high accuracy height above Ordnance Datum Newlyn. Marked by a low concrete pillar, and maybe surrounded by railings, they comprise an underground chamber protecting the reference point, built directly onto stable bedrock.
A shed used for the maintenance and repair of aircraft.
A site or building used to co-ordinate Air-Sea Rescue operations.
A hut used for the accommodation of members of the armed forces.
A circular concrete platform onto which aircraft would be taxied allowing the ground crew to calibrate, check and adjust the accuracy of the aircrafts compass, usually by rotating the platform.

A site which is known, or believed to be, where an aircraft crashed. It is an offence to interfere with the wreckage of crashed military aircraft without a licence (Protection of Military Remains Act 1986). Index with AIRCRAFT TYPE where known.
A level crossing designed to allow the passage of aircraft to and from a runway which has a railway or road running through it.
A building where non-commissioned aircrew are housed.
A site or building used for the storage and maintenance of both land and sea vehicles and from which terrestrial or maritime operations could be carried out.
A command post used to direct the guns of an anti aircraft battery.
A light anti aircraft position, usually open-walled and built of concrete, brick or sandbags used to emplace one or more machine guns mounted on pintels.
A purpose-built firing platform on which an anti-aircraft battery could be emplaced.
A piece of ground, or a building, on which artillery may be fired at targets.
An area of ground on which anti tank guns can be placed for testing purposes and to practice firing at targets.

A designated area within a town or village with fixed defences such as pillboxes, anti tank ditches and gun emplacements, designed to threaten the flanks of an enemy force which had broken through a stop line.
An anti tank wall constructed specifically to be used for training purposes.
Office used by a Piermaster.
A farmstead where mostly detached buildings have developed around one or more sides of an open cattle yard.
A farmstead where the working buildings are arranged around a yard.
A farmstead where mostly detached buildings have developed around four sides of an open cattle yard.
A farmstead where mostly detached buildings have developed around one side of an open cattle yard.
A farmstead where mostly detached buildings have developed around three sides of an open cattle yard.
A farmstead where mostly detached buildings have developed around two sides of an open cattle yard.
Regular courtyard farmsteads where the working buildings are carefully planned as linked ranges and are focused around one or more working yards. They often result from a single phase of building.

Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged as an E-shaped plan around two cattle yards. Cattle housing and stabling typically extend as three ranges from the longer main range which includes a barn or mixing house.

Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged as an F-shaped plan around two cattle yards. Cattle housing and stabling typically extend as three ranges from the longer main range which includes a barn or mixing house.
Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged around all four sides of the yard.
Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged as an H-shaped plan, commonly with cattle housing to two or more cattle yards.

Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged as two linked ranges to create an L-shape. They can comprise a barn and an attached shelter shed to a cattle yard or an interlinked cattle housing and fodder range.

A farmstead with multiple yards which are grouped together and regularly arranged (other than the defined E, F, H, T or Z plans). The yards may relate to one or more buildings or ranges which may be of either loose courtyard or regular courtyard form.
Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged as two ranges at right angles to each other.
Regular courtyard farmsteads where the buildings are arranged around three sides of a yard which is open to one side.
An uncommon form of a regular courtyard farmstead where the buildings are arranged in a Z-shaped form.
A farmstead where the buildings and yards are loosely arranged, with no focal yard. Use more specific type where known.
A dispersed farmstead where the farm buildings and farmhouse are loosely grouped together within the boundary of the farmstead.
A farmstead where the main range of working buildings are attached in-line and form a long row often facing a series of yards.
A turf-covered mound in a curvilinear E-shape, and hard-standing to take an aircraft. There were usually an access point to an air raid shelter at the rear. In use during WW2
Fruit native to the countries bordering the Mediterranean Sea.

Double-handled storage jars characterised by a long neck and long body used as food and wine containers and for carrying such goods as cargo, found on shipwrecks from Classical antiquity (Greek/Roman).

Roman-era pottery, principally made in areas from modern-day France and Germany, for food use, with a characteristic glossy red surface and which may be either decorated or plain, and often produced in quantity as an export cargo.
A machine that can be flown in the air, now specifically an aeroplane or helicopter.
Any part of an aircraft. Use more specific term where known.
Goods stowed in barrels and therefore indicating that the barrels were in use as containers with goods stored therein, rather than as cargo in their own right.
A vessel used to transport bombs and depth charges from the shore to flying boats during the Second World War.
A type of small boat that was often carried, or towed by a larger vessel and used as a ship's boat. Dinghies can also be used recreationally as independent sailing vessels.
A mine countermeasure vessel built to detect and destroy individual naval mines. (See Minesweeper for vessels that sweep and explode mined areas at sea without prior detection).
A vessel designed or adapted for the task of keeping shipping lanes and ports free from the threat of naval mines. Use specific type where known. of
A dispersed farmstead where buildings and yards (regular or loose courtyard in their form) are sited alongside a routeway.
A dispersed farmstead where buildings are arranged around scattered yards which can be loose or regular in their form.
A farmstead where the farmhouse and working buildings are attached and in-line. They can comprise the extension of linear farmsteads.
A farmstead where the house and working buildings are attached and in-line. Can include Bastles, Longhouses and Laithe houses.
A farmstead, often of linear plan, where the working buildings are placed opposite and parallel to the house and attached working buildings with a relatively narrow space between.
A medieval high status farmstead, acting as the centre of the estate, directly controlled by the lord and used for the benefit of his household and dependents.

A curved dam usually built of concrete and designed with the curve upstream so that the force of the water compresses the structure and strengthens it as it pushes it into its foundations. Arch dams are best suited to narrow gorges
A prepared area of ground, often enclosed, used for the game of basketball.

Traditionally an amber-coloured globe lamp atop a tall black and white pole, acting as a signal to road users that there is a pedestrian crossing. Modern beacons may also include an outer ring of flashing LED lights.
A hall, often associated with a synagogue, used for studying the Torah and other religious texts.
An elevated area or platform in a synagogue where the person reading aloud from the Torah stands.
A dam with a watertight upstream side, which may be flat or curved, supported by a series of buttresses on the downstream side.
A factory built for the production of breakfast cereals.
A woollen mill in which the cloth was passed over rollers covered in short spikes to raise the nap in one direction only.
Site or building used for paintballing.
A place of worship for the followers of Jainism
Established as king of York in the mid 870s. Driven out in 877.
A stone ring built to enclose and sometimes revet a burial mound or cairn.
A lime kiln built into a low hillside or slope to facilitate top loading of the limestone.
An area of land, usually enclosed, set aside for the breeding of hares.
A pit containing the waste product form iron working.

Armoured military vehicle with its own firepower, which operates on tracks for troop mobility over rough terrain. Some may be adapted, or purpose-built, to be amphibious, and may then be double-indexed as AMPHIBIOUS VEHICLE.
Vehicle either adapted, or purpose-built, to operate on both land and sea, for example a tank or DUKW.
Use both terms.
A large building used for the storage of finished cloth.
A facility used for the storage and distribution of fuel for transportation. Often associated with dockyards and railways.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
An airfield, and associated structures, used by one or more bomber squadrons.
A building, or buildings, providing accommodation for an infantry regiment.
A golf course, usually situated on or near the coast, consisting of sand dunes with few trees or water obstacles.
Use most appropriate term.
A fairground ride, often a permanent structure, consisting of a tower with an internal staircase and an external spiral shaped slide.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.
Use both terms.

A commercially manufactured air raid shelter, using prefabricated parabolic concrete panels which could be combined to produce any length of shelter.Usually semi-sunken and covered with earth they were mainly used on RAF sites.
Platform or structure used for viewing performances.
A building or site conducting research into communication techniques for use in the Royal Navy.
A building used for the daily administration of that branch of the RAF dealing with training pilots.

A structure, based on drawing number (3329/41), intended to be the headquarters for the coordination of an airfield's defences. Constructed above ground this design was found to be vulnerable and was superceded by the (11008/41).
Scaffolding erected on a beach and in the surf so as to prevent hostile forces from landing.
A factory used for the manufacture of ordnance including small arms, ammunition, artillery pieces and armoured fighting vehicles.
A prepared area of cleared ground on which an aircraft could make an emergency landing.
An area of hardstanding, surrounded on three sides by a protective wall or bank, used for parking aircraft, in a state of readiness, usually around the perimeter of an airfield.
An airfield, and associated structures, used by one or more fighter squadrons.
A shelter on a firing range from which the wepaons testing can be viewed in safety.
An area of ground where training in the use of grenades can be carried out.
A designated area of land, usually closed to the public, used for military exercises and training purposes.
A military base used for training service personnel.
A military camp providing training facilities.
Based on a typical 18ft span, 40ft long temporary brick hut but with two bay windows in the front elevation, one for the watch office and one for the chief instructor.
A building for housing, maintaining and repairing motor cars. Dating to the 1890s.
A grain grinding mill in which the meal is ground into flour between revolving metal rolls.
Purpose built accommodation for students built by a private company rather than a college or university.
Hut for use at Level Crossings that were not adjacent to Signal Boxes.
A free-standing cross made of stone in the form of a cross with a ring surrounding the intersection. Often used as a grave marker
A grave marker in the form of a casket.
Specialised fermenting vessel consisting of a two-storey system consisting of a shallow chamber approximately 2m high above which is a walled deck.
A school that is directly funded by central government (specifically, the Department for Education) and independent of direct control by local government in England.
An inclined plane built to allow tanks to be loaded and unloaded between rolling stock on the railway network and vehicular low loaders.
A building housing a Russian-style steam bath or banya.
The limit line of a county.
Essex
A fully automatic mounted or portable firearm, usually designed to fire bullets in quick succession from an ammunition belt or magazine.
A garden created to commemorate a person or event.

A conglomerate rock comprising well rounded flint pebbles in a very hard matrix of fine pale coloured sand, bound together by hard natural silica cement. The pebbles are usually coloured ochre or red and have black rims.
A moveable section of  light fence, traditionally made from wattle and used for herding livestock, to separate land or to act as river bank revetments.
A building used as a control centre for the Air Raid Precautions network, responsible for issuing air raid warnings and coordinating fire and rescue services.
A specialized lantern, with a reduced glare, for use in air raids.
An observation post used by Air Raid Precautions wardens to watch for aircraft and bomb strikes.
A centre used by the Air Raid Precautions network to co-ordinate reports of air raids in an area.
A sign used by the Air Raid Precautions network to assist in identifying vital equipment and resources in the event of an air raid or to aid movement during blackouts.
A brick built railway signal box, usually with a reinforced correct roof, designed to minimize the effects of blast damage from aerial bombardment and thus protect the signalling equipment.
A building used for the storage and distribution of civilian respirators and Air Raid Precautions equipment.
A centre used to train Air Raid Precautions wardens.
A siren used to warn of an impending attack by enemy aircraft.

A building or structure used to provide protection to an Air Raid Warden or firewatcher during an air raid, thus enabling the identification of the locations of fires caused by incendiary bombs in comparative safety.
A gun emplacement which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55414.
A gun emplacement which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55415.
A gun emplacement which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55422.
A gun emplacement which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55483.
A gun emplacement which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55491.
A gun emplacment which conforms to Department of Fortification and Works drawing number 55503
A structure, usually or concrete or sandbags, in which a machine gun was emplaced.
A distinctive, clerestory-roofed building of three 10ft and two 12ft bays, used for the drying, storage and packing of military parachutes and built to Air Ministry drawing number 10825/42.
A distinctive, clerestory-roofed building of five 10ft bays, used for the drying, storage and packing of military parachutes and built to Air Ministry drawing number 11137/41.
A protected parachute store similar in design to the 6351/37 except constructed wholly from reinforced concrete.
A distinctive, clerestory-roofed building of five 10ft bays, used for the drying, storage and packing of military parachutes and built to Air Ministry drawing number 17865/39.

A brick-built building with four windows on the north-facing wall with a pitched roof and with a dormer roof light on both sides, intended for drying, storing and packing parachutes.The 2355/25 was the first design for a purpose-built parachute store.
A hut 51ft long by 20ft wide used to dry, store and pack parachutes.Similar in design to the 2355/25, but constructed in timber instead of brick.
A protected parachute store built with permanent brick cavity walls and a roof of reinforced concrete slabs in two heights separated by lantern lights.
A power house built to Air Ministry drawing number 1380/24.
A power house built to Air Ministry drawing number 207/17 and comprising four rooms; a driver's room, workshop and store, battery room and engine room containing 2 generator sets.
The standard RFC power house built to Air Ministry drawing number 476/18 and comprising an engine room with a small workshop and driver's room.
A building housing the stand-by generator set and associated equipment which could supply electricity to all essential services in the event of a power cut.
A stand by set house built to Air Ministry drawing number 1039/41.
A stand by set house designed to drawing number 13244/41 and comprising of 4 rooms; a fuel storage room, a transformer chamber, a switchgear chamber and the main engine room with 2 diesel engines.

A stand by set house similar to 13244/41 and designed to drawing number 16302/41 and comprising of 4 rooms; a fuel storage room, a transformer chamber, a switchgear chamber and the main engine room with 3 diesel engines.
A portable stand by set house built to Air Ministry drawing number 3527/43.
A stand by set house built to Air Ministry drawing number 4238/44.
An expansion period stand by set house designed to drawing number 607/36 and containing a single generator set and switch board. Constructed in reinforced concrete.

A stand by set house built with a steel-framed pitched roof. Built to drawing number 8760/42 it was intended to supersede all earlier designs and was cheaper to produce. Both the transformer and fuel tanks were located outside the main building.
A system of lights to aid aircraft when landing at night. When viewed from above the runway lights form an outline of the runway.
A building or buildings used for the manufacture of metal boxes or cases.
A building in which cordite dough is stored before extrusion.
A building in which moist guncotton is dried by warm air for use in nitroglycerine manufacture.

Land which has been temporarily taken over for use by the military or civilian authorities. During wartime land was requisitioned for various purposes, such as for argriculture or for military training/events etc.
A building in which cordite paste is blended with the solvent acetone and Vaseline to form a cordite dough.
Fishing smack specialised both for working shoal water and for trawling for shrimp, predominantly in and around Morecambe Bay.
A building housing the generator set and associated equipment supplying electricity to a radar station.
A tall, usually steel, structure used to receive and transmit radio signals in order to determine the height, distance and number of aircraft approaching.
A tall, usually steel, structure used to receive and transmit radio telegraphy signals.
A small, industrially manufactured, air raid shelter, designed to be used inside buildings and to provide cover for nightwatchmen or firewatchers remaining on site during air raids.
A building or site used by the armed forces for the storage and issuing of military stores and materials.
A building in which photographers, taken for aerial reconnaissance purposes, are analysed and interpreted to provide intelligence on enemy activities.
A room used for directing military operations and exercises.
An area of ground used for the testing of, and practicing with, weapons against fixed and moveable targets.
A miniature railway on which targets can be placed to provide moving targets on a firing range.
A building or site used for the storage and distribution of the essential logistical requirements of an armed force.
A platform, usually in concrete, on which radar equipment was mounted to assist the targetting of artillery guns. The platform is often the only evidence surviving in the landscape.
A pit filled with rocks and metal, designed to be fired with an explosive charge.

A site used for the placing of an explosive, demolition charge. Many types of structures were prepared for demolition in the event of an invasion in order to cause the maximum disruption to the advance of hostile forces. Use more specifc type where known.

A steel pipe driven into the ground at a shallow, oblique angle and packed with explosives. They were intended to be detonated on the approach of a hostile amroured vehicle or tank in order to create an obstacle directly in its path.
A road which has had mines placed within its structure to enable it to be destroyed in the event of an invasion.
A mobile piece of equipment used by the Royal Observer Corps to track the movements of enemy aircraft.
A portable indoor air raid shelter in the form of a steel topped table, often with wire meshing around the sides.
A site associated with Operation PLUTO (Pipe Line Under The Ocean) the operation to supply the allies with fuel following the invasion of Normandy.
A military base for the training of SOE operatives in the skills and techniques required to survive in enemy-occupied territory.
An administrative building used to organize and co-ordinate the activities of members of the armed forces.
A building used for the administration of a squadron.
One or more coils of barbed wire intended to impede the advance of hostile troops.
Barbed wire in the form of a coil which could be extended concertina-like to form a barrier to impede the movement of hostile troops.
An expansion period stand by set house designed to drawing number 974/35 and containing a single generator set and switch board. Constructed with brick cavity walls.
A concrete, circular concave dish 20 feet in diameter used as an acoustic listening device to detect approaching enemy aircraft.
A concrete, concave wall 200 feet in length used as an acoustic listening device to detect approaching enemy aircraft.
A concrete, circular concave dish 30 feet in diameter used as an acoustic listening device to detect approaching enemy aircraft.
A building housing the acoustic detection equipment for a sound mirror

A site, building or structure used for the detection of approaching hostile aircraft, shipping or missiles early enough to allow a counterattack or defensive measures to be taken. Use more specific term.
A watch office with additional rooms given over to the meteorological section, including a forecast room and met store.

A two-storey, all-concrete construction with a watch office and additional rooms given over to the meteorological section, including a forecast room and met store. A concrete parapet all around the roof differentiates it from 5845/39.
An all timber constructed watch office with meterological section. Similar in design to 2328/39 and 5845/39. There were only two known examples built in the UK at Wick and St.Eval.
A temporary brick and timber watch office based on the all-timber 2423/39. Built after 1941 on many Operational Training Unit airfields the design was superseded by 8936/40.

A two-storey, brick construction with a watch office and additional rooms given over to the meteorological section, including a forecast room and met store. A brick parapet on the roof differentiates it from 2328/39.

Based on the previous all-timber design 2423/39 and the temporary brick and timber design 518/40, the 8936/40 was built with pre-cast concrete slabs replacing the timber floors and staircases with only the balcony and watch office roof in timber.
A two-storey watch office, built to Air Ministry drawing number 1959/34 but with slight design modifications as detailed in drawing number 1960/34.
A square, concrete pillbox-like structure with 36in thick walls and a single large embrasure used to emplace a Vickers Medium Machine Gun. The entrance was protected by an external blast wall.
A building containing a flight siumlator used to provide safe training for pilots.
A building housing a flight simulator designed to air ministry drawing number 10040/41.
A building housing a flight simulator designed to air ministry drawing number 1762/39.
A building housing a flight simulator designed to air ministry drawing number 4188/42.
A building housing a flight simulator designed to air ministry drawing number 7790/40.

An operations room, built to drawing number 3395/40, to control the lighting arrays of the 'T' type of bombing decoy in use during the Second World War. It was semi-sunken for added protection and then covered in earth

An operations room, built to drawing number 367/41, to control the lighting arrays of the DREM type of bombing decoy in use during the Second World War. Unlike earlier designs it was surface built and then covered in earth to protect against flooding.
A decoy fire positioned close to a legitimate target which would be lit in the event of an incendiary attack in the hope that subsequent bombs would be drawn to the area of the decoy.

Blocks of solid concrete, in the shape of a round bottomed cone usually 2 feet 6 inches across x 2 feet 9 inches high. Buoys were mainly used in road blocks intended to impede enemy movement in the event of invasion.

Blocks of concrete with four protruding arms so that, whichever way up the caltrop is placed, one arm will always point upward. Used in imitation of the iron caltrops thrown on the ground to impede cavalry.

Rectangular slabs of concrete with a sloping top usually with sides of 5 feet by 3 feet and 3 feet high which when placed in rows were intended to form a substantial barrier to enemy armoured divisions in the event of invasion.
Cubes of solid concrete, usually with sides of 3 feet 6 inches or 5 feet which when placed in rows were intended to form a substantial barrier to enemy armoured divisions in the event of invasion.
An area of a carriageway, usually delimited by road markings, for the sole use of bicycles.

Blocks of solid concrete, in the form of cylinders usually 2 feet across x 2 feet 6 inches or 3 feet high. Cylinders were mainly used in road blocks intended to impede enemy movement in the event of invasion.

Blocks of solid concrete,in the form of truncated pyramids usually 3 feet square x 2 feet high which could be placed in rows to impede enemy movement in the event of invasion. Pimples were recommended for use on soft ground.
Triangular concrete pyramids with 6 feet long sides and 5 feet high, intended to impede enemy movement in the event of invasion. Thought to be confined geogaphically to Southern Command.

Cones of solid concrete usually 3 feet 6 inches in diameter x 2 feet high which, when placed in rows or groups were intended to form a substantial barrier to enemy armoured divisions in the event of invasion.

A large, circular, reinforced-concrete tank supported on concrete staging built to Air Ministry drawing number 1178/25 and designed to hold 30,000 gallons of water. The height of the tower varied according to local site requirements.
A plate-steel water tower made with two compartments holding 30,000 gallons of water. Designed to Air Ministry drawing number 20/40.
A plate-steel water tank on a steel tower designed to hold 80,000 gallons of water. Designed to Air Ministry drawing number 9526/41.
A metal girder, usually of iron or steel, embedded in the ground designed to obstruct the progress of hostile tanks or armoured vehicles.
A road block formed by placing curved rails, "hairpins", in sockets in the road surface.
A man made ditch designed to obstruct the progress of a tank or armoured vehicle. Ditches were often reveted with concrete or wood.
A natural ditch the depth and/or width of which has been increased so as to prevent the progress of a tank or armoured vehicle.
Scaffolding intended to impede the advance of enemy armoured divisions. Often found in association with "one way" anti tank ditches.
A road block formed by placing rails or girders in an upright position in sockets in the road surface, forming a moveable barrier.
A modification of WATCH OFFICE (12779/41) where the original large windows were removed and smaller frames fitted, the gap being filled with straight-joint brickwork.
A building, originally used as a shelter for the duty pilot or officer on watch on an airfield, incorporating an operations room.
Watch Office with operations room designed to Air Ministry drawing number (13079/41)
Watch Office with operations room designed to Air Ministry drawing number (7345/41
A circular pillbox designed by the Croft Granite, Brick and Concrete Company, with six loopholes. With no roof or door access was gained through the roof.
A defensive position, often constructed from sandbags, designed to protect a group of infantry.
A pit dug to protect a small group of infantry men.
Obstacles placed in open spaces and alongside roads designed to prevent the successful landing of enemy airborne forces.
A purpose built trench designed to prevent the successful landing of enemy glider-borne and airborne forces.
A building used for the daily administration of the Royal Air Force.
A building used for the daily administration of an army.
A building used for the daily administration of the Royal Navy.
A building used as headquarters by the Territorial Army, the volunteer reserve of the British army.
A hostel used to accommodate members of the Womens Land Army who undertook essential agricultural work during the Second World War.
A camp used to accommodate members of the Womens Land Army who undertook essential agricultural work during the Second World War.
A camp used for the accommodation of members of the Womens Auxiliary Air Force who undertook a variety of essential roles within the RAF to enable their male counterparts to fight more effectively.
A designated area of water in which the perfromance of torpedoes can be evaluated.
A control tower designed for use on Very Heavy Bomber Station Airfields. Designed to Air Ministry drawing number 294/45 they were the first to be have a Visual Control Room

TERM: Very Heavy Bomber Station Control Tower (294/45)

SCOPE_NOTE: The largest boat belonging to a sailing vessel, and usually the means of escape from a sinking ship; powered by oars.
17th/18th century lightly armed privateer, usually either a 'Dunkirker' or Dutch.
A house in which a member of the Royal Court lives.
Heavy caterpillar tractors fitted with broad blades to the front for moving or levelling earth and obstacles.
Landing craft designed for carrying military vehicles and used for beach landings and as a ferry.

Inshore craft used for carrying troops and military equipment used either for beach landings or as a ferry; as cargo smaller landing craft could be carried aboard larger craft in the D-Day operations, for example.
A piece of stone or timber with a small cup shaped depression in its upper surface, set into the ground to fasten a door, gate, window etc to allow it to open and shut.
A road junction where two (or occasionally more) roads cross each other.
The central part of a road between the pavements or the verges.
A path, or marked lane, designated for use by cyclists.

Any structural component, usually of wood, which is believed to have derived from a vessel. Double index with the appropriate type of structural component eg. BEAM or if known the original term from the MARITIME FIXTURES AND FITTINGS thesaurus.
A craft designed for use on canals and inland waterways. Usually 70ft long x 7ft wide though can be longer and broader.
A wide street, traditionally lined with trees.
A chapel within a parish church or other religious building for use by the lord of the manor and his family
A garden building usually in a secluded spot, resembling a hermit's dwelling and built as a resting place, retreat or viewing point.
A screen separating the choir from other parts of the church.
In Orthodox churches, the screen that divides off the sanctuary, usually decorated with sacred images (icons). (Source: Pevsner Glossary)
In churches a niche, or shelf, within or beside a piscina, or a table for the sacramental elements and vessels. (Source: Pevsner Glossary)
A tower which rises above the space at the intersection of the nave, chancel and transepts of a church. Usually pierced by windows to provide light directly to the area below.
A gallery or platform within a place of worship housing the organ.
A structure, usually sunk into the ground, for the purpose of allowing total bodily immersion as part of a baptismal ceremony.
An enclosure, usually private, used for burial. Often found within a cemetery.
A building associated with funerary rites and burials.
A barn in which a central space is separated from a side aisle by posts and braces.
A settlement built to a pre-determined plan, including housing, infrastructure and associated amenities.
A planned, self-contained, community incorporating green open spaces and containing housing, industrial and agricultural zones.
A settlement carefully planned from its inception and usually constructed in an area which was previously undeveloped. Many new towns were developed following the New Towns Act 1946.
A largely residential area on the outskirts of a town or city.
An area including buildings dedicated to scientific research for commercial purposes. Often associated with, or operated by, a university or higher education institution.
Residential area built to house athletes and their coaches at the Olympic Games. The buildings are generally reused as public housing after the contest.
A structure composed of two large upright stone supporting a third, lintel stone.
A command centre used to co-ordinate information received from Royal Observer Corps observation and monitoring posts.

A building used by the Royal Observer Corps as a headquarters and reporting centre. It may also fulfil an observation and nuclear fallout monitoring role. Use term to describe headquarters for plotting and monitoring nuclear fallout.

A complex of buildings used as a headquarters and training base for Royal Navy personnel. Even though they are buildings on land shore establishments are deemed to be shipsand are designated 'HMS' eg. HMS Dolphin in Portsmouth.

A site, usually with docks and control buildings, used for the storage, maintenance and deployment of military vessels or the administration of the Royal Navy. May also include accommodation buildings for personnel.
A building or site used for the storage and distribution of the essential logistical requirements of the Royal Navy.
An airfield with associated hangars and control buildings used for the storage, maintenance and deployment of military aircraft and airships flown by the Royal Naval Air Service.

A site, usually with an airfield, hangars and control buildings, used for the storage and deployment of military aircraft or the administration of the Royal Air Force. May also include accommodation buildings for personnel.
A site with accommodation buildings and ancillary facilities for Royal Air Force personnel.
A large pillbox-like structure, often L-shaped or angular, with numerous loopholes used as a defensive position.
A building which has been altered to increase its defensive characteristics. Use more specific term where known.
A concrete, cylindrical pedestal on which a spigot mortar was mounted. The pedestal is often the only evidence for a Spigot Mortar emplacement to survive.
A telegraph pole, tree trunk or similar erected on the side of a road, or in an open space, to prevent the landing of hostile aircraft
The main administrative building and headquarters of a regiment
A building, administered by the Navy, Army and Air Force Institutes, providing retail and leisure services to members of the armed forces.
A building, on an airfield, used to house a fire engine.
A building, on an airfield, used to house a fire engine designed to Air Ministry drawing number 12563/40.
A building, on an airfield, used to house a fire engine designed to Air Ministry drawing number 5342/42.
An observation post used by members of the Home Guard.

A decoy site designed to replicate the layout of an RAF satellite airfield, complete with dummy aircraft, simulated runways and simple structures intended to fool enemy aircraft during daylight raids.
A purpose-built building with a tower used for the drying of parachutes.
A fortifed position, often including fieldworks or defensive structures, designed to keep enemy forces engaged to allow reinforcements to be mobilized.
A purpose-built building with a steel framed tower, based on drawing number (11595/42). Used for the drying of parachutes.
A brick tower, based on drawing number (9290/42), usually added to an existing building. Used for the drying of parachutes.
A purpose-built building with a brick tower constructed on one end, based on drawing number (9294/42). Used for the drying of parachutes.
A system of lights, controlled fires or dummy constructions, used to simulate a railway yard or sidings and thus confuse enemy aircraft into bombing these counterfeit targets.
A defensive battery positioned facing out to sea enabling the guns to be brought to bear on enemy shipping and amphibious craft.
A coastal battery containing one or more artillery pieces for to defend the coast against hostile motor torpedo boats.
A coastal battery constructed at short notice usually mounting a variety of artillery pieces.
A radar station with sets operating on a wavelength of 10cm or less. They were highly accurate radars and gave better sea level coverage than the earlier Chain Home Low stations.
A monument erected as a permanent reminder of a military victory. The design usually includes images of the spoils of the battle.
A watchtower used to guard prisons, camps or other facilities.
The grounds of an institution for higher education eg. a university, including the educational buildings, entertainment and sports facilities and student's halls of residence.
An area of land used for camping. Often includes facilities for washing, catering and entertainment.
A court, usually with only 2 walls, used for playing pelota and its variants.
A telescope which is mounted so as to allow the observation of only those objects in the sky which are passing over a local meridian, an event known as transit.
A building housing the instrumentation necessary for the observation and measurement of tremors generated by earthquakes.

A club often with a dance floor or small stage and featuring entertainment generally of an improvisational, satirical, or topical nature which can be watched by the clientele whilst they drink and dine.
Place for the cremation of animals.

World War II-era British merchant ships used in convoys as an emergency stop-gap until sufficient escort carriers became available. They were equipped with a rocket-propelled catapult launching a single Hawker Sea Hurricane plane.
A walkway on the top of a defensive wall, providing access to the parapets and towers.
A temporary, usually roofed, wooden structure placed on the ramparts or walls of a castle to improve the defenders field of fire along the length of a wall.
A school with religious education in addition to conventional education run by parishes.
A factory complex consisting of PRINTING SHOPS, COLOUR HOUSES, DYE HOUSES, etc, in which patterns are printed onto textiles.
A steam vessel propelled by rotating propellers called screws.
A mill, including a forge and powered hammers where hot metal is shaped by hammering and rolling.
A factory manufacturing timepieces, including clocks and watches.
A factory manufacturing bearings, including ball bearings for use in precision equipment.
A factory manufacturing electrical cables.
A factory manufacturing electrical equipment, such as engines, transformers and generators for use in industry.
A factory manufacturing personal hygiene and beauty products
A building or complex where soft skins are produced by tanning with alum.
A building or complex where skins are prepared, with their hair still on, to make fur products.
A building or complex where animal hair is processed, using a variety of means, for use in products such as brushes, mattresses etc.
A building or complex producing umbrellas, parasols and canes.
A building or complex where cork is treated and processed to be used in various products.
A building or complex where corks and stoppers are made for use in bottling.

A propulsion system for ships which need a maximum speed that is considerably faster than their cruise speed, particularly warships. It consists of diesel engines for cruising and gas turbines for high-speed transits.
A propulsion system for ships using a combination of steam turbines and gas turbines to power the shafts.
Internal combustion engine powered by diesel fuel.
A shaft allowing access to an area. Often used as an additional escape route to the main shaft in a mine or as an air shaft.
A series of locks usually with short reaches between them allowing boats to travel up and down a steep incline.
A pipe, usually of reinforced concrete or metal, which delivers pressurized water from a dam to hydraulic turbines.
A vertical shaft, usually with an internal ladder, allowing access to a sewer or underground counduit for inspection and maintenance.
A channel or pipe providing water to a canal or other body of water.
A bridge with two or more decks allowing it to carry various modes of transport at the same time.
A radar station with sets operating on a wavelength of 1.5m. Chain Home Low Stations were intended for use in locating low-flying aircraft but was also capable of detecting high-flying aircraft.

TERM: COAST DEFENCE CHAIN HOME LOW STATION
SCOPE_NOTE: A radar station with sets operating on a wavelenght of 1.5m established to provide radar plotting of both shipping and aircraft movements.
A building equipped with instruments and a flight simulator used to teach members of bomber crews how to correctly identify targets for bombing.
An observation tower located on or near to a bombing range.
Any structure or object, used for the purpose of practice bombing.
A protected building used for the storage of explosives and other pyrotechnic equipment and designed to Air Ministry drawing number 2647/37.
A barracks comprising eight barrack blocks accessed via a central corridor. With four blocks on either side of the corridor the whole structure resembled a spider in plan.
A mooring, usually consisting of a concrete plinth, to which a barrage balloon was attached.
A hangar used for the storage of barrage balloons.
A building associated with a barrage balloon site and intended to provide shelter for the balloon crew from air attack.
A building or site used for the storage and distribution lighter than air gases for use in barrage balloons.
A cable, usually erected between posts, used to prevent the landing or hostile aircraft.
A small, steel shelter designed for use as a firewatchers post during an air raid.
A trench, usually linking two or more rows of trenches, enabling the conveyance of messages or equipment safely from one trench to another.
A trench cut around a building or structure to prevent the spread of fire.
An emplacement mounting a small, portable electrically-powered searchlight.
Optical and/or navigational instruments with powerful lenses for observing remote objects or used in astronomy.
A prefabricated structure of reinforced concrete posts supporting a pitched roof frame with an infilling of sawdust concrete panels. Produced by Maycrete Ltd during WWII.

A prefabricated structure of reinforced concrete posts supporting a pitched roof frame with an infilling of concrete panels. Produced by during WWII as barrack accommodation and as emergency housing. Similar in style to Maycrete huts.

A concrete hut produced by the Ministry of Works as a cheaper alternative to the BCF Hut as any suitable wall cladding could be employed in its construction. Usually used to form barrack blocks on airfields from 1944 onwards.

A prefabricated structure consisting of trough shaped asbestos sheets bolted together to form a seven sided building in section with end walls of rendered brick. Manufactured from 1942 by the Universal Asbestos Company for use as airfield accommodation.

A prefabricated structure consisting of six curved asbestos cement sheets that were bolted together, without a frame, creating a hut semi-circular in section. Used on airfields during WWII and manufactured from 1942 by the Turner Asbestos Company.

A prefabricated temporary structure made of lightweight timber framed panels clad externally with corrugated iron sheets. Used during WWII as officers quarters. Possibly manufactured by Boulton and Paul Limited.

A prefabricated structure of lightweight timber wall sections bolted together. Externally the walls were clad with plasterboard covered with felt. Designed for use as officers accomodation during WWII.
A prefabricated timber structure similar to Sectional hutting that was used by the Air Ministry for accommodation at airfields during WWII. Manufactured by Gerrard and Sons from 1939 to 1941.
A prefabricated structure of a light timber frame with external weather boarded walls and a timber felt covered roof. They were used as barrack blocks during WWII. Manufactured by Magnet Limited.

A prefabricated structure of cant sided lightweight timber wall sections bolted together. Externally the walls were clad with plasterboard covered with felt. Designed for use as barrack accommodation during WWII.

A type of temporary military hutting used throughout WWII constructed of brick in 'stretcher bond' 4.5 inches thick with a light steel truss roof usually covered with corrugated asbestos sheeting. Used for accommodation, as gyms, training huts etc.

A hut consisting of a frame of reinforced concrete posts into which panels of either pre cast concrete or corrugated asbestos could be slotted. Designed by the British Concrete Federation during WWII.

A prefabricated structure of reinforced concrete posts and beams with infillings of pre stressed concrete planks and felted slabs. Initially used for military barracks in WWII and later for civilian housing. Manufactured by the Orlit Company.
A school design consisting of single-storey buildings with classrooms entered from a verandah.
A hut consisting of a frame of reinforced concrete posts into which panels could be slotted. Designed by the British Concrete Federation (BCF) during WWII.
A section of a hospital specializing in the treatment of patients with serious mental disorders.
A section of a psychiatric hospital or psychiatric ward set aside for children and/or adolescents with mental illness.
Specialist hospital treating patients with physical disabilities.
Equipment enabling a horse to be ridden or driven, eg. saddles, bridles, harnesses, stirrups etc.
Bells used either as a percussion instrument or for other purposes such as calling attention, marking time periods etc.

Articles intended for personal adornment, usually to be strung on items of jewellery or sewn onto clothing. They may be made out of worked raw materials (eg. shells) or be manufactured goods, for example glass beads.
A structure providing protection against the weather, situated on railway platforms.
17th to early 19th century muzzle-loaded long guns.
A mill in which oilcloth (a heavy cotton or linen cloth with a linseed oil coating) was produced.
A tool used for splitting straw. The straw splitter would be pushed down the hollow shaft of a piece of straw to produce six flat lengths of straw ready for plaiting. Used in straw hat making.
Boarding school for children of Travellers and Romany Gypsies while their parents were away on agricultural work
Brewery which produces lager
A threshing barn, usually timber framed which is raised on staddle stones.
Mass produced iron framed shed usually clad in metal sheeting.

A stone building with external access to the domestic accommodation via a permanent stair. The ground floor is normally used as a byre in rural contexts, but in an urban setting it may be intended for one of a number of other non domestic uses.
A site intended for use by the Auxiliary Units (or British Resistance Organisation) in the event of an invasion. Use more specific term.
A means of transportation where cars, chairs or cabins are carried above the ground by means of one or more cables suspended between towers or pylons.
An aerial lift in which cabins are suspended from a continuous cable between two towers which hold the winding mechanism. The cable may be supported by towers or pylons.
A large tent which can be used as accommodation for parties and exhibitions.

Device for extracting juice from apples, usually crab apples, for use in cooking and medicine. Consists of a stone base carved with channels in the upper surface which was used with an upper weight, often secured with a wooden beam wedged into position.
A body of water, building or structure found in a park or garden used as a water supply or ornament. Use more specific type where known.
A body of water placed in such a way as to reflect a building or landscape feature.
A geometrical planting of trees in the form of the number 5 as represented on a dice.
A plot of earth used for the raising of plants.
An area of land, usually planted with creeping plants and turf, laid out in a woodland landscape to produce the natural effect of a clearing.
A parterre consisting of square beds containing ornamental plants often laid out in intricate patterns mimicking embroidery.
A parterre consisting of an area of turf often with a pattern cut into it.
A timber frame placed in the bell chamber of a church tower or belfry designed to hold the bells.
An arch which is formed by keystones but is flat like a lintel
A passage constructed within the thickness of a wall.

Staircase whose moving steps are driven mechanically whilst remaining permanently in a horizontal plane allowing users or objects to be moved effortlessly from one level to another, within or outside a building.

An area of land incorporating bodies of water, either natural or manmade for use in water sports activities such as canoeing, rowing and sailing. Usually includes a leisure complex with facilities for the users.
A passage providing access to utility services or a larger tunnel for the purposes of monitoring and maintenance. May also provide be used as an evacuation route.
A machine consisting of a continuously moving band of fabric, rubber, or metal used for transporting people or objects from one place to another.
A vertical or inclined plane, channel, or passage through which objects are moved from a higher to a lower level by means of gravity.
A colonnade all around the exterior of a building or an interior space such as a courtyard.
A polygonal or circular stone forming part of the shaft of a column.
An arch which has a larger radius on the front face of a wall than on the back.
A water feature intended to play a trick on a visitor by drenching them unexpectedly. The device would be triggered by the visitors foot or remotely. Italian for 'water jokes'.
A flower bed, usually circular and convex in form, edged with wicker basketwork, iron hoops or terracotta.
A garden featrue where several allees radiate from a single point (usually the house). French for 'Goose Foot'

A prefabricated structure consisting of sectional timber framed units that were bolted together. The structure was clad with Canadian Cedar weatherboarding and had a roof of corrugated asbestos. They were used as temporary accommodation on airfields.

A prefabricated structure consisting of sectional timber framed units that were bolted together. The structure was clad with weatherboarding and had a felted roof. They were used as temporary accommodation on airfields. Also see 'Type A'

A prefabricated structure of standard lightweight timber wall sections bolted together. Externally the walls were clad with plasterboard covered with felt. Designed in 1940 for use as barrack accommodation.

A prefabricated structure of cellular hollow plywood 'aero' beams and columns clad with timber framed units of flat asbestos facing sheets and a felt roof. Designed as airfield accommodation that could be reused as post WWII emergency housing.

A hut consisting of a frame of reinforced concrete posts into which concrete panels were slotted. Designed by the British Concrete Federation during WWII to be resistant to bomb blasts & used for military accommodation, child nurseries and clinics etc.

A concrete arched military hut constructed by pouring concrete over hessian cloth that had been stretched over a temporary steel framework. Semi circular in section usually with end walls of brick. Designed by the Waller Housing Corp in 1943.

A well concealed structure, usually constructed undergound, intended for use by members of the Special Duties section of the Auxiliary Units (or British Resistance Organization) in the event of invasion.
An underground hideout containing radio equipment to be used by the Special Duties sections of the Auxiliary Units to send information to the control station for relaying to headquarters.

TERM: AUXILIARY UNIT SPECIAL DUTIES CONTROL STATION
SCOPE_NOTE: An underground hideout containing radio equipment to be used by the Special Duties sections of the Auxiliary Units to co-ordinate information collected by the outstations for relaying to headquarters.
A fire station built for use by the Auxiliary Fire Service, established in 1938 to supplement existing local brigades.

A building temporarily requistioned for use as a hospital. Auxiliary hospitals treated the less seriously wounded and were less strict than military hospitals although they remained under military control.
A structure, usually well concealed, used to store explosives intended for use by the Auxiliary Units (or British Resistance Organization) in the event of an invasion.
A reinforced concrete structure, usually sited underground,  intended to be used by the regional government as an air raid shelter in the event of a nuclear attack.
A building used for the storage of artillery pieces.
A garage for the storage and maintenance of motor vehicles, such as ambluances and fire engines, used for civil defence purposes.
A building used for the daily administration of Civil Defence activities.

A building or site used to train civilians and members of the services in the skills designed to protect the civilian population during times of war. Could also be used during times of national emergency.
A protected building or site used for the safe storage of chemical weapons

A mask worn over the face to protect the wearer from inhaling airborne pollutants and toxic gases. The mask forms a sealed cover over the nose and mouth, but may also cover the eyes and other vulnerable soft tissues of the face.
A building or structure of unknown function found on a railway. Use more specific type where known
A building or site used as a storage and distribution centre.
A semicircular niche in the wall of a mosque used to indicate the Qiblah - the direction to be faced during prayers. Qiblah is set as the direction of the Kaaba in Mecca.

Dutch coaster of the late 17th to late 19th centuries with a square hull and 2 masts, generally having a heavy keel and round stern and bilges, although later examples were built on more refined lines.
A shallow artificial pond, usually found on the coast, in which sea water is allowed to evaporate leaving behind the salt.
An entrance large enough for carriages and vehicles leading through a building or wall into an inner courtyard.
A building or subterranean structure used for the storage of spirits.
A surgery where patients who pay for medical treatments are seen and treated.
A limited programme of intrusive fieldwork which determines the presence or absence of archaeological features, structures, deposits, artefacts or ecofacts within a specified underwater area.

Controlled intrusive fieldwork which examines, records and interprets archaeological deposits, features and structures and, as appropriate, retrieves artefacts and ecofact remains within a specified underwater area.

The non intrusive processes by which information is collected about the location, distribution and organisation of past human activities that are now submerged by water. The approaches can be either extensive or intensive depending on the objectives.
Purpose built or modified structure or building used for scenery in a television program.

Composed of a wide variety of substances and materials such as whole or broken bricks, cobblestones, flints, pebbles and sand which are set into hydraulic lime. Used most often to form external walls and is commonly found in the Brighton/Lewes region.
Dung or compost, carried either as an export cargo or as waste to be dumped out at sea.
A large kitchen garden enclosed by a substantial wall, not usually adjacent to its associated house.
A strip of cultivated land situated against the exterior of a walled garden's perimeter, so placed to maximise usable wall space.
A small enclosure containing cold frames, often of brick and glass construction, usually situated against the exterior of a walled garden's south-facing garden.
A single-storey structure, usually situated against the exterior of a walled garden's south facing wall, used for storage and often accomodation.
A small pond, usually circular and serving as a feature at the centre of a walled garden, used for the purpose of filling watering cans.
A building or complex used for the temporary detention of people with no legal right to be in the UK who have refused to leave voluntarily.
A room set aside within a building where social and other functions such as parties, presentations and meetings can be held.
A military depot where horses were taken and trained for service in the army.
A factory where shirts are manufactured.
A factory where collars, for shirts and other garments, are manufactured.
